/* ============================================================================
   OPERATIONALIZING AI — practical, beginner-friendly how-to tutorials for using
   AI in real professional and academic settings. Each tutorial teaches ONE use
   case end to end, with a copy-paste prompt and BOTH a cloud route (Microsoft
   Copilot / Google Gemini / Anthropic Claude) and a private local-model route.
   Local-model SETUP is intentionally deferred to the future "AI Experimentation
   Station" (see the localNeedsSetup callouts). Authored from the "Operationalizing
   AI Use Cases" source via the authoring pipeline; regenerate rather than editing.
   ============================================================================ */

export const OPS_CATEGORIES = [{"id":"R","name":"AI for Research & Study","icon":"GraduationCap","blurb":"Learn faster, study smarter, and get through dense material — for students, researchers, and lifelong learners."},{"id":"W","name":"AI for Writing & Communication","icon":"PenLine","blurb":"Turn rough thoughts into polished, audience-ready writing — emails, updates, content, and cross-cultural messaging."},{"id":"B","name":"AI for Business & Strategy","icon":"Briefcase","blurb":"Pressure-test ideas and sharpen decisions — competitive analysis, strategy panels, and risk hunting."},{"id":"O","name":"AI for Workplace Operations","icon":"ClipboardList","blurb":"Tame the daily grind — meetings, inboxes, onboarding, briefings, and messy data turned into clean structure."},{"id":"T","name":"AI for Technical & Data Tasks","icon":"Terminal","blurb":"Do technical work without being technical — code explained, formulas written, gear troubleshot, manuals decoded."},{"id":"G","name":"AI for Governance, Risk & Compliance","icon":"ShieldCheck","blurb":"Handle sensitive, high-stakes work safely — compliance mapping, fact-checking, anonymization, and contract clarity."},{"id":"P","name":"Cloud AI Platforms","icon":"Cloud","blurb":"Get real work done on the big cloud AI platforms — Google Colab, Vertex AI Model Garden, and Microsoft Copilot Studio."}];
export const OPS_TUTORIALS = [{"id":"t1","num":1,"cat":"R","title":"The Deep Literature Synthesis Pipeline","tagline":"Turn dense academic papers into a clean, fact-checked table of methods, sample sizes, and limitations — entirely on your own computer, with nothing sent to the cloud.","audience":"Students writing literature reviews, graduate researchers screening dozens of papers, and policy analysts who must pull hard facts out of academic PDFs. It especially suits people handling unpublished manuscripts, embargoed data, or confidential drafts that legally or ethically cannot be uploaded to a public website.","why":"Academic papers bury the facts you actually need — the real sample size, what was measured, how data was gathered, and what the authors admit they got wrong — inside 8,000 words of dense prose. Reading twenty papers to build a literature review this way takes days, and it is easy to misremember which study had 40 subjects and which had 4,000. An AI can read one paper in seconds and lay those five facts out in a table, so you compare studies side by side instead of holding it all in your head. The catch is that AI can \"hallucinate\" — confidently invent a sample size that is not in the text — so this tutorial pairs extraction with a verification step. Reach for this whenever you are screening literature, and run it locally when the papers are unpublished, peer-review drafts, or otherwise not yours to share, because a local model reads the file without a single byte leaving your machine.","need":["A local AI chat app already set up and running (Ollama with Open WebUI, or LM Studio) with a model like Llama 3 or Gemma downloaded — or, for non-sensitive published papers, a free cloud account (Claude, Gemini, or Copilot)","The paper itself as selectable text — a PDF you can highlight and copy, or a .txt/.docx file (scanned image-only PDFs will not work until run through OCR)","A way to open the original paper alongside the AI so you can search it — a PDF reader or browser with Ctrl+F","About 10 focused minutes per paper the first time; two to three minutes once you have the rhythm","Basic comfort with copy and paste, and with searching text using Ctrl+F (Cmd+F on Mac)"],"steps":[{"title":"Decide cloud vs. local before you touch anything","detail":"If the paper is already published and public, a cloud tool is fine and easiest. If it is an unpublished manuscript, a draft you are peer-reviewing, grant-embargoed data, or anything you are not free to share, use a local model so the text never leaves your computer — this is the whole point of the local-first approach. Making this call first saves you from accidentally pasting confidential work into a public website. When in doubt, treat it as sensitive and go local."},{"title":"Get the paper into clean, copyable text","detail":"Open the PDF and try to highlight a paragraph. If the highlight works, you can copy the text; if nothing highlights, the PDF is a scanned image and the AI cannot read it until you run it through an OCR tool. Copy one section at a time — the Methods and Results sections hold almost everything you need — rather than dumping the entire 30-page file at once. Feeding smaller, relevant chunks makes the AI more accurate and avoids overwhelming a small local model's memory (its 'context window')."},{"title":"Set the rules with a strict system prompt","detail":"Before pasting the paper, give the AI the exact instructions in the Prompt section below. This is the most important step: it tells the model to extract only five specific facts, format them as a table, and — critically — write 'NOT STATED' instead of guessing when a fact is missing. That last rule is your main defense against hallucination, because a made-up sample size is far more dangerous than an honest blank. In Open WebUI or LM Studio you can paste this into the 'System Prompt' box so it applies to every paper in the session."},{"title":"Paste the paper text and run it","detail":"Immediately after the instructions, paste the section of the paper (or attach the file if your tool supports uploads). Send it and wait for the table. The AI will return five rows: core hypothesis, the variables, the exact sample size, the data-collection method, and the authors' stated limitations. If a row says 'NOT STATED,' that is a feature, not a failure — it means the fact genuinely was not in the text you pasted, so go find it in another section."},{"title":"Verify every row against the original — do not skip this","detail":"For each fact the AI gives you, open the original paper, press Ctrl+F (Cmd+F on Mac), and search for a distinctive word from that row — a number like '384' for the sample size, or a phrase like 'random assignment.' If you find it in the paper near where the AI said it appears, the row is trustworthy. If you search and cannot find it anywhere, the AI likely invented it — delete that row or mark it unverified. This two-minute check is what separates a reliable literature table from a pile of confident-sounding fiction."},{"title":"Repeat per paper and build your comparison table","detail":"Run the same prompt on each paper and paste the verified rows into one master spreadsheet or document, one paper per row-group. Because every paper is squeezed into the same five categories, you can now scan down a single column — say, sample size — and instantly see which studies were large and which were tiny. This side-by-side view is the real payoff: it turns a stack of unread PDFs into a structured evidence base you can actually reason about."}],"prompt":"You are an expert research auditor. Your job is to extract facts from an academic text with zero interpretation. Read only the text I provide below and analyze it.\n\nExtract the following five elements and format them into a clean Markdown table with two columns: \"Element\" and \"Finding\".\n\n1. Core Hypothesis or Research Question — what the study set out to test or answer.\n2. Variables — list the independent variable(s) (what the researchers changed or grouped by) and the dependent variable(s) (what they measured), clearly labeled.\n3. Exact Sample Size — the precise number of participants, observations, or data points (e.g., \"N = 384\"). Include subgroup sizes if stated.\n4. Data Collection Methodology — how the data was gathered (e.g., survey, randomized controlled trial, interviews, secondary dataset), including any instrument or timeframe named.\n5. Self-Identified Research Limitations — weaknesses the AUTHORS themselves acknowledge.\n\nStrict rules:\n- Do NOT summarize, interpret, or add anything outside these five categories.\n- Do NOT infer, extrapolate, or use outside knowledge. Use ONLY what is written in the text.\n- If an element is not present in the text, write exactly \"NOT STATED\" in that row. Never guess.\n- Where possible, keep the author's own wording so I can verify it by searching the original.\n\nHere is the text to analyze:\n[PASTE THE PAPER SECTION HERE — e.g., the Methods and Results sections]","promptNote":"Replace only the bracketed placeholder at the bottom with the actual text you copied from the paper; leave everything above it exactly as written, since those instructions are what force accuracy. Paste the Methods and Results sections first, as they contain four of the five facts. If you want facts from a specific section only, say so by editing the final line (e.g., \"Here is the Methods section:\").","cloud":{"bestTool":"Anthropic Claude, because it handles very long documents (you can paste or upload an entire paper into its large context window) and is notably disciplined about following the 'do not infer, write NOT STATED' rule instead of padding answers.","steps":["Go to claude.ai, sign in, and start a new chat.","Upload the paper as a PDF using the paperclip/attach button, or paste the Methods and Results text directly into the message.","Paste the full prompt from the Prompt section above the text (or before the attachment), then send.","Read the returned table, then open the original paper and Ctrl+F a few key facts (the sample size, a limitation phrase) to confirm they are real.","If any row looks thin, reply 'Recheck row 3 against the text and quote the exact sentence where the sample size appears' to make the AI show its source."]},"local":["Open your local chat app (Open WebUI for Ollama, or LM Studio) and select an installed model such as Llama 3 8B or Gemma.","Paste the full prompt into the 'System Prompt' field if your app has one, so the rules apply to every paper you process in this session; otherwise paste it at the top of your first message.","Copy the Methods and Results sections of the paper and paste them where the prompt says [PASTE THE PAPER SECTION HERE], then send.","Read the table, then switch to your PDF reader and Ctrl+F each fact against the original to catch any hallucination.","For the next paper, just paste its text again — the system prompt is already set — and repeat, keeping every paper's text on your machine the entire time."],"localNeedsSetup":true,"choose":"For published, publicly available papers, either option works and cloud tools like Claude are the fastest and most accurate — there is no privacy cost to sharing something already on the open internet. Go LOCAL whenever the paper is unpublished, a manuscript you are peer-reviewing under confidentiality, embargoed grant work, or a colleague's draft you were trusted with: uploading any of these to a public AI service can breach a confidentiality agreement or scoop the authors, and a local model reads the file with nothing ever leaving your computer. A local 8B model is a little slower and slightly less polished than a top cloud model, but for this narrow fact-extraction task it is more than capable — and the privacy guarantee is worth it. When you cannot tell whether a document is safe to share, default to local.","example":{"input":"You are an expert research auditor... [full prompt] ... Here is the text to analyze:\n\nWe examined whether a four-week mindfulness intervention reduces self-reported anxiety in undergraduates. Participants (N = 212; 118 women, 94 men) were randomly assigned to a mindfulness app group or a waitlist control. Anxiety was measured before and after using the GAD-7 scale. We acknowledge that reliance on self-report and the absence of a long-term follow-up limit the conclusions, and the single-university sample may not generalize.","output":"Element | Finding\nCore Hypothesis or Research Question | Whether a four-week mindfulness intervention reduces self-reported anxiety in undergraduates.\nVariables | Independent: group assignment (mindfulness app vs. waitlist control). Dependent: self-reported anxiety (GAD-7 score).\nExact Sample Size | N = 212 (118 women, 94 men).\nData Collection Methodology | Randomized assignment to two groups; anxiety measured pre- and post-intervention using the GAD-7 scale over four weeks.\nSelf-Identified Research Limitations | Reliance on self-report; no long-term follow-up; single-university sample may not generalize.","note":"Notice every row traces back to an exact phrase in the source — 'N = 212,' 'GAD-7,' 'single-university sample' — so you can Ctrl+F each one to confirm nothing was invented."},"tips":["Feed the Methods and Results sections first — they contain the sample size, variables, and methodology, which are the hardest facts to find by skimming.","When a row says 'NOT STATED,' paste a different section (like the Discussion) and ask again; the fact often lives elsewhere in the paper rather than being truly absent.","Ask the AI to 'quote the exact sentence' behind any suspicious row — this makes verification instant because you can copy that quote straight into Ctrl+F.","Keep one master spreadsheet with the five categories as columns and one paper per row, so your verified tables accumulate into a ready-made literature-review matrix.","For a small local model, split very long papers into two or three chunks; overloading its context window makes it drop details or hallucinate."],"mistakes":["Trusting the table without verifying — AI can fabricate a plausible sample size. Always Ctrl+F a few facts against the original before you cite anything.","Pasting a scanned image-PDF and getting garbage or nothing — if you cannot highlight the text, run the PDF through an OCR tool first so the words become selectable.","Dumping the entire 30-page paper into a small local model at once — it overflows the memory and starts inventing. Paste the relevant sections in chunks instead.","Uploading a confidential or unpublished manuscript to a public cloud tool — this can breach confidentiality. Match the tool to the sensitivity: local for anything not yours to share.","Deleting or ignoring 'NOT STATED' rows as errors — they are honest signals that the fact was missing from the text you provided, telling you exactly where to look next."],"related":["t2","t22","t23"]},{"id":"t2","num":2,"cat":"R","title":"Socratic Study Buddy Priming","tagline":"Turn any AI chatbot into a patient tutor that refuses to hand you the answer and instead asks one guiding question at a time until the concept clicks in your own head.","audience":"College and self-directed learners who want to genuinely understand a hard topic (tokenization, recursion, mitosis, supply-and-demand) rather than copy an answer. It is equally useful for anyone prepping for an exam, certification, or interview who learns best by being questioned, and for people who worry that using AI is \"cheating\" and want a study method that clearly is not.","why":"Left to its defaults, an AI chatbot is an answer-dispensing machine: ask \"what is tokenization?\" and it dumps three tidy paragraphs you will forget by tomorrow. Reading a correct answer feels like learning, but it usually is not — real understanding comes from struggling to retrieve and connect ideas yourself, what learning scientists call active recall and the generation effect. This tutorial flips the chatbot's default behavior with strict rules: never reveal the answer, ask one guiding question at a time, and adapt each question to what you just said. Reach for it whenever you have a study guide, homework concept, or dense reading you must actually own for a test or your job. A bonus: because the AI never states the answer outright, the understanding you walk away with is genuinely your own — no copying involved.","need":["A chatbot you can use: a free cloud account (Anthropic Claude, Google Gemini, or Microsoft Copilot) OR a local model already running on your machine (Ollama, LM Studio).","One specific concept you want to master, named precisely — 'tokenization,' not 'AI stuff.'","10–20 quiet minutes and a willingness to type real, thoughtful answers instead of one-word replies.","Optional but powerful: the exact homework question, study-guide item, or textbook paragraph you are working from, so the tutor stays on target.","A notepad (paper or a doc) to write the definition you build in your own words at the end."],"steps":[{"title":"Name the exact concept and the finish line","detail":"Before you open the chatbot, decide the one concept you want to master (e.g., 'tokenization' or 'how a for-loop works') and what 'done' looks like — usually being able to explain it in your own words without help. This matters because a vague target ('teach me AI') makes the tutor wander, while a sharp target lets it aim every question. Write the concept down; you will paste it into the prompt in the next step."},{"title":"Paste the tutor prompt and fill in the blanks","detail":"Copy the full prompt from the Prompt section below into a brand-new, empty chat. Replace [CONCEPT] with your topic and, if you have one, [YOUR COURSE OR LEVEL] with something like 'intro college AI course.' Sending this first, before anything else, is what 'locks in' the tutor persona — the rules only hold if they are the very first thing the model reads in the conversation."},{"title":"Wait for the tutor's first question — do not ask for the answer","detail":"After you send the prompt, the AI should reply with a short greeting and a single opening question, not a definition. If instead it dumps a paragraph explaining your concept, the lockdown failed — reply 'You broke the rules: ask me one guiding question and never state the answer,' and it will correct itself. From here on, your job is to answer its questions, not to interrogate it for facts."},{"title":"Answer honestly, in full sentences, and think out loud","detail":"Respond to each question with your genuine best guess, even when you are unsure — say 'I think it might be X because…' The tutor reads your reasoning and uses it to decide what to ask next, so a one-word answer starves it of information and a guess reveals exactly which link in your understanding is weak. Being wrong is useful here; it is how the tutor finds the gap to work on."},{"title":"When you get stuck, ask for a smaller hint — not the answer","detail":"If a question stumps you, do not type 'just tell me.' Instead say 'I'm stuck — can you break that into a simpler question?' or 'Give me a small hint, not the answer.' A good tutor prompt is built to refuse the full answer and instead lower the difficulty, which keeps you in the productive-struggle zone where actual learning happens. This back-and-forth is the whole point, not a failure."},{"title":"Prove you learned it: say it back in your own words","detail":"When the concept feels clear, type 'Let me try to explain it back to you' and give your own full definition or walkthrough. Ask the tutor to check your explanation for anything missing or wrong — it can point out gaps without ever having handed you the answer. Writing this final summary on your notepad cements the memory and gives you a study artifact to review before the exam."},{"title":"Run a quick self-audit on where you struggled","detail":"After the session, spend two minutes noticing which questions were hardest and where the tutor had to simplify most — those are your real weak spots. Ask the tutor 'Based on this session, what should I review next?' to turn the struggle into a study plan. This diagnostic reflection is what converts a single good session into steady, targeted mastery over time."}],"prompt":"You are an expert Socratic tutor for [CONCEPT], teaching a student in [YOUR COURSE OR LEVEL, e.g. an intro college AI course].\n\nYour goal is to guide me to discover and understand [CONCEPT] entirely on my own. You are a tutor, not an answer key.\n\nSTRICT RULES — follow all of them:\n1. NEVER give me the direct answer, the full definition, the finished code, or a paragraph-long explanation, under any circumstances.\n2. Ask me exactly ONE short, guiding question at a time, then stop and wait for my reply.\n3. Build each new question on what I just said. If my answer is partly right, acknowledge the correct part and probe the missing part. If it is wrong, do not correct me with the answer — ask a simpler question that helps me see the problem myself.\n4. If I say \"just tell me,\" \"give me the answer,\" or try to get you to skip ahead, politely refuse and instead ask an easier guiding question based on my last message.\n5. Keep your messages short: one or two sentences of framing at most, then your single question.\n6. Only when I explicitly say \"let me explain it back\" should you switch to checking my explanation — and even then, point out gaps with questions rather than stating the answer.\n\nStart now with a warm one-sentence greeting and your first guiding question about [CONCEPT]. Do not explain anything yet — just ask.","promptNote":"Replace [CONCEPT] with the exact thing you want to learn (e.g., \"tokenization\" or \"how recursion works\"). Replace [YOUR COURSE OR LEVEL] with your context so the tutor pitches questions at the right difficulty — omit it if you are unsure. The numbered rules are the important part; keeping all six is what stops the AI from reverting to answer-dumping.","cloud":{"bestTool":"Anthropic Claude, because it holds firmly to a multi-rule persona across a long back-and-forth without drifting back into answer-dumping, which is exactly what a strict no-answers tutor needs.","steps":["Go to claude.ai and open a brand-new chat (a fresh chat matters so no earlier messages weaken the tutor rules).","Paste the full tutor prompt from the Prompt section, filling in [CONCEPT] and your level, and send it.","Confirm the reply is a greeting plus a single question — not a definition; if it explains, reply 'Follow your rules: one guiding question, no answers.'","Answer each question in full sentences; when stuck, ask for 'a smaller hint, not the answer.'","When ready, type 'Let me explain it back to you,' give your own definition, and ask Claude to point out any gaps with questions."]},"local":["Open your local chat interface (Open WebUI for Ollama, or the chat tab in LM Studio) and start a new conversation with your already-installed model.","Paste the full tutor prompt from the Prompt section, fill in [CONCEPT] and your level, and send it. If your app has a 'System Prompt' box, paste the rules there instead — that makes them even harder for the model to ignore.","Check that the reply is a greeting plus one question. Smaller local models sometimes slip and give the answer; if so, reply 'One guiding question only, never the answer,' and it will usually recover.","Answer each question honestly; ask for 'a simpler question' whenever you are stuck instead of asking to be told.","When ready, say 'Let me explain it back,' give your own definition, and ask the model to quiz you on anything you missed."],"localNeedsSetup":true,"choose":"For ordinary schoolwork on general academic topics, the cloud tools are perfectly fine and the easiest place to start — there is nothing sensitive about studying tokenization or the French Revolution. Choose local instead when your study material is private or restricted: unpublished research, proprietary work training, a company's internal certification content, or anything under an NDA or academic-integrity rule that forbids sharing coursework with outside services. On a local model nothing you type ever leaves your computer, so you get the same Socratic coaching with zero data exposure. A practical middle path: use the cloud for the tutoring method and swap to local only when the specific text you paste is confidential.","example":{"input":"You are an expert Socratic tutor for tokenization, teaching a student in an intro college AI course. [full rules pasted] … Start now with a greeting and your first guiding question.\n\n(Student's first real reply:) I think computers just read text letter by letter, like we do?","output":"Tutor: Great starting point — let's test that idea. When you type the word \"unbelievable\" into an AI, do you think it would be more useful for the computer to handle it as 12 separate letters, or as a few meaningful chunks like \"un\", \"believe\", \"able\"? Why might chunks be handy?\n\nStudent: Chunks, maybe? Because \"un\" and \"able\" show up in lots of words.\n\nTutor: Exactly — you just spotted the key advantage. So if the computer breaks text into reusable chunks like that, what would you call each individual chunk, and roughly how many of them do you think a model needs to know?\n\nStudent: I'm stuck on the number. Just tell me.\n\nTutor: I won't hand you that one, but here's a smaller question: is it closer to a few hundred chunks, or tens of thousands? Think about how many word-pieces it would take to cover almost any English text.","note":"Notice the tutor never defines 'token' — it makes the student name the chunk and reason about the vocabulary size, and it refuses 'just tell me' with an easier question instead."},"tips":["Name the concept as narrowly as you can. 'Tokenization in large language models' produces sharper questions than 'AI text stuff,' because the tutor knows exactly what target to steer you toward.","Answer with your reasoning, not just a conclusion — 'I think X because Y' — since the tutor uses your 'because' to find and fix the exact gap in your understanding.","If you truly cannot answer, ask it to break the question down ('simpler question, please') rather than surrendering; this keeps you in the productive-struggle zone where learning actually sticks.","End every session by explaining the concept back in your own words and having the tutor check it — this 'teach it back' step is the single strongest way to lock in memory.","Paste the rules into a dedicated 'System Prompt' field if your tool has one (many local apps do); rules placed there are much harder for the model to forget mid-conversation."],"mistakes":["Asking 'just give me the answer.' It defeats the entire method — instead ask for a smaller hint or a simpler question so you still do the thinking.","Answering in one word ('yes,' 'chunks'). The tutor can't tell what you actually understand — reply in full sentences with your reasoning so it can adapt.","Adding the tutor rules halfway through an existing chat. Earlier messages dilute the persona — always start a fresh chat so the rules are the very first thing the model reads.","Giving up the moment a question is hard and switching to a plain 'explain tokenization' chat. That struggle is where learning happens; push through with hints instead of bailing to an answer dump.","Skipping the 'explain it back' step. Without it you never verify you truly learned it — always finish by stating the concept yourself and having the tutor find your gaps."],"related":["t1","t22","t23"]},{"id":"t22","num":22,"cat":"R","title":"The \"Reverse Outline\" Argumentative Logic Audit","tagline":"Turn your finished essay draft into a paragraph-by-paragraph X-ray that exposes every logical gap, off-topic tangent, and weak topic sentence before your professor does.","audience":"Students polishing a major term paper, essayists tightening a long piece, and policy or grant researchers who need every paragraph to earn its place. Anyone who has a complete first draft, suspects the argument wanders, but cannot see exactly where.","why":"A first draft always reads better in your own head than on the page, because you already know what you meant, so your brain quietly fills the gaps a reader will trip over. A \"reverse outline\" fixes this: instead of outlining before you write, you have the AI outline what you actually wrote — one sentence per paragraph — so you see the real skeleton of your argument stripped of pretty prose. When you lay those one-sentence summaries end to end, logical leaps (\"wait, how did we jump from cost to ethics?\"), repeated points, and paragraphs that quietly drifted from your thesis jump out immediately. Reach for this the moment you finish a draft and before you start line-editing sentences, because there is no sense polishing the wording of a paragraph you are about to cut or move. It is also the fastest way to find the \"so what?\" holes a grader or reviewer will circle in red.","need":["A completed first-draft essay in plain text you can copy (from Word, Google Docs, or a text file).","Your thesis statement identified — know which single sentence in your intro is the claim the whole paper defends.","One AI chat tool: a cloud assistant (Claude, Gemini, or Copilot) for convenience, or a local model via Ollama/LM Studio for privacy.","15 quiet minutes and a willingness to actually cut or move paragraphs, not just admire the report."],"steps":[{"title":"Get your draft into clean, copyable text","detail":"Open your essay and select the entire body — every paragraph from the introduction through the conclusion. If it lives in Word or Google Docs, copying the text is fine; you do not need fancy formatting, because the audit is about ideas, not fonts. The goal is one continuous block of text with the paragraph breaks intact, since the AI uses those breaks to know where one paragraph ends and the next begins."},{"title":"Identify and mark your thesis so the AI has a yardstick","detail":"Find the one sentence in your introduction that states the argument your whole paper is trying to prove — that is your thesis. Paste it into the prompt where the template asks for it, word for word. This matters enormously: the AI can only tell you a paragraph 'strays from the thesis' if it knows exactly what the thesis is, so a vague or missing thesis produces a vague, useless audit."},{"title":"Paste the draft and run the reverse-outline prompt","detail":"Copy the full prompt from the Prompt section below, fill in the two bracketed placeholders (your thesis and your draft), and send it. The prompt explicitly forbids the AI from rewriting your words — you want a diagnosis, not surgery, on this pass. Give it a moment; a long essay may take fifteen to thirty seconds to produce the full outline."},{"title":"Read the reverse outline as if it were the whole paper","detail":"Ignore your original prose for a minute and read only the AI's one-sentence summaries, top to bottom, in order. If those sentences flow as a logical chain — each one leading naturally to the next and back to the thesis — your structure is sound. Where you hit a jolt ('these two sentences don't connect') or a repeat ('didn't it already say this?'), you have found a real structural problem that was hidden by your polished wording."},{"title":"Work through the Logic Alerts one at a time","detail":"The AI flags paragraphs that make more than one competing point, or that do not clearly support your thesis. For each alert, decide on one of three fixes: cut the paragraph if it adds nothing, split it if it is trying to do two jobs at once, or add a bridging sentence if the point is good but the connection to your thesis is only in your head. Do not accept every flag blindly — you are the author, and sometimes a 'tangent' is a deliberate concession or counterargument the AI did not recognize."},{"title":"Re-run the audit on the revised draft to confirm the fix","detail":"After you rearrange, cut, or add bridges, paste the new version back in and run the same prompt again. A clean second pass — where the summaries now form an unbroken chain and the Logic Alerts have disappeared — is your proof that the structure actually holds, not just that you moved words around. This second pass takes two minutes and catches new gaps you accidentally opened while fixing the old ones."}],"prompt":"You are a rigorous writing tutor performing a STRUCTURAL audit of my draft essay. Do NOT change, rewrite, paraphrase, or correct any of my words, grammar, or style. Your only job is to X-ray the logic of my argument.\n\nMY THESIS STATEMENT (the single claim my whole paper must support):\n\"[PASTE YOUR THESIS SENTENCE HERE]\"\n\nMY FULL DRAFT (paragraphs separated by blank lines):\n\"\"\"\n[PASTE YOUR ENTIRE DRAFT HERE]\n\"\"\"\n\nDo the following, in this exact order:\n\n1. REVERSE OUTLINE. Number every paragraph in order. For each one, write a single plain sentence that states the exact claim or point that paragraph actually makes — not what I might have intended, but what the words on the page say. Format each as:\n   P1 — [one-sentence summary]\n   P2 — [one-sentence summary]\n   ...\n\n2. LOGIC ALERTS. After the outline, list a bulleted \"Logic Alert\" for any paragraph that has a problem. Flag a paragraph if ANY of these are true, and name which one:\n   - OFF-THESIS: its point does not clearly and directly support the thesis above.\n   - DOUBLE-DUTY: it makes two or more competing points that belong in separate paragraphs.\n   - LEAP: there is no logical bridge connecting it to the paragraph before it.\n   - WEAK TOPIC SENTENCE: its first sentence does not announce the paragraph's point.\n   - REDUNDANT: it repeats a point already made in an earlier paragraph (name which).\n   For each alert write: \"P#: [problem type] — [one sentence explaining what's wrong] — [one concrete suggestion: cut / split / move after P# / add a bridge to the thesis].\"\n\n3. FLOW CHECK. In two or three sentences, tell me whether the reverse outline reads as one connected chain of reasoning from thesis to conclusion, and name the single weakest link.\n\nBe direct and specific. Do not soften problems and do not compliment me. If a paragraph is fine, do not mention it in the alerts.","promptNote":"Fill the two placeholders in square brackets: [PASTE YOUR THESIS SENTENCE HERE] is the exact claim sentence from your intro, and [PASTE YOUR ENTIRE DRAFT HERE] is the full body text with blank lines between paragraphs. Keep the triple quotes so the AI knows where your draft begins and ends. If your paper has section headings (common in policy papers), leave them in — the AI will note them too.","cloud":{"bestTool":"Anthropic Claude, because its very large context window comfortably swallows a full 10–20 page draft in one paste and it is unusually good at following the strict 'diagnose, do not rewrite' instruction instead of helpfully editing your prose.","steps":["Go to claude.ai and start a new chat (Gemini at gemini.google.com works equally well, and is the better pick if your draft already lives in Google Docs).","Paste the full prompt from the Prompt section, then fill in your thesis and drop your entire draft between the triple quotes.","Send it and read the reverse outline first, top to bottom, before looking at any single paragraph of your original.","Reply in the same chat with follow-ups like 'Rewrite only the topic sentence of P4 so it announces its point' or 'Show me how to bridge P6 back to the thesis' — now that it understands your paper, it can help surgically.","After you revise, paste the new draft back and run the prompt again to verify the structure holds."]},"local":["Open your local chat UI (Open WebUI if you run Ollama, or the chat tab in LM Studio) and select an instruction-tuned model — an 8B model like Llama 3.1 8B or Qwen 2.5 7B handles this well; bigger is better for long drafts.","If your essay is long, raise the model's context length (in Ollama, set the 'context length' / num_ctx to 8192 or higher) so the whole draft fits, or the model will silently forget your earlier paragraphs.","Paste the same prompt from the Prompt section, insert your thesis and full draft, and send it.","Because a small local model can drift, keep it honest: if it starts rewriting your text instead of outlining, reply 'You changed my words. Summarize only — one sentence per paragraph, no rewriting,' and it will correct course.","For very long papers that overflow the context window, feed the draft in two halves (paragraphs 1–N, then the rest) with the same thesis each time, and stitch the two outlines together yourself."],"localNeedsSetup":true,"choose":"For a class essay or a public op-ed, the content is not secret, so a cloud tool is the easiest path and Claude or Gemini will give the sharpest audit with zero setup. Lean LOCAL when the draft itself is confidential: an unpublished thesis or dissertation chapter you do not want ingested into a vendor's systems, an internal policy paper, grant language tied to proprietary research, or anything under an NDA or embargo. On a local model via Ollama or LM Studio the entire draft stays on your machine and nothing is uploaded, which is the safe default whenever the words on the page are not yet public and their leakage would actually cost you.","example":{"input":"MY THESIS: \"Universal free public transit would cut urban carbon emissions more effectively than electric-vehicle subsidies.\"\n\nMY DRAFT (excerpt, 5 paragraphs):\nP1 Intro ending in the thesis above. P2 Cars are the largest source of city emissions and EV subsidies mostly reward wealthy buyers. P3 Cities with free transit, like Tallinn, saw ridership rise and car trips fall. P4 Also, free transit helps low-income residents afford to reach jobs, reducing inequality. P5 Therefore free transit beats EV subsidies on emissions.","output":"REVERSE OUTLINE\nP1 — Introduces the debate and states the thesis that free transit beats EV subsidies at cutting urban emissions.\nP2 — Argues EV subsidies are poorly targeted because cars are the top emitter and subsidies favor the wealthy.\nP3 — Uses Tallinn as evidence that free transit raises ridership and reduces car trips.\nP4 — Claims free transit reduces income inequality by improving job access.\nP5 — Concludes that free transit is the superior emissions policy.\n\nLOGIC ALERTS\n- P4: OFF-THESIS — the inequality/job-access point is about fairness, not carbon emissions, so it does not support a thesis specifically about emissions. Suggestion: cut it, or add a bridge showing that higher ridership from broader access is what lowers emissions.\n- P2: DOUBLE-DUTY — mixes 'cars are the top emitter' (a fact supporting transit) with 'subsidies favor the wealthy' (a fairness critique); split into two paragraphs or drop the second point to stay on emissions.\n\nFLOW CHECK\nThe chain P1 → P2 → P3 → P5 reads as connected reasoning, but P4 breaks the arc by switching from emissions to inequality. The single weakest link is P4 — it is the paragraph a grader will circle as off-topic.","note":"Notice the AI caught that P4 is well-written but argues the wrong point — a flaw invisible when you read the polished prose alone."},"tips":["Run this BEFORE you line-edit. Fixing commas in a paragraph you are about to delete is wasted effort — get the skeleton right first, then polish sentences.","Read the one-sentence summaries out loud in order. If saying them aloud makes you go 'huh?' between two lines, that gap is a real logical leap your reader will feel too.","Trust the outline over the alerts. Even when the AI's Logic Alerts miss something, the plain reverse outline itself often reveals a repeated or missing point the moment you see your argument compressed.","Push back in the chat. If the AI flags your deliberate counterargument as 'off-thesis,' tell it 'P5 is an intentional concession before I rebut it in P6' — a good tool will re-evaluate and often agree.","Keep the thesis and draft in the SAME message. The audit is only as good as the thesis you give it, so never make the AI guess your argument from the body alone."],"mistakes":["Letting the AI rewrite your prose. If it starts 'improving' your sentences, you lose your voice and the diagnosis. Fix: the prompt already forbids this — if it slips, reply 'Summarize only, do not rewrite.'","Pasting the draft without a thesis. With no yardstick, 'strays from the thesis' becomes meaningless and every alert is a guess. Fix: always paste your exact thesis sentence in the marked slot.","Accepting every Logic Alert as gospel. The AI sometimes flags a deliberate counterargument or concession as a tangent. Fix: you are the author — judge each flag, and cut only what truly doesn't serve the argument.","Fixing the report instead of the essay. Reading the audit and nodding does nothing; the value is in cutting, splitting, and moving paragraphs. Fix: for every alert, make an actual edit before moving on.","Skipping the second pass. Revisions often open new gaps where you stitched paragraphs together. Fix: re-run the exact same prompt on your revised draft to confirm the chain is now unbroken."],"related":["t1","t2","t23"]},{"id":"t23","num":23,"cat":"R","title":"Raw Text to Flashcard Anki Export Matrix","tagline":"Turn a dense textbook chapter into a clean deck of ready-to-study flashcards in minutes, without typing a single card by hand.","audience":"Students grinding through memorization-heavy subjects like anatomy, history, pharmacology, or law, and working professionals cramming for a certification exam. Anyone who has ever stared at a wall of reading and thought \"I need to turn this into flashcards but I don't have three hours to type them out.\"","why":"Flashcards work because of two proven learning ideas: active recall (forcing your brain to pull an answer from memory) and spaced repetition (reviewing on a schedule). Both beat plain re-reading by a wide margin. The catch is that building good cards by hand is slow and dull, and that tedium is the number one reason people never actually make them. An AI can read a chapter and instantly split it into clean question-and-answer pairs, so you skip the grunt work and go straight to studying. Reach for this whenever you have raw reading you must memorize — a textbook section, lecture notes, a scanned study guide — and you want it turned into a deck fast.","need":["A focused chunk of study text you can copy and paste (one chapter, module, or section — not a whole book at once)","An AI chat tool: a cloud assistant (Claude, Gemini, or Copilot) or a local model in a chat app (Ollama with Open WebUI, or LM Studio)","A flashcard app to study in afterward — Anki is the standard free choice; Quizlet also works","About 10 minutes to run the prompt, skim the cards for errors, and import them"],"steps":[{"title":"Pick your source text and grab a clean copy","detail":"Find the section you want to memorize and copy the actual words from a PDF, Word doc, lecture notes, or a website. Aim for a focused chunk (one chapter or module, roughly 500 to 3,000 words) rather than an entire book at once, because smaller batches produce sharper cards and let you spot mistakes easily. If you copy from a PDF, quickly delete obvious junk like page numbers or headers stuck mid-sentence, since the AI will faithfully make cards out of whatever mess you feed it."},{"title":"Open your AI tool and paste the prompt plus your text","detail":"Open your chosen assistant (see the cloud and local sections below to pick one). Copy the full prompt from the Prompt section, paste it into the message box, then paste your study text where the prompt says [PASTE YOUR STUDY MATERIAL HERE]. Keeping the instructions and the text together in one message tells the AI exactly what to do and what to do it to, which is the single biggest factor in getting a clean result the first time."},{"title":"Run it and read the cards critically","detail":"Send the message and let the AI produce the table. Now actually read the output — do not trust it blindly. Check that each answer is factually correct against your source and that questions target one fact each. AI can occasionally invent or blur a detail (this is called a hallucination), and a wrong flashcard is worse than no flashcard because you will memorize the mistake."},{"title":"Ask for fixes or more cards in plain English","detail":"If the cards are too vague, too easy, or missing topics, just tell the AI in a follow-up: for example, \"Make the questions harder,\" \"Add cards for the drug side effects you skipped,\" or \"Split card 4 into two separate facts.\" You do not need to re-paste the text; the AI remembers it. Iterating like this is normal and expected — the first pass is a draft, not the final deck."},{"title":"Copy the finished table out of the chat","detail":"When the cards look good, select the whole table and copy it. Keep the format the prompt asked for: each line is one card, with the question and answer separated by a Tab (or by a clear symbol like a pipe |). This exact structure is what lets a flashcard app read the file automatically instead of you retyping every card, so do not reformat it by hand."},{"title":"Import the cards into your flashcard app","detail":"In Anki, create or open a deck, choose File then Import, and pick your text file (Anki reads Tab-separated Question/Answer pairs out of the box); confirm the first column maps to Front and the second to Back. In Quizlet, use the Import option and tell it the term/definition separator is a Tab and each card is on a new line. Do a quick spot-check that the fronts and backs landed on the correct sides before you start studying."},{"title":"Study with active recall and repeat for the next chapter","detail":"Run through the deck, answering out loud or in your head before flipping each card — that retrieval effort is what actually builds memory. Mark the cards you miss so the app resurfaces them more often. Once a chapter is in your deck, repeat the whole process for the next section; after a few rounds it takes only a couple of minutes per chapter."}],"prompt":"You are an expert study-materials creator. Read the study material below and turn it into high-yield flashcards for active recall.\n\nRules:\n- Focus on the core definitions, mechanisms, causes/effects, classifications, and diagnostic or decision criteria in the text. Skip filler, examples, and anything not worth memorizing.\n- Each card must test exactly ONE specific fact. No compound or open-ended questions.\n- The Front is a clear, specific question (not \"Discuss X\" but \"What is X?\" / \"Which structure does Y?\" / \"What is the first-line treatment for Z?\").\n- The Back is a concise, direct answer — ideally under 20 words. No fluff.\n- Do not invent facts. If something is not stated in the text, do not create a card about it.\n- Produce roughly [NUMBER, e.g. 15-25] cards, ordered to match the flow of the material.\n\nOutput format — a plain-text table with ONE card per line, the question and answer separated by a single Tab character, and nothing else (no numbering, no headers, no extra commentary), like this:\nFront question<TAB>Back answer\nFront question<TAB>Back answer\n\nDifficulty/level: [e.g. undergraduate anatomy / bar exam / CompTIA Security+ cert].\n\nSTUDY MATERIAL:\n[PASTE YOUR STUDY MATERIAL HERE]","promptNote":"Replace [NUMBER] with how many cards you want (15-25 is a good range per chapter), set [difficulty/level] to your exam or course so the AI pitches questions correctly, and paste your text where marked. If your app needs a different separator than Tab, change \"a single Tab character\" to \"a pipe symbol |\" — but Tab is what Anki and Quizlet expect by default.","cloud":{"bestTool":"Anthropic Claude, because it handles very long pasted readings reliably and is especially good at following strict formatting rules like a Tab-separated one-card-per-line table.","steps":["Go to claude.ai and start a new chat (sign in with a free account).","Paste the full prompt from the Prompt section, then paste your chapter where it says [PASTE YOUR STUDY MATERIAL HERE].","Send it, then read the returned table and verify a few answers against your source text.","If needed, reply with plain-English fixes like 'make these harder' or 'add cards for the section on X', then copy the final table.","Optional: for a very long chapter, upload the file directly instead of pasting, and add 'Use the attached file as the study material.'"]},"local":["Open your local chat app (Open WebUI if you run Ollama, or LM Studio) and select an installed model — a mid-size instruct model works well for this.","Paste the full prompt from the Prompt section, then paste your study text where it says [PASTE YOUR STUDY MATERIAL HERE], and send it.","If a smaller local model produces a messy or non-table result, feed it a shorter chunk (500-1,000 words) and add 'Return ONLY the table, nothing else.'","Read the cards for accuracy, ask for fixes in a follow-up message the same way you would with a cloud tool, then copy the final table into a .txt file for import."],"localNeedsSetup":true,"choose":"For most textbook and general-knowledge studying (anatomy, history, biology, standard certification material), the content is not sensitive, so a cloud tool is the easiest and fastest choice and Claude or Gemini will handle long chapters comfortably. Go local instead when your study material is confidential or contains private information — for example law students working from privileged case files or client notes, medical trainees using real patient charts, or professionals studying from a proprietary internal training manual or NDA-covered documents. In those cases run a local model so the text never leaves your computer, which keeps you clear of confidentiality, HIPAA, or NDA problems. Rule of thumb: if you would hesitate to email the document to a stranger, keep it local.","example":{"input":"[Prompt above, with level set to 'undergraduate anatomy', followed by:] The heart has four chambers: two atria on top and two ventricles on the bottom. Deoxygenated blood returns from the body via the superior and inferior vena cavae into the right atrium, passes through the tricuspid valve into the right ventricle, and is pumped through the pulmonary valve to the lungs. Oxygenated blood returns from the lungs via the pulmonary veins into the left atrium, passes through the mitral (bicuspid) valve into the left ventricle, and is pumped through the aortic valve into the aorta to the body. The left ventricle has the thickest wall because it must pump blood to the entire body.","output":"How many chambers does the human heart have?\t4 (two atria, two ventricles)\nWhich valve separates the right atrium from the right ventricle?\tThe tricuspid valve\nWhich vessels return deoxygenated blood to the right atrium?\tThe superior and inferior vena cavae\nThrough which valve does the right ventricle pump blood to the lungs?\tThe pulmonary valve\nWhich valve separates the left atrium from the left ventricle?\tThe mitral (bicuspid) valve\nInto which large artery does the left ventricle pump blood?\tThe aorta, via the aortic valve\nWhy is the left ventricle's wall the thickest?\tIt must pump blood to the entire body","note":"Notice each question targets exactly one fact and each answer is short — that is what makes the deck fast to drill and easy to import (the invisible Tab between question and answer is what Anki reads)."},"tips":["Tell the AI your exam or level in the prompt (e.g. 'bar exam' or 'CompTIA Security+'); it dramatically changes how hard and how specific the questions are.","Work one chapter at a time. Smaller batches give sharper cards, are easy to fact-check, and keep local models from choking on too much text.","For subjects with lists or comparisons, add 'Create separate cards for each item and use cloze-style fill-in-the-blank cards where helpful' to get better coverage.","Keep the Tab separator the AI produces intact — do not clean it up in Word, which can silently swap Tabs for spaces and break the import.","Save each raw output as a plain .txt file. You then have a reusable import file and a record of the source, which helps if you spot an error later."],"mistakes":["Trusting the cards blindly. AI can occasionally state a fact wrong (a hallucination), and a wrong flashcard trains the wrong answer — always spot-check against your source before studying.","Pasting an entire book at once. The AI skims and produces shallow, generic cards; feed it one focused section at a time instead.","Letting questions stay vague. If you see 'Explain the cardiac cycle', reply 'break vague questions into single-fact cards' so each card tests one thing.","Reformatting the table in Word or Google Docs before importing. That often converts Tabs to spaces and the flashcard app then can't split fronts from backs — copy straight from the chat into a plain .txt file.","Skipping the level/difficulty setting. Without it the AI guesses, often producing cards that are too easy for a real exam; always tell it who the cards are for."],"related":["t1","t2","t22"]},{"id":"t24","num":24,"cat":"R","title":"Competitive Interview Simulation and Blindside Triage","tagline":"Turn any AI chatbot into a tough, realistic hiring manager who grills you one question at a time on a specific job, then coaches every answer so you walk into the real interview rehearsed instead of rattled.","audience":"Job-seeking students, professionals switching careers, and internal candidates going for a promotion who have a real job description in hand and want to practice out loud before the real thing.","why":"Most people prepare for interviews by silently re-reading their resume and hoping the right words come out under pressure. That does not work, because interviewing is a performance skill that only improves with live reps and honest feedback, and a friend rehearsing you is usually too polite to push. An AI can play an assertive hiring director who asks one pointed behavioral question at a time based on a real job description, waits for your answer, then grades it and tells you what an interviewer would quietly infer from your wording. That last part is the real payoff: it surfaces the vague claims, missing numbers, and rambling setups you cannot hear yourself making. Reach for this the week before an interview, or any time a job posting intimidates you and you want low-stakes practice against that exact role.","need":["The full text of a specific job description you are targeting (copy it straight from the posting)","A current copy of your resume as text (copy from your Word or PDF file, or paste the plain text)","An AI chat tool: a free cloud one (Anthropic Claude, Google Gemini, or Microsoft Copilot), or a local model if your resume feels too personal to upload","30 to 45 uninterrupted minutes and a willingness to answer for real, out loud or typed, not skim","Optional: a short list of 3 to 5 accomplishments or projects you are proud of, to jog your memory mid-drill"],"steps":[{"title":"Gather your two inputs as plain text","detail":"The whole simulation runs on two documents: the target job description and your resume. Open the job posting, select the full description, and copy it. Do the same with your resume: if it is a PDF or Word file, open it, select all, and copy the text (the AI reads the words, not the fancy formatting). Having both ready as plain text before you start means you can paste them in one clean block instead of fumbling mid-session."},{"title":"Open your AI tool and paste the setup prompt with both documents","detail":"Open your chosen AI chat (see the cloud and local sections below for which to pick). Copy the big prompt from the Prompt section of this tutorial, then replace the two bracketed placeholders by pasting your job description where it says [PASTE THE FULL JOB DESCRIPTION HERE] and your resume where it says [PASTE YOUR RESUME TEXT HERE]. Send it as a single message. This one message tells the AI exactly who to be, what to read, and how to behave, which is why the setup is worth doing carefully."},{"title":"Answer the first question as if it were the real interview","detail":"The AI will ask ONE tough behavioral question and then stop and wait for you. Resist the urge to look up a perfect answer; respond the way you actually would in the room, in a few sentences. If you can, say your answer out loud first and then type the gist, because speaking exposes filler words and rambling that typing hides. The point is to practice under mild pressure, so a messy honest first attempt is far more useful than a polished paragraph you edited for five minutes."},{"title":"Read the Coach Assessment carefully, especially the 'secret inference'","detail":"After each answer the AI gives you a short Coach Assessment: a score out of 10, what worked, and what an interviewer might quietly infer from your wording. That inference line is the gold. It catches things like 'you said we a lot, so I cannot tell what YOU personally did,' or 'no numbers, so the impact sounds guessed.' Do not argue with it or get discouraged by a low score; treat every note as a specific, fixable instruction for your next attempt."},{"title":"Redo the same answer once using the feedback, then move on","detail":"Before you take the next question, ask the AI 'Let me try that one again' and deliver an improved version that fixes what the coach flagged. This rewrite loop is where the learning sticks, because you are not just hearing advice, you are immediately performing the better version. A good target is the STAR shape most interviewers expect: briefly set the Situation and Task, spend most of your words on the Action YOU took, and always end with a concrete Result. Then let the AI ask the next question."},{"title":"Run 4 to 5 full rounds, then ask for a wrap-up debrief","detail":"Do at least four or five question-answer-coach cycles so the pressure starts to feel normal. When you are done, type: 'Give me a final debrief: my three biggest recurring weaknesses across all my answers, my two strongest stories, and the three questions I should rehearse most before the real interview.' This turns a pile of individual notes into a focused study list. Save that debrief and re-run the whole drill a day or two before the interview to measure how much you have tightened up."}],"prompt":"You are an assertive but fair corporate hiring director interviewing me for the specific role described below. Your job is to pressure-test me the way a real, skeptical interviewer would.\n\nFIRST, silently read the job description and my resume. Identify the gaps, weak spots, and unproven claims in my background relative to what this role demands.\n\nTHE JOB DESCRIPTION:\n[PASTE THE FULL JOB DESCRIPTION HERE]\n\nMY RESUME:\n[PASTE YOUR RESUME TEXT HERE]\n\nHOW TO RUN THIS INTERVIEW:\n1. Ask me ONE tough, realistic behavioral interview question at a time, targeted to this role and to my specific gaps. Do NOT give me a list of questions. Ask one, then STOP and wait for my answer.\n2. After I answer, give a short \"Coach Assessment\" with exactly these three parts:\n   - Score: X/10\n   - What worked / what was weak (2-3 bullet points)\n   - Secret inference: what an interviewer might quietly conclude about me based on my wording, tone, or what I left out\n3. Then ask if I want to retry that answer or move on. If I retry, re-score it. Then ask your NEXT question.\n4. Escalate difficulty as we go: start with a warm-up, then push into conflict, failure, ambiguity, and the areas where my resume is thin.\n5. Stay in character as the hiring director. Be direct and probing, but never insulting.\n\nBegin now with your first question. Ask only one question and wait.\n\n[Optional add-ons you can paste at the end: \"The role level is [ENTRY / MID / SENIOR / MANAGER].\" — \"Focus your questions on [e.g. leadership, technical trade-offs, stakeholder conflict].\" — \"Ask your questions in a [phone screen / panel / final-round] style.\"]","promptNote":"Replace [PASTE THE FULL JOB DESCRIPTION HERE] with the real posting text and [PASTE YOUR RESUME TEXT HERE] with your resume text. The optional add-ons at the bottom let you set your seniority, steer the question topics, or match the interview stage; delete any you do not need.","cloud":{"bestTool":"Anthropic Claude, because this task hinges on a long, nuanced read of two documents plus staying consistently in a demanding persona across many turns, which is where Claude's large context window and steady role-play shine (Gemini is a fine substitute, especially if your resume already lives in Google Docs).","steps":["Go to claude.ai and sign in (a free account is enough to start).","Copy the full prompt from this tutorial, paste your job description and resume into the two bracketed spots, and send it as one message.","Answer each question in the chat box; after every Coach Assessment, either type 'let me retry' or 'next question' to keep the drill moving.","Do 4 to 5 rounds, then paste the final-debrief request from Step 6 to get your recurring weaknesses and a rehearsal list.","If answers feel too easy or too generic, tell it so ('make these harder' or 'push me on the leadership gap'), and it will recalibrate."]},"local":["Open your local chat interface (for example Open WebUI connected to Ollama, or LM Studio) and select a capable instruct model you already have, such as a Llama 3 or Qwen chat model.","Start a new chat and paste the full interview prompt, dropping your real job description and resume into the two bracketed placeholders.","Answer each question in the box; after each Coach Assessment, type 'retry' or 'next' just as you would with a cloud tool.","If a smaller local model forgets the rules or asks several questions at once, gently re-anchor it: 'Remember: ask only ONE question, wait for me, then give the Coach Assessment.'","Run your 4 to 5 rounds and request the final debrief; nothing you typed, including your resume, ever leaves your computer."],"localNeedsSetup":true,"choose":"Your resume and work history are personal data: home address, employment gaps, sometimes the fact that you are quietly job-hunting while employed. If that privacy matters to you, or your current employer's confidential projects would show up in your answers, run this locally so nothing leaves your device. For most students and job seekers using a general resume with no confidential details, a cloud tool like Claude or Gemini is perfectly fine and by far the easiest path, and you can always delete the chat afterward. When unsure, strip your street address and phone number from the pasted resume, and lean local.","example":{"input":"[Prompt pasted, then:] JOB DESCRIPTION: Customer Success Manager, SaaS. Owns a book of 40+ mid-market accounts, drives renewals and expansion, de-escalates at-risk customers, partners with Sales and Product. MY RESUME: 3 years as a Support Team Lead; handled escalations, trained 6 new reps, improved CSAT from 82% to 91%. No formal quota or renewal-ownership experience.\n\n[After the AI's first question 'Tell me about a time you turned around an unhappy customer who was ready to walk,' I answer:] \"We had a client who was really frustrated with our product and we worked hard and eventually they were happy again and stayed with us.\"","output":"Coach Assessment\n\nScore: 3/10\n\nWhat worked / what was weak:\n - You picked a relevant, on-topic story (customer save) — good instinct.\n - It is almost all summary. There is no specific situation, no action that was clearly YOURS, and no number proving the save.\n - 'We' three times, 'you' zero times — I cannot tell what you personally did.\n\nSecret inference: An interviewer would suspect you were near the save, not driving it. For a role that OWNS at-risk accounts, that vagueness reads as 'has not personally carried a retention outcome.'\n\nWant to retry this one, or move on?\n\n[I retry:] \"A mid-market client, about 15K a year, opened a cancellation ticket after two failed integrations. I owned it end to end: I got on a call within an hour, mapped their three blockers, pulled in an engineer for the integration fix, and set a weekly check-in for a month. They renewed, and expanded to a second team the next quarter.\"\n\nCoach Assessment\n\nScore: 8/10\n\nWhat worked / what was weak:\n - Clear Situation, a dollar figure, and specific actions in first person — much stronger.\n - Real Result (renewed + expanded). This now sounds like YOUR win.\n - Could still name the retention/expansion metric and one sentence on what you learned.\n\nSecret inference: Now reads as someone who can own an at-risk account, which is exactly the gap your resume had. Next question...","note":"Notice the same story jumps from 3 to 8 out of 10 with zero new facts — just specifics, first-person ownership, and a number. That is the whole skill this drill builds."},"tips":["Answer out loud before you type. Hearing yourself is what exposes rambling and filler; the typed version can hide it.","Reuse the same story bank the pros use: have 6 to 8 flexible stories ready (a conflict, a failure, a leadership moment, an ambiguous call, a measurable win) and ask the AI which of your stories best fits each question.","Always close with a Result and a number. 'CSAT rose from 82 to 91 percent' beats 'customers were happier' every time, and the AI will keep docking you until you do it.","When a question is too easy, say 'push harder' or 'ask the follow-up an interviewer would ask' — the real value is in the uncomfortable follow-ups where weak examples fall apart.","Re-run the whole drill a day or two before the real interview and compare scores; watching your average climb is a genuine confidence boost that shows up in the room."],"mistakes":["Asking the AI for a LIST of questions and answers to memorize. That produces stiff, scripted-sounding answers; keep it to one live question at a time so you practice thinking on your feet.","Writing polished paragraphs you edited for five minutes. That is not what happens in the room. Give your honest first-attempt answer so the coaching targets your real weak spots.","Skipping the retry. Reading feedback is not the same as fixing it; immediately redoing the answer the better way is what makes the improvement stick.","Using a generic job description. The magic is specificity, so paste the exact posting; a vague or wrong role gives you vague, off-target questions.","Treating a low score as a verdict on you. It is a note on one answer's wording. Fix the note, re-answer, and watch the score jump, exactly like the 3-to-8 example above."],"related":["t1","t2","t22"]},{"id":"t27","num":27,"cat":"R","title":"Syllabi and Course Calendar Master Roadmap Assembler","tagline":"Turn four or five messy course syllabi into one clean, week-by-week master schedule so no deadline ever ambushes you again.","audience":"University and community-college students carrying a full load of concurrent classes, each with its own separate syllabus PDF or web page. Also useful for anyone juggling several deadline-heavy documents at once, such as a parent tracking multiple kids' school calendars or a professional coordinating overlapping project timelines.","why":"Every professor writes their syllabus in a different format, and none of them know or care what your other four classes are doing. That means your real workload for any given week is scattered across five separate documents and stays effectively invisible until it is too late to plan around it. AI is genuinely good at this specific job: it can read all five schedules at once, pull out every date and deadline, and merge them into one timeline sorted by calendar week. The payoff is that you can spot \"bottleneck weeks\" (say, two exams and a project all landing in the same seven days) weeks ahead of time and start studying early instead of pulling an all-nighter. Reach for this at the very start of a semester, right after you download your syllabi, and again anytime a professor revises their schedule.","need":["A free AI chat tool (Anthropic Claude, Google Gemini, or Microsoft Copilot) OR a local model running in a chat app like LM Studio or Open WebUI.","Your syllabi as PDF/Word files you can upload, or as text you can copy and paste. The weekly schedule / course calendar section of each is the part that matters most.","The exact name of each class, so the merged timeline is readable (e.g. 'BIO 101' instead of 'the biology one').","The semester start date (or the date of Week 1), in case a syllabus lists 'Week 1, Week 2' instead of real calendar dates. This lets the AI turn week numbers into actual due dates.","Ten quiet minutes and a place to save the result: a Google Doc, a Notion page, or your phone's notes app."],"steps":[{"title":"Collect every syllabus in one place","detail":"Download or open all of your course syllabi for the semester before you touch the AI. You only really need the section that lists the weekly schedule, due dates, exams, and readings, so if a syllabus is 15 pages of policies, just find the calendar/schedule part. Having them side by side means you can feed the AI everything in one pass instead of doing five separate conversations, which is what makes the merged timeline possible."},{"title":"Get each schedule into the AI (upload or paste)","detail":"The easiest path is to upload the actual PDF or Word files if your tool allows it (Claude and Gemini both do). If you would rather paste text, open each syllabus, copy the schedule section, and paste it into the chat one after another. Critically, label each block before you paste it, for example type 'CLASS: BIO 101' on its own line, then paste that syllabus, then 'CLASS: ENG 210' and its syllabus. Without labels the AI cannot tell which deadline belongs to which class."},{"title":"Run the master-timeline prompt","detail":"Copy the prompt from the Prompt section below, fill in the square-bracket placeholders (your class names and the semester start date), and send it. The prompt tells the AI exactly what to extract (every assignment, exam, reading, and project), how to sort it (strictly by calendar week), and what columns to put it in. Being this specific is the difference between a useful table and a vague summary."},{"title":"Read the result and hunt for bottleneck weeks","detail":"The AI returns a table sorted Week 1, Week 2, and so on, with every class's tasks side by side. Scan down the Week column and look for any week with two or more graded items (exams, projects, big papers) stacked together. Those are your danger weeks. Also glance for suspiciously empty weeks, which are the calm periods you should use to work ahead on the busy ones."},{"title":"Spot-check a few dates against the originals","detail":"AI is very good at this task but not perfect; it can occasionally misread a date or attach a deadline to the wrong week. Pick your two or three highest-stakes items (final exams, the big term paper) and confirm their dates against the actual syllabus. This 60-second check protects you from planning your whole semester around one wrong number. If you find an error, just tell the AI 'The ENG 210 midterm is Week 8, not Week 7 — please fix and regenerate.'"},{"title":"Save it somewhere you will actually see it","detail":"A perfect timeline is useless if it dies in a chat window you never reopen. Copy the finished table into a Google Doc, a Notion page, or your notes app, and if you like, ask the AI to also output it as a calendar-friendly list you can paste into Google Calendar. Then, in the same chat, ask it to suggest study blocks: 'Based on this timeline, tell me which weeks I should start preparing early and roughly how many study hours each week needs.'"}],"prompt":"You are my academic scheduling assistant. Below are the weekly schedule sections from [NUMBER] of my course syllabi for this semester. Each one is labeled with its class name.\n\nThe semester (Week 1) begins on [SEMESTER START DATE, e.g. August 26, 2026]. If a syllabus uses week numbers instead of dates, use this start date to work out the real calendar date for each item.\n\nYour job:\n1. Read all of the schedules below.\n2. Extract EVERY single dated item from each class: assignments, quizzes, exams, reading milestones, project deadlines, and presentations. Do not skip anything with a date attached.\n3. Combine everything into ONE master timeline, sorted strictly in chronological order by calendar week (Week 1, Week 2, Week 3, ...).\n4. Present it as a table with these exact columns:\n   Week | Date (if known) | Class | Task Description | Type (Reading / Assignment / Quiz / Exam / Project)\n5. After the table, add a short section called \"Heavy Weeks\" that lists any week containing two or more graded items (quizzes, exams, projects, or papers), so I can prepare early.\n6. If any date is unclear or missing in a syllabus, list that item at the bottom under \"Needs My Attention\" instead of guessing.\n\nHere are the schedules:\n\nCLASS: [CLASS 1 NAME]\n[PASTE SYLLABUS 1 SCHEDULE HERE]\n\nCLASS: [CLASS 2 NAME]\n[PASTE SYLLABUS 2 SCHEDULE HERE]\n\nCLASS: [CLASS 3 NAME]\n[PASTE SYLLABUS 3 SCHEDULE HERE]\n\n(Add or remove CLASS blocks as needed.)","promptNote":"Replace [NUMBER] with how many classes you're combining, [SEMESTER START DATE] with the real date Week 1 begins, and each [CLASS X NAME] / [PASTE SYLLABUS X SCHEDULE HERE] with your class name and its schedule text. If you're uploading files instead of pasting, you can delete the CLASS blocks at the bottom and just write \"The schedules are in the attached files, named by class.\"","cloud":{"bestTool":"Anthropic Claude, because this task hinges on accurately reading several long documents at once and it handles large amounts of pasted or uploaded text with strong attention to detail, which keeps dates from getting jumbled (Google Gemini is an excellent second choice, especially if your syllabi live in Google Drive).","steps":["Go to claude.ai (or gemini.google.com) and sign in; the free tier is fine for this.","Start a new chat. Upload your syllabus PDFs/Word files, or paste each schedule with a 'CLASS: name' label above it.","Paste the master-timeline prompt from above, fill in your class names and semester start date, and send it.","Read the table, then iterate in plain English: ask it to fix any wrong date, convert the timeline into a Google Calendar-ready list, or suggest study blocks for the heavy weeks.","Copy the final table into a Google Doc or your notes app so it lives somewhere permanent."]},"local":["Open your local chat app (LM Studio, or Open WebUI connected to Ollama) and load a capable model — a modern 8B-or-larger instruct model handles this well.","Because many local setups can't read PDFs directly, open each syllabus and copy the schedule text. Paste each block into the chat with a 'CLASS: name' label above it so the model knows which deadline belongs to which class.","Paste the master-timeline prompt from above, filling in your class names and the semester start date.","If a very long combined paste gets truncated or the model seems to forget an early class, feed the syllabi in two smaller batches and ask it to merge the two resulting tables at the end.","Review the table, correct any dates in plain English, and copy the final result out to your notes app or a document."],"localNeedsSetup":true,"choose":"For most students this is a low-sensitivity task and a cloud tool (Claude or Gemini) is the easiest, most accurate choice — course schedules are not secret, and the cloud models handle long documents best. Lean local only if your syllabi contain something you'd rather not upload, such as a disability-accommodation note, personal health information, or an instructor's private contact details, or if you simply prefer that nothing leaves your machine. A good middle ground: paste only the plain weekly-schedule rows (dates and task names) into the cloud, and keep the personal policy sections out of it entirely.","example":{"input":"CLASS: BIO 101\nWeek 2: Read Ch. 3. Week 4: Quiz 1 (Cells). Week 7: Midterm Exam. Week 11: Lab Report due. Week 15: Final Exam.\n\nCLASS: ENG 210\nWeek 3: Essay 1 draft due. Week 7: Essay 1 final due. Week 10: Read 'Beloved' ch. 1-5. Week 14: Research Paper due.\n\nCLASS: MATH 150\nWeek 4: Problem Set 3. Week 7: Exam 1. Week 12: Exam 2. Week 15: Final Exam.\n\n(Semester starts Aug 26, 2026.)","output":"Master Timeline\n\nWeek | Date | Class | Task | Type\n2 | Sep 8 | BIO 101 | Read Ch. 3 | Reading\n3 | Sep 15 | ENG 210 | Essay 1 draft due | Assignment\n4 | Sep 22 | BIO 101 | Quiz 1 (Cells) | Quiz\n4 | Sep 22 | MATH 150 | Problem Set 3 | Assignment\n7 | Oct 13 | BIO 101 | Midterm Exam | Exam\n7 | Oct 13 | ENG 210 | Essay 1 final due | Assignment\n7 | Oct 13 | MATH 150 | Exam 1 | Exam\n10 | Nov 3 | ENG 210 | Read 'Beloved' ch. 1-5 | Reading\n11 | Nov 10 | BIO 101 | Lab Report due | Project\n12 | Nov 17 | MATH 150 | Exam 2 | Exam\n14 | Dec 1 | ENG 210 | Research Paper due | Project\n15 | Dec 8 | BIO 101 | Final Exam | Exam\n15 | Dec 8 | MATH 150 | Final Exam | Exam\n\nHeavy Weeks\n- Week 7: THREE graded items — BIO 101 Midterm, ENG 210 Essay final, MATH 150 Exam 1. Start prepping by Week 5.\n- Week 15: Two finals same week (BIO 101, MATH 150).","note":"Notice how Week 7 instantly reveals a hidden triple-deadline pileup you would never have seen looking at the three syllabi separately."},"tips":["Always label each syllabus with its class name before pasting. This one habit prevents the most common failure: deadlines getting assigned to the wrong course.","Give the AI your real semester start date. That turns vague 'Week 7' labels into actual calendar dates like 'Oct 13,' which you can drop straight into Google Calendar.","After you get the table, ask a follow-up: 'Reformat this as a CSV I can import into Google Calendar' or 'Group this by month instead of week.' You can reshape the same data endlessly without re-pasting.","Ask it to flag the heavy weeks explicitly (the prompt already does this). Seeing 'Week 7 has three graded items' in writing is what actually changes your study behavior.","Re-run this whenever a professor updates a due date. Paste the corrected schedule and ask the AI to regenerate just that class's rows and re-merge."],"mistakes":["Pasting syllabi without labels, so the AI can't tell which class a deadline belongs to. Fix: type 'CLASS: [name]' above each pasted block.","Trusting the timeline blindly without checking. AI can occasionally misread a date. Fix: spot-check your two or three highest-stakes deadlines against the original syllabus before you rely on the schedule.","Only pasting one or two syllabi and wondering why nothing overlaps. The whole point is seeing all classes together. Fix: include every class you're taking this term in a single prompt.","Leaving the finished timeline stranded in the chat window. Fix: immediately copy it into a Google Doc, Notion, or your notes app, and optionally export it to your calendar.","Dumping entire 15-page syllabi (policies, grading rubrics, contact info) into the prompt. This buries the schedule in noise and, in the cloud, over-shares personal sections. Fix: paste only the weekly schedule / course calendar portion of each syllabus."],"related":["t1","t2","t22"]},{"id":"t7","num":7,"cat":"W","title":"Enterprise Communicator and Executive Tone-Shifter","tagline":"Turn blunt, technical, or emotionally-charged internal notes into polished, stakeholder-ready corporate messages in under a minute, without losing a single fact.","audience":"Team leads, technical managers, engineers, and customer success staff who have to deliver hard news (outages, delays, mistakes, missed numbers) to executives, clients, or other departments.","why":"Under pressure your first draft is honest but raw: it blames a vendor, admits fault too bluntly, or buries the one fact the reader actually needs. Rewriting that by hand costs time and emotional energy you do not have during an incident, and a single defensive or finger-pointing sentence can dent a client relationship or make leadership lose confidence in you. An AI tone-shifter fixes this by keeping every fact you give it while re-encoding the delivery: it strips blame, adds a resolution-focused frame, and matches the register your audience expects. Reach for it whenever you must communicate up or out about something uncomfortable, when polish matters and the reader is senior or external, or simply when you want a strong first draft to edit instead of a blank page. The point is not to hide the truth; it is to state the truth in a way that keeps people calm and keeps their confidence in you.","need":["A chat AI tool you can paste text into: Microsoft Copilot, Google Gemini, or Anthropic Claude in the cloud; or a local model (Llama 3, Mistral) running in Open WebUI or LM Studio.","Your raw, unfiltered notes about what happened, written however you actually think it. Bullet points are perfectly fine.","The facts that must stay exactly right and cannot be softened or invented: timelines, numbers, dates, system names, and any commitments you are willing to make.","A clear picture of the audience: an external executive, an internal VP, and an angry customer each need a different tone.","Two minutes to read the result out loud and confirm it says what you actually mean before you hit send."],"steps":[{"title":"Dump your raw thoughts, unfiltered","detail":"Open a plain note or the chat box and write exactly what happened the way you would vent to a trusted coworker. Do not edit, do not be diplomatic, and do not worry about tone yet. The AI can only keep facts you actually give it, so a blunt line like 'DB went down because the vendor skipped a patch, we are down 4 more hours, it is their fault but we look bad' is far more useful than a vague, pre-sanitized sentence. This raw dump is your source of truth, and getting all the real facts out now is what makes the polished version accurate later."},{"title":"Tell the AI WHO is reading and WHAT tone you want","detail":"The single biggest lever on quality is naming the audience and the goal. 'External executive stakeholders' produces a very different message than 'my own manager' or 'the customer whose site is down.' State the register you want (calm, analytical, resolution-focused), and explicitly say what to avoid (blame, defensiveness, naming individuals). This is the difference between a generic rewrite and a message engineered for the exact person who will open it."},{"title":"Lock the facts so the AI cannot change them","detail":"AI tools sometimes 'smooth over' a number or invent a reassuring detail to make prose flow, which is dangerous in a status update. In your instruction, list the facts that must appear verbatim (the 4-hour window, the root cause, any deadline) and add the rule 'do not invent any facts, commitments, or timelines I did not provide.' This keeps you fully transparent and stops the AI from promising something you cannot deliver."},{"title":"Paste the full prompt and run it","detail":"Copy the prompt template from the Prompt section below, drop your raw notes into the [RAW NOTES] slot, fill the other brackets, and send it. In one pass you will get a subject line, a greeting, a clear body, and a professional close. Read it once for accuracy first (are all my facts intact and correct?) and only then for tone."},{"title":"Refine with plain-English follow-ups","detail":"You almost never need to re-type the whole prompt. Just reply conversationally in the same chat: 'Make it two sentences shorter,' 'This feels too apologetic, make it more confident,' 'Add a line offering a follow-up call,' or 'Give me a warmer version and a more formal version so I can choose.' Each reply refines the previous draft, so you can dial the message in with a few quick nudges instead of starting over."},{"title":"Read it aloud, then own it before sending","detail":"Read the final version out loud. Your ear will catch anything that sounds robotic, over-formal, or subtly wrong that your eyes skim past. Confirm three things: every fact is accurate, the tone matches the relationship, and there are no invented promises. You are the sender and you are accountable for the message, so make the final small edits in your own voice before it goes out."}],"prompt":"You are an experienced corporate communications advisor. Rewrite my raw, unpolished notes below into a professional, stakeholder-ready [MESSAGE TYPE: e.g. email / Slack update / status page post] addressed to [AUDIENCE: e.g. external executive stakeholders / my VP / the affected customer].\n\nRAW NOTES:\n\"\"\"\n[RAW NOTES: paste your unfiltered thoughts here, bullet points are fine]\n\"\"\"\n\nRewrite it to be [DESIRED TONE: e.g. calm, analytical, proactive, resolution-focused] and [LENGTH: e.g. brief, about 150 words].\n\nRules:\n- Preserve these facts exactly and do not change or soften them: [KEY FACTS TO KEEP: e.g. the 4-hour restoration window, the root cause, the next update time].\n- Do NOT invent any facts, numbers, commitments, or timelines I did not provide. If something important is missing, list your questions at the end instead of guessing.\n- Remove all blame and finger-pointing. Do not name or fault specific individuals or vendors; describe issues in neutral, process-focused terms.\n- Avoid defensive or apologetic-sounding language. Project accountability and control.\n- Emphasize what we are doing to resolve it and how we are preventing recurrence (monitoring, validation, next steps).\n- Structure it as: a clear subject line, a one-line summary of the situation, what happened (neutral), current impact, our resolution plan with the timeline, and a confident close with the next update time.\n\nAfter the rewrite, add a short note listing anything you were unsure about or any fact I should double-check.","promptNote":"Fill every [SQUARE BRACKET] with your specifics. [AUDIENCE] and [DESIRED TONE] are the two that most change the result, so be precise (say 'external client CIO' not just 'stakeholder'). [KEY FACTS TO KEEP] is your safety rail against the AI altering a number; the 'do not invent' rule is what keeps you honest and transparent. Delete the [MESSAGE TYPE] structure line if you want a Slack blurb instead of a formal email.","cloud":{"bestTool":"Microsoft Copilot, because this task usually ends in an email and Copilot lives directly inside Outlook and Word, letting you rewrite the draft in the exact window you will send it from without copy-pasting between apps.","steps":["In Outlook, start (or open) the email, click the Copilot icon, and choose 'Draft with Copilot' or 'Coaching by Copilot'; or just open copilot.microsoft.com in a browser.","Paste the full prompt template from the Prompt section, drop your raw notes into the [RAW NOTES] slot, and fill the [AUDIENCE], [TONE], and [KEY FACTS] brackets.","Run it, then read the draft for accuracy first (all facts intact and correct?) and tone second.","Refine in the same chat with plain follow-ups like 'shorter and more confident' or 'add a line offering a call,' or use Copilot's Coaching feature to score the tone.","Copy the final version into your email, make the last edits in your own voice, and send."]},"local":["Open your local chat UI (Open WebUI for Ollama, or LM Studio) and select an installed instruct model such as Llama 3 8B or Mistral. Confirm it is running fully offline (turn off Wi-Fi to be sure nothing leaves your machine).","Paste the same prompt template from the Prompt section, then paste your raw notes into the [RAW NOTES] slot and fill the remaining brackets.","Send it and read the draft, checking that every fact you provided survived unchanged; smaller local models occasionally drop a detail, so verify against your notes.","Refine with the same plain-English follow-ups ('shorter,' 'more formal,' 'remove the apology'). If a small model over-formalizes or adds fluff, add a rule like 'no more than 140 words, no filler phrases.'","Copy the final text into your email client yourself. Nothing was ever transmitted, so this is safe for outage details, client names, and internal specifics."],"localNeedsSetup":true,"choose":"For a routine internal update or a low-stakes note, the cloud tools are easiest and give the most polished writing; use Copilot, Gemini, or Claude and move on. But the moment your raw notes contain client names, contract terms, security-incident details, financials, HR matters, or anything under an NDA, run it on a LOCAL model instead. Your unfiltered draft names the vendor, admits the fault, and describes the exact failure, and that is precisely the kind of text you do not want sitting in a third party's servers. Local keeps every word on your machine, so you can be totally candid in the raw dump, which is exactly what makes the polished output accurate.","example":{"input":"Raw notes I paste: 'DB broke because the vendor missed a major patch. We are down another 4 hours. Honestly it is their fault but we look bad. Customer is already emailing asking wtf. We restored from backup once but it failed again. Root cause is a bad index migration in their patch. Next update by 3pm.' Audience: external executive stakeholders. Tone: calm, analytical, resolution-focused. Keep exactly: 4-hour window, 3pm next update, restored-from-backup step.","output":"Subject: Service Disruption Update, Estimated Restoration Within 4 Hours\n\nDear [Stakeholder name],\n\nI am writing to give you a transparent update on a service disruption affecting our database platform and to outline the steps underway to restore full service.\n\nWhat happened: A recent infrastructure patch introduced a database indexing issue that impacted availability. Our team identified the root cause and is actively working to resolve it.\n\nCurrent status: We executed a restoration from backup and, after that initial attempt did not fully hold, our engineers are now applying a targeted fix to the affected migration. We estimate full restoration within approximately 4 hours.\n\nPrevention and monitoring: Our continuous validation and monitoring protocols flagged the issue promptly, and we are adding an additional pre-deployment validation checkpoint to reduce the likelihood of recurrence.\n\nWe will send our next update by 3:00 PM, or sooner if the situation changes. Thank you for your patience and partnership; please reach out to me directly with any questions.\n\nWarm regards,\n[Your name]\n\n---\nNote: I kept your 4-hour window and 3:00 PM update time as stated. I described the vendor's patch as 'a recent infrastructure patch' to avoid naming or blaming a third party; if you want to name them, tell me. Double-check the exact restoration estimate before sending.","note":"Notice the AI kept every hard fact (4 hours, 3pm, backup step) but removed 'it is their fault,' turned blame into a neutral 'a recent infrastructure patch,' and reframed the whole thing around resolution and monitoring."},"tips":["Ask for two versions at once ('give me a formal version and a warmer version') so you can pick the tone that fits the relationship instead of guessing.","Always include the 'do not invent facts, list your questions instead' rule. A good AI will then tell you what is missing rather than fabricate a reassuring detail you never approved.","Name the emotion you want the reader to feel, not just the tone you want to write in: 'I want them to feel that we are in control and this is handled' steers the wording better than 'be professional.'","Keep a reusable prompt with your brackets pre-filled for your common scenarios (outage update, deadline slip, invoice dispute) so next time you only swap the raw notes.","For anything going to a client or executive, paste the final draft back and ask 'read this as the recipient, what could be misread or land badly?' to catch a bad-sounding line before they do."],"mistakes":["Sanitizing your notes before pasting them. If you soften the facts first, the AI has less to work with and may miss the real issue; dump the raw truth and let the AI handle the diplomacy.","Not naming the audience, so you get a generic corporate voice. Always state exactly who reads it (external CIO vs. your own manager) because the right tone is completely different.","Trusting the numbers blindly. AI can quietly change '4 hours' to 'a few hours' or invent a cause; always re-check every fact and timeline against your original notes before sending.","Sending it word-for-word without a human pass. Overly formal AI phrasing ('I am writing to inform you') can sound robotic; read it aloud and edit a few lines into your own voice so it sounds like you.","Pasting sensitive incident details, client names, or contract terms into a public cloud tool for a confidential matter. When in doubt about sensitivity, use a local model so nothing leaves your machine."],"related":["t12","t14","t19"]},{"id":"t12","num":12,"cat":"W","title":"Cross-Border Communication and Cultural Nuance Tuning","tagline":"Turn a blunt, fast-paced Western business email into one that lands as respectful and trustworthy with partners in Japan, Germany, or anywhere else, without changing a single fact.","audience":"International sales managers, customer success representatives, and global team leads who write to clients, vendors, or colleagues in other countries.","why":"The same email can build trust in one country and quietly damage a relationship in another. A crisp, get-to-the-point update that a manager in Texas reads as efficient can read as blunt or even rude to a partner in Tokyo, where a warm opening and indirect phrasing signal respect; a German counterpart, by contrast, may want the facts even more precisely and formally than you gave them. AI is genuinely good at this because it has read enormous amounts of business writing from every region, so it can re-shape greetings, tone, ordering, and level of directness while leaving your dates, numbers, and commitments untouched. Reach for it whenever a message crosses a border and the relationship matters: a project update to an overseas client, a delicate \"we're slipping the deadline\" note, a first introduction, or a negotiation reply. It protects you from the two expensive mistakes, sounding rude by being too direct, or sounding wishy-washy by over-correcting.","need":["A finished draft of the email or update you actually want to send, written in your normal style.","The destination: the country or region of the person receiving it (Japan, Germany, Saudi Arabia, South Korea, Brazil, and so on).","The relationship and seniority: a brand-new prospect, a long-time client, a peer, or a senior executive, since etiquette shifts a lot with rank.","An AI chat tool, either a cloud one (Microsoft Copilot, Google Gemini, or Anthropic Claude) or a local model in a chat app like LM Studio or Open WebUI.","Two minutes to read the result critically and, ideally, a native-speaking colleague to spot-check anything high-stakes."],"steps":[{"title":"Write your message normally first, then get it out of your email client","detail":"Draft the email exactly as you always would, plainly and completely, without trying to make it 'international' yourself. You want the AI to do the cultural work, so give it your real, unpolished voice as the starting point. Copy the whole thing, including the subject line and any bullet-point timelines or metrics, so nothing gets lost in translation."},{"title":"Open your AI tool and paste the draft into a fresh chat","detail":"Start a brand-new conversation so leftover context from earlier chats doesn't bleed in. Paste your draft, but don't hit send yet. On the very next line you'll add the instruction that tells the AI what to do with it, keeping your content and your command clearly separated so the AI never confuses the two."},{"title":"Give it the destination, the relationship, and one firm rule: do not change the facts","detail":"Fill in the prompt below with the country and who you're writing to, because 'a first email to a new senior client in Japan' needs very different handling than 'a quick note to a long-time German colleague.' The single most important instruction is that timelines, numbers, names, and commitments must stay exactly the same, only the tone and structure change. This is what keeps the AI from 'softening' a hard deadline into something vague and getting you into trouble later."},{"title":"Ask for a short explanation of what it changed and why","detail":"Add a line asking the AI to list the cultural adjustments it made, for example 'added a seasonal greeting,' 'softened the direct request into a collaborative one,' or 'moved the apology before the ask.' This turns the tool into a teacher: you learn the etiquette instead of blindly copying, and you can catch anything that went too far. Over a few uses you'll start to internalize the patterns for each region."},{"title":"Read the result critically and push back where it overshot","detail":"Check two things: that every date, figure, and deliverable survived unchanged, and that the tone still sounds like a competent professional, not a groveling one. If it got too flowery or buried your actual point, reply with a follow-up like 'Keep it warm but make the deadline unmistakable' or 'Half this length.' Iterating in the same chat is normal and fast; the first draft is a starting point, not the final word."},{"title":"Sanity-check high-stakes messages with a human before sending","detail":"For a first contact, a contract, or anything where a misstep is costly, have a native speaker or an experienced local colleague glance at it. AI is very good at general etiquette but can miss company-specific or very current nuances, like whether this particular client actually prefers English and brevity. Treat the AI as an expert first-drafter, not the final authority, and you'll get the speed benefit without the risk."}],"prompt":"You are an expert in international business communication and cross-cultural etiquette.\n\nBelow is an email I wrote in a direct, fast-paced Western style. Rewrite it for the recipient described, so it aligns with the business etiquette, formality level, greeting conventions, and communication norms of that culture.\n\nRECIPIENT COUNTRY / REGION: [e.g. Japan]\nMY RELATIONSHIP TO THEM: [e.g. first email to a new, senior client]\nDESIRED FORMALITY: [e.g. high and respectful / warm but professional / peer-to-peer casual]\n\nHard rules:\n1. Do NOT change any facts. All dates, deadlines, numbers, metrics, deliverables, names, and commitments must stay exactly as written.\n2. Only adjust tone, greeting, structure, level of directness, and closing.\n3. Keep it concise; do not pad it into something long-winded.\n4. Match the language: write the reply in [English / the recipient's language].\n\nAfter the rewrite, add a short section titled \"What I changed and why\" listing each cultural adjustment in one line so I understand the etiquette.\n\nHere is my draft:\n---\n[PASTE YOUR FULL EMAIL HERE, INCLUDING SUBJECT LINE]\n---","promptNote":"Replace the three bracketed setup lines with your specifics, then paste your real email where indicated. The country and relationship lines do the heavy lifting, so be precise (\"senior executive\" vs. \"long-time peer\" changes the result a lot). If you want the reply in the recipient's own language, say so; otherwise it stays in English.","cloud":{"bestTool":"Microsoft Copilot, because for most professionals this task lives inside Outlook, where Copilot can rewrite the email in place, in the exact window you're already sending from.","steps":["Open the draft in Outlook (desktop or web) and start Copilot from the ribbon, or open copilot.microsoft.com in a browser and paste the draft there.","Paste the full prompt above, fill in the country, relationship, and formality lines, and drop your email into the marked spot.","Run it, then read both the rewrite and the 'What I changed and why' list to confirm your dates and numbers are untouched.","If it's too formal, too long, or buried your ask, reply in the same chat with a one-line correction like 'Keep the deadline blunt' and let it revise.","Copy the final version back into your email, and for anything high-stakes, have a native-speaking colleague glance at it before sending."]},"local":["Open your local chat app (LM Studio, or Open WebUI connected to Ollama) and load a capable general model such as Llama 3.1 8B, Qwen 2.5, or a larger one if your machine allows.","Start a new chat and paste the full prompt above, filling in the country, relationship, and formality, then paste your email into the marked spot.","Run it locally; nothing leaves your computer, which matters when the email names a client, a contract value, or an unannounced deadline.","Read the rewrite and the 'What I changed and why' list, and refine with follow-up messages in the same chat until the tone is right.","If a smaller local model produces stiff or generic phrasing, ask it to 'make this sound like a real person, not a template,' or step up to a larger model for the important messages."],"localNeedsSetup":true,"choose":"For a routine project update to a known partner, a cloud tool is fine and fastest, especially Copilot right inside Outlook. Lean local, however, whenever the email exposes something sensitive: an unannounced product slip, contract figures, a client's internal problems, layoffs, or legal or pricing details. Those messages often contain exactly the kind of confidential business information you don't want sitting in a third-party service's logs, and a local model keeps the whole rewrite on your own machine. A good rule: if you'd hesitate to forward the email to an outside vendor, do the rewrite locally.","example":{"input":"RECIPIENT COUNTRY: Japan | RELATIONSHIP: first update to a new, senior client | FORMALITY: high and respectful\n\nSubject: Project Falcon - 2 week delay\n\nHi Tanaka-san,\n\nQuick update. We hit a snag with the API integration, so the launch is slipping. New go-live is March 14 instead of Feb 28. The QA numbers are still solid - 98.5% test pass rate. Let me know if this works for you.\n\nThanks,\nDana","output":"Subject: Update on Project Falcon Schedule and Continued Commitment\n\nDear Mr. Tanaka,\n\nThank you very much for your continued trust and support on Project Falcon. I hope this message finds you and your team well.\n\nI am writing to share an important update regarding our schedule. During the API integration phase we encountered a technical challenge that requires additional time to resolve properly. To ensure the quality you expect, we have revised the go-live date to March 14, rather than the original February 28.\n\nPlease be assured that quality remains strong: our current test pass rate stands at 98.5%. We are fully committed to delivering a reliable result and would be grateful to hear your thoughts on this revised timeline.\n\nThank you again for your understanding. We look forward to your guidance.\n\nWarm regards,\nDana\n\nWhat I changed and why:\n- Used the full name \"Mr. Tanaka\" and a formal \"Dear\" opening | shows respect for a senior first contact.\n- Added a gratitude line before the news | in Japan, appreciation and relationship come before business.\n- Reframed \"we hit a snag / it's slipping\" as a challenge requiring care | direct blame or bluntness reads as unprofessional.\n- Kept Feb 28, March 14, and 98.5% exactly | facts must never change.\n- Invited their \"guidance\" rather than a yes/no | signals collaboration and deference, not a demand.","note":"Notice the dates and the 98.5% figure are identical to the original; only the framing, greeting, and directness changed."},"tips":["Always keep the 'do not change any facts' rule in the prompt. Without it, models sometimes 'soften' a hard deadline into vague language, which is exactly the misunderstanding you're trying to avoid.","Tell the AI the seniority and history, not just the country. 'A senior client we've never met' and 'a peer I email weekly' in the same country get very different, and more accurate, results.","Ask for the 'what I changed and why' list every time at first. It teaches you the etiquette so that within a few weeks you'll need the AI less for routine messages.","For truly important messages, generate two versions ('give me a more formal and a slightly warmer version') and pick the one that fits, or blend them.","If you want it in the recipient's language, ask the AI to also provide a plain-English back-translation so you can verify it didn't change your meaning."],"mistakes":["Trusting a language you can't read. If you have it write in Japanese or German, always ask for a back-translation into English and, for anything important, get a native speaker to confirm before sending.","Over-correcting into a grovel. Beginners often accept the most flowery version; if it buries your actual point or sounds servile, tell it to 'stay respectful but make the key request clear.' Competent and polite beats obsequious.","Letting facts drift. Skim the output and match every date, number, and deliverable against your original. If the AI paraphrased '98.5% pass rate' into 'strong results,' put the exact figure back.","Using one style for a whole region. 'Asia' or 'Europe' isn't a culture; Japan, South Korea, and China differ, as do Germany, Spain, and Sweden. Always name the specific country.","Pasting confidential emails into a public cloud tool by habit. If the message names a client's problems, unreleased plans, or contract numbers, run it on a local model instead so nothing sensitive leaves your machine."],"related":["t7","t14","t19"]},{"id":"t14","num":14,"cat":"W","title":"First-Draft Creative Block Breaker (The Content Matrix)","tagline":"Turn one raw feature sheet or announcement into a ready-to-use grid of channel-specific messages in a single pass.","audience":"Marketing coordinators, internal communications specialists, and HR managers who have to take one set of facts (a new product feature, a policy change, a benefits update) and rewrite it several times for a newsletter, a chat channel, and a professional social feed. It is for people who are strong writers but tired of staring at a blank page and manually reformatting the same information three ways.","why":"The hardest part of channel communication is not writing, it is starting and then repeating yourself. You have the facts, but you have to re-package them for an internal newsletter, a casual Slack or Teams message, and a polished LinkedIn-style post, each with a different tone and length. An AI is very good at this specific job because you feed it the facts once and ask for several rewrites at different registers in one shot, which beats the blank page and saves the tedious copy-reformat-repeat cycle. It also protects consistency: because every version is generated from the same source notes, your facts stay aligned across channels instead of drifting as you rewrite by hand. You stay the editor and approver; the AI just gives you strong first drafts to react to, which is far easier than inventing them from scratch.","need":["A raw source of facts to work from: a bulleted feature sheet, a release note, or an announcement text","Access to one AI chat tool (a cloud one like Copilot, Gemini, or Claude, or a local model in a chat app like LM Studio or Open WebUI)","Clarity on your channels: which outputs you actually need (newsletter, internal chat, external social, etc.)","A rough sense of your house voice, so you can tell the AI what tone each channel uses","5 to 10 minutes to review, fact-check, and polish the drafts before anything ships"],"steps":[{"title":"Gather your source facts in one place","detail":"Before you open any AI tool, copy the raw material you are working from into a single block: the bulleted feature list, the policy paragraph, or the announcement draft. Do not clean it up or make it pretty; the AI works best from the unpolished source because that is where the real facts live. Having it ready in one place means you paste once and avoid feeding the AI half the story, which is the most common cause of a weak or invented draft."},{"title":"Open your AI tool and start a fresh chat","detail":"Use a new, empty conversation so nothing from an earlier chat bleeds into your results. A fresh chat means the AI only considers the notes and instructions you give it right now, which keeps the output focused and predictable. If you are handling sensitive HR or unreleased product information, choose a local model instead of a cloud one (see the local steps and the guidance below)."},{"title":"Paste the prompt, then paste your notes underneath","detail":"Copy the full prompt template from the Prompt section, then replace the bracketed placeholders with your real channel names and tone. Paste your source facts where the template asks for them. The prompt tells the AI to build a table with one column per channel and, critically, to never change or invent a technical fact, which is what keeps you safe from confidently wrong copy."},{"title":"Run it and read the whole table critically","detail":"Send the prompt and let the AI generate the content matrix. Read every cell against your original notes, not for style but for truth: check that every number, feature name, date, and policy detail survived the rewrite unchanged. AI can smooth a sentence so nicely that it quietly alters a fact, so this fact-check pass is the single most important thing you do."},{"title":"Ask for fixes and variations in plain language","detail":"You almost never keep the first draft as-is, and you do not need to. Reply in the same chat with plain requests like 'make column 2 warmer and drop the emoji' or 'give me two more options for the social post, one shorter.' The AI keeps the same facts and context, so each round gets closer to your voice without you re-explaining anything."},{"title":"Curate, polish, and move to production","detail":"Pick the best version from each column, paste it into wherever it actually ships (your newsletter tool, chat channel, or social scheduler), and do a final human edit. Add anything only you would know: the real link, the exact publish date, the internal owner's name. The AI got you from blank page to strong draft; your judgment is what makes it publishable."}],"prompt":"You are a communications editor. Below are raw, factual source notes. Do not add, remove, or alter any technical fact, number, name, or date in them. If something is missing, leave a clearly marked [PLACEHOLDER] rather than inventing it.\n\nFrom these notes, generate a content matrix as a table with one row per key point and these three columns:\n\nColumn 1 — Internal Newsletter: a concise 3-sentence summary in a [warm, professional] tone for a company-wide email newsletter.\nColumn 2 — Internal Chat (e.g. Slack/Teams): a short, conversational message in a [friendly, casual] tone suitable for a team messaging channel; keep it to 1-2 sentences.\nColumn 3 — External Professional Post: a polished update in a [confident, on-brand] tone for a professional social network such as LinkedIn; 2-4 sentences, no hashtags unless I ask.\n\nRules:\n- Keep every technical fact identical across all three columns.\n- Match the tone I specified for each column; do not make everything sound the same.\n- After the table, list any facts you were unsure about so I can verify them.\n\nSOURCE NOTES:\n[PASTE YOUR RAW FEATURE SHEET OR ANNOUNCEMENT HERE]","promptNote":"Replace the tone words in [square brackets] with your actual house voice for each channel, and paste your real notes at the bottom. If you need different channels (say an all-hands script instead of social), just rename a column and describe what it is for; the structure works the same.","cloud":{"bestTool":"Microsoft Copilot, because most marketing, comms, and HR teams already live in Microsoft 365 and Copilot can pull directly from a feature sheet in Word or an announcement in Outlook and drop the finished table straight back into your working documents.","steps":["Open Microsoft Copilot (copilot.microsoft.com, or the Copilot panel inside Word/Outlook) and start a new chat.","Paste the prompt template, edit the bracketed tone and channel names to match your house voice, and paste your source notes at the bottom.","Send it, then read the table and fact-check every cell against your original notes.","Reply with plain-language fixes ('shorten column 3', 'warmer tone in the newsletter') until each column sounds right.","Copy the winning cells into your newsletter tool, chat channel, and social scheduler, then do a final human polish."]},"local":["Open your local chat app (for example LM Studio, or Open WebUI connected to Ollama) and select your installed model.","Start a new conversation and paste the prompt template, editing the bracketed tone and channel names for your team.","Paste your source notes at the bottom of the prompt and send it; because the model runs on your machine, none of this data leaves the device.","Read the generated table and check every fact against your notes, then reply in the same chat asking for tone or length tweaks.","Copy the final versions out to wherever they ship, and edit for the last human details."],"localNeedsSetup":true,"choose":"For a public product feature that is already announced or about to be, a cloud tool like Copilot is perfectly fine and the fastest path. Switch to a local model whenever the source is sensitive: unreleased product details under embargo, internal HR or personnel policy, layoffs, compensation, or anything legal or financial. In those cases the whole point of a local model is that the announcement never leaves your computer, so there is no vendor, no cloud log, and no risk of a confidential internal update sitting on someone else's server before you have even published it.","example":{"input":"New feature notes — Dashboard v2.4:\n- Adds real-time sync; data refreshes every 30 seconds (was 5 minutes)\n- New role-based access: Admin, Editor, Viewer\n- Export to CSV and PDF now supported\n- Available to all Pro and Enterprise plans on March 18\n- No price change","output":"Key point | Internal Newsletter | Internal Chat | External Professional Post\n\nReal-time sync | Dashboard v2.4 brings real-time sync, refreshing data every 30 seconds instead of every 5 minutes. Your teams see changes as they happen. It rolls out March 18. | Heads up: Dashboard v2.4 now syncs every 30 seconds instead of 5 minutes. Live data, finally! | We shipped Dashboard v2.4 with real-time sync — data now refreshes every 30 seconds, down from 5 minutes, so teams act on current information.\n\nRole-based access | v2.4 introduces role-based access with Admin, Editor, and Viewer roles for tighter control. It arrives March 18 for Pro and Enterprise plans at no added cost. | New in v2.4: Admin, Editor, and Viewer roles. Cleaner permissions for everyone. | Dashboard v2.4 adds role-based access — Admin, Editor, and Viewer — giving teams finer control over who can do what.\n\nExport | You can now export to CSV and PDF, available March 18 on Pro and Enterprise plans with no price change. | You can now export to CSV and PDF. Reporting just got easier. | v2.4 now supports CSV and PDF export, making it simpler to share results beyond the dashboard.\n\nFacts to verify: rollout date (March 18) and that there is no price change.","note":"Notice every column keeps the exact facts (30 seconds, March 18, the three role names) but changes tone and length, and the AI flags which facts to double-check."},"tips":["Name your tones concretely. 'Warm but not gushy, second person' beats 'professional' and gets you closer on the first try.","Give a length limit per column ('max 3 sentences', 'one line for chat'). AI tends to over-write, and a cap keeps chat messages actually short.","Paste one real example of your house voice ('here is a past post we liked') so the AI mirrors your style instead of a generic corporate tone.","Keep the 'list any facts you were unsure about' rule in the prompt — it surfaces exactly where the AI might have guessed, so you know where to look.","Do all your revisions in the same chat. The AI remembers the facts and context, so 'shorter and less salesy' is enough; you never re-paste the notes."],"mistakes":["Trusting the draft's facts. AI can subtly change a number or feature name while polishing a sentence; always check every cell against your original notes before shipping.","Feeding vague or incomplete notes. If you paste half the feature sheet, the AI fills gaps by inventing plausible details. Give it the complete raw source and tell it to leave [PLACEHOLDER] for anything missing.","Shipping the first output as-is. The first table is a starting point, not a final. Do at least one revision round and a human polish, or every channel will sound faintly robotic.","Using a cloud tool for confidential material. Pasting unreleased or HR-sensitive content into a public AI can leak it. For anything sensitive, use a local model so nothing leaves your device.","Asking for one giant blob instead of a table. Without the column structure the AI blends the tones together. Keep the table format so each channel stays distinct and easy to copy out."],"related":["t7","t12","t19"]},{"id":"t19","num":19,"cat":"W","title":"The Multi-Channel Marketing Copy Framework","tagline":"Turn a one-line description of your product or event into a fill-in-the-blanks marketing scaffold, so you never stare at a blank page again.","audience":"Small business owners, communications coordinators, and social media managers who need to write promotional copy (social posts, emails, flyers, event announcements) but have no formal marketing training. It is for the person who knows their product cold but freezes the moment it is time to write the words that actually sell it.","why":"Effective marketing copy is not about clever wording, it is about following a proven psychological order: grab attention, build interest, spark desire, then ask for action. That order is called AIDA, and copywriters have leaned on it for a century because it mirrors how a reader's brain decides whether to care. The trouble for beginners is not a lack of ideas, it is not knowing what belongs where, so they bury the exciting part in paragraph three and forget to actually tell the reader what to do next. This tutorial uses AI to build the skeleton for you, labeling exactly which emotional or factual hook belongs in each slot, so you just fill the blanks with facts only you know. Reach for it whenever you launch a product, announce an event, kick off an initiative, or need a message that converts instead of merely informs.","need":["A free AI chat tool (Anthropic Claude, Google Gemini, or Microsoft Copilot) or a local model running in a chat app like LM Studio or Open WebUI.","One clear sentence describing what you are promoting: the product, service, event, or initiative.","Two or three basic facts you can supply yourself: who it is for, the date or price, and the single thing that makes it worth caring about.","A rough idea of the channel (Instagram caption, email blast, printed flyer) so you can tell the AI how long and how formal to be.","Five quiet minutes to fill in the scaffold once the AI hands it back to you."],"steps":[{"title":"Learn what AIDA is before you touch the AI","detail":"AIDA stands for Attention, Interest, Desire, and Action, and it is the exact order your copy should travel through. Attention is the opening line that makes someone stop scrolling, Interest gives them a reason to keep reading, Desire makes them feel they want it, and Action tells them precisely what to do next. Knowing these four beats matters because the AI is going to build a slot for each one, and you will fill them in, so you want to recognize why each slot exists rather than guessing."},{"title":"Write one honest sentence about what you are promoting","detail":"Before you prompt the AI, define your subject in plain language, for example: We are launching a community green initiative next month that lets neighbors swap unused garden tools for free. Include who it is for and the one detail that makes it special. This is the raw material the AI needs, and a vague subject in means vague copy out, so be specific about the real thing you are offering."},{"title":"Open your AI tool and paste the scaffolding prompt","detail":"Open Claude, Gemini, Copilot, or your local model, and paste the full prompt from the prompt box below, swapping the bracketed placeholders for your real details. This prompt asks the AI to act as a marketing coach and hand you four labeled blocks, one per AIDA stage, each with a written instruction plus a short example template. You are not asking it to write your final copy yet, you are asking it to build the blueprint you will fill in."},{"title":"Read the scaffold and fill in each block with your own facts","detail":"The AI returns four blocks labeled ATTENTION, INTEREST, DESIRE, and ACTION, each explaining what hook to write and showing a one-sentence example. Go block by block and replace the example with your real words, the numbers, the date, the neighborhood name, the discount. This is the heart of the method: the AI supplies the structure and psychology, and you supply the truth, because only you know the actual details and only real specifics build trust."},{"title":"Ask the AI to assemble and tighten your draft","detail":"Once you have filled all four blocks, paste your filled-in version back into the same chat and say: Assemble these four blocks into one flowing [Instagram caption / short email / flyer paragraph], keep my facts exactly, and tighten any clunky wording. The AI now stitches your material into finished copy while preserving the AIDA order. Because you fed it real facts, the result sounds like you and not like generic AI filler."},{"title":"Sanity-check the final copy before you publish","detail":"Read the finished piece out loud and confirm three things: the first line genuinely grabs attention, every fact is accurate, and there is one clear call to action with a link, date, or next step. AI can accidentally invent a detail or soften your ask, so verify the numbers and make sure the Action block tells the reader exactly what to do. When it passes, copy it into your post, email, or flyer and ship it."}],"prompt":"I need help writing a promotional message, and I want you to act as an expert marketing writing coach.\n\nHere is what I am promoting: [ONE SENTENCE DESCRIBING YOUR PRODUCT, SERVICE, EVENT, OR INITIATIVE].\nWho it is for: [YOUR AUDIENCE, e.g. local homeowners / new parents / small nonprofits].\nThe one thing that makes it worth caring about: [YOUR KEY BENEFIT OR HOOK].\nThe channel this will run on: [e.g. Instagram caption / marketing email / printed flyer].\nTone: [e.g. warm and community-minded / bold and urgent / professional].\n\nDo NOT write the final copy yet. Instead, build me a structural scaffold using the AIDA framework (Attention, Interest, Desire, Action).\n\nGive me four clearly separated blocks labeled exactly [ATTENTION], [INTEREST], [DESIRE], and [ACTION]. Under each block, provide:\n1. A strict, specific instruction telling me what emotional or factual hook I need to write myself for that stage, tailored to my subject above.\n2. One short example template sentence I can imitate for formatting.\n\nKeep the examples relevant to my actual subject, not generic. After the four blocks, add one line reminding me what to double-check before publishing.","promptNote":"Replace each [SQUARE BRACKET] with your own details. The subject sentence and the key hook are the two that matter most, because everything the AI scaffolds is built from them. Adjust the channel and tone lines to control length and voice; for a flyer say printed flyer, for social say Instagram caption.","cloud":{"bestTool":"Anthropic Claude, because it is especially strong at following multi-part structural instructions and producing clean, consistently labeled blocks with on-topic examples rather than generic filler.","steps":["Go to claude.ai and sign in (a free account works fine for this).","Start a new chat and paste the full prompt from the prompt box, replacing every [BRACKET] with your real product, audience, and channel details.","Read the four AIDA blocks it returns, then fill each block in with your own facts directly in the chat.","Paste your filled-in blocks back and ask Claude to assemble them into one finished caption, email, or flyer while keeping your facts exact.","Verify the final copy: check the numbers, the date, and that the call to action is clear before you publish."]},"local":["Open your local chat app (LM Studio or Open WebUI) and confirm your model is loaded and the chat box is ready.","Start a new conversation and paste the same scaffolding prompt from the prompt box, filling in your bracketed details.","Read the four AIDA blocks, then type your real facts into each block right there in the chat.","Paste your filled-in blocks back and ask the model to assemble them into one flowing piece of copy in your chosen channel and tone.","If a smaller local model drifts or forgets a block, remind it: keep all four AIDA blocks labeled and use only the facts I gave you."],"localNeedsSetup":true,"choose":"For most marketing copy the data is not sensitive (you are about to publish it to the world anyway), so a cloud tool like Claude is the easiest and fastest choice and there is no privacy downside. Lean local only if your promotion involves details you do not want on a third-party server before launch, such as an unannounced product name, confidential pricing, a partner not yet public, or client-identifying information in a case-study post. In those pre-announcement or confidential situations, run it on a local model so nothing leaves your device until you choose to go public.","example":{"input":"Act as a marketing writing coach. Here is what I am promoting: We are launching a community green initiative next month, a free monthly Tool Library where neighbors borrow garden and repair tools instead of buying them. Audience: local homeowners and renters in the Oakwood neighborhood. Key hook: save money and reduce waste. Channel: Instagram caption. Tone: warm and community-minded. Build me an AIDA scaffold with four labeled blocks.","output":"[ATTENTION] Instruction: Open with a relatable pain your neighbors feel, spending money on a tool they use once a year. Ask a question or state a surprising fact. Example template: \"How many times has that hedge trimmer sat in your garage this year?\"\n\n[INTEREST] Instruction: Introduce the Tool Library and how it works in one plain sentence, then add the launch date. Example template: \"Starting [DATE], Oakwood neighbors can borrow tools free from our new community Tool Library.\"\n\n[DESIRE] Instruction: Paint the payoff, money saved plus less clutter and waste. Make them picture it. Example template: \"Skip the $180 purchase, borrow it for the weekend, and keep your garage and your wallet a little fuller.\"\n\n[ACTION] Instruction: Give one clear next step with a specific how. Example template: \"Reserve your first tool at the link in our bio, first checkout is this Saturday.\"\n\nBefore publishing, double-check: the launch date is correct, the link in bio works, and your first line truly stops the scroll.","note":"Notice the AI does not write your post, it hands you labeled slots with on-topic example lines, so you just swap in your real date and link."},"tips":["Feed the AI real specifics (exact price, date, neighborhood, a number) in your subject sentence; specifics are what make the DESIRE and ACTION blocks convincing instead of generic.","Ask for three different ATTENTION lines so you can pick the strongest hook, the opening line does most of the work in stopping a scroll.","Tell the AI your channel and character limit up front (Instagram caption, 300 characters); it will scale the scaffold so your assembled copy actually fits.","Keep your call to action to a single ask with a single link, one clear next step converts far better than three competing options.","Save your favorite finished scaffold as a template and reuse it for the next launch, just swap the subject and facts."],"mistakes":["Letting the AI write the whole post from a vague prompt, you get bland, factless filler; fix it by making the AI scaffold first and filling the blocks with your own real details.","Skipping the Action block or making it fuzzy (learn more), so readers never actually do anything; always end with one concrete step and a link, date, or button.","Front-loading features instead of attention, opening with we are pleased to announce puts the boring part first; lead with the reader's pain or a hook, not your announcement.","Trusting invented details, AI can guess a price or date you never gave it; always verify every number and fact before you publish.","Making it too long for the channel, a flyer paragraph pasted as an Instagram caption gets truncated; tell the AI the format and length so the assembled copy fits where it will live."],"related":["t7","t12","t14"]},{"id":"t20","num":20,"cat":"W","title":"Technical-to-Plain-Language Structural Translator","tagline":"Turn a wall of dense engineering specs or IT patch notes into a clear writing plan — so you can explain a complex internal system to everyday users without getting lost.","audience":"Business analysts, technical writers, customer-support coordinators, and training specialists who have to take something built by engineers or accountants and explain it to non-technical customers, staff, or students — people who are strong writers but not subject-matter experts in the system they're documenting.","why":"When you have to write help docs, a policy explainer, or a training page about a complicated internal system, the hardest part isn't the writing — it's figuring out where to start and what your reader actually needs to understand. Staring at a dense spec, most people either copy the jargon straight through (and lose the reader) or over-simplify and leave out the one warning that prevents support tickets. This technique flips the usual AI move: instead of asking the AI to write the explanation for you (which produces generic, sometimes wrong text), you ask it to build a writing scaffold — the analogy to use, the acronyms you must define, the how-to layout, and the mistake to warn about. You stay the author, so the final words are accurate and in your voice, but you skip the blank-page paralysis and the risk of forgetting a key piece. Reach for this whenever a tech-heavy update has to be understood by people who didn't build it.","need":["The dense source text you need to translate: engineering specs, IT patch/release notes, an internal accounting rule, or a system-design doc — a chunk you can copy and paste","A cloud AI assistant OR a local model running in a chat interface","A rough idea of who the final reader is (customers? new hires? non-finance staff?) so you can tell the AI who to aim at","5-10 minutes to review the scaffold and then write from it — the AI plans, you write"],"steps":[{"title":"Gather the technical source text","detail":"Copy the dense material you have to explain — the engineering spec, the IT patch notes, the accounting rule, whatever it is. Paste it into a scratch note first so you can see it plainly; if it's a PDF or a long document, most cloud tools let you upload the file directly instead of pasting. The AI can only build a good scaffold from what you give it, so include the whole relevant section, not just a sentence."},{"title":"Tell the AI who the real reader is","detail":"Before you run the prompt, decide your audience in plain terms: paying customers, brand-new employees, or staff outside the technical team. This one detail changes everything the AI suggests — an analogy that lands for engineers is useless for retirees using a billing portal. You'll drop this into the prompt where it says [WHO YOUR READERS ARE]."},{"title":"Run the 'build me a scaffold, don't write it' prompt","detail":"Paste the prompt below along with your source text. Notice the crucial instruction: 'Do not write the explanation for me.' This is deliberate. You want the AI to act like an instructional designer handing you a blueprint — an analogy, the acronyms to define, a how-to outline, and a warning to include — not to hand you finished paragraphs that might contain invented details."},{"title":"Sanity-check the scaffold against your source","detail":"Read the four pieces the AI gives back. Does the analogy actually fit, or is it cute but misleading? Are the acronyms it flagged really the confusing ones in your text? Look up any acronym definition it offers against your source doc — the AI can guess wrong on internal, company-specific terms it has never seen. Keep what's right, fix what's off; the scaffold is a starting point, not gospel."},{"title":"Write the documentation yourself, following the scaffold","detail":"Now you write — but you're no longer facing a blank page. Open the analogy, define the three acronyms in plain words, fill in the how-to steps the outline gave you, and add the warning callout. Because you're writing the actual sentences, the final doc is accurate, in your organization's voice, and safe to publish. This is the payoff: the AI removed the planning burden, and you kept full control of the words your users will read."},{"title":"Do a final read as if you were the user","detail":"Read your finished draft slowly, pretending you know nothing about the system. If any sentence would make a first-time reader pause, simplify it. Confirm every number, setting name, and step matches the original technical source exactly — this is the step that prevents a wrong instruction from turning into a flood of support tickets."}],"prompt":"You are an expert instructional designer and plain-language editor. I need to explain a complex internal system to a non-technical audience, and I want YOU TO BUILD A WRITING SCAFFOLD — do NOT write the explanation or the final documentation for me.\n\nMy readers are: [WHO YOUR READERS ARE — e.g., paying customers with no technical background / brand-new employees on day one / staff outside the finance team].\n\nBased only on the technical source text below, generate a 4-part scaffold optimized for absolute beginners:\n\nSTEP 1 — ANALOGY: Suggest one clear, everyday real-world analogy I can use to explain the core concept. Explain in one sentence why it fits, and note any way it could mislead a reader so I can avoid overstretching it.\n\nSTEP 2 — ACRONYMS & JARGON TO DEFINE: Identify the top 3 acronyms or technical terms from the source text that I MUST explicitly define for a non-expert. For each, give a plain-language, one-sentence definition. Flag with \"(VERIFY)\" any term that appears to be internal or company-specific so I know to double-check it against our own docs.\n\nSTEP 3 — HOW-TO OUTLINE: Give me a bullet-point outline (headings and sub-points, not full sentences) for a step-by-step \"How-To\" guide the reader could follow. Put the steps in the correct order and note where a screenshot or example would help.\n\nSTEP 4 — WARNING CALLOUT: Identify the single most likely mistake this reader would make, and tell me what the \"Warning\" callout box should caution them about. State the consequence of the mistake in plain terms.\n\nDo not summarize the source text and do not write finished paragraphs — return only the four scaffold parts as labeled sections.\n\nTECHNICAL SOURCE TEXT:\n[PASTE THE ENGINEERING SPEC / PATCH NOTES / RULE HERE]","promptNote":"Replace [WHO YOUR READERS ARE] with your actual audience and [PASTE THE ENGINEERING SPEC...] with your source text. The load-bearing line is 'do NOT write the explanation for me' — that's what turns the AI into a planner instead of a ghostwriter, which keeps the final words accurate and in your voice.","cloud":{"bestTool":"Anthropic Claude — it handles very long, messy technical documents in one paste and is strong at plain-language rewriting, so you can drop in a whole spec or full set of patch notes without trimming it down.","steps":["Open claude.ai and start a new chat.","Upload your spec/patch-notes file, or paste the source text directly into the message.","Paste the prompt above, fill in [WHO YOUR READERS ARE], and send.","Review the four parts; if the analogy is weak, reply 'give me two alternative analogies aimed at total beginners' and pick the best.","Ask a follow-up like 'quote the exact line in the source where you found the DTC deadline' for anything you plan to publish as fact."]},"local":["Open your local chat interface (for example, Open WebUI connected to Ollama, or LM Studio) — the model is already installed and ready.","Select a capable instruction-following model such as Llama 3 or Gemma.","Paste the prompt above with your source text and audience filled in, then run it.","Read the four scaffold parts and iterate right there if needed — because everything runs on your own machine, an unreleased feature spec, internal patch notes, or a confidential accounting rule never leaves your device."],"localNeedsSetup":true,"choose":"If the source is already-public or low-sensitivity — a general help article, a feature most customers already know about — a cloud tool like Claude is the fastest and easiest choice. But this task very often involves INTERNAL systems: unreleased engineering specs, security-relevant patch notes, or proprietary accounting rules that describe how your company actually works. That's exactly the kind of material that shouldn't be pasted into a third-party service. When the source text is unreleased, confidential, security-sensitive, or covered by an NDA, use a local model so the spec never leaves your computer — you still get the same scaffold, with none of the exposure.","example":{"input":"PATCH NOTE v4.2 — MFA enforcement. Effective 08/01, all users must complete TOTP-based 2FA enrollment via the IdP portal. Grace period: 14 days post-first-login. Users who do not enroll before the DTC (Drop-Dead Cutoff) will be locked out and must contact the helpdesk for manual SSO re-provisioning. RADIUS fallback is deprecated.","output":"STEP 1 — ANALOGY\nUse a house with a new deadbolt: your password is the doorknob lock, and 2FA is the second deadbolt you now also have to turn with a code from your phone. Fits because it shows 'two locks, not one.' Caution: don't imply the phone code is optional — with a deadbolt you can skip it, but here you cannot.\n\nSTEP 2 — ACRONYMS TO DEFINE\n- MFA / 2FA: Signing in with two proofs — your password plus a one-time code from an app on your phone.\n- TOTP: The 6-digit code that refreshes every 30 seconds in an authenticator app.\n- DTC (Drop-Dead Cutoff) (VERIFY): The final date to enroll before you're locked out — confirm the exact date against our internal calendar.\n\nSTEP 3 — HOW-TO OUTLINE\n- Before you start: install an authenticator app (screenshot of app store)\n- Step 1: Log in to the IdP portal\n- Step 2: Open Security > Enroll in 2FA\n- Step 3: Scan the QR code with your app (screenshot)\n- Step 4: Enter the 6-digit code to confirm\n- Step 5: Save your backup codes somewhere safe\n\nSTEP 4 — WARNING CALLOUT\nWarn: 'You have 14 days after your first login — enroll before the cutoff date. Miss it and you'll be locked out and must call the helpdesk to regain access.' Most likely mistake: assuming the grace period means it's optional.","note":"Notice the AI flagged 'DTC' with (VERIFY) because it's an internal term — a cue to check the real date before publishing, not to trust the AI's guess."},"tips":["Always name your reader in the prompt. 'Explain to beginners' is vague; 'explain to retirees using our billing app for the first time' produces a scaffold that actually fits.","If the analogy feels weak, ask for two or three alternatives and pick the one that fits your audience — analogies are the highest-leverage part of the scaffold.","Ask the AI to 'quote the exact source line' behind any acronym definition or deadline before you publish it as fact — it protects you from a confidently wrong internal term.","Run the scaffold prompt once per reader type. The same patch note needs a different analogy and warning for customers than for internal staff.","Keep the AI's four-part output pinned next to your draft so you can check off each piece — analogy used, acronyms defined, steps written, warning added."],"mistakes":["Letting the AI write the whole explanation. The instruction 'do not write it for me' exists on purpose — finished AI paragraphs can smuggle in invented details about your internal system. Keep the AI as a planner and write the words yourself.","Trusting acronym definitions blindly. The AI can confidently mis-define a company-specific term it has never seen; verify anything flagged (VERIFY) — and ideally everything — against your real source doc.","Skipping the audience line. If you don't tell the AI who reads this, you'll get a generic scaffold aimed at nobody; fill in [WHO YOUR READERS ARE] every time.","Pasting confidential internal specs into a public cloud tool. If the material is unreleased or sensitive, use a local model instead so nothing leaves your machine.","Publishing without a final beginner read-through. The scaffold gets you 80% there, but a wrong number or an unexplained step still causes support tickets — read it once as if you knew nothing about the system."],"related":["t7","t12","t14"]},{"id":"t30","num":30,"cat":"W","title":"The Performance Review Metric Matrix Builder","tagline":"Turn a scribbled list of \"stuff I did this year\" into polished, metric-driven performance-review bullet points that make your impact obvious to a boss.","audience":"Employees writing their own annual self-evaluation who freeze up when the review form asks them to \"describe your accomplishments,\" and managers drafting assessments for the people on their team. No writing skill, HR jargon, or AI experience is assumed. If you can describe what you did in plain everyday words, you can do this.","why":"Most people are genuinely bad at describing their own work, not because they did little, but because they write it the way they'd tell a friend: \"I helped clean up the intake forms.\" A reviewer reading that has no idea whether you saved the team ten minutes or ten thousand dollars. AI is unusually good at this exact translation job: you feed it the flat, modest version and it reframes each item to lead with the business result (time saved, errors reduced, people trained), swaps weak verbs like \"helped\" and \"worked on\" for strong ones like \"led\" and \"streamlined,\" and adds the structure that turns a chore into an achievement. Reach for this whenever you have to fill in a review form, update a promotion packet, refresh a resume, or write a \"brag document\" and you're staring at a blank box, unsure how to make routine work sound like the real contribution it was.","need":["A chat AI tool: a cloud one (Microsoft Copilot, Google Gemini, or Anthropic Claude) or a local model already running on your computer.","A rough, unpolished list of what you actually did this review period, written however it comes out of your head. Spelling and grammar do not matter.","Any real numbers you can remember or look up: how many people, how many hours, how often, how much, the before-versus-after. These are what turn a vague chore into a credible achievement.","Your company's core values or the review form's rating categories, if you have them, so the phrasing can aim at what your employer actually rewards.","Five quiet minutes at the end to read every bullet and confirm it is true. You are signing your name to this, so nothing invented is allowed."],"steps":[{"title":"Brain-dump everything you did, in plain words","detail":"Before you touch the AI, open a blank note and list your accomplishments the way you'd tell a coworker over coffee: 'redid the intake forms, ran some onboarding sessions, stayed late to get the monthly report out.' Do not try to make it sound impressive yet, that is the AI's job. The goal here is completeness, so skim your calendar, sent email, and finished projects to jog your memory, because the biggest mistake is forgetting your own wins."},{"title":"Add the numbers you can remember","detail":"Go back through your dump and tack a number onto anything you can: 'ran 3 onboarding sessions for 12 new hires,' 'monthly report, normally takes 2 days, I got it out in half.' Numbers are the single biggest difference between a bullet a reviewer skims and one they remember. If you truly don't have a figure, leave it out rather than guessing, and you'll tell the AI not to invent any."},{"title":"Open your AI tool and paste in the prompt","detail":"Open Copilot, Gemini, Claude, or your local chat app and paste the full prompt from the Prompt section below. Then replace the bracketed placeholders with your own brain-dump, your company's core values, and your job level. The prompt does the heavy lifting: it tells the AI to lead with business impact, use strong verbs, and, critically, never fabricate numbers you didn't provide."},{"title":"Read the draft with a skeptical eye","detail":"The AI will hand you clean, punchy bullets, but treat every one as a proposal, not a finished product. Read each and ask two questions: Is this literally true? and Would my manager agree I did this? Watch specifically for inflated claims (an AI loves to promote 'helped with' into 'spearheaded companywide') and for any number you did not give it, which it may have quietly guessed. Cross out or fix anything that overreaches, because an exaggeration a reviewer can disprove damages you more than a modest truth."},{"title":"Push back to sharpen or retarget","detail":"You are not stuck with the first draft. Type follow-ups in plain English: 'Make bullet 2 shorter,' 'These sound too corporate, dial it back one notch,' 'Rewrite all of them to emphasize teamwork instead of leadership,' or 'Give me a version aimed at a promotion to senior.' Each reply refines the same list. This back-and-forth is where a good draft becomes yours, so spend a minute or two here."},{"title":"Pick the strongest ones and paste them into the real form","detail":"You rarely need every bullet the AI produced. Choose the 4 to 8 that best cover your biggest results and map to your review's rating categories, then paste those into your official self-evaluation, promotion packet, or resume. Do a final read in the actual form to confirm the tone matches your workplace and that each line still sounds like something you'd comfortably say out loud in the review meeting."}],"prompt":"You are an expert career coach who writes performance-review self-evaluations. Below are my rough, casual notes about what I accomplished this review period. Transform them into professional self-evaluation bullet points for a [YOUR LEVEL, e.g. mid-level analyst / senior manager] annual performance review.\n\nRules:\n- Reframe each activity to lead with the business impact: time saved, cost or overhead reduced, errors avoided, people trained, or process improved.\n- Start every bullet with a strong active verb (Led, Streamlined, Built, Trained, Reduced, Delivered). Do not use weak openers like \"Helped,\" \"Worked on,\" or \"Was responsible for.\"\n- Use ONLY the facts and numbers I give you. Do NOT invent, estimate, or inflate any metric, headcount, dollar figure, or percentage. If a bullet would be stronger with a number I didn't provide, add \"[add metric]\" as a placeholder so I can fill it in.\n- Keep each bullet to one or two sentences. Plain, confident business English, no empty buzzwords.\n- Where it fits naturally, connect the accomplishment to these company core values / review categories: [PASTE YOUR CORE VALUES OR RATING CATEGORIES, or write \"none\"].\n- After the bullets, add a short section titled \"Numbers to confirm\" listing every place I should double-check or fill in a figure.\n\nMy rough notes:\n[PASTE YOUR CASUAL BRAIN-DUMP HERE]","promptNote":"Replace [YOUR LEVEL] with your role so the tone matches (a senior manager's bullets emphasize leadership; an analyst's emphasize execution). Paste your unpolished list into [PASTE YOUR CASUAL BRAIN-DUMP HERE]. Drop your company's core values or the form's rating categories into the bracketed values line, or write \"none\" if you don't have them. The \"do not invent numbers\" rule and the \"Numbers to confirm\" section are the safety net that keeps you from signing off on something untrue.","cloud":{"bestTool":"Anthropic Claude, because this is pure nuanced business writing where wording quality matters most, and Claude produces the most natural, non-buzzwordy professional phrasing of the three; pick Microsoft Copilot instead if your review form lives in Word or your company standardizes on Microsoft 365, since it can draft right inside the document.","steps":["Open claude.ai (or Copilot / Gemini) in your browser and sign in, then start a new chat.","Paste the full prompt from the Prompt section, then fill in the three placeholders with your brain-dump, your level, and your core values.","Press enter and read the bullets it returns, paying attention to the 'Numbers to confirm' section at the bottom.","Refine with plain-English follow-ups like 'shorten these' or 'emphasize teamwork more,' then copy the winners into your review form."]},"local":["Open your local chat interface (for example Open WebUI connected to Ollama, or LM Studio) and pick your installed model, ideally a capable general-purpose one like a Llama, Qwen, or Mistral chat model.","Start a new conversation and paste the full prompt from the Prompt section, then fill in your brain-dump, level, and core values in the brackets.","Send it and review the bullets. Local models can be a little more repetitive, so if a bullet is weak, ask it to 'rewrite bullet 3 to be more specific' or 'vary the opening verbs.'","Since your notes and the polished result never leave your computer, freely include real names, dollar figures, and internal project details, then copy the final bullets into your review form."],"localNeedsSetup":true,"choose":"Your honest self-assessment is sensitive HR data: it can name projects, salaries implied by dollar figures, coworkers, and internal weaknesses, and it is tied directly to your career. If your notes mention confidential financials, client names, unreleased projects, or anything about other employees, do it on a LOCAL model so nothing about your review ever touches an outside company's servers. For a routine self-eval built from generic, non-confidential accomplishments, a cloud tool is perfectly fine and by far the easiest, just avoid pasting in secrets, and when in doubt, keep it local.","example":{"input":"Please turn these into performance review bullets for a mid-level operations analyst. Core values: Customer Focus, Efficiency, Teamwork. My notes: redid the customer intake forms because people kept filling them out wrong, ran a couple onboarding workshops for the 8 new hires this year, and I stayed late a bunch of times to get the monthly finance report out, it usually takes 2 full days and I got it down to about 1.","output":"Self-evaluation bullets:\n\n- Redesigned the customer intake forms to eliminate the most common submission errors, reducing rework for downstream teams and improving data quality at first contact (Customer Focus). [add metric: % drop in form errors]\n\n- Designed and led onboarding workshops for all 8 new hires this year, accelerating their ramp-up and strengthening team consistency (Teamwork).\n\n- Streamlined the monthly finance reporting process, cutting turnaround from roughly 2 days to 1 and freeing analyst time for higher-value work (Efficiency).\n\nNumbers to confirm:\n- Form-error reduction: you said errors dropped but gave no figure, add the percentage or before/after count if you have it.\n- Onboarding: 8 new hires confirmed. Consider adding number of workshops.\n- Finance report: 2 days down to ~1 day confirmed. You could add how many months you did this.","note":"Notice it led with the result (fewer errors, faster report), swapped 'stayed late a bunch' for 'streamlined,' tagged each bullet to a core value, and refused to invent the error-rate number, flagging it as [add metric] instead."},"tips":["Feed it numbers or it will feel generic. 'Trained new hires' is forgettable; 'Trained 12 new hires across 3 sessions' is a fact a reviewer remembers. Even rough estimates you can defend beat none.","Ask for the same accomplishment aimed different ways. Try 'give me one version for my review and one for my resume,' or 'rewrite emphasizing leadership' if you're going for a promotion. Same facts, retargeted framing.","Give it your company's actual core values or the review form's rating categories. The AI will thread your work through them, which is exactly what a reviewer scores you against.","Keep a running 'brag document' all year in a plain note. Jot wins as they happen, then run the whole thing through this prompt at review time instead of trying to remember 12 months in one panicked evening.","If a bullet sounds too slick or corporate, tell it 'dial the tone down one notch, make it sound like a real person.' Over-polished bullets read as AI-written and undercut your credibility."],"mistakes":["Signing off on inflated claims. AIs love to promote 'helped organize' into 'spearheaded a companywide initiative.' Read every bullet and cut anything your manager could reasonably dispute, because one exaggeration a reviewer catches poisons the whole document.","Accepting invented numbers. If you didn't give a figure, any percentage or dollar amount in the output was guessed. The prompt tells it not to, but verify: replace every [add metric] with a real number or delete the claim.","Pasting in confidential data on a cloud tool. Salaries, client names, unreleased products, or comments about coworkers should go through a local model, not an outside company's server. Strip secrets first or work locally.","Using every bullet it produces. More is not better on a review form. Pick the 4 to 8 strongest that map to your rating categories; a tight list of real wins beats a long list of padded ones.","Doing it all in one late-night session from memory. You'll forget your best work. Build the brain-dump over days, check your calendar and sent mail, then run it, so the AI has real material to sharpen."],"related":["t7","t12","t14"]},{"id":"t10","num":10,"cat":"B","title":"Multi-Agent Role-Play Strategic Sandbox","tagline":"Turn any AI chat into a virtual boardroom where a skeptical CFO, a risk-averse security chief, and an aggressive marketing VP tear into your plan before real stakeholders ever see it.","audience":"Business students refining a class pitch, entrepreneurs polishing an investor deck or launch plan, and executives or managers stress-testing a strategy before a real meeting. In short: anyone who has to defend a decision to people with competing priorities and would rather find the holes in private first.","why":"Good plans die in meetings because the person who built them can only see them from one angle. A founder in love with growth forgets what it costs; a numbers person forgets the security exposure; nobody stress-tests the brand story. This trick forces the AI to argue with itself from three hostile-but-realistic viewpoints at once, so you hear the CFO's \"what does this cost and when do we earn it back?\", the security chief's \"where does customer data leak and what regulation does that break?\", and the marketing VP's \"why will anyone care and how fast can we ship?\" all in one sitting. It is a rehearsal, not a verdict: the AI is not deciding anything, it is surfacing the objections you would otherwise get blindsided by. Reach for it before a pitch, a board review, a funding ask, or any go/no-go decision, so you walk into the real room already knowing your three weakest points with an answer ready for each.","need":["A written version of your plan or pitch — even a rough paragraph works, but the more specific the better","An AI chat tool: a cloud one (Claude, Gemini, or Copilot) for convenience, or a local model for privacy","A clear idea of which three viewpoints matter most for your decision (money, risk, growth is a strong default)","About 20–30 minutes and a willingness to hear your plan get criticized","A blank doc or notepad to capture the objections you will actually fix"],"steps":[{"title":"Write your plan down before you open the AI","detail":"The panel can only critique what you actually tell it, so spend five minutes writing your proposal in plain language first. Include the what (the product or decision), the who (target customer), the money (rough costs, price, and how you make revenue), and the timeline. A vague pitch gets vague criticism; a specific one like 'a $29/month app that stores client tax documents' gets sharp, usable objections you can act on."},{"title":"Cast your panel and give each persona one narrow job","detail":"The magic is in the constraints: each executive must care about only one thing, because that is what makes them argue instead of politely agreeing. The default trio covers the three ways plans fail — the CFO attacks the money, the Chief Information Security Officer attacks the risk and compliance, and the VP of Marketing attacks the growth story. Paste the ready-made prompt below, which locks in those mandates and tells the AI to keep the personas in character."},{"title":"Paste the prompt, then paste your plan","detail":"Send the panel-setup prompt first and let the AI confirm the three roles are ready. Then paste your written plan as the next message. Splitting it into two messages matters: it lets the AI fully 'become' the panel before it sees your idea, which produces sharper, more in-character critiques than dumping everything at once."},{"title":"Read the critique looking for what you did NOT already know","detail":"You will get a structured reply where each executive raises specific objections from their mandate. Skim past anything you already planned for and star the objections that genuinely land — the security gap you had not considered, the cost you underestimated, the reason a customer might shrug. Those two or three real hits are the entire point of the exercise; everything else is noise."},{"title":"Push back and make them defend their objections","detail":"This is a conversation, not a report. Reply to the panel — 'CFO, I actually have a lower-cost path using existing tools, does that change your view?' or 'CISO, we plan to encrypt everything at rest, is that enough for HIPAA?'. Making the personas respond to your rebuttals either confirms the objection is real or reveals your answer is weak. This back-and-forth is where you rehearse the actual defense you will give in the real meeting."},{"title":"Ask for a consensus verdict and a fix list","detail":"Once the dialogue settles, ask the panel to step out of character and give you a combined summary: the top three risks across all viewpoints and the single most important change each executive wants. This turns a messy debate into a short, prioritized to-do list. It also forces the AI to reconcile the conflicts — for example, the marketing VP's 'ship fast' versus the security chief's 'slow down and audit.'"},{"title":"Revise your plan and, if it matters, run the panel again","detail":"Update your written proposal to close the real gaps you found — add the missing budget line, the encryption plan, the sharper value proposition. For a high-stakes pitch, start a fresh chat, paste the same panel prompt, and feed it your revised plan. If the objections have shrunk from 'this will fail' to nitpicks, you are ready for the real room."}],"prompt":"Act as a panel of three distinct corporate executives running a boardroom review of my business proposal. Each of you cares about ONLY your own mandate and must stay in character. Do not soften your critiques to be polite, and do not agree with each other by default — if you disagree, say so.\n\nThe three personas are:\n\n1. CHIEF FINANCIAL OFFICER (CFO) — Skeptical and numbers-driven. You care only about immediate ROI, cash flow, cost of customer acquisition, and minimizing operating expense. You distrust optimistic projections and always ask \"what does this cost, when do we break even, and what happens if we're half as successful as planned?\"\n\n2. CHIEF INFORMATION SECURITY OFFICER (CISO) — Risk-averse and compliance-focused. You care only about data privacy, security vulnerabilities, and regulatory exposure (e.g., [GDPR / HIPAA / PCI-DSS / SOC 2 — keep whichever apply]). You always ask \"where does sensitive data live, who can access it, and what law or standard do we violate if it leaks?\"\n\n3. VP OF MARKETING — Aggressive and growth-obsessed. You care only about speed to market, brand positioning, competitive differentiation, and hyper-scale growth. You always ask \"why will a customer choose us over the alternative, and what's slowing us down?\"\n\nHere is how I want you to work:\n- First, briefly confirm the three roles are ready (one line). Do NOT critique yet.\n- I will then paste my proposal in my next message.\n- After you see it, produce a structured critique: a clearly labeled section for each executive listing their top 2–3 objections, phrased in their voice, each tied to a specific part of my plan.\n- End each executive's section with the single question they most want me to answer.\n- Then pause and let me respond, so we can have a real back-and-forth.\n\nMy industry / context is: [DESCRIBE YOUR BUSINESS OR PROJECT IN ONE LINE]. My audience for the eventual real pitch is: [e.g., a venture investor / my professor / my company's board]. Confirm you understand the three roles and are ready for my proposal.","promptNote":"Fill the bracketed spots: pick the regulations that actually touch your business (delete the rest), describe your business in one line, and name who you will really pitch to so the panel calibrates its bar. You can also swap a persona — replace the CISO with a \"Head of Operations\" or a \"Legal Counsel\" if that risk matters more to your specific decision.","cloud":{"bestTool":"Anthropic Claude — it holds three distinct personas in character over a long back-and-forth without them blurring into one polite voice, which is exactly what a multi-turn boardroom simulation needs.","steps":["Go to claude.ai and start a new chat. Paste the panel-setup prompt above (with your brackets filled in) and send it; wait for Claude to confirm the three roles are ready.","Paste your written proposal as the next message. Read the structured critique and note which objections genuinely surprised you.","Reply directly to specific executives to push back and test your answers ('CFO, here's my lower-cost path — does that change your view?'). Keep the thread going until the objections stop landing.","Ask the panel to drop character and give you a consensus summary: the top three risks and the one change each executive most wants.","Copy that fix list into your notes, revise your plan, and — for a high-stakes pitch — open a fresh chat and run the same prompt against your revised version to check the objections have shrunk."]},"local":["Open your local chat interface (Open WebUI if you run Ollama, or the chat tab in LM Studio) and pick a capable instruct model — a 7B–8B model like Llama 3.1 8B or Mistral handles this well; a larger model keeps the three personas more distinct.","Paste the same panel-setup prompt above and send it. Wait for the model to confirm the three roles before you feed it anything sensitive.","Paste your real proposal — including confidential numbers, client names, or unreleased strategy — because on a local model nothing leaves your machine.","Have the back-and-forth: reply to individual personas, push on weak objections, and if a smaller model starts letting the three voices blend together, remind it with 'Stay in character — CFO responds only about ROI and cost.'","Ask for the consensus verdict and fix list, then copy it out. Because the whole session is local, you can save the transcript to a private file without worrying about where it was stored."],"localNeedsSetup":true,"choose":"If your proposal contains anything you would not email to a stranger — unreleased financials, a client roster, a patentable idea, acquisition plans, or personal data — run this on a LOCAL model, because a strategy sandbox works best when you paste the real, sensitive numbers, and on a local model that data never leaves your computer. A pitch you are about to make public anyway (a class project, a generic launch concept) is low-risk, so a cloud tool like Claude is the easier, higher-quality choice and its stronger persona control is worth it. When in doubt with early-stage or confidential strategy, default to local: the honest critique depends on feeding it details you would not want leaking.","example":{"input":"Proposal: 'TaxVault' — a $29/month web app where independent bookkeepers upload and store their clients' tax documents (W-2s, 1099s, receipts). We plan to launch in 8 weeks, spend our whole $15k budget on Instagram ads, and store files on a standard cloud bucket. Revenue is subscriptions; we project 500 paying users in month one.","output":"Panel ready. Here is our review of TaxVault.\n\nCHIEF FINANCIAL OFFICER\n- $15k spent entirely on Instagram ads to reach bookkeepers is a mismatch — your buyers are on LinkedIn and in accounting forums, not scrolling Reels. Your cost per acquisition assumption is invisible here.\n- 500 paying users in month one from a cold start is a fantasy. At $29/mo that's $14,500 revenue against $15k spend — you break even on paper and have zero cash cushion for month two.\n- Most important question: What is your realistic cost to acquire ONE paying bookkeeper, and how many months of runway do you have if you get 50 users, not 500?\n\nCHIEF INFORMATION SECURITY OFFICER\n- You are storing other people's tax documents — that is highly sensitive PII. A 'standard cloud bucket' with no stated encryption or access controls is a breach waiting to happen and a lawsuit if it leaks.\n- Bookkeepers handling this data may fall under IRS Publication 4557 and state privacy laws; you have named no compliance posture at all.\n- Most important question: Where exactly does this data sit, is it encrypted at rest and in transit, and who on your team can access a client's files?\n\nVP OF MARKETING\n- 'Store your tax docs' is a feature, not a reason to switch. Bookkeepers already dump files in Dropbox for free — what is the one painful problem you solve that they can't ignore?\n- 8 weeks to launch is fine, but you have no positioning against QuickBooks or Dropbox, so you'll be invisible.\n- Most important question: In one sentence, why does a busy bookkeeper fire their current tool and pay you $29/month?\n\nYour move — respond to any of us and we'll dig in.","note":"Notice the three voices never overlap: the CFO ignores security entirely, the CISO ignores growth, and each ends with the one question you must be able to answer in a real pitch."},"tips":["Give each persona ONE mandate and forbid overlap — the moment two executives start caring about the same thing, they agree instead of arguing, and you lose the tension that makes this useful.","Feed the panel real numbers and specifics, not a polished summary. 'We'll spend the marketing budget wisely' produces a shrug; '$15k, all on Instagram, targeting bookkeepers' produces a devastating, fixable objection.","Argue back. The first critique is just the opening; the value comes when you defend your plan and the personas either concede or expose that your defense is thin.","Match the panel to your actual risks — swap the CISO for a Legal Counsel, an Operations lead, or a skeptical Customer, whichever viewpoint would really sink your plan.","End with the 'drop character, give me the top 3 fixes' request so you leave with a prioritized action list, not a wall of debate you have to re-read."],"mistakes":["Making the personas too agreeable — if you write 'a helpful panel of advisors,' they'll flatter you. Explicitly tell them to be skeptical, aggressive, and to disagree with each other.","Pasting a vague, one-line pitch and expecting sharp feedback. Weak input equals weak output; write the specific plan first (step 1) before you ever open the AI.","Treating the AI's critique as a final verdict. It is a rehearsal that surfaces objections, not a decision-maker — you still judge which objections are real and worth fixing.","Using a cloud tool for genuinely confidential strategy. If the plan involves real client data, unreleased numbers, or IP, run it locally so nothing leaves your machine — otherwise you're pasting secrets into someone else's server.","Reading the critique and doing nothing with it. The exercise only pays off if you capture the two or three real hits and actually revise the plan (steps 6 and 7) before the real meeting."],"related":["t16","t21","t26"]},{"id":"t16","num":16,"cat":"B","title":"Competitive Product Feature Comparison Matrix","tagline":"Turn a pile of competitor marketing blurbs and spec sheets into one clean, side-by-side comparison table that instantly shows where each product wins, loses, or stays suspiciously vague.","audience":"Product managers, business development and sales staff, and retail or procurement buyers who need to size up competing products fast.","why":"When you are trying to position your product or decide which supplier to buy from, the hardest part is not finding information — it is that every competitor describes themselves differently. One brags about \"blazing speed,\" another quotes an exact number, a third stays silent on price. Reading five web pages and mentally lining them up is slow and error-prone, and you tend to miss the gaps — the things a competitor conveniently left out. An AI model is very good at this specific chore: you paste in the raw promotional text, and it reorganizes everything into the same rows and columns so you can compare apples to apples in seconds. The real payoff is the \"Notes\" column, where the AI flags vague claims and missing information — those gaps are exactly where your sales talking points or your negotiating leverage live.","need":["An AI chat tool: a cloud one (Claude, Google Gemini, or Microsoft Copilot) for speed, or a local model (via LM Studio or Ollama + Open WebUI) if the pricing/deal info is confidential.","The raw text for each competitor: copied from their website, a product PDF, a spec sheet, or a marketing pamphlet. Two to four competitors works best.","A clear idea of which attributes matter to you (price, performance, warranty, target customer, etc.) so you can tell the AI what rows to build.","A few minutes to sanity-check the result against the original text — the AI organizes what you give it, it does not fact-check the competitor's claims for you."],"steps":[{"title":"Gather each competitor's raw text into separate, clearly labeled blocks","detail":"Go to each competitor's product page, spec sheet, or brochure and copy the relevant text — pricing, features, performance claims, warranty terms, who it is for. Paste each competitor's text into a scratch document under a clear heading like 'COMPETITOR A: Acme Pro' and 'COMPETITOR B: BoltMax'. Keeping them separate and labeled is what lets the AI keep the columns straight; if you paste everything in one undifferentiated wall of text, it will guess at the boundaries and may mix up who said what."},{"title":"Decide which rows (attributes) you actually care about","detail":"The comparison is only useful if it compares the things that drive your decision. The default set — Pricing Model, Stated Performance Limits, Included Warranties, and Target Audience — is a solid start, but add rows that matter to you, such as 'Integrations', 'Support Hours', 'Contract Length', or 'Certifications'. Deciding this up front means the table answers your real question instead of a generic one. You will list these rows inside the prompt in the next step."},{"title":"Paste the prompt, then paste the competitor blocks beneath it","detail":"Copy the prompt from the Prompt section below into the AI chat box. Replace the bracketed placeholders with your chosen attributes and competitor names, then paste your labeled competitor blocks right underneath where the prompt says to. The prompt does the heavy lifting: it tells the AI to build a markdown table, put attributes as rows and competitors as columns, and — critically — add a 'Notes' column that flags anything vague or missing. Send it and you will get a formatted table back in seconds."},{"title":"Read the Notes column first — that is where the strategy is","detail":"Skim the table top to bottom, but pay special attention to the Notes column. When the AI writes something like 'Competitor B gives no specific number, only the word fast' or 'No warranty length stated', it has just handed you a gap in their story. These gaps are your leverage: a missing warranty is a talking point for your sales team, and a vague performance claim is a question to raise with a buyer. This is the difference between a table that just informs you and one that actually sharpens your positioning."},{"title":"Verify a few cells against the original text","detail":"AI models occasionally 'fill in' a plausible-sounding detail that was never in the source, or misread a number. Before you trust the table, spot-check two or three of the most important cells — especially prices and performance numbers — against the text you pasted. If a cell says something the source did not, tell the AI 'The source for Competitor A never mentions a price; correct that cell to say Not stated.' This 30-second check keeps you from walking into a meeting with a confidently wrong figure."},{"title":"Ask a follow-up to turn the table into talking points or a recommendation","detail":"You are already in a conversation, so put the AI to work on the 'so what'. Ask 'Based on this table, write three sales talking points that highlight where Competitor B is weakest,' or 'Given my priorities are price and warranty, which product is the better buy and why?' Because the AI already has the full table in context, these answers are grounded in the comparison you just built rather than generic advice. Copy the table and the talking points into your deck, email, or buying memo."}],"prompt":"You are a competitive analyst helping me build a side-by-side product comparison.\n\nBelow are text blocks describing competing products, each labeled with the competitor's name. Read every block carefully and use ONLY the information stated in the text — do not invent, estimate, or add anything from outside knowledge.\n\nBuild a single, clean comparison in a markdown table.\n\n- Make each of these attributes a ROW (add or remove rows to fit what the text actually covers):\n  [Pricing Model], [Stated Performance / Limits], [Included Warranties], [Target Audience], [ADD YOUR OWN, e.g. Support Hours, Integrations, Contract Length]\n- Make each competitor a COLUMN, in this order: [Competitor A name], [Competitor B name], [Competitor C name if any].\n- Add one final COLUMN titled \"Notes\" where, for each row, you flag anything that is vague, unmeasurable marketing language (e.g. \"blazing fast\", \"industry-leading\"), inconsistent, or missing entirely from a competitor's text. If a competitor does not mention an attribute at all, write \"Not stated\" in that competitor's cell.\n\nRules:\n- Keep each cell short — a phrase or one sentence, not a paragraph.\n- Never leave a cell blank; use \"Not stated\" when the text is silent.\n- After the table, add a short section titled \"Biggest gaps\" listing the 3 most important pieces of missing or ambiguous information across all competitors, and why each matters to a buyer.\n\nHere are the competitor text blocks:\n\n[PASTE COMPETITOR A TEXT HERE]\n\n[PASTE COMPETITOR B TEXT HERE]\n\n[PASTE COMPETITOR C TEXT HERE — delete if only two]","promptNote":"Replace the bracketed row names with the attributes you care about and the bracketed competitor names with the real product names. The big brackets at the bottom are where you paste each competitor's raw copied text — keep them labeled so the AI keeps the columns straight. Delete the third column and third block if you only have two competitors.","cloud":{"bestTool":"Anthropic Claude — it is the strongest at carefully reading several pasted text blocks, keeping who-said-what straight, and returning a clean, well-structured table without inventing details, which is exactly this task; Google Gemini is the best alternative if your source material is very long (many pages of PDFs).","steps":["Go to claude.ai (or gemini.google.com) and sign in; open a new chat.","Paste the prompt from the Prompt section, then fill in your attribute rows and competitor names.","Paste each labeled competitor text block into the spots at the bottom of the prompt (or, in Gemini/Claude, attach the PDFs directly instead of copy-pasting), then send.","Read the returned table and the 'Biggest gaps' section; spot-check two or three key cells against your source text.","Iterate in the same chat: 'Add a row for Integrations', 'Turn Competitor B's weaknesses into three sales talking points', or 'Which is the better buy if price matters most?'"]},"local":["Open your local chat interface (LM Studio, or Open WebUI connected to Ollama) and select your installed model — a mid-size instruct model handles this comparison task well.","Start a new chat and paste the same prompt from the Prompt section, with your attribute rows and competitor names filled in.","Paste each labeled competitor text block beneath the prompt. If a competitor's material is a PDF, copy the text out of it first, since most local chat UIs read pasted text more reliably than attached files.","Send it and review the markdown table; if the formatting looks messy, add 'Return the table as clean markdown with a header row and aligned columns' and regenerate.","Refine privately in the same chat — ask for talking points or a buy recommendation — knowing none of the pricing or deal information ever left your computer."],"localNeedsSetup":true,"choose":"For comparing information a competitor has already published publicly — website copy, brochures, public spec sheets — a cloud tool is perfectly fine and by far the fastest, since that text is not secret. Lean local, however, the moment the blocks include anything you should not hand to a third party: confidential pricing you obtained through a deal, a partner's non-public quote, internal notes on your own product's weaknesses, or client-specific figures. In that case run it on a local model so the sensitive numbers and your strategic thinking never leave your device, which also keeps you clear of any confidentiality or NDA concerns.","example":{"input":"COMPETITOR A: Acme Pro\nAcme Pro is priced at $49 per user per month, billed annually. Handles up to 10,000 records with 99.9% uptime. Comes with a full 2-year hardware warranty. Built for mid-sized sales teams.\n\nCOMPETITOR B: BoltMax\nBoltMax offers flexible pricing to fit any budget — contact sales for a quote. Blazing-fast performance that scales effortlessly. Industry-leading support. The smart choice for growing businesses.","output":"Attribute | Acme Pro | BoltMax | Notes\nPricing Model | $49/user/mo, billed annually | Not stated (quote only) | BoltMax hides price behind 'contact sales'; hard to compare cost\nStated Performance / Limits | Up to 10,000 records, 99.9% uptime | 'Blazing-fast, scales effortlessly' | BoltMax gives no measurable numbers — pure marketing language\nIncluded Warranties | 2-year hardware warranty | Not stated | BoltMax lists no warranty at all\nTarget Audience | Mid-sized sales teams | 'Growing businesses' | Both vague-ish; Acme is more specific\n\nBiggest gaps:\n1. BoltMax has no published price — a buyer cannot budget or compare without contacting sales.\n2. BoltMax states no performance numbers, only 'blazing-fast' — unverifiable.\n3. BoltMax mentions no warranty, while Acme offers 2 years — a real risk difference.","note":"Notice how every one of BoltMax's fuzzy marketing phrases becomes a concrete gap in the Notes column — those are your exact talking points."},"tips":["Tell the AI to write 'Not stated' for anything missing rather than leaving cells blank — visible gaps are the whole point, and blanks are easy to overlook.","Explicitly instruct it to flag vague marketing words like 'blazing-fast' or 'industry-leading' in the Notes column; that is where competitors hide the absence of real numbers.","After the table, ask a second question — 'Rank these from best to worst value for a budget buyer' or 'Write my three strongest talking points' — since the AI already has the full comparison loaded.","If a competitor gives numbers in different units (per month vs per year, GB vs TB), add 'Normalize all prices to a monthly figure' so the columns are truly comparable.","Keep the original source text saved alongside the table, so anyone who questions a cell in a meeting can trace it straight back to the competitor's own words."],"mistakes":["Pasting all competitors as one undivided blob — the AI then guesses where one product's text ends and the next begins. Fix: label each block with the competitor's name before pasting.","Trusting every cell blindly. The AI organizes claims, it does not verify them, and it can occasionally invent a plausible number. Fix: spot-check prices and performance figures against the source before you rely on them.","Treating a competitor's marketing claim as fact. If BoltMax says 'blazing-fast', the table should record that it is vague, not translate it into a real spec. Fix: keep the 'flag vague claims' instruction in the prompt.","Comparing mismatched units and drawing a wrong conclusion — e.g. reading a yearly price as monthly. Fix: ask the AI to normalize units, and eyeball the numbers yourself.","Uploading confidential negotiated pricing or NDA-covered quotes to a public cloud tool. Fix: if any block is non-public, run the whole comparison on a local model instead."],"related":["t10","t21","t26"]},{"id":"t21","num":21,"cat":"B","title":"Multi-Stakeholder Persona Mirroring","tagline":"Pressure-test any big announcement by simulating how different groups of people will actually read it — before you hit send.","audience":"Product managers, change-management leads, HR and internal-communications staff, and customer-experience directors who are about to announce a major policy shift or product change.","why":"Big announcements fail not because the decision is wrong, but because the wording lands badly with one specific group who then reacts with anger, confusion, or quiet resentment. Normally you only discover those reactions after launch — in the tense all-hands meeting or the flood of support tickets — when it is expensive and embarrassing to walk anything back. This technique, \"persona mirroring,\" asks the AI to role-play as several distinct audiences and read your draft through each of their eyes, surfacing the unspoken fear and the likely pushback for each one. Because the AI has absorbed enormous amounts of human writing about work, change, and grievance, it is genuinely good at predicting the emotional reaction a given sentence will trigger. Reach for it whenever a message hits a mixed audience and the cost of getting the tone wrong is high: reorg emails, price increases, feature deprecations, return-to-office mandates, and benefit changes.","need":["A written draft of the announcement or change — even a rough, unpolished one","A clear idea of the distinct groups who will read it (roles, life situations, or customer segments), not just 'everyone'","Access to one AI chat tool: a cloud assistant (Claude, Gemini, or Copilot) or a local model on your own computer","Optional: any known sore spots or past complaints from these groups, so the AI can factor them in"],"steps":[{"title":"Get your rough draft ready — it does not need to be perfect","detail":"Write or paste the actual announcement you plan to send, even if it is messy. The AI needs the real words your audience will read, not a summary of your good intentions, because tone lives in the exact phrasing. If you only have bullet points so far, that is fine — just label them as a rough draft so the AI treats the wording as changeable."},{"title":"Name your real audiences, not just 'employees' or 'customers'","detail":"This technique lives or dies on choosing distinct personas. Pick three or four groups who genuinely experience the change differently — for a return-to-office memo that might be a working parent with a long commute, a new graduate who wants mentorship, and a senior engineer who works solo. Vague personas ('staff') produce vague, useless feedback, so describe each one in a short concrete phrase that captures their stake in the outcome."},{"title":"Paste the draft and the personas into one prompt","detail":"Open your AI tool and use the ready-made prompt below, dropping your draft and persona list into the bracketed spots. Keeping the draft and the personas in a single message is what lets the AI cross-reference specific sentences against specific fears. Send it and wait for the feedback report — this usually takes under a minute."},{"title":"Read the report as a map of friction, not a verdict","detail":"The AI will return, for each persona, an unspoken anxiety, the most likely point of pushback, and a suggested rewrite. Treat these as predictions to sanity-check against what you know of your people, not as facts — the AI is inferring from typical human reactions, so it can be slightly off for your specific culture. Cross out anything that does not ring true and star the anxieties that make you wince because they are probably real."},{"title":"Rewrite the draft to defuse the biggest friction points","detail":"Now edit your announcement to preemptively answer the anxieties you starred, ideally before the reader can even form the objection. If two personas fear opposite things (one wants more flexibility, one wants clear rules), name both tensions openly rather than pretending they do not exist — acknowledgment lowers the temperature more than false reassurance. Fold the AI's suggested phrasings in only where they sound like your real voice."},{"title":"Run the revised draft through the same personas again","detail":"Paste your edited version back and ask the AI to re-score each persona's reaction and flag any anxiety you failed to address. This second pass catches new problems your edits may have introduced and confirms the worst friction points are actually resolved. Two rounds is usually enough; stop when the remaining pushback is honest disagreement with the decision itself, not a fixable wording problem."},{"title":"Sanity-check with one real human before you send","detail":"The AI simulates reactions, but a trusted colleague from one of your actual audiences will catch the thing it missed. Show them the near-final draft and ask which sentence they would screenshot and complain about. This keeps a human in the loop on a message that affects real people, which is exactly where judgment should stay."}],"prompt":"You are an expert in organizational psychology and change communication. I am about to send the announcement below and want to predict how different audiences will react before I send it.\n\nHere is the draft announcement:\n\"\"\"\n[PASTE YOUR FULL DRAFT HERE — the exact wording you plan to send]\n\"\"\"\n\nContext you should factor in:\n- Who is sending this: [YOUR ROLE, e.g. Head of People Operations]\n- The situation / any known tension: [e.g. two prior reorgs this year, morale is fragile]\n\nAnalyze this draft and generate a multi-perspective feedback report. Show me how these distinct personas will each interpret the exact text:\n1. [PERSONA 1 — a concrete one-line description, e.g. \"a working parent with a 90-minute commute\"]\n2. [PERSONA 2 — e.g. \"a recent entry-level graduate seeking mentorship and career growth\"]\n3. [PERSONA 3 — e.g. \"a senior technical engineer who works independently and values autonomy\"]\n4. [PERSONA 4 — optional, add or remove personas as needed]\n\nFor EACH persona, give me:\n- Primary unspoken anxiety: the fear they will not say out loud but will feel.\n- Likely point of pushback: the specific sentence or idea they will object to, and quote the exact phrase that triggers it.\n- Suggested rewrite: how I could rephrase that part to address their concern without weakening the message or over-promising.\n\nThen present a summary table with columns: Persona | Unspoken anxiety | Trigger phrase | Overall reaction (Positive / Neutral / Negative).\n\nFinally, flag any place where two personas want opposite things, and tell me honestly whether that is a wording problem I can fix or a genuine conflict I need to acknowledge directly. Do not soften your analysis — I need the uncomfortable reactions, not reassurance.","promptNote":"Replace the bracketed parts: paste your real draft, fill in your role and any known tension so the AI reads the room accurately, and describe each persona in one concrete phrase (a life situation or job reality, not just a title). Add or delete numbered personas to match your real audiences — three or four works best.","cloud":{"bestTool":"Anthropic Claude — its strength is nuanced reading of tone and human subtext in longer text, which is exactly what persona mirroring demands, and it handles a long draft plus multiple personas in one pass.","steps":["Go to claude.ai and sign in (the free tier is enough for a single draft).","Copy the prompt template above, fill in your draft and personas, and paste the whole thing into the message box.","Send it and read the feedback report; then paste your revised draft back in the same conversation and ask it to re-score each persona.","If a persona's feedback feels off, reply in plain English — e.g. 'Persona 2 would actually welcome this because our new hires asked for structure' — and it will adjust.","Verify against your own knowledge of these people before acting; the AI predicts typical reactions, not your specific team's."]},"local":["Open your local chat interface (for example Open WebUI connected to Ollama, or LM Studio) and select an already-installed instruct model such as Llama 3.1 8B or a Mistral model.","Paste the same prompt template, with your real draft and personas filled into the brackets.","Send it and read the per-persona report; because the draft never leaves your computer, this is the right choice for sensitive HR, legal, or financial announcements.","Paste your revised draft back into the same chat and ask it to re-check each persona and flag anything still unaddressed.","If a smaller local model gives shallow answers, ask it to handle one persona at a time — 'Now analyze only Persona 1 in depth' — which keeps the reasoning focused."],"localNeedsSetup":true,"choose":"Choose based on how sensitive the announcement is. A confidential reorg, layoff, compensation change, legal notice, or anything naming real individuals or unreleased business moves should run on a LOCAL model, because pasting an unannounced internal decision into a cloud tool means it leaves your control before you have even told your own staff — a real leak and compliance risk. For lower-stakes, non-confidential messaging (a product feature change, a routine policy tweak, external marketing copy), a cloud tool like Claude is faster, sharper, and perfectly fine. When in doubt about confidentiality, treat it as sensitive and stay local.","example":{"input":"Analyze this draft. Personas: (1) a working parent with a long commute, (2) a recent graduate seeking mentorship, (3) a senior engineer who works independently.\n\nDraft: \"Team — starting next month we're moving from our hybrid model to a mandatory 4-day in-office schedule. We believe in-person collaboration drives our best work and strengthens our culture. Fridays remain remote. We're excited about the energy this will bring back to the office.\"","output":"MULTI-PERSPECTIVE FEEDBACK REPORT\n\n1. Working parent, long commute\n- Unspoken anxiety: \"This just quietly erased the flexibility I built my childcare around, and no one asked me.\"\n- Likely pushback: the word \"mandatory\" plus the cheerful \"excited\" — the tone assumes everyone gains, ignoring the people it costs the most.\n- Trigger phrase: \"We're excited about the energy this will bring back.\"\n- Suggested rewrite: \"We know a 4-day schedule is a real adjustment for those with commutes or care responsibilities. Here is who to talk to about your situation, and the flexibility we can still offer.\"\n\n2. Recent graduate seeking mentorship\n- Unspoken anxiety: \"Actually good for me — but will I look bad for being one of the few who's happy about it?\"\n- Likely pushback: minimal; may quietly welcome more face time with senior colleagues.\n- Suggested rewrite: name the upside explicitly — \"more chances to learn directly from experienced teammates\" — so the benefit they feel is stated, not left unspoken.\n\n3. Senior engineer, works independently\n- Unspoken anxiety: \"My deep-focus work happens alone and at home. This treats my productivity as a culture problem.\"\n- Likely pushback: \"in-person collaboration drives our best work\" reads as a blanket claim that dismisses solo work.\n- Suggested rewrite: \"Collaboration matters, and so does focused solo time — we'll protect quiet space and no-meeting blocks in the office.\"\n\nSUMMARY TABLE\nPersona | Unspoken anxiety | Trigger phrase | Reaction\nWorking parent | Flexibility erased without consultation | \"excited about the energy\" | Negative\nRecent graduate | Fears standing out as the happy one | (none strong) | Positive\nSenior engineer | Solo work dismissed as a culture gap | \"in-person drives our best work\" | Negative\n\nOPPOSING NEEDS: The graduate wants more in-office time; the engineer wants protected solo focus. This is a genuine conflict, not just wording — acknowledge both directly rather than claiming the policy is great for everyone.","note":"Notice the AI quotes the exact trigger phrase and separates fixable wording ('excited') from a real conflict you must name out loud."},"tips":["Make personas concrete and specific — 'a night-shift warehouse worker with no company laptop' yields sharp feedback; 'an employee' yields mush.","Include a genuinely skeptical or already-frustrated persona on purpose; the whole point is to surface the reaction you are least prepared for.","When the AI suggests a rewrite, only keep phrasing that sounds like you — a message that reads as AI-smoothed can feel more corporate and less trustworthy than an honest one.","Ask a follow-up like 'What is the single sentence most likely to get screenshotted and shared angrily?' to find your biggest liability fast.","Feed it the reactions you already got from a past announcement so it calibrates to your real culture, not generic assumptions."],"mistakes":["Pasting a confidential or unannounced decision into a cloud tool — treat any un-launched internal change as sensitive and run it on a local model instead.","Using vague personas like 'staff' or 'users' — always describe a concrete life or work situation, or the feedback is worthless.","Treating the AI's report as fact — it predicts typical reactions, so cross-check every anxiety against what you actually know about your people before acting.","Copy-pasting the AI's rewrites wholesale so the final message sounds robotic — adapt them into your own voice.","Over-editing until the message says nothing — some pushback reflects honest disagreement with the decision, which you should acknowledge, not paper over with softer words."],"related":["t10","t16","t26"]},{"id":"t26","num":26,"cat":"B","title":"The \"Explain It Like I'm a Professional in a Different Field\" Analogy Engine","tagline":"Turn a concept your listener's eyes glaze over at into a vivid picture built entirely from their own industry.","audience":"Consultants, sales engineers, solutions architects, and cross-departmental project leads who have to make a technical idea land with a client or executive who has zero background in it — and who won't be won over by jargon.","why":"People don't buy or approve what they can't picture. When you explain a technical concept to someone outside your field, the words are correct but the mental image is missing, so they nod politely and stay unconvinced. A good analogy fixes this instantly by borrowing something they already understand deeply — the workflows and vocabulary of their own industry — and mapping your idea onto it, so the unfamiliar becomes obvious. AI is unusually good at this because it can hold two whole domains in mind at once (say, distributed databases and hospital operations) and find the parallels a busy human wouldn't. The result is a bridge that turns a glazed-over stare into an \"oh, I get it\" in one sentence.","need":["One technical concept you need to explain, in your own words","The specific industry (and ideally the role) of the person you're explaining it to","A cloud assistant OR a local model with a chat interface","Two minutes to sanity-check the analogy before you use it live"],"steps":[{"title":"Nail down the one concept","detail":"Write down the single technical idea you need to land — not five ideas, one. For example, 'how a decentralized database keeps every copy in sync across servers.' Being specific here is what separates a sharp analogy from a mushy one; a vague concept produces a vague analogy that convinces nobody."},{"title":"Name your listener's world exactly","detail":"Identify the industry AND, if you can, the person's role: not just 'construction' but 'a commercial general contractor who runs job sites,' or 'a hospital's chief operating officer.' The more precisely you name their world, the more the AI can pull from workflows they touch every day, which is what makes the analogy feel like it was made for them."},{"title":"Run the prompt","detail":"Paste the prompt below into your AI tool, filling in the two brackets — your concept and their industry. The prompt forces the AI to build the entire analogy from their industry's vocabulary and physical operations, and to spell out exactly which real part maps to which technical part, so you get a working translation rather than a throwaway one-liner."},{"title":"Pressure-test the mapping","detail":"Read the analogy as if you were the client. Does each mapping actually hold up, or does one part break down and mislead? Ask the AI 'where does this analogy break down?' — every analogy has a limit, and knowing it keeps you from getting caught out when the executive pushes on the weak point."},{"title":"Trim it to one clean line plus a follow-through","detail":"You rarely need the whole essay in the room. Ask the AI for a single opening sentence (the hook) and two or three follow-up sentences you can use if they lean in. This gives you a tight version for a slide or a cold open and a deeper version for the conversation that follows."},{"title":"Deploy and watch their face","detail":"Drop the hook into your pitch deck, opening line, or intro meeting, then read the room. If they light up, go deeper with the follow-through; if they look puzzled, ask the AI for a second analogy from a different corner of the same industry. Keep the analogy you land on — a good one is reusable across every client in that field."}],"prompt":"You are an expert communicator who specializes in cross-industry analogies. I need to explain a technical concept to a person who has no background in my field, using an analogy drawn entirely from THEIR world.\n\nTHE TECHNICAL CONCEPT I NEED TO EXPLAIN:\n[INSERT THE TECHNICAL CONCEPT IN PLAIN WORDS, e.g. \"how a decentralized database keeps every copy synchronized across many servers\"]\n\nMY LISTENER:\n[INSERT THEIR INDUSTRY AND ROLE, e.g. \"a senior executive in commercial construction who runs large job sites and does not understand software\"]\n\nDo the following:\n1. Build ONE comprehensive, working analogy drawn entirely from the workflows, vocabulary, and physical operations of my listener's own industry. Do not use any software, computer, or engineering terms in the analogy itself.\n2. Give me a one-sentence HOOK I can open with.\n3. Then give a short paragraph that walks through the analogy in more detail.\n4. Provide a MAPPING TABLE with two columns: \"In their world\" and \"What it actually is (my concept)\", so I can see exactly which real thing stands for which technical part.\n5. End with one sentence describing WHERE THIS ANALOGY BREAKS DOWN, so I know its limit before I use it.\n\nKeep it concrete, specific, and free of buzzwords.","promptNote":"Fill in the two brackets: your concept in plain words, and your listener's industry plus role. The more precisely you name the role (not just \"healthcare\" but \"a hospital COO\"), the more the analogy draws on things they personally deal with. The \"where it breaks down\" line is what keeps you safe when a sharp executive tests the analogy.","cloud":{"bestTool":"Anthropic Claude — it produces the most nuanced, genuinely-mapped analogies and follows the multi-part structure (hook, table, breakdown) reliably, which matters when the analogy has to survive scrutiny in a real meeting.","steps":["Open claude.ai (or gemini.google.com if you already live in Google Workspace).","Paste the prompt and fill in the two brackets: your concept and your listener's industry and role.","Send it, then read the mapping table as if you were the client.","Iterate: ask 'give me a second analogy from a different part of their industry' or 'where does this break down?' and pick the strongest version.","Copy the one-line hook into your deck and keep the fuller version in your notes."]},"local":["Open your local chat interface (for example, Open WebUI with Ollama, or LM Studio).","Select a capable general model such as Llama 3 or Gemma.","Paste the prompt with your concept and your listener's industry filled in, and run it.","Because it runs on your machine, an unreleased product detail or a named client's situation never leaves your device.","Ask for a second angle or the 'where it breaks down' line right in the same chat until the analogy is sharp."],"localNeedsSetup":true,"choose":"For most analogies the concept itself is generic (how a database syncs, how encryption works) and there's nothing sensitive about it, so a cloud tool is fastest and gives the best results. Switch to a local model when your concept description names a specific unreleased product, a named client and their private situation, proprietary architecture, or anything under NDA — in that case the details you paste are the sensitive part, and a local model keeps them on your machine.","example":{"input":"Concept: how a decentralized database keeps every copy synchronized across many servers, with no single master server in charge. Listener: a senior executive in commercial construction who runs large job sites and does not understand software.","output":"HOOK: It's like running one giant job site where every foreman keeps their own identical set of blueprints, and any change gets confirmed by the crew before it becomes official — so no single trailer holds the 'only real' set.\n\nDETAIL: On your site, imagine ten foremen, each with a full copy of the plans. When one wants to change a beam spec, he doesn't just cross it out — he broadcasts the change, the other foremen check it against their copies, and only once a majority confirm does everyone update their plans at the same time. No master trailer can go down and freeze the whole site, and no two crews end up building from different drawings.\n\nMAPPING:\nIn their world | What it actually is\nA foreman with a full set of plans | One server holding a full copy of the data\nBroadcasting a proposed change | A write request being proposed\nOther foremen checking their copies | Nodes validating the change\nMajority confirms before it's official | Consensus before a commit\nNo single master trailer | No single point of failure\n\nWHERE IT BREAKS DOWN: Real job sites don't reconcile thousands of tiny changes per second the way servers do, so don't push the 'speed' part of the analogy too hard.","note":"Notice every piece of the analogy is a thing the contractor already touches (foremen, blueprints, trailers) — and the honest 'breaks down' line protects you when they test it."},"tips":["Name the role, not just the industry — 'hospital COO' beats 'healthcare' because it pins the analogy to the workflows that one person actually owns.","Always ask 'where does this break down?' — knowing the analogy's limit before the meeting is what keeps you from getting caught flat-footed.","Ask for two or three different analogies and let the client's own reaction pick the winner; the one that makes them smile is the one to keep.","Save the analogies that land — a strong one is reusable with every future client in that same field.","For a slide, use only the one-line hook; save the full mapping table for the conversation, not the projector."],"mistakes":["Letting technical words leak into the analogy — if 'server' or 'node' appears in the story, add 'use zero software terms in the analogy itself' and rerun.","Picking an industry the listener only sort-of belongs to; use their actual daily role so the parallels feel personal, not generic.","Cramming three concepts into one analogy — it collapses. Do one concept per analogy and chain them if you need more.","Trusting the analogy blindly; read each mapping row as the client would and cut any part that misleads, even if it sounds clever.","Using the full essay in the room — lead with one sentence and only go deeper if they lean in."],"related":["t10","t16","t21"]},{"id":"t28","num":28,"cat":"B","title":"The Blind Spot and Risk Assumption Counter-Weight","tagline":"Hand your business plan to a ruthless AI critic that hunts down the fatal flaws you're too close to see — before they cost you money.","audience":"Small business owners, event coordinators, product-launch leads, and operational strategists who have a plan on paper and want to find its weak points before real money, real dates, and real reputations are on the line.","why":"When you build a plan, you fall in love with it. Your brain quietly fills gaps with optimism — the vendor will deliver on time, the weather will hold, attendance will hit target — and those unspoken assumptions are exactly where plans blow up. This tutorial flips the AI into a professional pessimist whose only job is to find the hidden ways your plan fails, then hand you a concrete backup for each one. It is cheap insurance: ten minutes of hard questions now can save a ruined launch day, a blown budget, or an event with no plan B. Reach for it any time you're about to commit money, a public date, or your reputation to something that can't easily be undone.","need":["A written outline of your plan — a launch, event itinerary, expansion, or operational rollout (even rough bullet points work)","A cloud AI assistant OR a local model running in a chat app","Your real numbers where you have them: budget, dates, headcount, vendor names, capacity limits","About 15 minutes to read the critique and decide which risks to act on"],"steps":[{"title":"Write down the plan as it actually is","detail":"Paste your real plan, not a polished pitch version. Include the timeline, budget, who does what, which vendors or partners you depend on, and the numbers you're betting on (expected attendance, sales target, headcount). The AI can only find blind spots in what you show it, so vague input produces vague warnings — the messier and more honest the input, the sharper the critique."},{"title":"Order the AI to be your enemy, on purpose","detail":"Paste the prompt below. It casts the AI as a hyper-critical risk consultant whose job is to save you from an expensive disaster, and it forbids reassurance. This role-play matters: a default AI tends to be encouraging and agreeable, but here you explicitly want it to attack the plan, because a cheerleader can't protect you and a skeptic can."},{"title":"Demand a Plan B for every problem","detail":"The prompt requires a concrete, do-it-now mitigation for each flaw — not just 'this is risky.' A risk with no countermeasure is just anxiety; a risk with a written backup plan is manageable. Insisting on paired problem-plus-solution is what turns a scary list into an action list you can actually work through."},{"title":"Pressure-test the critique itself","detail":"Read the flaws and push back on anything that feels off. Ask follow-ups like 'What's the single most likely one to actually happen?' or 'You missed the risk around [X] — walk through that.' The first pass is a draft; two or three rounds of you challenging it will surface the deeper issues that one prompt can't reach."},{"title":"Bake the fixes into the real plan","detail":"Don't leave the mitigations in the chat window — that's where good advice goes to die. Add the buffers and backups directly to your master timeline and budget: pad the schedule, name a backup vendor, set a go/no-go date, reserve contingency cash. A safety margin only protects you if it's written into the plan everyone actually follows."}],"prompt":"You are a hyper-critical corporate risk consultant. Your only goal is to save my company from a costly, avoidable disaster, so you must be brutally honest and skeptical — do NOT reassure me or praise the plan.\n\nReview the operational plan below. Then:\n\n1. Identify the top 5 most dangerous hidden vulnerabilities, unstated assumptions, or fatal operational blind spots — the things that are most likely to go wrong or that I am silently assuming will \"just work.\"\n2. For EACH vulnerability, provide:\n   - Why it is dangerous (the realistic worst-case if it hits)\n   - How likely it is (High / Medium / Low) and roughly how much it would cost me in money, time, or reputation\n   - A concrete, proactive \"Plan B\" mitigation I can implement THIS WEEK — specific actions, not vague advice\n3. End with the single biggest risk you would fix first if you could only fix one, and the one question I most need to answer before proceeding.\n\nFormat the 5 vulnerabilities as a clear table with columns: Vulnerability | Why It's Dangerous | Likelihood & Cost | Plan B Mitigation.\n\nAssume nothing works out perfectly. Where my plan is missing information, state the assumption you're forced to make and flag it as a risk.\n\nOPERATIONAL PLAN:\n[PASTE YOUR PLAN — timeline, budget, roles, vendors, and the numbers you're counting on (attendance, sales target, headcount, capacity)]","promptNote":"Replace only the bracketed block at the bottom with your actual plan; the more real numbers and vendor names you include, the sharper the critique. The lines telling it not to reassure you and to assume nothing works out perfectly are the load-bearing ones — they're what stop the AI from being a polite cheerleader.","cloud":{"bestTool":"Anthropic Claude or Google Gemini — both hold a long, detailed plan in context without losing track, and both are strong at structured, reasoned critique; lean Claude for the sharpest adversarial reasoning, Gemini if your plan already lives in Google Docs.","steps":["Open claude.ai or gemini.google.com and start a new chat.","Paste the full prompt, then paste your plan into the bracketed block at the bottom (or upload the plan document if you have one).","Send it, then read the table and push back: ask 'Which of these is most likely to actually happen?' and 'What did you miss?'","Ask it to rewrite your timeline with the buffers and backups built in, then copy that into your real planning doc."]},"local":["Open your local chat app (for example, Open WebUI connected to Ollama, or LM Studio).","Pick a capable instruct model such as Llama 3.1 8B or a larger model if your machine can run it — bigger models give sharper critiques.","Paste the full prompt with your real plan, budget, and vendor names filled in, and run it entirely offline.","Iterate with follow-ups the same way — 'rank these by likelihood,' 'add a 6th risk about staffing' — knowing none of your confidential numbers ever leave your computer."],"localNeedsSetup":true,"choose":"For a generic plan with no secrets — a community bake sale, a public workshop — a cloud tool is fastest and perfectly fine. But this exercise usually means feeding in your real budget, profit margins, vendor contracts, client names, and expansion strategy, and that is exactly the kind of competitively sensitive information you don't want sitting on a third party's servers or potentially informing a future model. When the plan contains money figures, unannounced moves, partner names, or anything a competitor would love to see, run it on a local model so the whole stress-test happens on your own machine and nothing leaves the device.","example":{"input":"Plan: First outdoor 'Fall Food Truck Festival', Saturday Oct 18, city park. Budget $12,000. Expecting 2,000 attendees at $10 entry to break even. 15 food trucks confirmed (verbal). One local band. Ticketing at the gate, cash only. Two porta-potties. Marketing: Instagram posts starting Oct 1. I'm running it with 4 volunteer friends.","output":"Vulnerability | Why It's Dangerous | Likelihood & Cost | Plan B Mitigation\nRain has no backup — it's an outdoor October event | One rainy Saturday and attendance collapses; you still owe vendors and permits | HIGH · could lose most of the $12,000 | Add a rain date to permits now; buy event insurance (~$300); post a clear rain-or-shine/refund policy before selling tickets\nVendors only confirmed verbally | Trucks can cancel last-minute for a better-paying gig, leaving empty space and refund demands | MEDIUM · a dead festival + reputation hit | Send signed one-page agreements with a small deposit and a cancellation clause this week; line up 3 backup trucks\n2,000-attendee target is an untested assumption | Break-even depends entirely on a number you've never hit before | HIGH · below ~1,200 you lose money | Model 800 / 1,500 / 2,000 scenarios; pre-sell online tickets to gauge real demand before locking spend\nCash-only at the gate | Slow lines, theft risk, and you lose every attendee without cash on hand | MEDIUM · lost sales + a security exposure | Add tap-to-pay (Square) readers; pre-sell tickets online to shorten gate lines\nTwo porta-potties for 2,000 people | Wildly under-provisioned; long lines and a health-code problem | HIGH · complaints, bad reviews, possible fine | Standard is ~1 per 75–100 people; book 15–20 units and confirm the city's requirement now\n\nBiggest risk to fix first: the rain contingency — it can wipe out the entire budget in one day. Most important question to answer before proceeding: what is the realistic, evidence-based attendance number, and does the plan survive if you only hit half of it?","note":"Notice it didn't just say 'it might rain' — it attached a likely dollar impact and a specific, do-it-this-week action to every single risk."},"tips":["Give it your real numbers. 'Budget $12k, need 2,000 attendees to break even' produces far sharper warnings than 'we have a budget and hope for a good turnout.'","Run it twice with different framings: once as a risk consultant, once as 'a competitor trying to predict how this fails.' The two angles catch different blind spots.","After the list, ask it to rank the five by likelihood times cost, so you fix the genuinely dangerous ones first instead of the scariest-sounding ones.","Ask for a 'go/no-go checklist' — the specific conditions that must be true a week out, or you postpone. It turns vague worry into a clear decision rule.","Feed the plan back after your edits and ask it to attack the improved version. Good plans survive a second round; you'll find risks the first pass created."],"mistakes":["Pasting a polished sales pitch instead of the honest plan — the AI can only find flaws in the real details, so hide nothing about the shaky parts.","Accepting the first list as gospel. It's a draft brainstorm, not a verdict; challenge weak points and ask what it missed before you act on anything.","Letting the AI invent facts it wasn't given — if a risk hinges on a number you never provided, make it flag that as an assumption rather than treat it as truth.","Reading the critique, feeling reassured you 'thought about risk,' and changing nothing. The value is entirely in baking the buffers into your actual timeline and budget.","Using a public cloud tool for a confidential expansion or unannounced launch — that's exactly the sensitive case where you should run it locally instead."],"related":["t10","t16","t21"]},{"id":"t4","num":4,"cat":"O","title":"Automated Multi-Source Meeting Triage","tagline":"Turn a messy, wall-of-text meeting transcript into a clean executive summary, an owner-by-owner action list with deadlines, and a flagged risk list in under two minutes, without the transcript ever leaving your computer.","audience":"Working professionals who run or sit in meetings and are tired of retyping notes: project managers, team leads, executive assistants, program coordinators, and administrators. If you can get a transcript (from Teams, Zoom, Google Meet, a phone recorder, or a free local tool) and paste text into a chat box, you can do this.","why":"Every meeting produces two things that matter later: decisions and commitments. But those live buried inside a chaotic block of speech-to-text, with no punctuation, people talking over each other, filler words, tangents, and half-finished sentences. A person needs 30 to 45 minutes to comb through that and write clean minutes, and still often loses track of who agreed to do what by when. An AI reads the entire mess in seconds and reshapes it into a fixed, predictable format: what was decided, who owns each task and its deadline, and what concerns people raised. Reach for this any time you walk out of a meeting with a transcript or a recording and need shareable, accountable notes fast, especially for recurring status meetings, project kickoffs, and client or stakeholder calls where \"who committed to what\" genuinely matters. The catch: transcripts are among the most sensitive text in any workplace. They name clients, quote salary and budget figures, and capture unguarded remarks. That is precisely why this guide centers on running the job on a local model, where nothing is transmitted anywhere.","need":["A meeting transcript as text: either an auto-generated one (Teams, Zoom, Google Meet, Otter) or one you create locally from an audio file with a free tool like Whisper.","A chat interface to talk to an AI: a local one such as Open WebUI (Ollama) or LM Studio for sensitive meetings, or a cloud one (Claude, Gemini, Copilot) for low-stakes internal ones.","A rough sense of who was in the meeting: real first names help the AI assign action items to the correct owner instead of guessing.","Two minutes to skim and correct the result: the AI is fast and accurate but not infallible, and you are the one signing off on the notes."],"steps":[{"title":"Get your meeting into text form","detail":"The AI reads text, not audio, so you first need a transcript. If your meeting platform (Teams, Zoom, Google Meet) already generates one, download it as a .txt or .vtt file and open it. If you only have an audio recording, run it through a free local speech-to-text tool like Whisper, which converts the audio to a text file entirely on your own machine. The output will look ugly, with run-on sentences and no clear speaker labels, and that is completely fine, because cleaning it up is the AI's job, not yours."},{"title":"Open a chat window with your AI and paste the whole transcript","detail":"Open the tool you are using (see the Cloud and Local sections below for exactly which). Copy the entire raw transcript, however messy, and paste it into the message box. Do not trim, reword, or pre-clean it: the AI performs better with the full context, including the tangents, because a comment buried in a side conversation is often where a real risk or decision actually surfaced. If the transcript is very long, that is fine, since these models handle many pages of text at once."},{"title":"Add the extraction prompt above the transcript","detail":"Before the pasted transcript, add the instruction prompt provided in the Prompt section. This prompt is the real engine of the tutorial: it tells the AI to sort everything into three fixed buckets (decisions, action items with owners and deadlines, and risks) instead of writing a vague paragraph summary. Using the exact same prompt every time is what makes your notes consistent from meeting to meeting, so people always know where to look. Fill in the bracketed placeholders (like the meeting name and the list of attendees) before you send."},{"title":"Run it and read the result","detail":"Send the message and the AI returns your structured summary in a few seconds. Read it against your own memory of the meeting. The most important thing to verify is the Action Items section: check that each task is assigned to the right person and that deadlines match what was actually said. The AI is careful to only extract what was stated, so if a deadline was never mentioned it will mark it as 'not stated' rather than inventing one, which is exactly what you want."},{"title":"Fix gaps by asking follow-up questions","detail":"You do not need to re-run everything to make a correction. Just type a plain-English follow-up in the same chat, such as 'The database migration task should be assigned to Priya, not Sam' or 'You missed the decision to push the launch to March.' The AI keeps the transcript in mind and updates only what you asked. This back-and-forth is normal and fast, and it is how you turn a good first draft into final, shareable minutes."},{"title":"Copy the finished notes where your team will see them","detail":"Once the summary is correct, copy it out and paste it into wherever your team lives: an email, a project tracker like Asana or Jira, a shared doc, or a Teams or Slack channel. Because the action items already carry owners and deadlines, they drop cleanly into a task list. Send it out the same day while the meeting is fresh, which is the single biggest reason notes actually get acted on."}],"prompt":"You are an executive assistant. Read the chaotic, unstructured meeting transcript at the bottom of this message. It comes from an automatic speech-to-text tool, so it has no punctuation, no clear speaker labels, filler words, cross-talk, and tangents. Parse it carefully and produce an executive-ready summary using this EXACT structure and headings.\n\nMeeting: [MEETING NAME, e.g. \"Q3 Product Roadmap Sync\"]\nDate: [DATE]\nAttendees: [LIST OF FIRST NAMES, e.g. Priya, Sam, Dana, Marcus]\n\n1. Key Decisions Made\n- List only definitive agreements the group actually reached. One bullet per decision, in plain past-tense language. If no decisions were made, write \"None recorded.\"\n\n2. Action Items and Ownership Matrix\nPresent as a table, one row per task:\nTask | Owner | Deadline\n- Task: a short, specific description of what needs to be done.\n- Owner: the single person responsible. Use a real name from the attendee list. If ownership was never assigned, write \"UNASSIGNED\".\n- Deadline: the date or timeframe stated. If none was stated, write \"NOT STATED\". Do not invent dates.\n\n3. Identified Risks and Roadblocks\n- List concerns, blockers, dependencies, or objections that any participant explicitly raised. One bullet each, noting who raised it if clear. If none, write \"None raised.\"\n\nRules:\n- Extract ONLY what is actually in the transcript. Never guess, embellish, or add advice.\n- If something is ambiguous, prefer \"UNASSIGNED\" or \"NOT STATED\" over guessing.\n- Keep it concise and scannable. No preamble, no closing commentary.\n\nTRANSCRIPT:\n[PASTE THE ENTIRE RAW TRANSCRIPT HERE]","promptNote":"Fill in the four placeholders at the top ([MEETING NAME], [DATE], [ATTENDEES]) so the AI can attribute tasks to real people, then paste your full messy transcript where it says [PASTE THE ENTIRE RAW TRANSCRIPT HERE]. The \"NOT STATED\" and \"UNASSIGNED\" rules are the important part: they stop the AI from inventing deadlines or guessing owners, which is the most common way auto-generated notes go wrong.","cloud":{"bestTool":"Anthropic Claude, because meeting transcripts are long and unstructured and Claude handles very large blocks of text reliably while following a strict output format closely, which is exactly what a triage template needs (use Gemini instead if your notes live in Google Docs, or Copilot if the meeting came from Microsoft Teams).","steps":["Open claude.ai (or Gemini / Microsoft Copilot) and start a new chat.","Paste the extraction prompt from the Prompt section first, filling in the meeting name, date, and attendee names.","Below it, paste the entire raw transcript, however messy, and send the message.","Read the result and correct anything with a plain follow-up, for example 'reassign the vendor call to Dana' or 'you missed the budget-freeze decision'.","Copy the finished summary into your email, task tracker, or shared doc."]},"local":["Open your local chat interface (Open WebUI if you run Ollama, or LM Studio) and confirm at the top that a model is loaded and it says it is running locally / offline.","Start a new chat and paste in the extraction prompt from the Prompt section, filling in the meeting name, date, and attendee names.","Paste the full raw transcript underneath and send it; everything is processed on your own machine, so no text is transmitted anywhere.","Review the three sections and refine with follow-up messages in the same chat until the owners and deadlines are correct.","Copy the final notes out to your email or task tracker. For extra assurance you can disconnect from Wi-Fi before running it and watch it still work, proving the data never left your device."],"localNeedsSetup":true,"choose":"Strongly favor LOCAL for this task. Meeting transcripts are some of the most sensitive text a workplace produces: they name clients, quote exact budget and salary numbers, capture HR-adjacent complaints, and record unguarded remarks people would never put in an email. Running triage on a local model (Ollama or LM Studio) means the transcript is read and summarized entirely on your own computer and is never uploaded to any company's servers, which keeps you clean on confidentiality agreements, client contracts, and internal policy. Cloud tools (Claude, Gemini, Copilot) are perfectly fine only for low-stakes internal meetings with no confidential names, numbers, or personnel matters, such as a team retro or an internal planning sync. When in doubt about sensitivity, use local.","example":{"input":"so yeah um about the mobile launch i think we're all agreed we push it to march right the ios build isnt stable dana you said qa needs more time yeah at least three more weeks okay so march 15 target sam can you own getting the updated timeline into jira by friday sure and marcus the appstore review thing that could bite us if apple flags the new payment flow we should sock that away as a risk oh and priya the client at northwind still hasnt signed the change order until that lands legal wont let us start the integration work so thats blocking us dana can you chase the northwind signature no i dont have the contact priya has it okay priya you take that um what else budget we didnt decide the extra qa headcount lets table that","output":"Meeting: Mobile Launch Sync\nDate: 2026-07-05\nAttendees: Dana, Sam, Marcus, Priya\n\n1. Key Decisions Made\n- The mobile launch was pushed to a target date of March 15.\n- The decision on extra QA headcount was tabled (deferred).\n\n2. Action Items and Ownership Matrix\nTask | Owner | Deadline\nEnter the updated launch timeline into Jira | Sam | Friday\nChase the Northwind client for the signed change order | Priya | NOT STATED\n\n3. Identified Risks and Roadblocks\n- QA needs at least three more weeks; the iOS build is not yet stable (raised by Dana).\n- The App Store review may flag the new payment flow (raised by Marcus).\n- Northwind has not signed the change order; legal will not allow integration work to begin until it lands, blocking the project (raised by Priya).","note":"Notice the AI marked Priya's deadline as NOT STATED rather than inventing one, and correctly reassigned the Northwind chase from Dana to Priya after the group corrected itself mid-conversation."},"tips":["Always include the attendee first names in the prompt. Given real names, the AI assigns each action item to the correct owner; without them, it falls back to vague labels like 'the team' that no one feels responsible for.","Reuse the exact same prompt for every meeting. Consistency is the whole point: when the structure never changes, your colleagues learn exactly where to find decisions versus action items versus risks.","Trust the 'NOT STATED' and 'UNASSIGNED' flags, and treat them as a to-do list. They are the AI honestly telling you the meeting left something open, which is your cue to pin down the missing owner or deadline before the notes go out.","For a long series of meetings, ask a follow-up like 'compare this to last week's action items and flag anything still open.' The AI can carry forward unfinished business so nothing quietly drops.","If cross-talk confuses the owner of a task, paste just that confusing snippet back and ask 'who committed to this?' rather than re-running the whole transcript."],"mistakes":["Pasting a sensitive client or HR transcript into a free public chatbot. Fix: for anything naming clients, money, or people's performance, use a local model so the text never leaves your machine.","Pre-cleaning the transcript by hand before pasting. Fix: paste it raw; the messy tangents often contain the actual risks and decisions, and manual editing wastes time and can delete the very lines that mattered.","Taking the first draft as final and forwarding it unread. Fix: always skim the Action Items section against your memory of the meeting and correct owners or deadlines with a quick follow-up before sending.","Assuming a blank deadline means 'no deadline'. Fix: read 'NOT STATED' as an open question to resolve, and follow up with the owner to set a real date.","Leaving out attendee names and then wondering why tasks are assigned to 'someone' or the wrong person. Fix: always list the real first names in the prompt so ownership lands correctly."],"related":["t11","t17","t18"]},{"id":"t11","num":11,"cat":"O","title":"Structured JSON Data Extraction Wrapper","tagline":"Turn messy customer emails, tickets, and complaints into clean, uniform JSON your database and support tools can sort automatically.","audience":"Operations managers, customer-service team leads, and the people who feed data into help-desk systems, spreadsheets, or databases. You do not need to write code — if you can copy, paste, and read, you can do this. It is aimed at anyone drowning in free-form inbound messages who wishes each one arrived as tidy, labeled fields.","why":"Real customer messages are chaos: a three-paragraph rant might contain one actual request buried under apologies, order numbers, and frustration. Computers cannot sort or prioritize that reliably because every message is shaped differently. This technique uses AI as a translator that reads the human mess and hands back the same fixed set of fields every single time — always the same keys, always the same value types. That uniform shape (called JSON) is exactly what databases, spreadsheets, and ticketing tools can ingest, filter, and route without a human touching it. Reach for this whenever you have many free-text inputs that must become structured rows: support tickets, product feedback, survey comments, intake forms, or lead inquiries.","need":["An AI chat tool — Anthropic Claude, Google Gemini, or Microsoft Copilot in the cloud, OR a local model (Ollama, LM Studio) if the messages contain private customer data","The raw text of one message to start (an email, ticket, or complaint) copied to your clipboard","A decision about your exact fields — what four or five pieces of information you want pulled from every message","A place for the output to land: a spreadsheet column, a database import, or a ticketing tool that accepts JSON","Five quiet minutes to test on 3-4 sample messages before you trust it on real volume"],"steps":[{"title":"Decide the exact shape you want every message to become","detail":"Before you touch the AI, write down the handful of fields you need from every message and what each one is allowed to contain. For example: urgency (only LOW, MEDIUM, or HIGH), the product named (a word, or 'Unknown'), a frustration score (1 to 10), and a one-sentence summary of what they actually want. Deciding this first is the whole game — the AI can only be consistent if you tell it precisely what 'consistent' means, and a vague schema produces vague, unusable output."},{"title":"Copy one real message and paste it into the prompt","detail":"Open your AI tool and paste the prompt template from the Prompt section below. Replace the [PASTE THE RAW CUSTOMER MESSAGE HERE] placeholder with an actual email or ticket, warts and all — keep the typos, the emotion, the rambling. You want to test the AI against genuine mess, not a cleaned-up example, because the messy real thing is what it will face in production."},{"title":"Run it and read the JSON that comes back","detail":"Send the prompt. The AI should return a single block of JSON wrapped in code marks, with your exact field names and nothing else — no 'Sure, here you go!' intro, no closing pleasantries. Read the values and sanity-check them against the original message. If the frustration score feels off or it invented a product that was never mentioned, that is a signal to tighten the rules, not to give up."},{"title":"Test on three or four different messages before trusting it","detail":"Run a calm message, an angry one, a vague one, and one with no clear request. This variety exposes weak spots: does a polite email still get a fair urgency rating? Does a message with no product named correctly return 'Unknown' instead of a guess? Consistency across very different inputs is what makes the output safe to feed a machine, so spend your testing budget here rather than on one perfect example."},{"title":"Lock the field rules so the output never drifts","detail":"If any field came back in an unexpected form — 'Medium' instead of 'MEDIUM', or a paragraph where you wanted one sentence — add an explicit rule to the prompt spelling out the allowed values. The prompt template already constrains urgency to three exact words and the summary to one sentence; extend that pattern to every field. The stricter your rules, the more the AI behaves like a predictable form-filler instead of a creative writer."},{"title":"Move the clean JSON into your system","detail":"Once the shape is reliable, take the JSON output and feed it where it needs to go. For a spreadsheet, the four field values become four columns in a new row. For a ticketing tool or database, the JSON can often be imported directly or pasted into an import field. Now you can sort by urgency, filter for HIGH frustration, or auto-assign the actionable request — work that was impossible while the data was trapped in prose."},{"title":"Scale up by batching many messages at once","detail":"When one message works flawlessly, ask the AI to process several at a time by pasting multiple messages and requesting a JSON array (a list) — one object per message. This turns a full inbox into an importable table in a single run. Always eyeball the first batch or two before automating, because an error repeated across 200 rows is far more expensive than one you caught on row one."}],"prompt":"You are a precise data-extraction engine. Read the customer message below. Ignore all emotional filler, greetings, apologies, and small talk. Extract only the facts into the exact JSON schema shown. \n\nRules you must follow:\n- Return ONLY a single valid JSON object inside a ```json code block. No introduction, no explanation, no text before or after.\n- Use these exact keys and value formats. Do not add, rename, or reorder keys.\n- If a value is not stated in the message, use \"Unknown\" (for text fields) — never guess or invent.\n- \"ticket_urgency\" must be exactly one of: \"LOW\", \"MEDIUM\", or \"HIGH\", judged from the language and any deadlines mentioned.\n- \"customer_frustration_score\" must be a whole number from 1 (calm) to 10 (furious), judged from tone.\n- \"actionable_request\" must be ONE plain sentence describing what the customer actually wants done.\n\nSchema:\n{\n  \"ticket_urgency\": \"LOW / MEDIUM / HIGH\",\n  \"core_product_mentioned\": \"product name as a string, or Unknown\",\n  \"customer_frustration_score\": 1,\n  \"actionable_request\": \"one-sentence summary of the request\",\n  \"order_or_account_id\": \"the ID/number if present, or Unknown\"\n}\n\nCustomer message:\n\"\"\"\n[PASTE THE RAW CUSTOMER MESSAGE HERE]\n\"\"\"","promptNote":"Replace only the text inside the triple quotes with your real message. To fit your own needs, edit the Schema block: rename keys, add fields, or change the allowed values (for example swap the urgency levels for your own priority tiers) — but for every field you add, also add a matching Rule above so the AI knows exactly what that field may contain.","cloud":{"bestTool":"Anthropic Claude, because it follows strict formatting instructions faithfully and reliably returns JSON with no chatty intro or outro — the single most important quality for machine-readable output.","steps":["Open Claude (claude.ai) and start a new chat.","Paste the full prompt template, then replace the placeholder inside the triple quotes with one real customer message.","Send it and confirm the reply is a clean JSON block with your exact keys and nothing else around it.","Run three or four more messages of different tones to confirm the shape stays identical; if a field drifts, tighten its rule and re-run.","Once stable, paste several messages at once and ask for a JSON array to process a whole batch in one go."]},"local":["Open your local chat interface (Open WebUI for Ollama, or the LM Studio chat window) and select an already-installed instruction-following model such as Llama 3.1 8B or Mistral.","Paste the same prompt template and drop one real customer message inside the triple quotes.","Run it and check the JSON has your exact keys and allowed values; smaller local models sometimes add a stray sentence, so add 'Output nothing but the JSON code block' if needed.","Test a few messages of different tones, then process them in small batches (5-10 at a time) to keep a local model accurate.","Copy the resulting JSON straight into your spreadsheet or database import — because the model ran on your own machine, no customer text ever left it."],"localNeedsSetup":true,"choose":"Customer emails and tickets routinely contain names, order numbers, account IDs, phone numbers, and sometimes payment or health details — this is personal data your customers trusted you with. If you are processing real customer messages at any volume, strongly prefer a LOCAL model so that raw personal information never leaves your device or your company's control, which keeps you clear of privacy rules and vendor data-retention questions. Use the cloud tools (Claude especially) for setup and testing on fake or scrubbed sample messages, or for genuinely low-sensitivity text with no personal identifiers — that path is faster and needs no setup.","example":{"input":"Subject: STILL waiting?!?\n\nHi, I've now emailed THREE times about my SoundWave X2 headphones (order #48812) that arrived with a cracked left earcup. It's been 11 days. I have a conference on Monday and genuinely need working headphones by then. At this point I honestly just want my money back if you can't ship a replacement overnight. Really disappointed in you guys.\n\n- Dana","output":"{\n  \"ticket_urgency\": \"HIGH\",\n  \"core_product_mentioned\": \"SoundWave X2 headphones\",\n  \"customer_frustration_score\": 8,\n  \"actionable_request\": \"Ship a replacement overnight or issue a refund for the cracked headphones.\",\n  \"order_or_account_id\": \"48812\"\n}","note":"Notice the AI stripped all the emotion and repetition but still used the angry tone and the Monday deadline to justify HIGH urgency and a frustration score of 8 — and it pulled the order number without being told where to look."},"tips":["Give the AI one worked example inside the prompt (a sample message plus the exact JSON you'd want back). This 'show, don't just tell' trick sharply improves consistency on tricky fields like the frustration score.","Force closed lists wherever you can: 'LOW/MEDIUM/HIGH' is far safer than a free-text priority field, because a fixed set of values is what lets your database filter and sort reliably.","Always include a catch-all rule like 'use Unknown if not stated' so the AI never invents an order number or product that wasn't in the message — a confident wrong value is worse than a blank.","Set the AI's temperature/creativity to its lowest setting if your tool exposes it; extraction wants boring, repeatable answers, not creativity.","Keep a tiny 'test set' of 4-5 messages covering calm, furious, vague, and no-request cases, and re-run it any time you change the prompt so you can see instantly whether your edit helped or broke something."],"mistakes":["Trusting it after one perfect example. Great output on a clean message says nothing about the angry, vague, or emoji-filled ones — always test across several very different messages before you rely on it.","Leaving fields loosely defined. Asking for 'urgency' without listing the allowed words invites 'fairly urgent' and 'kinda high', which your database can't sort — pin every field to an exact set of allowed values.","Not blocking the chatty intro. If the reply starts with 'Sure! Here is the JSON:' it will break an automated import — the instruction to return ONLY the code block, with nothing before or after, is not optional.","Letting the AI guess missing data. Without an explicit 'use Unknown if not stated' rule, models will helpfully invent an order number or product — insist on Unknown so a blank stays a blank.","Pasting real customer data into a cloud tool for a sensitive workload. Test and design in the cloud with fake messages, then run the real volume on a local model so personal information never leaves your control."],"related":["t4","t17","t18"]},{"id":"t17","num":17,"cat":"O","title":"The Onboarding Curriculum Builder","tagline":"Turn a dense internal operations manual into a ready-to-hand-out, 5-day new-hire training schedule in about 20 minutes.","audience":"Corporate trainers, department leads, and HR specialists who own new-hire onboarding but aren't technical. You have the raw material (an operations manual, SOPs, or a task list) but not the hours it takes to hand-craft a day-by-day curriculum, and you want something a brand-new employee can actually follow on their first week.","why":"Onboarding usually fails not because information is missing but because it is shapeless: a 60-page manual dropped on someone's first day teaches nothing. An AI can read your existing procedures and reorganize them into a paced, learnable sequence — a morning concept, an afternoon hands-on task, and self-check questions — so a new hire builds skills in order instead of drowning. Reach for this whenever you are standing up a new role, refreshing a stale onboarding packet, or trying to get consistency across managers who each onboard differently. It saves hours of instructional-design work and, just as importantly, exposes gaps: when the AI cannot build a coherent Day 3, that is usually a sign your SOP for that step is thin. The result is a strong first draft, not the final word — you still edit it — but it beats staring at a blank page.","need":["A written source: your operations manual, SOP documents, or even a bulleted list of what the role does day to day.","One AI tool: a cloud assistant (Claude, Gemini, or Microsoft Copilot) for convenience, or a local model for privacy.","The role's job title and level (e.g. entry-level accounts-payable clerk) so the schedule targets the right person.","10 to 20 minutes to run the prompt, read the draft, and correct anything that is wrong or missing.","Optional but ideal: the name of the person or team the new hire should shadow or ask questions of each day."],"steps":[{"title":"Gather your source material in one place","detail":"Collect the procedures the new hire actually needs: the SOP documents, the operations manual, and a plain list of the core tasks for the role. If it is spread across files, paste the relevant parts into one document or note. The AI can only build a curriculum from what you give it — a vague brief yields a generic schedule, real procedures yield a real, role-specific one."},{"title":"Decide what is sensitive before you pick a tool","detail":"Skim your material for anything confidential: client names, employee data, contract terms, security procedures, internal system credentials, or trade-secret workflows. If it contains any of that, plan to use a local model so nothing leaves your computer (see the local steps). If it is generic 'how we file expense reports' material, a cloud tool is faster and perfectly fine. Making this call up front saves you from pasting sensitive internal docs into a public chatbot."},{"title":"Paste the prompt and your procedures together","detail":"Open your chosen tool, copy the prompt from the Prompt section below, and fill in the square-bracket placeholders (role, department, tone). Then paste your SOPs and task list underneath where the prompt says to. Keeping the instructions and the source material in one message is what lets the AI ground every day of the schedule in your actual workflows instead of inventing plausible-sounding filler."},{"title":"Read the draft critically, not passively","detail":"When the 5-day schedule comes back, read it as if you were the new hire on Day 1. Check that the order makes sense (basics before advanced), that nothing safety- or compliance-critical was skipped, and that the afternoon exercises are things a beginner could actually do. The AI does not know your real deadlines, tools, or people — treat its output as a knowledgeable intern's first draft that a manager must approve."},{"title":"Refine with plain-language follow-ups","detail":"You do not need to rewrite the prompt to fix things. Just reply in the same chat: 'Day 2 is too heavy, move the reconciliation task to Day 4' or 'Add a 30-minute compliance briefing every morning' or 'Make the reflection questions harder.' The AI keeps the context and revises just that part. Iterating this way two or three times is normal and gets you from good to genuinely usable."},{"title":"Fill in the human details the AI cannot know","detail":"Once the structure is right, add the specifics only you have: real meeting times, the actual Slack channel or shared drive, who to shadow, the login the new hire needs, and any 'ask [name] before you do this' guardrails. This is the step that turns a generic template into your company's onboarding plan, and it takes five minutes because the hard structural work is already done."},{"title":"Export it into your welcome documentation","detail":"Copy the finished schedule into your onboarding packet, a shared doc, or the tool your team already uses (a wiki page, an email, a printed handout). Keep the AI draft you started from so that next quarter, when an SOP changes, you can paste the updated procedure back in and regenerate just the affected day rather than rebuilding from scratch."}],"prompt":"You are an expert instructional designer building new-employee onboarding.\n\nI am onboarding a new [ROLE / JOB TITLE, e.g. entry-level accounts-payable clerk] in the [DEPARTMENT, e.g. Finance] department. Below the line are our real standard operating procedures and the core tasks for this role.\n\nTurn these procedures into a comprehensive 5-day (Monday–Friday) onboarding schedule for someone brand new to this role and possibly new to the industry. Write it so a manager could hand it to the new hire as-is.\n\nFor EACH of the 5 days, provide:\n1. A one-line theme for the day.\n2. A MORNING FOCUS MODULE — the concept or procedure to learn, in plain language, with why it matters to our team.\n3. An AFTERNOON PRACTICAL EXERCISE — a concrete, hands-on task the new hire actually does to practice that morning's concept.\n4. THREE SELF-REFLECTION QUESTIONS the new hire answers to test their own understanding of our workflow.\n\nRules:\n- Order the days so basics come first and build toward independence by Friday.\n- Keep language simple; assume no prior knowledge of our tools or jargon, and briefly define any term you use.\n- Ground every module and exercise in the procedures I provide below — do not invent steps we do not have. If a procedure is missing or unclear for a day, flag it in a line that starts with \"GAP:\" so I know to fill it in.\n- Use a [TONE: friendly and encouraging / formal and precise] tone.\n- Format as clean text with clear Day headings I can paste into a document.\n\nHere are our procedures and core tasks:\n---\n[PASTE YOUR SOPs, OPERATIONS MANUAL SECTIONS, AND TASK LIST HERE]","promptNote":"Replace [ROLE / JOB TITLE], [DEPARTMENT], and [TONE] with your specifics, then paste your actual procedures where the last line indicates. The \"GAP:\" rule is the quiet star of this prompt — it forces the AI to admit where your source material is thin instead of papering over holes with invented steps.","cloud":{"bestTool":"Anthropic Claude — it handles a long operations manual pasted in one shot without losing track of earlier sections, and it follows multi-part formatting instructions (5 days x 4 parts) reliably.","steps":["Go to claude.ai and start a new chat (a free account is enough for a document this size).","Copy the prompt from the Prompt section, fill in the role, department, and tone placeholders.","Paste your SOPs and task list under the '---' line, or use the paperclip/upload button to attach the manual as a file, then send.","Read the draft, then refine by replying in plain English (e.g. 'Day 3 has a GAP flag — here is the missing procedure: ...').","Copy the final schedule into your onboarding doc. If your team lives in Google Workspace, Gemini is an equally good pick because it drops results straight into Google Docs; if you live in Microsoft 365, Copilot can pull from a manual already stored in SharePoint."]},"local":["Open your local chat interface (for example Open WebUI connected to Ollama, or LM Studio) and select an already-installed instruction-following model such as Llama 3.1 8B, Qwen2.5, or Mistral.","Paste the same prompt from the Prompt section, filling in the role, department, and tone placeholders.","Paste your SOPs and task list beneath the prompt. Because everything runs on your machine, it is safe to include confidential names, systems, and internal procedures.","Send it and let the model generate the 5-day schedule; on a laptop this may take a minute or two, which is normal for local models.","Refine with follow-up messages the same way you would in the cloud, then copy the result into your onboarding packet. If a smaller local model produces a thin schedule, feed it your procedures one or two days at a time instead of all at once."],"localNeedsSetup":true,"choose":"This decision hinges entirely on what is inside your procedures. Onboarding material is deceptively sensitive: it often embeds internal system names, security and access steps, client-handling rules, financial controls, or HR data — the kind of thing you do not want sitting in a public chatbot's logs. If your source contains any of that, use a LOCAL model so nothing leaves your device. If the procedures are generic and low-stakes (how we run the weekly stand-up, how to submit a timesheet), a cloud tool is faster, produces a cleaner draft, and is perfectly appropriate. When in doubt, redact the sensitive names into placeholders and use the cloud, or just run it locally.","example":{"input":"You are an expert instructional designer... I am onboarding a new entry-level accounts-payable clerk in the Finance department... [pasted SOPs] Invoice intake: invoices arrive in the shared AP inbox; log each in the tracker with vendor, amount, due date. 3-way match: match invoice to purchase order and receiving report before approval. Exceptions over $5,000 route to the Controller. Payment run: batch approved invoices every Thursday. Month-end: reconcile the AP aging report.","output":"DAY 1 — Getting Oriented: How Invoices Reach Us\n\nMorning Focus Module: The AP inbox and the invoice tracker. An invoice is a bill a vendor sends us; every one must be logged before anything else happens. You will learn where the shared AP inbox lives and how we record each invoice (vendor, amount, due date) in the tracker so nothing gets lost or paid twice.\n\nAfternoon Practical Exercise: Log 5 sample invoices from the practice inbox into the tracker. Confirm each has a vendor, amount, and due date filled in.\n\nSelf-Reflection Questions:\n1. Why must every invoice be logged before it is paid?\n2. What three pieces of information does our tracker require for each invoice?\n3. What would happen downstream if you skipped logging one?\n\nDAY 2 — The 3-Way Match\n\nMorning Focus Module: Matching an invoice to its purchase order (the pre-approved order we sent the vendor) and the receiving report (proof we got the goods). This is how we make sure we only pay for what we actually ordered and received.\n\nAfternoon Practical Exercise: Complete a 3-way match on 3 practice invoices; flag any where the numbers do not line up.\n\nSelf-Reflection Questions:\n1. What are the three documents in a 3-way match?\n2. What should you do when an invoice does not match its PO?\n3. Why does this step protect the company from overpaying?\n\nDAY 3 — Approvals and Exceptions\nGAP: The SOP does not specify who approves invoices UNDER $5,000. Please confirm the approver so I can complete this module.\n... (Days 4 and 5 continue: Thursday payment run, then month-end reconciliation and working independently)","note":"Notice the 'GAP:' line on Day 3 — the AI caught that your SOP never says who approves small invoices, turning a hole in your manual into a to-do rather than an invented answer."},"tips":["Give the AI the role's level, not just its title. 'Entry-level clerk, first job out of school' produces gentler pacing and more definitions than a bare job title.","Ask for the 'GAP:' flags explicitly (the prompt does this). They are a free audit of your own documentation — every gap is a real hole a new hire would have hit.","Regenerate one day at a time when refining. 'Rewrite only Day 4' keeps the good days intact instead of shuffling the whole schedule.","Ask the AI to add a short glossary of your internal jargon at the end; new hires cite 'undefined acronyms' as a top onboarding frustration.","Save your final prompt and the pasted procedures. When an SOP changes next quarter, you paste the new version and regenerate in two minutes instead of rebuilding."],"mistakes":["Pasting a one-line brief instead of real procedures. The AI will happily invent a generic schedule that has nothing to do with your workflow — always feed it your actual SOPs.","Putting confidential internal procedures into a public cloud chatbot. Check for client names, credentials, and financial or HR data first, and use a local model if any are present.","Handing the raw AI draft straight to a new hire. It does not know your real times, tools, or people — always do the human-details pass and a manager review before it goes live.","Cramming everything into Day 1 by not asking for pacing. Explicitly tell the AI to build from basics to independence, or it may front-load the hardest tasks.","Ignoring the 'GAP:' flags. They are the AI telling you your own manual is incomplete; skipping them means the new hire hits that same missing step in real life."],"related":["t4","t11","t18"]},{"id":"t18","num":18,"cat":"O","title":"The Executive Briefing Scaffolding Matrix","tagline":"Turn a messy pile of project notes into a clean, five-section executive briefing outline in about two minutes, so your update to leadership practically writes itself.","audience":"Directors, team leads, and project managers who owe periodic status updates to executives or a steering committee. Especially useful for the non-technical professional who has plenty to report but freezes at the blank page, or who tends to bury the one important number three paragraphs down where nobody sees it.","why":"Executives skim. In seconds they want to know: Are we on track, what does it cost, what is at risk, and what do you need from me? The hardest part of an executive briefing is not the words, it is deciding what goes where and in what order. This tutorial uses AI as an organizer, not a ghostwriter. You dump every fact you have, and the AI sorts your raw notes into a proven five-part structure, showing you exactly which of your facts belong under each heading. Then you write the final memo yourself. Because you keep the pen, the numbers stay accurate and the voice stays yours; you just skip the paralyzing \"how do I structure this?\" step. Reach for it whenever a quarterly review, board update, or leadership stand-up is due and your raw material is a chaotic list.","need":["A pile of raw project notes: wins, blockers, budget figures, dates, and any decisions you need approved (a messy bulleted list is exactly right; it does not need to be tidy)","Any AI chat tool: a cloud one (Claude, Google Gemini, or Microsoft Copilot) or a local model running in a chat app on your own computer","The copy-pasteable prompt below (the whole trick is in that one prompt)","About 10 minutes: 2 to run the prompt, the rest to write the final memo from the outline it gives you","A sense of who the reader is (a busy VP, a board, your director) so you can judge the tone of the final draft"],"steps":[{"title":"Gather every fact into one raw brain dump","detail":"Open a blank note and dump everything you know about the project right now: finished work, active blockers, dollar figures, deadlines, and any decision you need leadership to make. Do not organize it, write full sentences, or worry about duplicates. The AI works best with the complete picture, so include too much rather than too little; a stray fact is easy to delete later, but a missing one can leave a hole in your briefing."},{"title":"Open your AI tool and paste the prompt first, then your notes","detail":"Start a fresh chat so old conversation does not confuse the AI. Paste the full prompt from the Prompt section, then paste your brain dump where it says [PASTE YOUR RAW PROJECT NOTES HERE]. Putting the instructions before the messy data matters: it tells the AI what job to do before it sees the pile, so it reads your notes as raw material to sort rather than a report to summarize."},{"title":"Notice the key instruction: build the scaffold, do not write the report","detail":"The single most important line in the prompt is telling the AI NOT to write the final memo, only to sort your notes into a labeled outline. This keeps you in control of the actual wording and, critically, stops the AI from inventing facts or numbers to fill gaps. You want a skeleton with your real notes clipped under the right headings, not a polished paragraph that might contain a figure you never gave it."},{"title":"Read the outline and spot the empty sections","detail":"Run the prompt and read what comes back: five numbered headers with your notes sorted underneath. The most valuable thing here is often the gaps. If \"Required Approvals\" is empty, ask yourself whether you actually need a decision from leadership and forgot to note it. If \"Financial Metrics\" is thin, that is your cue to pull the real budget number before you present. The scaffold reveals what your update is missing while there is still time to fix it."},{"title":"Fix the sort if anything landed in the wrong bucket","detail":"The AI sorts by best guess and will occasionally misfile a note; a hiring delay might land under Milestones when it belongs under Risks. Just tell it in plain language: \"Move the note about the delayed vendor contract from Milestones to Immediate Risks.\" You can also add a fact you forgot: \"Add under Financial Metrics that we are $12K under budget for Q3.\" Iterating in conversation is normal and fast."},{"title":"Write the final memo yourself, section by section","detail":"Now the hard part is done. Walk through the outline top to bottom and turn each cluster of sub-bullets into two or three tight sentences in your own voice. Lead with the Strategic Summary so a skimming executive gets the headline first. Because every fact under each heading is one you supplied, you can write confidently and fast, and you never have to double-check whether the AI made something up."},{"title":"Do a final read as if you were the executive","detail":"Read your draft once from your reader's chair. Can they answer \"on track? cost? risk? what do you need from me?\" in under a minute? Trim anything that does not help them decide something. If a section is still weak, that is a real signal to go get the missing information, not to pad it with words. A short, honest briefing beats a long, vague one every time."}],"prompt":"Review the chaotic project notes at the bottom of this message.\n\nIMPORTANT: Do NOT write the final report or any polished prose. Your only job is to build a strict writing scaffold (an outline template) that I will use to write the report myself.\n\nOrganize my notes into exactly these five numbered headers, in this order:\n1. Strategic Summary (the one-line \"are we on track\" headline)\n2. Financial Metrics (budget, spend, forecast, any dollar figures)\n3. Milestones Achieved (completed work, wins, delivered items)\n4. Immediate Risks (blockers, delays, threats, dependencies)\n5. Required Approvals (decisions, sign-offs, or resources I need from leadership)\n\nRules:\n- Under each header, place the relevant items from my notes as short, logical sub-bullets, quoting my facts and numbers exactly as I wrote them. Do not invent, estimate, or add any facts, numbers, or dates I did not provide.\n- If a note could fit two headers, put it under the most decision-relevant one and note that briefly.\n- If a header has NO matching notes, still list the header and write \"[GAP - nothing provided; do I need this?]\" underneath so I can see what is missing.\n- Keep it as a bare outline of my own words. No introductions, no conclusions, no full sentences of your own.\n\nAudience for the eventual memo: [WHO WILL READ IT, e.g. \"our VP of Operations and the executive steering committee\"].\n\nHere are my raw project notes:\n[PASTE YOUR RAW PROJECT NOTES HERE]","promptNote":"Replace [WHO WILL READ IT] with your actual audience so the AI can flag what a reader at that level will care about, and paste your messy notes where marked. The two lines that do the heavy lifting are \"Do NOT write the final report\" (keeps you in control and prevents invented facts) and the \"[GAP]\" rule (surfaces what your update is missing). Everything else you can leave exactly as written.","cloud":{"bestTool":"Anthropic Claude, because it excels at faithfully reorganizing long, messy text without inventing details and reliably obeys the strict 'do not write the report, only build the scaffold' instruction, which is the whole point of this task.","steps":["Go to claude.ai and sign in (the free tier is plenty for this). Start a New Chat so no earlier conversation interferes.","Copy the full prompt above, paste it into the message box, fill in your audience, and paste your raw notes where marked.","Press Enter and read the five-header outline it returns. Look especially at any header marked [GAP] to see what you are missing.","Refine in plain English if needed: 'Move the budget overrun note to Immediate Risks' or 'Add under Required Approvals that I need sign-off to hire a contractor.'","When the outline looks right, copy it out and write your final memo from it. Optionally paste your finished draft back and ask, 'As a skimming executive, is my Strategic Summary clear in the first line?' for a quick sanity check."]},"local":["Open your local chat app (for example Open WebUI connected to Ollama, or LM Studio's chat window) and confirm your model is loaded and selected at the top.","Start a new chat, paste the full prompt above, fill in the audience line, and paste your raw project notes where marked.","Send it and read the five-header scaffold. Because the whole conversation stays on your machine, this is the safe place to include real names, exact dollar figures, and internal blockers.","Iterate in the same chat: 'That risk about the vendor belongs under Immediate Risks, move it,' or 'Add the Q3 budget number under Financial Metrics.'","Copy the finished outline into your own document and write the memo yourself. If your model supports file upload, you can attach the notes as a text file instead of pasting."],"localNeedsSetup":true,"choose":"Match the tool to how sensitive the update is. If your notes name unannounced layoffs, an at-risk client account, pre-release financials, legal exposure, or personnel issues, use a LOCAL model: an executive briefing is often the single most sensitive document you write, and running it locally means those numbers and names never leave your computer or land in a vendor's logs. For a routine internal project update with nothing confidential, a cloud tool like Claude is faster, needs no setup, and is perfectly fine. When in doubt with anything financial, personnel-related, or client-specific, keep it local.","example":{"input":"Audience: VP of Ops + steering committee. Notes: launched beta to 200 users, feedback mostly positive. behind on the mobile version, vendor is 3 weeks late on the API. spent $84K of $100K budget. onboarding flow done and shipped. need approval to hire one contractor (~$15K) to catch up mobile. also legal still hasn't signed off on the data policy. go-live target still end of Q3. churn a little higher than we hoped, ~8%.","output":"1. Strategic Summary\n  - On track overall for end-of-Q3 go-live, but mobile is at risk\n  - Beta launched to 200 users, feedback mostly positive\n\n2. Financial Metrics\n  - Spent $84K of $100K budget\n  - Requested: ~$15K for one contractor (see Required Approvals)\n\n3. Milestones Achieved\n  - Beta launched to 200 users\n  - Onboarding flow done and shipped\n\n4. Immediate Risks\n  - Mobile version behind schedule\n  - Vendor 3 weeks late on the API (root cause of mobile delay)\n  - Legal has not signed off on the data policy\n  - Churn ~8%, higher than hoped\n\n5. Required Approvals\n  - Approve hiring one contractor (~$15K) to recover mobile timeline\n  - [Note: legal sign-off on data policy may also need escalation - decide if this is an approval ask]","note":"Notice it split the single 'hire a contractor' note across Financial Metrics and Required Approvals, and flagged the legal item as a possible approval you had filed only as a risk."},"tips":["Fill in the audience line honestly. 'The board' versus 'my direct manager' changes what belongs in the Strategic Summary and how blunt the Risks section should be.","Treat empty [GAP] headers as a to-do list, not a failure. An empty Required Approvals section usually means you forgot to ask for the decision you actually need.","After the outline is built, ask the AI one follow-up: 'What is the single most important fact an executive would want in line one?' It is great at spotting the buried headline.","Keep your exact numbers in the notes and tell the AI not to touch them. You want it moving your figures around, never rounding or recomputing them.","Save the finished prompt as a reusable template. Next reporting cycle, you only swap in fresh notes and you are done in two minutes."],"mistakes":["Letting the AI write the whole memo. If you skip the 'build a scaffold, do not write the report' rule, it will produce smooth prose that may contain numbers you never gave it. Keep the pen; use the AI only to organize.","Pasting notes that are too sparse. If you give it three vague bullets, the outline will be three vague bullets. Do a genuine brain dump first; richer input means a more useful skeleton.","Trusting any figure it produces. The AI should only relocate your numbers, never generate them. Verify every dollar amount and date against your source before it goes to leadership.","Using a cloud tool for a confidential update. Pre-release financials, layoffs, or client-specific risks should go through a local model so nothing leaves your device. Decide the sensitivity before you paste.","Sending the outline itself as the briefing. The scaffold is your workbench, not the deliverable. Always turn the sub-bullets into short, readable sentences in your own voice before it reaches an executive."],"related":["t4","t11","t17"]},{"id":"t25","num":25,"cat":"O","title":"High-Volume Email Inbound Categorization and Triage Sieve","tagline":"Sort a huge pile of unread client emails into a ranked, color-coded triage table so you know exactly who to call back first.","audience":"Customer support leads, account executives, and public relations managers who open their inbox to dozens or hundreds of unread client messages and need to know, at a glance, which ones are angry, urgent, and about to churn — before they waste time reading them in random order.","why":"When you have 60 unread messages, the natural instinct is to read them top-to-bottom in the order they arrived. That is exactly backwards: the furious client threatening to cancel might be sitting at message 47, while the first ten are routine \"how do I reset my password\" notes. Reading in arrival order means your most valuable, most at-risk relationships wait the longest. AI can read the entire pile in one pass, judge each message's urgency and emotional tone, and hand you a single ranked table with the fires at the very top. You stop triaging by hand and start acting — calling the frustrated urgent accounts first, which is where customer retention is actually won or lost.","need":["A batch of raw incoming messages you can copy and paste (support tickets, client emails, feedback notes)","A cloud AI assistant OR a private local model","Two minutes to skim the table and sanity-check the top few rows before you act","A simple way to separate each message — a line of dashes works fine"],"steps":[{"title":"Collect the raw pile into one block","detail":"Copy your unread messages and paste them one after another into a single text block. Between each message, put a line of three dashes (---) so the AI can tell where one message ends and the next begins. Do not clean them up, fix typos, or trim them — the AI needs the raw, unfiltered wording, because a client's exact phrasing (\"this is the third time I've asked\") is what signals real frustration."},{"title":"Include the sender's name with each message","detail":"Make sure each message carries a name or account label, even if it's just the email 'From' line pasted at the top of that chunk. The AI can only put a name in the table if the name is somewhere in the text you give it. If a message is anonymous, that's fine — the AI will simply mark it 'Unknown', and you'll still get its priority and tone."},{"title":"Run the triage prompt","detail":"Paste the prompt from the next section above your pile of messages and send it. The prompt does three jobs at once: it reads every message, scores each on urgency and sentiment, and builds one combined table. The single most important instruction in it is the sort order — angry AND urgent accounts are forced to the very top, so the worst fires are literally the first rows you see."},{"title":"Read the top of the table first","detail":"The output is one table sorted worst-first. Start at row one and work down only as far as your time allows. The top rows are your \"call these people right now\" list; the bottom rows (calm, low-risk requests) can wait for a quieter moment or be handled by a teammate. This is the whole payoff: your effort now flows to the relationships most likely to be lost."},{"title":"Spot-check two or three rows before acting","detail":"Pick the top row and one middle row, then glance back at the original message to confirm the AI read the tone correctly. AI is very good at this but occasionally mistakes polite firmness for calm, or sarcasm for satisfaction. A ten-second check protects you from calling someone in the wrong tone or skipping a real emergency."},{"title":"Act in order, then re-run as new mail arrives","detail":"Work the list top-down, handling the urgent-and-frustrated accounts first to maximize retention. When a fresh wave of messages lands later in the day, paste the new batch and run the exact same prompt again — the process is repeatable, so your inbox never rebuilds into an unsorted backlog."}],"prompt":"You are an experienced customer support triage specialist. Below is a raw batch of inbound client messages, each separated by a line of three dashes (---). Read and process EVERY message, then organize them into one aggregated table with exactly these four columns:\\n\\n1. Sender Name — the person or account the message is from. If no name is present, write \\\"Unknown\\\".\\n2. Core Operational Request — one short plain-language phrase describing what they actually need (e.g., \\\"Refund for double charge\\\", \\\"Login broken\\\", \\\"Asking about renewal price\\\").\\n3. Priority Tier — classify as Urgent, Standard, or Low Risk. Treat anything mentioning outages, lost money, cancellation threats, legal/contract issues, or a hard deadline as Urgent.\\n4. Sentiment Flag — classify the writer's tone as Frustrated, Neutral, or Satisfied, based on their wording.\\n\\nSort the ENTIRE table so that Frustrated + Urgent accounts appear at the absolute top, followed by other Urgent, then Standard, then Low Risk at the bottom. Do not invent messages, do not merge two clients into one row, and do not editorialize outside the four columns. After the table, add one line: the total number of messages processed.\\n\\nMESSAGES:\\n[PASTE YOUR BATCH OF MESSAGES HERE, EACH SEPARATED BY --- ]","promptNote":"The only thing you replace is the bracketed line at the bottom — paste your real messages there, each separated by a line of three dashes. Everything above it is the fixed instruction set. If you use different buckets (say, \"P1/P2/P3\" instead of \"Urgent/Standard/Low Risk\"), just swap those words in column 3.","cloud":{"bestTool":"Microsoft Copilot in Outlook — it lives right inside the inbox where the messages already are, so you can summarize and triage without copy-pasting each one out by hand.","steps":["Open Outlook on the web or desktop and click into the Copilot pane, or open copilot.microsoft.com in a browser.","Select the batch of unread messages (or copy their text) and paste them below the prompt, each separated by a line of three dashes.","Send the prompt and let it build the ranked table.","Skim the top rows, then ask a follow-up like 'draft a two-line apology reply to the top three frustrated clients' to go straight from triage to action."]},"local":["Open your local chat interface (for example, Open WebUI running on Ollama, or LM Studio) — the model is already installed and running on your machine.","Pick a capable general model such as Llama 3 or Gemma.","Paste the triage prompt, then paste your batch of client messages below it, separated by lines of three dashes.","Run it and read the ranked table exactly as you would in a cloud tool — the difference is that not one client name, complaint, or email address ever left your computer."],"localNeedsSetup":true,"choose":"This task is almost always privacy-sensitive: real client names, account details, billing complaints, and sometimes contract or legal threats are exactly the kind of data you should not hand to a public cloud service without checking your company's policy. If the messages contain identifiable customer information, strongly prefer a LOCAL model so nothing leaves your device — you get the same ranked table with zero data exposure. Reach for a cloud tool (ideally Copilot in Outlook) only when the messages are already internal-safe or fully anonymized, or when your organization has an approved enterprise agreement that keeps the data private.","example":{"input":"From: Dana Reyes\nThis is the THIRD time I'm emailing. Our team has been locked out of the dashboard for two days and we have a board demo tomorrow. If this isn't fixed today we are cancelling.\n---\nFrom: Marcus Bell\nHi, quick question — where do I download last month's invoice? No rush.\n---\nFrom: Priya Shah\nJust wanted to say your new export feature is fantastic, saved us hours. Thanks!\n---\nFrom: (no name)\nI was charged $240 twice this morning and my card is now overdrawn. Please reverse one of these ASAP.","output":"Sender Name | Core Operational Request | Priority Tier | Sentiment Flag\nDana Reyes | Locked out of dashboard, cancellation threat before board demo | Urgent | Frustrated\nUnknown | Reverse a duplicate $240 charge, card overdrawn | Urgent | Frustrated\nMarcus Bell | Where to download last month's invoice | Standard | Neutral\nPriya Shah | Positive feedback on new export feature | Low Risk | Satisfied\n\nMessages processed: 4","note":"Notice Dana and the double-charge sit at the top even though Priya's happy note and Marcus's question arrived in between — the two fires are what you handle first."},"tips":["Keep each batch to a manageable size (roughly 20-50 messages). Very large pastes can make the AI rush or drop rows — split a huge backlog into two runs.","Add a fifth column if it helps you act, such as 'Suggested First Reply' or 'Owner' (which teammate should take it), by editing the column list in the prompt.","Ask for a follow-up in the same chat: 'Now draft a calm two-sentence reply for each Urgent+Frustrated row.' You go from sorted list to ready-to-send responses in seconds.","If your team already uses priority codes like P1/P2/P3, tell the AI to use those exact labels so the table drops straight into your existing workflow."],"mistakes":["Pasting messages without separators so the AI blends two clients into one row — always put a line of three dashes between messages.","Trusting the sentiment column blindly. A politely worded but genuinely urgent message can get flagged 'Neutral'; spot-check the top rows against the originals.","Stripping out the sender names before pasting, which forces every row to say 'Unknown' — leave the 'From' line in so the table is actually actionable.","Reading the whole table top-to-bottom out of habit. The point is to act on the top rows immediately, not to admire the full list.","Sending real customer names and billing details to a public cloud tool without checking your company's data policy — when in doubt, run it locally."],"related":["t4","t11","t17"]},{"id":"t3","num":3,"cat":"T","title":"The Non-Technical Code Explanation Engine","tagline":"Paste any scary-looking terminal command or code snippet and get a plain-English, line-by-line explanation of what it does and what could go wrong before you run it.","audience":"Non-technical students, business managers, and professionals who have been handed a command-line script, a Python snippet, or a local-AI setup instruction (for example, a copy-paste line from a tutorial, a README, or a colleague) and need to understand exactly what it does before running it. You do not write code, you just need to run or approve it safely and explain it to yourself or others.","why":"Copy-pasting a command you do not understand and pressing Enter is one of the most common ways people accidentally break their computer, delete files, expose a password, or install something unwanted. The problem is that terminal commands are written in a dense shorthand built for machines, not humans, so a single line can quietly do several powerful things at once. An AI is unusually good at this specific job because it has read millions of scripts and documentation pages, so it can reliably translate each symbol and flag into everyday language and flag the dangerous parts. Reach for this whenever you are about to run something you did not write yourself, when a tutorial tells you to paste a \"one-liner,\" or when you simply want to learn what a script your team uses actually does. It turns a blind leap of faith into an informed decision.","need":["An AI chat tool: a cloud one (Anthropic Claude, Google Gemini, or Microsoft Copilot) or a local model you already have running in a chat window like LM Studio or Open WebUI.","The exact code or command you want explained, copied to your clipboard (the whole thing, not a partial line).","A rough sense of your own setup so you can judge the risk (for example: Windows or Mac, and whether this is your personal laptop or a work machine).","A few minutes to read the explanation before you run anything. The whole point is to slow down for 60 seconds."],"steps":[{"title":"Copy the entire command or script, exactly as given","detail":"Select the full block of code you were told to run and copy it, including every symbol, slash, and quotation mark. Do not retype it or clean it up, because the exact characters are what determine the behavior, and a single missing dash can change what a command does entirely. If it spans multiple lines, grab all of them so the AI sees the complete picture and does not guess at missing parts."},{"title":"Open your AI chat tool and paste the prompt template plus your code","detail":"Open Claude, Gemini, Copilot, or your local chat window and paste the ready-made prompt from the Prompt section below. Then paste your copied command in the spot marked with the square brackets, replacing the placeholder text. Using the structured prompt rather than just asking 'what does this do?' is what forces the AI to go line-by-line and to call out danger, instead of giving a vague one-paragraph summary."},{"title":"Tell it your operating system and machine, so the risk notes are accurate","detail":"In the prompt there is a spot to say whether you are on Windows or Mac and whether this is a personal or work computer. This matters because the same command can be harmless on one system and destructive on another, and 'run as administrator' means very different things at home versus on a locked-down work laptop. Giving this context makes the 'what could go wrong' warnings specific to you instead of generic."},{"title":"Read the line-by-line breakdown before touching your keyboard","detail":"The AI returns each line of your code with two things: a plain-English translation of what it commands the computer to do, and the practical risk if it runs wrong. Read every line, not just the first one, because dangerous commands often hide the harmful part in the middle or at the end. This reading step is the entire safety benefit, so do not skip ahead to running it."},{"title":"Ask follow-up questions about anything that still feels fuzzy","detail":"If a line's explanation still does not make sense, or a risk sounds serious, just ask in plain language: 'Which of these lines actually change or delete files?' or 'Is line 3 safe to run on a shared work computer?' The AI keeps the earlier context, so it will answer about your specific script. Treat it like a patient expert sitting next to you, not a one-shot search box."},{"title":"Decide, and only then run it (or don't)","detail":"With the plain-English map in hand, make a real decision: run it, modify it, or walk away. If the AI flagged a line as risky (for example, one that permanently deletes files or downloads and runs code from the internet), pause and get a second opinion from a person you trust before pressing Enter. The goal is that you now understand what you are about to do, so nothing that happens is a surprise."}],"prompt":"You are a patient expert who explains code to complete beginners. I am non-technical and about to run the command/script below on my own computer, and I want to fully understand it first.\n\nMy setup: [WINDOWS or MAC], and this is my [PERSONAL or WORK] computer.\n\nHere is the exact command/script:\n[PASTE THE FULL COMMAND OR SCRIPT HERE]\n\nAnalyze it and break it down line by line. For EVERY single line (and every meaningful part of a long line), give me a two-part bullet:\n1. Literal translation — in plain, everyday English, what does this specific line tell the computer to do? No jargon; if you must use a technical term, define it in the same sentence.\n2. Risk or consequence — what could go wrong, break, or be dangerous if this line runs incorrectly, in the wrong place, or on my type of machine? Say clearly whether it changes files, deletes things, needs admin/administrator rights, connects to the internet, or downloads and runs outside code.\n\nAfter the line-by-line breakdown, give me:\n- A one-paragraph plain-English summary of what the whole thing does.\n- A short \"Before you run this\" list: the single most dangerous line, anything I should double-check, and whether this looks safe for my type of computer.\n- A \"Safe to run?\" verdict: Yes / Yes with caution / No, and one sentence why.\n\nDo not assume I know any programming. If something is unclear or looks suspicious or malicious, say so directly.","promptNote":"Replace [WINDOWS or MAC] and [PERSONAL or WORK] with your actual setup, and paste your full command where it says [PASTE THE FULL COMMAND OR SCRIPT HERE]. The two-part bullet structure and the \"Safe to run?\" verdict are the load-bearing parts, they force the AI to be thorough and to commit to a clear recommendation instead of hedging.","cloud":{"bestTool":"Anthropic Claude, because it explains code carefully and in a calm, teacherly plain-English style, handles long multi-line scripts in one paste without losing track, and reliably follows the strict line-by-line-plus-risk format this task needs.","steps":["Go to claude.ai in your browser and start a new chat (sign in with a free account if needed).","Paste the full prompt template from the Prompt section, fill in your operating system and personal-or-work choice, and paste your command where marked.","Press Enter and read the complete line-by-line breakdown, paying special attention to the 'Safe to run?' verdict at the end.","Ask any follow-up in plain English, such as 'Which line is the most dangerous?' or 'Rewrite this so it only shows me what it would do without changing anything.'","If you are unsure the AI understood, paste the command again and add 'Double-check line 3 specifically' to verify the part that worried you."]},"local":["Open your local chat window (for example LM Studio's chat tab, or Open WebUI connected to Ollama) and make sure a capable model is selected. A general-purpose or coding-capable model works best for reading scripts.","Start a new conversation and paste the same prompt template from the Prompt section, including your operating-system and personal-or-work details.","Paste your command where the template marks it, then send. Because everything runs on your own machine, the script never leaves your computer, which matters if it contains company server names, file paths, API keys, or passwords.","Read the line-by-line breakdown and ask follow-ups just as you would with a cloud tool; the local model keeps the conversation context too.","If the explanation feels thin or the model misreads a line, ask it to 'go slower and explain every symbol,' or try a larger model if you have one installed, since bigger local models read code more reliably."],"localNeedsSetup":true,"choose":"For most everyday commands from a public tutorial, README, or open-source project, a cloud tool like Claude is perfectly fine and the easiest path, since that code is already public and there is nothing private to protect. Switch to a local model when the command itself contains sensitive details you should not send to an outside service: internal server names or IP addresses, file paths that reveal client or project names, database connection strings, API keys, tokens, or passwords. Setup and deployment scripts for work systems very often embed exactly these secrets, so when in doubt about a work-related script, run the explanation locally so nothing sensitive ever leaves your device. A simple rule: if you would be uncomfortable posting the command publicly, explain it with a local model.","example":{"input":"curl -fsSL https://example.com/install.sh | sudo bash","output":"Line-by-line breakdown (Mac, personal computer):\n\n• curl -fsSL https://example.com/install.sh\n   1. Literal translation: 'curl' is a tool that downloads a file from the internet. This part reaches out to the website example.com and downloads a setup script named install.sh. The letters -fsSL just tell it to download quietly and to follow any redirects to the real location.\n   2. Risk / consequence: This connects to the internet and pulls in code written by whoever controls example.com. It does not run anything yet by itself, but you are trusting that website completely for the next step.\n\n• | sudo bash\n   1. Literal translation: The '|' pipe hands the just-downloaded script straight into 'bash', which runs it. 'sudo' means run it as the administrator, with full power over your Mac.\n   2. Risk / consequence: This is the dangerous part. It runs downloaded internet code immediately, with the highest privileges, without you ever seeing what is inside first. A malicious or buggy script here could install anything, change system settings, or delete files.\n\nPlain-English summary: This one line downloads a setup script from example.com and immediately runs it as administrator, sight unseen.\n\nBefore you run this:\n- Most dangerous line: the whole thing, because of 'sudo bash' on downloaded code.\n- Double-check: do you trust example.com completely? Consider downloading the script first and reading it before running.\n- Safe for a personal Mac only if you fully trust the source.\n\nSafe to run? Yes with caution — only if example.com is a source you genuinely trust, otherwise download and read install.sh first.","note":"Notice the AI singled out the exact fragment ('| sudo bash') that turns a harmless download into a run-anything-as-admin risk, which is the part a beginner would never spot on their own."},"tips":["Always include your operating system and whether it is a work or personal machine; the same command can be harmless on one and destructive on another, and this context makes the risk warnings actually apply to you.","For a truly scary line, add 'Rewrite this as a safe 'dry run' that only shows me what it would do without changing anything' so you can preview the effect before committing.","If a tutorial gives you several commands, paste them all at once so the AI can tell you how they work together and warn you if the order matters.","Ask the AI to rank the lines from most to least dangerous; this instantly tells you where to focus instead of reading every risk with equal alarm.","When a script pulls something from a web address, ask 'Is this download link trustworthy, and what exactly is it fetching?' so you understand what is entering your machine."],"mistakes":["Trusting a confident-sounding explanation blindly. The AI can occasionally misread an obscure command, so for anything that deletes files or needs admin rights, get a second opinion from a person before running it.","Only reading the first line or the summary. Dangerous commands often hide the harmful action in the middle or at the very end, so read every single line's risk note.","Pasting only part of a multi-line script. The AI then guesses at the missing pieces and can miss how the lines interact; always paste the complete block.","Sending a work script full of secrets to a cloud tool. If the command contains passwords, API keys, or internal server names, use a local model instead so nothing sensitive leaves your computer.","Treating 'Yes with caution' as a green light. That verdict means stop and check the specific thing the AI flagged, not proceed as if it said plain 'Yes.'"],"related":["t6","t15","t29"]},{"id":"t6","num":6,"cat":"T","title":"Non-Technical Data Cleansing Assistant","tagline":"Turn a plain-English description of your messy spreadsheet problem into a working Excel formula, SQL query, or cleanup script — without writing or knowing any code.","audience":"Operations staff, bookkeepers and accountants, marketing coordinators, and any office professional who lives in spreadsheets but has never written a formula more complex than SUM. If you have ever stared at a column of jumbled data thinking \"I know exactly what I want, I just don't know how to make Excel do it,\" this is for you.","why":"Real-world data is almost never clean: names, phone numbers, and zip codes get smashed into one cell; dates arrive in five different formats; extra spaces and stray characters break your sorts and lookups. Traditionally, fixing this meant either hours of tedious manual retyping or knowing exactly which of Excel's 500+ functions to nest inside each other — a real skill barrier. AI removes that barrier: you describe the problem in ordinary words and it hands back the exact formula, so the machine writes the code and you stay in charge of checking it. This is the single highest-leverage AI skill for a non-technical office worker, because it turns a task that used to take an afternoon (or a favor from the IT department) into a two-minute conversation. It also scales — once you have the formula, it runs on 10 rows or 100,000 rows just the same.","need":["A spreadsheet app you already use — Microsoft Excel or Google Sheets — with a few real rows of your messy data open in front of you.","Access to one AI assistant: Microsoft Copilot, Google Gemini, or Anthropic Claude in a browser (free tiers work fine for this).","A clear picture of two things: exactly what your data looks like now, and exactly what you want the result to look like.","2–3 copied example rows from your real data to paste in as samples (this is what makes the formula actually fit).","For sensitive data (client records, financials, HR, anything regulated): a locally installed model via Ollama or LM Studio, so the data never leaves your computer."],"steps":[{"title":"Define the problem before you touch the AI","detail":"Write one or two sentences describing what you HAVE and what you WANT. Be painfully literal: 'I have a column where names, phone numbers, and 5-digit zip codes are jammed together separated by hyphens, and I want just the zip code in a new column.' The clearer this sentence is, the better the formula — the AI can only solve the problem you actually describe, so spending 60 seconds here saves you five rounds of back-and-forth later."},{"title":"Grab 2 or 3 real sample rows","detail":"Copy a small handful of actual cells from your sheet — including at least one weird or edge-case row (a missing value, an extra-long entry, a blank). Paste these into the prompt as examples. This is the single most important thing you can do: a formula built against your real data patterns will work; one built against the AI's guess about your data often breaks on row 4. Never skip the samples."},{"title":"Tell the AI which app you're using","detail":"An Excel formula, a Google Sheets formula, and a SQL query are written differently, and even within Excel the newer TEXTSPLIT/TEXTBEFORE functions only exist in Microsoft 365. State your exact tool ('Excel for Microsoft 365' or 'Google Sheets') so you get a formula that actually pastes and runs. If a formula comes back with a #NAME? error, it usually means it used a function your version doesn't have — just tell the AI your version and ask for an alternative."},{"title":"Send the structured prompt","detail":"Paste the prompt template from the Prompt section below, dropping your problem description and sample rows into the brackets. It forces the AI to give you the formula in a clean, copy-ready block plus a short plain-English explanation of how it handles the tricky parts (like where one field ends and the next begins). The explanation matters — it's how you learn to trust or question the result instead of blindly pasting."},{"title":"Paste it into ONE cell and eyeball the result","detail":"Put the formula in the first empty cell next to your data and press Enter. Look at that single result against the original row: is the zip code exactly right? Did it grab 5 digits, not 4 or 6? Do NOT drag it down the whole column yet. Testing one cell first catches 90% of problems while they're still easy to fix."},{"title":"Test on your tricky rows, then fill down","detail":"Copy the formula down over 10–20 rows, deliberately including the weird ones you noticed in step 2. Scan for anything that looks off — a blank, an error like #VALUE!, a result that captured too much or too little. If something breaks, copy the exact broken input back to the AI and say 'this row returned X but should return Y, fix the formula.' Only once it survives the tricky rows do you fill it down the entire column."},{"title":"Freeze the results if you're done with them","detail":"A formula keeps recalculating and depends on the original messy column staying put. If you want the cleaned values as permanent, standalone data, select the result column, copy it, then use Paste Special > Values to replace the formulas with the plain text they produced. Now you can safely delete or move the original messy column without your clean data vanishing."}],"prompt":"You are an advanced data-engineering assistant helping someone who does not write code. Write a clean, working [Excel for Microsoft 365 / Google Sheets / SQL] formula to solve the data problem below.\n\nWHAT I HAVE: [Describe your current data in plain words — e.g., \"a single column, A2:A500, where a person's name, phone number, and a 5-digit US zip code are combined and separated by hyphens.\"]\n\nWHAT I WANT: [Describe the exact result — e.g., \"just the 5-digit zip code pulled into its own column.\"]\n\nREAL SAMPLE ROWS (these are exactly what my cells look like, including the messy edge cases):\n[Paste 2–4 real rows here, e.g.:\nJane Doe-713-555-0142-77002\nBob-O'Brien-8325550199-77598-EXTRA\n(blank row)]\n\nRULES FOR YOUR ANSWER:\n1. Output the exact, ready-to-paste formula inside a code block, written for a cell in row 2 (so I can fill it down).\n2. Assume my data starts in cell A2. Tell me which cell to paste the formula into.\n3. Only use functions available in the tool I named above.\n4. Then give a brief 3–4 sentence plain-English explanation of how the formula finds the boundaries between the fields — where one piece of data ends and the next begins.\n5. Tell me what the formula will return for a blank cell or a row that doesn't match the expected pattern, so I know what errors to watch for.\nDo not write an essay. Formula first, short explanation second.","promptNote":"Replace the tool name in the first line and delete the options you don't need. Fill the three bracketed blocks with your own words and — critically — your own real sample rows. If your data starts somewhere other than cell A2, say so; the formula depends on it.","cloud":{"bestTool":"Microsoft Copilot in Excel, because it lives inside the spreadsheet, can read your actual columns, and writes the formula straight into the cell — so you skip all copy-pasting and it already knows which functions your Excel version supports.","steps":["Open your spreadsheet in Excel (Microsoft 365 with a Copilot license). Click an empty cell next to your messy data, or type = and choose 'Ask Copilot for a formula.'","Describe the task in plain English using the pattern from the Prompt above — Copilot can see your data, so you can say 'pull the 5-digit zip out of column A' without pasting samples.","Let it insert the suggested formula, press Enter, and check the single result against the original row before doing anything else.","If it's wrong, click Copilot again and refine — e.g., 'that grabbed 6 digits, I only want the last 5' — then re-run.","Once one cell is correct, fill the formula down and spot-check your tricky rows. If you don't have Copilot in Excel, paste the same prompt into Gemini or Claude in a browser and copy the formula back into your sheet by hand."]},"local":["Open your local chat app (Open WebUI in front of Ollama, or LM Studio) and pick a capable installed model — an instruction-tuned model in the 7B–14B range, or a code-focused one like a Qwen-Coder or Llama variant, handles formulas well.","Paste the exact prompt template from the Prompt section, including your real sample rows. Because the model runs entirely on your machine, those rows never leave your computer — safe for client, financial, or HR data.","Read the formula it returns and copy it into your spreadsheet. Paste it into one cell first and verify the result, just as you would with a cloud tool.","If it breaks on a row, paste the broken input back into the same chat and ask for a fix — the whole conversation stays local.","Optional power move: if you've installed an Excel-to-Ollama add-in, you can call the model directly from a cell, but for one-off formulas the copy-paste-from-chat approach is simpler and needs no setup."],"localNeedsSetup":true,"choose":"For everyday, non-sensitive data — a marketing list of public store locations, a tidy-up of your own event RSVPs — a cloud tool is the easiest and fastest choice, and Copilot inside Excel is hard to beat. But the moment your spreadsheet contains anything you wouldn't email to a stranger — customer PII, employee salaries, patient IDs, financial records, anything under HIPAA, GDPR, or a client confidentiality agreement — use a LOCAL model instead. The reason is simple and non-negotiable: pasting real sample rows into a cloud AI sends that data to an outside company's servers, which can violate compliance rules and your own data-handling policies. A local model keeps every byte on your machine, so you get the same formula-writing help with zero data exposure. When in doubt about sensitivity, go local.","example":{"input":"You are an advanced data-engineering assistant... Write a clean, working Excel for Microsoft 365 formula.\nWHAT I HAVE: a single column A2:A500 where a name, phone number, and 5-digit zip are combined, separated by hyphens.\nWHAT I WANT: just the 5-digit zip in its own column.\nREAL SAMPLE ROWS:\nJane Doe-713-555-0142-77002\nBob-O'Brien-8325550199-77598\n(blank cell)","output":"Formula (paste into cell B2, then fill down):\n\n=IFERROR(TEXTAFTER(A2,\"-\",-1),\"\")\n\nHow it works: TEXTAFTER pulls everything after a chosen hyphen. The -1 tells it to count from the RIGHT, so it grabs whatever follows the LAST hyphen in the cell — which is always your zip code, no matter how many hyphens came before it. IFERROR wraps the whole thing so that a blank cell or a row with no hyphen returns an empty string instead of an error.\n\nWhat to watch for: a blank cell returns blank. A row where the zip isn't last (e.g., a trailing '-EXTRA' tag) would return 'EXTRA' — if you have those, tell me and I'll add a 5-digit check.","note":"Notice it counts hyphens from the right (-1), which is why it survives rows with different numbers of hyphens — and it flags exactly the edge case that would break it."},"tips":["Always paste real sample rows, not a description of them. 'Names and zips separated by hyphens' is far weaker than three actual pasted cells — the AI spots patterns you forgot to mention, like an apostrophe in O'Brien or a stray trailing tag.","Ask for the plain-English explanation every time and actually read it. It teaches you what TEXTAFTER or MID is doing, so next time you'll catch a wrong answer instantly instead of trusting a bad formula on 5,000 rows.","When a formula is wrong, don't start over — reply with the exact input and the wrong output ('row 12 was ...-77598-EXTRA and it returned EXTRA, I need 77598') and let the AI patch it. Iterating beats rewriting.","Name your exact app and version. Say 'Excel for Microsoft 365' or 'Google Sheets' — modern functions like TEXTSPLIT and TEXTBEFORE don't exist in older Excel or in Sheets, and a mismatch gives you a #NAME? error.","For a truly one-off cleanup you don't need to repeat, ask the AI to just return the cleaned values directly, or use Excel's Flash Fill (type the answer for the first 2 rows, then Ctrl+E) — sometimes you don't need a formula at all."],"mistakes":["Dragging the formula down the whole column before testing one cell. Always verify a single result first, then 10 tricky rows, THEN fill down — a wrong formula applied to 100,000 rows is a mess to untangle.","Giving no sample data, so the AI guesses your format wrong. Fix: always paste 2–4 real rows, including your ugliest edge case.","Not specifying the tool, then getting a #NAME? error from a function your version lacks. Fix: state 'Excel for Microsoft 365' or 'Google Sheets' up front, and if you hit #NAME? tell the AI your exact version and ask for an alternative.","Pasting confidential client or employee data into a public cloud AI. Fix: if the data is sensitive or regulated, use a local model so nothing leaves your machine.","Deleting the original messy column while the clean column is still a live formula — the results vanish. Fix: Copy the results, Paste Special > Values to lock them in, and only then remove the original."],"related":["t3","t15","t29"]},{"id":"t15","num":15,"cat":"T","title":"Complex Troubleshooting Diagnostic Companion","tagline":"Turn a broken machine and a vague symptom into a safe, ranked, step-by-step diagnosis you can act on in minutes, without waiting for a field engineer.","audience":"Facilities managers, field service technicians, maintenance staff, and operations supervisors who keep equipment running: HVAC units, compressors, conveyors, pumps, generators, kitchen or lab equipment, and production machinery. It assumes zero AI experience and only the hands-on knowledge you already have about your own equipment.","why":"When a machine fails, the two most expensive mistakes are guessing wrong and skipping a safety step. A troubleshooting companion turns a jumbled symptom (\"orange light, clicking, fan dead\") into a structured plan: first the safety lockout steps you must do before you touch anything, then the most likely causes ranked from the cheap five-minute check to the expensive one. That ordering matters because most real failures are the simple thing, a tripped breaker, a clogged filter, a blown fuse, a stuck contactor, and checking those first often saves a costly service call. Reach for it whenever you are staring at a failure you can't immediately place, when you want a second opinion before escalating, or when you need to hand a junior tech a safe, do-this-next checklist. It does not replace your judgment or a licensed professional for high-voltage, gas, refrigerant, or pressure work; it makes your first twenty minutes systematic instead of frantic.","need":["A chat AI tool: a cloud one (Microsoft Copilot, Google Gemini, or Anthropic Claude) or a local model already installed on your PC (LM Studio, or Ollama with Open WebUI).","The equipment's make, model number, and any error code or blinking-light pattern (usually on the nameplate, door label, or display).","A plain-language description of what the machine is doing and not doing, plus any noises, smells, leaks, or recent changes.","Your site's lockout/tagout (LOTO) rules and your PPE (gloves, safety glasses); the AI's safety list supplements them, it does not replace them.","For anything involving high voltage, gas, refrigerant, or pressure vessels: the phone number of a licensed professional to escalate to."],"steps":[{"title":"Gather the facts before you open the chat","detail":"Walk to the unit and write down four things: the make and model from the nameplate, any error code or light pattern, exactly what it does versus what it should do, and any noise, smell, leak, or recent change (a storm, a filter swap, a power blip). The AI can only be as accurate as the details you feed it, so 'clicking three times then an orange light, fan never spins' beats 'it's broken.' Snap a phone photo of the nameplate and the display so you copy the model number exactly, one wrong digit sends the AI to the wrong manual."},{"title":"Open your AI tool and set the role","detail":"Open a cloud chat (Copilot, Gemini, or Claude) or your local chat app. Start the conversation by telling it who to be and what you want, because a generic assistant gives generic answers, but 'act as a master maintenance technician, safety first' primes it to lead with lockout steps and think in failure modes. You'll paste one big prompt (the template below) that sets the role and asks the two questions at once, so you don't have to steer it turn by turn."},{"title":"Paste the prompt with your real symptoms filled in","detail":"Copy the prompt template, replace every [BRACKET] with your specifics, and send it. Be literal: put the exact model number, the exact light color and blink count, and the exact sounds in order. The more concrete the symptom, the tighter the ranked causes, vague inputs produce vague, useless 'could be many things' answers."},{"title":"Do the safety checklist first, in order, no skipping","detail":"The AI's first output is a pre-inspection safety checklist: cut power, lock out and tag out, discharge stored energy, verify zero energy, let hot or moving parts stop. Do every item physically before you touch the machine, even the 'obvious' ones, because the whole point of a written checklist is to catch the step you'd skip when you're rushing. If any item is beyond your training or authorization (opening a gas line, handling refrigerant, live high-voltage testing), stop and escalate, that is a correct outcome, not a failure."},{"title":"Work the ranked causes from simplest to hardest","detail":"The AI gives its top likely causes ordered cheap-and-easy first (breaker, fuse, filter, loose plug) to complex-and-costly last (failed compressor, control board). Check them in that order and rule each out before moving on, because starting at the easy end is where most real failures actually live and it stops you from expensively chasing the exotic cause first. After each check, tell the AI what you found, 'breaker is fine, capacitor reads zero on the meter', and it narrows the diagnosis with you."},{"title":"Resolve, or escalate with a clean handoff","detail":"If you find and safely fix the cause (reset the breaker, swap the fuse, clear the clog), verify the machine runs normally before restoring it to service. If it points to something beyond your scope or you've exhausted the safe checks, ask the AI to 'summarize the symptoms, what I tested, and what I ruled out, as a handoff note for the field engineer.' Handing a service tech a tidy list of what's already been eliminated saves diagnostic time and money, and makes you look sharp."},{"title":"Verify the advice against reality, not the other way around","detail":"Treat the AI as a knowledgeable colleague who can be confidently wrong, not as the equipment manual. If a suggested reading, torque spec, or wiring detail matters for safety, confirm it against the actual service manual or the nameplate before acting on it. The AI is excellent at structuring your thinking and jogging your memory on failure modes; it is not a substitute for the manufacturer's documentation on the specifics."}],"prompt":"Act as a master maintenance technician with 20+ years of hands-on experience, and safety is your first priority.\n\nHere is the equipment and the problem:\n- Equipment type: [E.G. ROOFTOP HVAC UNIT / AIR COMPRESSOR / CONVEYOR MOTOR]\n- Make and model: [EXACT MAKE AND MODEL FROM THE NAMEPLATE]\n- Error code or indicator: [EXACT ERROR CODE, OR LIGHT COLOR AND BLINK PATTERN, E.G. \"ORANGE LED, 3 BLINKS THEN PAUSE\"]\n- What it is doing vs. what it should do: [E.G. \"MAKES 3 CLICKS THEN GOES SILENT; FAN NEVER SPINS; SHOULD START AND RUN\"]\n- Sounds / smells / leaks: [E.G. \"FAINT BURNING SMELL, NO LEAK, HUMMING FOR ~2 SECONDS BEFORE CLICKS\"]\n- Recent changes or events: [E.G. \"POWER FLICKERED IN A STORM LAST NIGHT\" OR \"NONE\"]\n- My skill level and what I'm allowed to do: [E.G. \"TRAINED ON BASIC ELECTRICAL AND LOTO; NOT LICENSED FOR REFRIGERANT OR HIGH-VOLTAGE WORK\"]\n\nPlease respond in exactly three parts:\n\n1) PRE-INSPECTION SAFETY CHECKLIST: a numbered, do-in-order list of the safety steps I must complete before I touch or open this unit (power isolation, lockout/tagout, discharging stored energy, verifying zero energy, waiting for hot/moving parts). Flag any step that requires a licensed professional and tell me to stop there if it is beyond my stated skill level.\n\n2) TOP 3 MOST LIKELY CAUSES: for this specific failure mode, ordered from simplest/cheapest to check first, to most complex/costly last. For each cause, give: (a) why it fits these symptoms, (b) the specific check or test to confirm it, in plain steps, and (c) roughly how hard/expensive the fix is.\n\n3) DECISION POINT: tell me clearly when I should stop and call a licensed field engineer instead of continuing.\n\nAsk me any clarifying question if a detail would change your diagnosis. Do not guess at safety-critical values, tell me to confirm them against the service manual.","promptNote":"Fill in every [BRACKET] with your real specifics, the exact model number and the exact symptom (light color, blink count, sound sequence) are the two that most change the answer. The \"my skill level\" line is important: it tells the AI where to draw the stop-and-escalate line for you. You can delete any bracket line that truly doesn't apply, but keep the three-part structure so you always get safety steps before causes.","cloud":{"bestTool":"Anthropic Claude, because troubleshooting is a back-and-forth reasoning conversation where you report each test result and it re-narrows the diagnosis, and Claude is strong at that structured, step-by-step reasoning and at holding the thread across many turns.","steps":["Go to claude.ai (or Copilot / Gemini, any of the three works fine here) and sign in, then start a new chat.","Paste the prompt template above with your [BRACKETS] filled in with the exact model, error code, and symptoms; if you have a photo of the nameplate or error display, attach it so it reads the model number itself.","Send it, then physically complete the safety checklist it returns before touching the unit.","After each cause you check, reply in the same chat with what you found ('breaker OK, capacitor reads 0 microfarads on my meter') so it narrows to the next step.","Before acting on any safety-critical number it gives (voltages, torque, refrigerant pressures), confirm it against the actual service manual, then ask it to write a handoff summary if you need to escalate."]},"local":["Open your local chat app (LM Studio, or Open WebUI if you run Ollama) and select an already-installed model; a general 7B-8B model like Llama 3.1 8B or Mistral is plenty for this.","Start a new chat and paste the same prompt template with your [BRACKETS] filled in; note that a local model can't see photos unless it's a vision model, so type the model number and error code as text.","Send it, complete the safety checklist it returns before touching the equipment, then check the ranked causes simplest-first.","Reply in the same chat with each test result so it narrows the diagnosis, exactly like the cloud flow, everything stays on your machine.","For any safety-critical spec, verify against the real service manual, because a smaller local model is more likely to state a plausible-sounding wrong number confidently."],"localNeedsSetup":true,"choose":"For most routine equipment troubleshooting, cloud is fine and easiest, the make, model, and 'the fan won't spin' aren't secrets, and cloud tools give you photo upload and sharper reasoning. Lean local when the details are sensitive: proprietary or prototype machinery, defense or regulated facilities, equipment tied to a client under NDA, or failure data you're not allowed to send off-site. On a local model nothing leaves your PC, so you can paste internal part numbers, site layouts, and incident context freely; that privacy is the reason to accept a slightly less capable model. A practical middle path: use the cloud for the general diagnosis, but strip out any confidential identifiers first.","example":{"input":"Act as a master maintenance technician, safety first. Equipment: rooftop HVAC unit. Make/model: Carrier 48TCED08. Indicator: orange LED, 3 blinks then a pause, repeating. What it's doing vs should: hums for ~2 seconds, then 3 clicks, then silent; condenser fan never spins; should start and cool. Sounds/smells/leaks: faint hum before the clicks, no burning smell, no leak. Recent: power flickered in a storm last night. My skill level: trained on basic electrical + LOTO, NOT licensed for refrigerant or high-voltage work.","output":"1) PRE-INSPECTION SAFETY CHECKLIST\n  1. Set the unit's disconnect switch to OFF at the rooftop disconnect box.\n  2. Lock out and tag out that disconnect (your lock, your tag).\n  3. Confirm the thermostat/call for cooling is off so it can't try to restart.\n  4. Wait 5 minutes and treat the run capacitor as CHARGED, it stores a dangerous shock even with power off. Discharge it only if trained; if not, STOP and call a pro.\n  5. Verify zero voltage at the contactor with a meter before touching wiring.\n  NOTE: A 3-blink code on many Carrier boards points to a specific fault, confirm the exact meaning on the unit's fault-code label or service manual before trusting my read.\n\n2) TOP 3 MOST LIKELY CAUSES (simplest first)\n  Cause | Why it fits | How to check | Fix effort\n  Failed run capacitor | Hum-then-click, fan won't start, and a storm surge commonly kills capacitors | With power locked out and cap discharged, read microfarads with a meter; compare to the rating printed on it | Cheap part, easy swap\n  Stuck/failed contactor | Clicking is the contactor chattering; storm surge can pit the contacts | Inspect for pitting/melting; check it pulls in and passes voltage through | Low-cost part, moderate\n  Board fault / seized fan motor | 3-blink code + no fan can mean a control-board fault or a locked-rotor motor | Confirm the blink-code meaning; test motor windings, escalate if board-level | Costly, often a pro job\n\n3) DECISION POINT\n  Do the capacitor and contactor checks only if you can safely lock out and discharge the cap. The moment it points to the control board, refrigerant, or high-voltage testing, stop, that's beyond your stated scope, call a licensed HVAC engineer. Want a handoff note summarizing what you tested?","note":"Notice it leads with lockout and the capacitor-discharge warning before any diagnosis, ranks the five-dollar fix ahead of the board replacement, and hands the exotic causes to a licensed pro."},"tips":["Give it the exact fault code or blink pattern, not just the color. 'Orange, 3 blinks then pause' unlocks a specific failure meaning; 'orange light' does not.","Feed results back after every check. The tool gets sharper as you tell it what you ruled out, treat it as a live conversation, not a one-shot answer.","Attach a photo of the nameplate and the error display (cloud tools). It reads the exact model number and code so you don't transcribe a digit wrong.","End every session by asking for a handoff summary, even if you fixed it. A one-paragraph record of symptom, cause, and fix builds your maintenance log and speeds up the next occurrence.","Tell it your skill and authorization level up front so its stop-and-escalate line matches what you're actually allowed to touch."],"mistakes":["Skipping the safety checklist to jump straight to the fix. The checklist exists to catch the step you'd skip when rushing, do every item, including the 'obvious' power-off.","Trusting a safety-critical number the AI states (voltage, refrigerant pressure, torque). Models can sound confident and be wrong, always confirm those against the real service manual.","Feeding it a vague symptom ('it's not working'). You get a vague, useless list back, describe the noises, lights, and sequence in concrete order instead.","Continuing past your training because the AI listed a next step. If a step needs a license (refrigerant, gas, live high-voltage), stopping and escalating is the correct move, not a failure.","Putting confidential equipment or site details into a cloud tool when policy forbids it. If the data is sensitive, use a local model where nothing leaves your machine, or strip the identifiers first."],"related":["t3","t6","t29"]},{"id":"t29","num":29,"cat":"T","title":"Technical Documentation and User Manual Sifter","tagline":"Turn a 300-page equipment or software manual into a 30-second, plain-English answer for the exact error code or setting you are stuck on.","audience":"Office managers installing new hardware, administrative assistants configuring software, and field or facilities staff standing in front of a machine that just threw an error code. Anyone who has ever flipped through a giant PDF manual trying to find the one paragraph that matters while the equipment sits broken.","why":"Technical manuals are written to be legally complete, not readable. The one sentence you need is buried in hundreds of pages of safety boilerplate, spec tables, and warranty language, and the index almost never lists your exact error code. An AI can read that entire wall of text in seconds, find the passage that matches your specific problem, and rewrite it in language a non-technician can act on. This saves you from either guessing (and possibly damaging the equipment or voiding the warranty) or waiting hours for a technician to fix something you could have handled yourself in two minutes. Just as importantly, a good prompt forces the AI to tell you the thing manuals bury: the exact point where you must stop and call a professional for safety or warranty reasons.","need":["The manual, either as a PDF you can upload or as text you can copy and paste (from the PDF, the manufacturer's website, or a photo run through a phone scanner app).","The exact error code, model number, or setting name you are trying to resolve — copied character-for-character, including dashes and letters (for example '14-B', not '14b').","One AI chat tool: a free cloud account (Google Gemini, Anthropic Claude, or Microsoft Copilot) or a local model already running on your computer.","The prompt template below, ready to paste and fill in.","The physical equipment or the software screen in front of you, so you can act on the answer immediately and safely."],"steps":[{"title":"Grab the exact code or setting, and the section that describes it","detail":"Before you touch the AI, write down the precise error code, model number, or setting name exactly as the machine or screen shows it — capitalization and dashes matter, because '14-B' and '14B' can be different faults in the same manual. Then get the relevant part of the manual into a form the AI can read: either save the whole PDF to upload, or open the troubleshooting/error-code section and copy the text. If your only copy is paper, photograph the pages with a free scanner app (like the one built into your phone's Notes or Files) so it becomes selectable text."},{"title":"Open your AI tool and start a fresh chat","detail":"Open Google Gemini, Anthropic Claude, or Microsoft Copilot in your browser (or your local chat app). Start a new, empty conversation so old topics don't confuse the answer. Starting fresh matters because these tools remember earlier messages in the same chat, and leftover context from an unrelated question can bleed into your troubleshooting answer."},{"title":"Give the AI the manual — upload the file or paste the text","detail":"If the tool lets you attach files (Gemini and Claude both do, Copilot does too), click the paperclip or attach button and upload the whole PDF; this is best because the AI can search the entire document, not just the part you happened to find. If you can only paste text, paste the troubleshooting section into the message box. Don't worry if it's long — that's exactly the filler the AI is built to wade through for you."},{"title":"Paste the prompt and fill in your specifics","detail":"Copy the prompt template from the section below into the same message, then replace every [BRACKETED] placeholder with your real details — the equipment name, the model number, and the exact error code. The prompt is written to force three things a manual buries: which physical part is at fault, a reset you can safely do yourself, and the exact point where you must stop and call a technician. Filling in the placeholders precisely is what makes the answer about YOUR problem instead of a generic summary."},{"title":"Read the answer, then verify it against the manual","detail":"The AI will hand you a short, plain-English answer. Before you act, do a 10-second sanity check: ask it 'Quote the exact sentence from the manual that says this' or scroll the PDF to the code it cited. This matters because AI can occasionally 'fill in' a plausible-sounding step that isn't in your manual (this is called a hallucination), and with equipment a wrong step can be unsafe or costly. If the cited text matches, you're safe to proceed."},{"title":"Perform only the safe, self-serviceable steps — and know when to stop","detail":"Do the manual reset or reconnection steps the AI listed as user-safe, one at a time, checking whether the error clears after each. The moment you reach the 'stop and call a technician' line — anything involving opening a sealed panel, high voltage, gas, pressure, or 'authorized service only' — STOP. That boundary exists for your safety and to keep the warranty valid, and no time saved is worth an injury or a voided service contract."},{"title":"Save the working answer for next time","detail":"When a fix works, paste it (and the error code) into a shared notes doc, a team wiki, or an email to yourself. Error codes recur, and the second time this machine throws '14-B' you or a colleague can skip the whole process. Over a few months this quietly becomes your own searchable, plain-English troubleshooting cheat sheet built from the manuals you actually use."}],"prompt":"You are a plain-language technical assistant helping a NON-TECHNICAL user troubleshoot equipment safely. I am attaching (or pasting below) troubleshooting documentation from the manual for my equipment.\n\nEquipment: [MAKE AND MODEL, e.g. Carrier 48TC rooftop HVAC unit]\nThe exact problem indicator showing on the equipment: [ERROR CODE / MESSAGE / SETTING, e.g. Error Code 14-B]\n\nDo the following:\n1. Find the EXACT code/message \"[PASTE THE SAME CODE AGAIN]\" in the documentation. If that exact code is NOT present in the text, say so plainly and do not guess — list the closest codes you do find instead.\n2. Once found, give me a summary written for someone with NO technical background, in exactly these four bullets:\n   - WHAT IS WRONG: In one sentence, which physical component or setting is failing, in plain words.\n   - WHAT I CAN SAFELY TRY MYSELF: The manual reset or reconnection sequence, as numbered steps, using only actions a non-technician can safely perform (no opening sealed panels, no electrical/gas/pressure work).\n   - STOP AND CALL A TECHNICIAN IF: The exact point at which I must stop for safety or warranty reasons, and why.\n   - SOURCE CHECK: Quote the single sentence or line from the documentation that this fix is based on, word for word, so I can verify it.\n\nRules: Use only what is in the documentation I gave you. Do not invent steps that aren't in the text. If the manual is unclear or the code isn't there, tell me directly rather than guessing. Keep it short and skimmable.\n\nDOCUMENTATION:\n[PASTE THE TROUBLESHOOTING SECTION HERE, OR ATTACH THE PDF AND WRITE \"See attached file.\"]","promptNote":"Replace [MAKE AND MODEL] and [ERROR CODE / MESSAGE / SETTING] with your real details, and paste the exact code a second time where the prompt repeats it — that repetition is what forces the AI to locate the precise fault instead of summarizing the whole section. If you uploaded the PDF, just write \"See attached file.\" where the documentation goes instead of pasting text. You can reuse this template for software settings too — swap \"physical component\" wording for \"which setting or menu.\"","cloud":{"bestTool":"Google Gemini — its very large context window can ingest an entire multi-hundred-page manual PDF at once, so it searches the whole document rather than just the section you happened to find (Claude is an excellent second choice for accuracy; use Copilot if the manual already lives in your Microsoft 365 files).","steps":["Go to gemini.google.com and sign in with a free Google account, then start a new chat.","Click the upload/attach (paperclip or plus) icon and upload the manual PDF; wait for it to finish processing.","Paste the prompt template, fill in your equipment model and exact error code, and send it.","Read the four-bullet answer, then reply 'Quote the exact page or sentence this came from' to verify before you act.","If the code wasn't found, reply with any alternate wording the machine shows, or upload a different section of the manual."]},"local":["Open your local chat interface (for example Open WebUI connected to Ollama, or LM Studio) and select an installed model that accepts file uploads or long text, such as a Llama or Mistral instruct model.","Start a new chat. If the model supports document upload, attach the manual PDF; otherwise copy the troubleshooting section and paste it directly into the message.","Paste the prompt template and fill in your equipment model and the exact error code.","Send it, then ask the model to 'quote the exact line from the text this is based on' so you can verify against the manual before acting.","If the pasted section is very long and the model slows or truncates, split it in half and run the two halves as separate messages, or paste only the pages around your error code."],"localNeedsSetup":true,"choose":"For a public, off-the-shelf appliance or software manual, the content is not sensitive — it is the same PDF anyone can download from the manufacturer — so a cloud tool like Gemini is the easiest and fastest choice, and its huge context window handles giant manuals best. Lean local, however, when the manual is a confidential internal document: proprietary machinery specs, defense or infrastructure equipment, an unreleased product, or anything under NDA. In those cases run it on a local model so the document never leaves your computer, since uploading a controlled or contractually protected manual to a cloud service could breach that agreement.","example":{"input":"See attached file. Equipment: Trane Voyager rooftop HVAC unit. Error on the controller reads: Error Code 14-B.\n\n[User attaches the 280-page unit installation and troubleshooting PDF.]","output":"Found Error Code 14-B in the Fault Codes table on p. 147.\n\nWHAT IS WRONG: The unit's high-pressure safety switch has tripped, which usually means airflow across the outdoor condenser coil is blocked (dirty coil, blocked fan, or debris).\n\nWHAT I CAN SAFELY TRY MYSELF:\n1. Turn the thermostat off and wait 5 minutes.\n2. Visually check the outdoor coil and fan for leaves, dirt, or debris and clear anything loose by hand (power off).\n3. Confirm the outdoor fan spins freely.\n4. Turn the thermostat back on; the controller auto-resets the 14-B lockout after power cycles.\n\nSTOP AND CALL A TECHNICIAN IF: The code returns after one clean reset, OR the coil looks clean. A repeat 14-B points to a refrigerant-charge or compressor issue — do NOT open the refrigerant lines or electrical panel. Refrigerant work is EPA-licensed only and DIY attempts void the warranty.\n\nSOURCE CHECK: \"Code 14-B: High-pressure switch open. Check condenser airflow and coil cleanliness. If fault persists after reset, service refrigeration circuit — qualified personnel only.\" (p. 147)","note":"Notice the SOURCE CHECK bullet quotes the manual's own line and cites the page, so you can confirm the fix in 10 seconds before touching the unit."},"tips":["Always paste the exact error code twice — once as your problem and once inside the 'find this exact code' instruction. This anchors the AI to the precise fault and stops it from summarizing the whole troubleshooting chapter.","Upload the whole PDF instead of pasting a snippet whenever the tool allows it. The right answer is often cross-referenced on a different page (a code table on p. 147, the fix on p. 190), and only the full document lets the AI connect them.","Insist on a source quote. The 'quote the exact sentence' bullet turns the AI from a confident guesser into a verifiable research assistant, which is essential when a wrong step could damage equipment or hurt someone.","If the first answer is too technical, just reply 'explain step 2 like I've never seen this machine before.' You can iterate in plain English until it's actually usable — you don't have to get the prompt perfect the first time.","Keep a running notes doc of code-plus-fix pairs that worked. Recurring error codes are the norm, and your saved answers become a faster reference than the manual itself."],"mistakes":["Trusting a fix with no source. If the AI doesn't cite the manual, don't act — ask it to quote the exact line, and if it can't, the step may be invented (a hallucination). Verify before you touch the equipment.","Mistyping the code. '14B' versus '14-B' versus 'E14' can be three different faults. Copy the code exactly as shown, or photograph the display, so the AI matches the right one.","Ignoring the 'stop and call a technician' line to save time. That boundary protects your safety and your warranty — opening a sealed panel or touching refrigerant, gas, or high-voltage parts is never worth the minutes saved.","Uploading a confidential internal manual to a public cloud tool. If the document is proprietary or under NDA, use a local model so it never leaves your computer.","Pasting a giant manual into a tool with a small memory (like the basic Copilot) and getting a cut-off answer. For very long documents, prefer a large-context tool like Gemini, or paste only the pages around your error code."],"related":["t3","t6","t15"]},{"id":"t5","num":5,"cat":"G","title":"Regulatory Control Cross-Mapping Blueprint","tagline":"Have an AI read your internal policy against two regulatory frameworks at once and hand you a gap-analysis table with ready-to-paste remediation language.","audience":"Cyber compliance officers, risk managers, and data-governance auditors who own internal policy documents and must prove those policies satisfy external regulations.","why":"A control cross-map is the tedious core of compliance work: you line up every requirement in a framework (like NIST's AI Risk Management Framework or the EU AI Act) against your own policy and mark where you fall short. Done by hand it takes days per framework, is easy to get wrong, and must be redone every time a regulation changes. An AI model can read a long policy and two dense frameworks in one pass and return a structured gap table in minutes, so your human hours go to judgment and remediation instead of line-by-line reading. Reach for this when onboarding a new regulation, preparing for an audit, updating a policy after a rule change, or sanity-checking coverage before a board or regulator asks. Treat the output as an expert first draft a human must verify, never as the final compliance determination.","need":["Your internal policy as text you can paste or a file you can upload (e.g. a Data Handling Policy, AI Use Standard, or Information Security Policy)","A short, accurate summary of each framework you are mapping against — e.g. NIST AI RMF 1.0's Govern/Map/Measure/Manage functions and the EU AI Act's four risk tiers plus high-risk obligations","An AI chat tool: a cloud assistant (Claude, Gemini, or Copilot) for non-sensitive drafts, or a local model in LM Studio / Open WebUI for sensitive documents","Clarity on which framework version and date applies to you — regulations change (the EU AI Act's high-risk deadlines shifted in 2026), so a stale summary produces a wrong map","15–30 minutes, and a subject-matter reviewer to sign off on the AI's findings before anything becomes official"],"steps":[{"title":"Gather your three source documents first","detail":"Before you touch the AI, collect exactly three things in plain text: your internal policy, a summary of Framework A, and a summary of Framework B. The AI can only map what you give it, so if your framework summary is thin or outdated the gaps it finds will be wrong. Pull the framework text from an authoritative source (the NIST publication, the official EU AI Act text) rather than a random blog, and note the version and date at the top of each summary."},{"title":"Choose cloud or local based on how sensitive the policy is","detail":"Your internal policy is an unpublished company document that names your actual controls and weaknesses — a roadmap of where you are exposed. If it contains anything confidential, run this on a local model so nothing leaves your machine (see the Local section). If it is a generic or already-public draft and speed matters more than secrecy, a cloud assistant is faster and easier. Decide this before pasting anything, because you cannot un-send data to a cloud tool."},{"title":"Feed the model all three documents in one conversation","detail":"Open your chosen tool and load the two framework summaries and your policy into a single chat — upload them as files if the tool supports it, otherwise paste each under a clear heading like 'FRAMEWORK A: NIST AI RMF', 'FRAMEWORK B: EU AI ACT', and 'INTERNAL POLICY'. Keeping all three in one conversation is what lets the model cross-reference them; mapping is impossible if it only sees one at a time. Label each block so the model never confuses your policy with the regulation."},{"title":"Run the structured audit prompt","detail":"Paste the prompt from the Prompt section, which tells the model to act as a senior compliance auditor and return a fixed three-column table: Framework Requirement, Current Internal Gap, and Recommended Remediation Text. The rigid table format is deliberate — it forces the model to tie every finding to a specific requirement and to hand you drop-in policy language, instead of writing a vague essay. Ask it to cite the exact clause or function (e.g. 'EU AI Act Art. 9' or 'NIST AI RMF GOVERN 1.1') in the first column."},{"title":"Interrogate the output before you trust it","detail":"Read every row and challenge it: does the requirement actually exist in that framework, or did the model invent it? AI models can 'hallucinate' plausible-sounding clauses, so spot-check a few requirements against the real source text. Ask follow-ups like 'Show me the exact sentence in the framework each requirement comes from' and 'Did you miss any high-risk obligation?' to surface both fabrications and omissions."},{"title":"Have a human own the remediation text, then file it","detail":"The 'Recommended Remediation Text' column gives you draft policy language you can paste into your document repository — but a qualified person must edit it to match your terminology, systems, and legal counsel's guidance before it becomes policy. Track each accepted row as a remediation item with an owner and due date. The AI closes the analysis gap fast; accountability for the final control still sits with you."}],"prompt":"Act as a senior cybersecurity and AI compliance auditor with deep expertise in [FRAMEWORK A, e.g. NIST AI RMF 1.0] and [FRAMEWORK B, e.g. the EU AI Act].\n\nI am giving you three documents:\n1. FRAMEWORK A — a summary of [FRAMEWORK A, version/date].\n2. FRAMEWORK B — a summary of [FRAMEWORK B, version/date].\n3. INTERNAL POLICY — our [e.g. Internal Data Handling Draft].\n\nTask: Perform a control cross-mapping. Go through the concrete requirements of BOTH frameworks and, for each one, determine whether our internal policy contains a specific, actionable control that satisfies it. Identify every place our policy is missing, vague, or only partially covers a requirement.\n\nRules:\n- Only use requirements that genuinely appear in the frameworks I provided. Do NOT invent requirements. If you are unsure a requirement exists, say so instead of guessing.\n- In column 1, cite the exact framework clause, article, or function ID (e.g. \"EU AI Act Art. 9\" or \"NIST AI RMF GOVERN 1.1\").\n- If a requirement IS fully covered by our policy, do not list it — only report gaps and partial coverage.\n- After the table, list any high-risk or mandatory obligation you believe we are completely missing.\n\nOutput STRICTLY as a table with these columns and no other prose inside the table:\nFramework Requirement | Current Internal Gap | Recommended Policy Remediation Text\n\nMake the \"Recommended Policy Remediation Text\" a clause I could paste directly into our policy, written in [our house style / plain formal policy language].\n\nHere are the three documents:\n[PASTE FRAMEWORK A SUMMARY]\n[PASTE FRAMEWORK B SUMMARY]\n[PASTE INTERNAL POLICY]","promptNote":"Replace the bracketed placeholders with your two framework names and versions and your policy's title. The version/date matters because regulations change — pin it so the model maps against the rule that actually applies to you. The final bracket lets you dictate the writing style of the remediation clauses so they drop into your document repository with minimal editing.","cloud":{"bestTool":"Anthropic Claude, because a two-framework cross-map means feeding several long documents at once and Claude's large context window and careful, citation-friendly reasoning handle dense regulatory text with fewer invented requirements","steps":["Go to claude.ai and start a new chat (use a Team/Work plan for a confidentiality agreement if the policy is even mildly sensitive; for anything truly confidential, use the Local path instead).","Upload or paste your two framework summaries and your internal policy, each under a clear heading so Claude can tell them apart.","Paste the structured audit prompt and run it.","Review the table, then push back: 'Quote the exact framework sentence behind rows 3 and 7' and 'Which mandatory high-risk obligations did you omit?' to catch hallucinations and gaps.","Export the verified table and hand the remediation column to a human reviewer before it touches your policy repository."]},"local":["Open your local chat UI (LM Studio, or Ollama behind Open WebUI) and select an already-installed instruction model with a large context window — a bigger model handles multi-document reasoning far better than a tiny one.","Confirm you are offline / local: this is the whole point — your unpublished policy and its weaknesses never leave your machine, which is exactly what a compliance document demands.","Load all three documents into one conversation. If the tool supports file upload use it; otherwise paste each under a clear FRAMEWORK A / FRAMEWORK B / INTERNAL POLICY heading, trimming the framework summaries to the key requirements so you stay within the model's context limit.","Paste the same structured audit prompt and generate the gap table.","Because local models are more prone to inventing requirements, verify every row against the real framework text yourself, and re-run with a tighter, shorter framework summary if the output drifts or fabricates clauses."],"localNeedsSetup":true,"choose":"For this task, lean local. Your internal policy is an unpublished document that spells out your actual controls and — by design — exactly where you fall short, which is sensitive information you do not want sitting in a third-party cloud, especially under regulations you are trying to prove you comply with. Running it on a local model keeps the policy, the gaps, and the remediation language entirely on your machine. Use a cloud assistant (Claude) only when the policy is generic, already public, or a throwaway draft and you value speed over secrecy; even then, prefer a business plan that contractually excludes your data from training.","example":{"input":"FRAMEWORK A: NIST AI RMF 1.0 (Jan 2023) — Govern/Map/Measure/Manage; GOVERN-1.1 requires legal and regulatory requirements involving AI to be understood, managed, and documented; MEASURE-2.7 requires AI system security and resilience to be evaluated and documented. FRAMEWORK B: EU AI Act — four risk tiers; Art. 9 requires a risk management system for high-risk AI; Art. 14 requires human oversight of high-risk AI. INTERNAL POLICY (excerpt): 'All AI tools used by staff must be approved by IT. Personal data fed to AI tools should be minimized. The security team reviews new tools annually.'","output":"Framework Requirement | Current Internal Gap | Recommended Policy Remediation Text\nNIST AI RMF GOVERN-1.1 (legal/regulatory requirements documented) | Policy names IT approval but does not require mapping each AI system to the laws that apply to it. | \"For every approved AI system, the owner shall document the specific legal and regulatory requirements that apply (including applicable AI regulations) and review that mapping at least annually.\"\nEU AI Act Art. 9 (risk management system for high-risk AI) | Policy has an annual tool review but no defined risk-management process, and never classifies tools by risk tier. | \"Each AI system shall be classified against the EU AI Act risk tiers on intake. Any system classified high-risk shall be governed by a documented, continuously maintained risk-management process covering identification, evaluation, and mitigation.\"\nEU AI Act Art. 14 (human oversight of high-risk AI) | Policy is silent on human oversight of AI decisions. | \"For any high-risk AI system, a named human reviewer with authority to override or halt the system shall be assigned, and their oversight actions logged.\"\n\nMissing mandatory obligations: no AI-nature disclosure to users (EU AI Act limited-risk transparency); no security/resilience evaluation of AI systems (NIST MEASURE-2.7).","note":"Notice each row cites a specific clause and hands you paste-ready policy language — and the model flags obligations your excerpt missed entirely, not just the ones you mentioned."},"tips":["Map two frameworks at once, but keep them clearly labeled — the whole value here is seeing where a single policy gap trips both NIST and the EU AI Act, which a one-framework map hides.","Feed the AI the real framework text, not just names. 'Map against NIST AI RMF' with no summary invites the model to invent requirements from memory; pasting the actual functions and articles keeps it grounded.","Always demand citations in column 1 and then verify a sample against the source. A cross-map is only defensible in an audit if every requirement traces to a real clause.","Run it in passes: first a broad map, then a focused follow-up like 'now only the high-risk / mandatory obligations' so nothing critical is buried in a long table.","Save the exact prompt and framework summaries as a reusable template — when a regulation updates, you swap in the new summary and re-run instead of starting over."],"mistakes":["Trusting the table as final compliance truth. AI can hallucinate requirements and miss others; treat every row as a lead to verify, and have a qualified human sign off before anything becomes policy.","Pasting a confidential internal policy into a free consumer cloud chat. That can expose your control weaknesses to a third party — use a local model or a business plan that excludes your data from training for anything sensitive.","Using an outdated framework summary. Regulations move (the EU AI Act's high-risk deadlines shifted in 2026); a stale summary yields a confidently wrong map, so always pin the version and date.","Giving the model only framework names and expecting accuracy. Without the actual clause text it fills gaps from memory and invents plausible-but-fake requirements — always paste the real summaries.","Pasting the remediation clauses straight into your policy repository unedited. They are drafts written in generic language; a human must adapt them to your systems, terminology, and legal counsel's guidance first."],"related":["t8","t9","t13"]},{"id":"t8","num":8,"cat":"G","title":"Adversarial Output Fact-Checking (The Verifier Framework)","tagline":"Catch fabricated facts, fake statistics, and made-up citations in any AI-written report by running the text back through a second, deliberately skeptical AI reviewer before you trust or share it.","audience":"Corporate professionals, students, and content creators who use AI to draft reports, briefs, or analyses and now need to make sure the numbers, dates, and claims inside those drafts are real before anything reaches a client, a boss, a grader, or the public.","why":"Language models are built to produce fluent, confident-sounding text, not verified truth. That means one will occasionally invent a statistic (\"revenue grew 34%\"), misdate a historical event, cite a study that does not exist, or state a plausible-sounding \"fact\" that is simply wrong. This is called hallucination, and the danger is that hallucinated content reads exactly as smoothly as correct content, so you cannot catch it just by rereading your own draft. The Verifier Framework fixes this by making a fresh AI session act as an adversarial fact-checker: instead of writing, its only job is to attack the draft, list every checkable claim, and flag the ones that look like guesses. You still make the final call (the human-in-the-loop step), but now you are auditing a short, prioritized list of suspects instead of hunting through pages of prose. Reach for this any time an AI draft contains numbers, dates, names, or assertions that would embarrass you or cause real harm if they turned out to be fabricated.","need":["A first-draft document that contains factual claims worth checking (a report, memo, article, or analysis) - AI-written or human-written.","Access to an AI chat tool: a cloud assistant (Claude, Gemini, or Copilot) or a local model running in a chat UI (Open WebUI or LM Studio).","The ability to open a SECOND, fresh chat window separate from the one that wrote the draft.","A way to spot-check flagged claims yourself: your source documents, a search engine, or internal records.","About 15-30 minutes and a willingness to be the final human judge - the AI flags, you decide."],"steps":[{"title":"Generate or gather the draft you want to verify","detail":"Start with the text you need to check: something an AI just wrote for you, a draft a colleague sent, or your own writing that quotes numbers and facts. Have the full text ready to copy, because the fact-checker needs to see everything in context, not a fragment. If you are generating it fresh, write a normal prompt (for example, 'Write a one-page market summary of the U.S. electric-vehicle industry') and let the model produce the draft. Do not fix anything yet - you want the raw output so the audit catches the model's real mistakes."},{"title":"Open a SEPARATE, fresh chat window for the audit","detail":"This is the most important and most-skipped step. Open a brand-new conversation - a new chat tab, a new session, not a follow-up message in the same thread that wrote the draft. The reason: an AI asked to check its own answer in the same conversation tends to defend what it just said, because that text is part of its 'memory' of the chat. A clean session has no attachment to the draft and no reason to protect it, so it audits honestly. Think of it as sending the document to an outside reviewer who has never seen it before."},{"title":"Paste the adversarial fact-checker prompt, then the draft","detail":"Copy the exact prompt from the Prompt section below into the fresh chat. Then paste your draft immediately after it, clearly marked (the prompt tells the AI where the draft begins and ends). The prompt instructs the model to switch roles from writer to skeptical auditor, to find every checkable claim, and to sort each one into 'sound,' 'contradictory,' or 'high-risk possible hallucination.' Send it and let it produce the flagged list. You are not asking it to rewrite anything yet - only to expose the risky claims."},{"title":"Read the flagged list and understand the three categories","detail":"The AI returns a table or list where each claim carries a verdict. 'Logically sound' means the claim fits the surrounding facts and is probably safe (but still worth a glance). 'Contradictory' means two parts of the document disagree - a real red flag you can often fix from the text itself. 'High-risk possible hallucination' means the claim reads like a confident guess: an oddly precise percentage with no source, a suspiciously round number, a specific date or citation that could easily be invented. Treat this last category as guilty until proven innocent."},{"title":"Verify each flagged claim against a real source - this is your job, not the AI's","detail":"This is the human-in-the-loop step and it is non-negotiable, because the fact-checker AI can be wrong in both directions: it can miss a fabricated claim or wrongly flag a true one. For every high-risk item, go to a real source - your own data, the original document, an official website, or a search engine - and confirm the number, date, or fact yourself. Never let the fact-checker 'correct' a claim by generating a replacement number, because that replacement can itself be hallucinated. The AI narrows your search; you close the case."},{"title":"Correct the draft and, optionally, run a second pass","detail":"Fix or delete every claim that failed verification, and rewrite contradictory statements so the document agrees with itself. If you changed a lot, paste the cleaned version into another fresh chat and run the same audit again - a second pass often catches items introduced or missed the first time. Stop when the flagged list comes back with only low-risk, verifiable items. Keep a note of what you checked and where, so you can defend the final document if anyone questions it."}],"prompt":"You are an adversarial fact-checker and skeptical editor. Your ONLY job is to attack the text below and expose weak or fabricated claims. Do NOT rewrite it, praise it, or improve its style.\n\nWork in this order:\n1. Read the [TEXT BLOCK] between the markers.\n2. Extract EVERY discrete factual claim: each statistic, percentage, dollar figure, date, historical event, named person or organization, quotation, citation, and any definitive assertion of fact.\n3. For each claim, assign exactly ONE verdict:\n   - SOUND: consistent with the rest of the text and with common knowledge; no obvious problem.\n   - CONTRADICTORY: conflicts with another statement in the text, or is internally inconsistent.\n   - HIGH-RISK POSSIBLE HALLUCINATION: reads like a confident guess - an oddly precise or suspiciously round number, an unsourced statistic, a specific date/quote/citation that could plausibly be invented, or a claim you cannot ground in structural logic.\n4. For every CONTRADICTORY or HIGH-RISK item, add a one-line reason and a one-line \"How to verify\" pointing to the kind of source a human should check (e.g., \"company 10-K filing,\" \"official census data,\" \"the cited study's DOI\").\n\nOutput ONLY a table with these columns:\nCLAIM (quoted exactly) | VERDICT | WHY | HOW TO VERIFY\n\nAfter the table, list the 3 claims a human MUST check first, ranked by how much damage a wrong value would cause.\n\nRules: When unsure, flag as HIGH-RISK rather than SOUND - false confidence is the failure I am trying to prevent. Do NOT invent corrected values; your job is to flag, not to fix. Do not skip any claim, even small ones.\n\n=== BEGIN TEXT BLOCK ===\n[PASTE YOUR DRAFT HERE]\n=== END TEXT BLOCK ===","promptNote":"Replace only [PASTE YOUR DRAFT HERE] with the full text you want audited; leave the two === markers in place so the AI knows exactly where your draft starts and stops. Everything above the markers is the instruction and should be pasted unchanged. If your draft is long, paste it all - the audit is only as good as the text it can see.","cloud":{"bestTool":"Anthropic Claude, because fact-audit work rewards a long context window and careful, literal instruction-following, so it handles multi-page drafts and the strict flag-don't-fix rule especially well.","steps":["Go to claude.ai and start a BRAND-NEW chat (do not continue the chat that wrote the draft - a fresh session audits more honestly).","Paste the adversarial fact-checker prompt from the Prompt section, then paste your full draft between the === markers.","Send it and read the returned table; note which claims are marked HIGH-RISK or CONTRADICTORY.","For each flagged claim, verify it yourself against a real source - do not ask Claude to supply the correct number, because that replacement could also be invented.","If you made many corrections, open another new chat and run the same prompt on the cleaned draft for a confirming second pass."]},"local":["Open your local chat UI (Open WebUI for Ollama, or LM Studio) and select an already-installed instruction-following model such as Llama 3.1 8B, Qwen 2.5, or Mistral.","Start a NEW conversation so nothing from an earlier chat influences the audit - the fresh-session rule matters just as much locally.","Paste the adversarial fact-checker prompt, then paste your draft between the === markers, and send it.","Read the flagged table; because smaller local models can be less thorough, consider running the same prompt a second time and combining both flag lists.","Verify every high-risk item yourself against real sources, then correct the draft - nothing you pasted ever left your machine, which is the whole point of doing this locally."],"localNeedsSetup":true,"choose":"If the draft contains sensitive material - legal analysis, unreleased financials, client data, HR matters, meeting transcripts, or anything under compliance or NDA - do this LOCALLY, because a local model keeps every word of the document on your own machine and nothing is transmitted to an outside company. That privacy guarantee is exactly why the Verifier Framework was designed to run inside local boundaries. For low-sensitivity, public-facing content - a blog post, a general market summary, a school essay drawing on public facts - a cloud tool is perfectly fine and usually easier and sharper, so reach for Claude or Gemini there. When in doubt about sensitivity, choose local; the small extra effort is cheaper than a leaked document.","example":{"input":"=== BEGIN TEXT BLOCK ===\nThe global EV market reached $412.7 billion in 2023, growing 34.2% year over year. Tesla held a commanding 62% of U.S. sales. The first mass-market electric car, the Nissan Leaf, launched in 2012 and sold over 500,000 units in its first year. Analysts at Goldman Sachs project the market will triple by 2028, though our own regional data shows demand fell 8% last quarter.\n=== END TEXT BLOCK ===","output":"CLAIM | VERDICT | WHY | HOW TO VERIFY\n\"$412.7 billion in 2023\" | HIGH-RISK | Oddly precise figure with no cited source | Cross-check a named market-research report (e.g., IEA / BloombergNEF)\n\"growing 34.2% year over year\" | HIGH-RISK | Suspiciously exact growth rate, unsourced | Compare against the same report's prior-year total\n\"Tesla held a commanding 62% of U.S. sales\" | HIGH-RISK | Round-ish share stated without a date qualifier or source | Cross-check registration data (e.g., Cox Automotive / Kelley Blue Book)\n\"Nissan Leaf, launched in 2012\" | HIGH-RISK | The Leaf launched in Dec 2010, not 2012 - likely wrong date | Verify against Nissan's official history / press release\n\"sold over 500,000 units in its first year\" | HIGH-RISK | Implausibly high first-year volume for an early EV | Verify against Nissan annual sales figures\n\"Goldman Sachs project ... triple by 2028\" | HIGH-RISK | Attributed forecast with no report title or date | Locate the specific Goldman research note\n\"our own regional data shows demand fell 8% last quarter\" | CONTRADICTORY | Conflicts with the 'triple by 2028' growth story in the same paragraph | Reconcile against your internal quarterly dashboard\n\nCHECK THESE FIRST (most damaging if wrong):\n1. Nissan Leaf launch date + first-year units - a factual error that undermines the whole document's credibility.\n2. Tesla 62% U.S. share - a headline number likely to be quoted by readers.\n3. The $412.7B / 34.2% market-size pair - the report's central statistics.","note":"Notice the AI flags the internal contradiction (an 8% drop sitting next to a 'triple by 2028' claim) that is easy to miss by eye, and it tells you exactly where to look rather than inventing a 'correct' number."},"tips":["Feed it one document at a time. Auditing a single draft in a clean session gives sharper, more complete flag lists than dumping several documents together.","Push back on 'all clear.' If the AI flags nothing, reply 'Assume you missed something - re-examine the three most quantitative sentences and justify why each is safe.' This defeats lazy passes.","Ask for the sources it would expect, not the answers. The AI is reliable at saying 'this should come from a 10-K filing'; it is unreliable at telling you the actual figure, so use it as a research router, not an oracle.","Run two different models on high-stakes work. A cloud model and a local model (or two local models) rarely hallucinate the same way, so claims both of them flag are your top priorities.","Keep an audit trail. Save the flagged table and note what you verified and where - if anyone later questions the document, you can show your work."],"mistakes":["Auditing in the same chat that wrote the draft. The model defends its own text. Always open a fresh, separate session for the audit.","Letting the AI 'correct' the numbers. A replacement figure can be hallucinated just like the original. Use the flags to guide YOUR verification against real sources, and only trust a number you confirmed yourself.","Trusting a clean report as proof of accuracy. A short flag list means the suspects are narrowed, not that the document is true - you still have to check the flagged items and eyeball the rest.","Pasting only a snippet. The fact-checker needs full context to catch contradictions between distant sentences, so paste the entire draft, not a paragraph.","Sending sensitive documents to a cloud tool out of habit. If the content is confidential, legal, financial, or client data, run the audit on a local model so nothing leaves your machine."],"related":["t5","t9","t13"]},{"id":"t9","num":9,"cat":"G","title":"Client-Facing Data Anonymization Checklists","tagline":"Turn any messy document full of names, dollar figures, and system names into a clean, safely shareable version in one pass, without trusting your eyes to catch every leak.","audience":"Contractors, consultants, and legal assistants who regularly hand documents, logs, or corporate emails to people outside their inner circle: a client, a vendor, a partner team, or an external reviewer.","why":"When you share a document across a project boundary, anything identifying you leave in it, a person's name, an exact revenue figure, a real server or database name, can quietly become a leak: a breach of a client NDA, a privacy violation, or a competitor learning your internals. Doing this by hand is slow and unreliable because the human eye skims and misses the fourth mention of a name or a dollar figure buried in a table. An AI model reads every single line at the same level of attention and can swap each sensitive marker for a consistent placeholder like [REDACTED_USER_ID] while leaving the actual meaning of the text intact, so the reader still follows the story without learning who or what it was about. Reach for this whenever you are about to paste, forward, or upload internal text into a space where people outside the trust boundary can see it. Because the entire point is to protect sensitive data, how you run the tool matters as much as the prompt: for genuinely confidential material you should run it on a local model so the sensitive original never leaves your computer.","need":["A document or text block you need to clean up: a corporate email thread, a log or telemetry export, a memo, or a section of a report.","One AI chat tool ready to go: a local model (LM Studio, or Ollama with Open WebUI) for sensitive data, or a cloud assistant (Claude, Google Gemini, or Microsoft Copilot) for low-sensitivity material.","A clear idea of what counts as sensitive in your document: names, money figures, and system/server names are the default three, but add anything specific to your work (case numbers, client IDs, addresses).","A blank scratch file or note where you can paste and read the cleaned result before it goes anywhere.","Two minutes to eyeball the AI's output afterward, because you are the final quality check, not the model."],"steps":[{"title":"Pick the right tool based on how sensitive the document is","detail":"Before you touch a prompt, decide where this text is allowed to go. If the document contains real client data, legal matter details, financials, or anything under an NDA, use a local model so the original never leaves your machine (covered in the local steps below). If it is low-stakes internal text with no real confidential markers, a cloud assistant is faster and fine. This one decision is the most important part of the whole task, because a redaction tool that leaks the original while cleaning it defeats its own purpose."},{"title":"Gather the document as plain text and skim it once","detail":"Copy the text you want to share into your clipboard, or save it as a .txt file if it is long. Give it a ten-second skim so you know roughly what is in there: how many people are mentioned, whether there are dollar figures, whether server or database names appear. You are not redacting yet; you just want a rough mental count so that when the AI hands back its result you can sanity-check that it caught about the right number of things."},{"title":"Tell the AI exactly what to replace and what to leave alone","detail":"Open your chosen tool and paste the prompt from the Prompt section, then paste your document where it says [PASTE YOUR DOCUMENT HERE]. The prompt does two jobs at once: it lists the exact categories to redact (names, money, system names) and the exact placeholder to use for each, and it explicitly tells the model to keep the technical story readable. Being this specific matters because a vague instruction like 'remove sensitive info' makes the model guess, and it will either miss things or over-redact and destroy the meaning."},{"title":"Ask for a consistency table alongside the cleaned text","detail":"The prompt tells the model to also return a small mapping table showing which placeholder replaced which category, and to reuse the exact same placeholder every time the same item appears. This is what makes the result trustworthy: if 'Maria Chen' shows up five times, all five must become the identical [REDACTED_USER_ID], not five different tags. The table also gives you a fast way to verify coverage at a glance instead of re-reading the whole document line by line."},{"title":"Read the cleaned version locally before it goes anywhere","detail":"Paste the AI's output into your scratch note and read it as if you were the outside recipient. Search the text (Ctrl+F) for the riskiest leftovers: a first name, a dollar sign, an '@' in an email, the name of a known internal system. The model is good but not perfect, and this manual pass is your safety net. Only after this check should the text move into an external email, shared drive, or team workspace."},{"title":"Fix any misses with a quick follow-up, then finalize","detail":"If your read-through found something the model left in, do not start over. Reply in the same chat with a short correction like 'You missed the name Priya in paragraph three and the figure $2.4M in the last line; redact those too using the same placeholders.' The model keeps the context and patches just those spots. Repeat until your search turns up nothing sensitive, then copy the final clean text out."}],"prompt":"You are a careful data-anonymization assistant. Your job is to redact sensitive markers from the text I provide while keeping the underlying narrative fully readable and technically intact.\n\nReview the document below and replace EVERY instance of the following, using these EXACT placeholders:\n- Every unique human name (first, last, or full) -> [REDACTED_USER_ID]\n- Every exact financial figure (revenue, cost, salary, budget, valuation, any dollar/currency amount) -> [REDACTED_FINANCIAL_METRIC]\n- Every server, host, database, or system/environment name -> [REDACTED_SYSTEM_NODE]\n- [ADD ANY EXTRA CATEGORIES YOU NEED, e.g. email addresses -> [REDACTED_EMAIL], client/company names -> [REDACTED_ORG], case or ticket numbers -> [REDACTED_CASE_ID]]\n\nRules:\n1. Be consistent: the same real item must always map to the same placeholder every time it appears.\n2. Do NOT redact ordinary words, dates, or generic technical terms that carry no identity (e.g. \"the database,\" \"Q3,\" \"latency,\" \"the production environment\" without a proper name).\n3. Preserve sentence structure, formatting, and the technical story so a reader still understands what happened, just not who or what specifically.\n4. Do not invent, summarize, or drop content. Redact in place only.\n\nAfter the cleaned text, output a short table titled \"Redaction Map\" with two columns: Placeholder | What category it replaced (do NOT list the original sensitive values). Then add one line: \"Items redacted: [count]\".\n\nHere is the document:\n[PASTE YOUR DOCUMENT HERE]","promptNote":"Replace [PASTE YOUR DOCUMENT HERE] with your actual text. The [ADD ANY EXTRA CATEGORIES YOU NEED] line is optional: delete it if the default three categories cover you, or add your own markers (emails, client names, case numbers) with their own placeholder tags. Keep the placeholder names in [SQUARE_BRACKETS] so they stand out and are easy to search for later.","cloud":{"bestTool":"Anthropic Claude, because redaction depends on reading a long document carefully end to end and following precise rules consistently, and Claude handles large text blocks with strong instruction-following, though for low-sensitivity data only.","steps":["Open Claude (claude.ai) and start a new chat.","Paste the full prompt from the Prompt section, then paste your document where it says [PASTE YOUR DOCUMENT HERE]. For a long document, attach it as a .txt file instead of pasting.","Send it, then read the cleaned text and the Redaction Map it returns.","Use Ctrl+F on the result to hunt for any leftover name, dollar sign, or system name; if you find one, reply in the same chat naming exactly what to fix.","Copy the final clean text out only after your search turns up nothing sensitive. Reminder: only do this in the cloud for low-sensitivity text, never real confidential client data."]},"local":["Open your local chat interface (LM Studio, or Open WebUI if you run Ollama) and make sure your model is selected and the little status shows it is loaded and running on your machine.","Confirm you are offline-safe: a local model sends nothing to the internet, so this is the right place for real client, legal, or financial documents. If you want to be certain, you can literally disconnect Wi-Fi and it will still work.","Start a new chat, paste the full prompt from the Prompt section, and paste your sensitive document where it says [PASTE YOUR DOCUMENT HERE].","Run it, then read the cleaned output and the Redaction Map. Smaller local models sometimes miss an item, so read carefully and use the follow-up correction step if needed.","Copy the final clean text into your document. The sensitive original never left your computer, which is the entire reason to work locally for this task."],"localNeedsSetup":true,"choose":"For this task, strongly prefer LOCAL whenever the document contains anything genuinely confidential: client data, legal matter details, financials, HR records, or anything under an NDA. The reason is specific to redaction: to clean a document you must send the tool the un-redacted original, so a cloud tool would receive exactly the sensitive data you are trying to protect, and it may be retained or logged. A local model keeps that original entirely on your machine, so nothing sensitive ever crosses the wire. Use a cloud assistant only for low-stakes internal text where a leak would not matter, in which case it is faster and needs no setup.","example":{"input":"From: Maria Chen\nTo: Devs\nSubject: prod incident write-up\n\nAt 2am the db-atlas-01 database hit 94% CPU and orders stalled. Maria and Raj Patel restarted the auth-gw service, which cleared it. Estimated revenue impact was $47,300 for the hour. We'll bill the client $12,000 for the emergency work. Raj is drafting the RCA.","output":"From: [REDACTED_USER_ID]\nTo: Devs\nSubject: prod incident write-up\n\nAt 2am the [REDACTED_SYSTEM_NODE] database hit 94% CPU and orders stalled. [REDACTED_USER_ID] and [REDACTED_USER_ID] restarted the [REDACTED_SYSTEM_NODE] service, which cleared it. Estimated revenue impact was [REDACTED_FINANCIAL_METRIC] for the hour. We'll bill the client [REDACTED_FINANCIAL_METRIC] for the emergency work. [REDACTED_USER_ID] is drafting the RCA.\n\nRedaction Map\nPlaceholder | What category it replaced\n[REDACTED_USER_ID] | Human names\n[REDACTED_SYSTEM_NODE] | Server / database / service names\n[REDACTED_FINANCIAL_METRIC] | Financial figures\n\nItems redacted: 7","note":"Notice the story still makes sense (a database spiked, two people restarted a service, there was a cost) but every name, system, and dollar figure is gone, and repeats of the same person collapse to the identical tag."},"tips":["Search the cleaned output for the specific danger signs: a '$' or a stray digit, an '@', and the first names of anyone you know is in the document. These three searches catch the vast majority of misses in seconds.","Keep your placeholder names distinctive and bracketed like [REDACTED_FINANCIAL_METRIC] so a later Ctrl+F can confirm they are present and no real value slipped through.","If a document is long, paste it in sections and run the same prompt on each, rather than truncating it. A model that runs out of room may silently stop redacting partway through.","Ask for the Redaction Map count and compare it to your own rough count from the skim. If you expected around ten sensitive items and it reports three, something was missed.","For recurring work, save the prompt as a reusable snippet or text-expander so every teammate anonymizes the same way and placeholders stay consistent across documents."],"mistakes":["Trusting the model blindly and skipping the manual read. AI redaction is very good but not guaranteed; always do the Ctrl+F pass before the text leaves your control.","Pasting real confidential data into a cloud tool for convenience. That hands the sensitive original to exactly the service you are trying to shield it from; use a local model for anything under NDA or containing client, legal, or financial data.","Using vague instructions like 'remove anything sensitive.' The model then guesses and either misses items or over-redacts and mangles the meaning; name the exact categories and placeholders as in the prompt.","Redacting only the first mention of a name or figure. Skimming humans do this constantly; the prompt's consistency rule and the placeholder search are what stop it, so lean on them.","Over-redacting harmless words like 'database' or a date, which makes the result unreadable. The prompt's rule to leave generic terms and dates alone prevents this; if the model still over-does it, tell it which words to restore."],"related":["t5","t8","t13"]},{"id":"t13","num":13,"cat":"G","title":"The Contract and Lease Clause Clarifier","tagline":"Turn any dense contract or lease clause into plain English you actually understand, so you know your real obligations and risks before you ever call a lawyer.","audience":"Real estate agents, small business owners, office managers, and procurement or operations staff who regularly sign or forward commercial leases, vendor agreements, and service level agreements (SLAs) but have no legal training. It is for the person who needs to grasp what a clause actually means today, not for anyone trying to replace a lawyer or give legal advice.","why":"Contracts are written to be legally airtight, not readable, so a single clause about \"indemnification,\" \"liquidated damages,\" or \"consequential loss\" can bury an obligation that costs you real money or lets the other side walk away penalty-free. Most people sign or forward these documents without truly understanding what they promised, which is how businesses get surprised by auto-renewals, late fees, or repair duties they never realized they took on. An AI clause clarifier acts like a patient translator: it restates the legalese in everyday words, spells out exactly what you must do and what happens if you don't, and hands you a short list of sharp questions. Reach for it before you sign anything, before you forward a draft to your attorney (so you use their expensive time well), and any time a clause makes you squint. It does not replace legal review — it makes your legal review faster, cheaper, and far more focused.","need":["An AI chat tool: a cloud one (Claude, Google Gemini, or Microsoft Copilot) for quick everyday clauses, or a local model (via Ollama or LM Studio) when the contract is confidential","The actual contract text you can copy and paste — a lease paragraph, a vendor SLA, a renewal clause, or a whole page","A basic idea of who \"you\" are in the deal (the tenant, the customer, the buyer) so the AI answers from your side","5 to 10 quiet minutes to read the plain-English summary and jot down questions","A reminder to yourself that this is for understanding only — a lawyer still makes the final call on anything that matters"],"steps":[{"title":"Find and copy the exact clause that worries you","detail":"Open your lease, vendor agreement, or SLA and select the paragraph you don't fully understand — often the sections titled Term, Renewal, Indemnification, Limitation of Liability, Default, or Service Levels. Copy the text exactly as written, including the defined terms in capital letters like \"Tenant\" or \"Provider,\" because those words carry specific meaning the AI needs. You can paste one dense paragraph or several related ones; a focused chunk gets a sharper answer than dumping the entire 40-page contract at once."},{"title":"Tell the AI who you are and paste the clause","detail":"Open your AI tool and use the prompt provided below, replacing the bracketed placeholders with your details — most importantly which side of the deal you are on (tenant vs. landlord, customer vs. vendor), because the same clause protects one party and exposes the other. Paste the copied clause where the prompt marks it. Being explicit about your role is what turns a generic definition into a straight answer about what YOU are on the hook for."},{"title":"Run it and read the plain-English breakdown","detail":"Send the prompt and read the reply slowly. A good answer restates the clause in everyday language, then directly answers the two questions that matter most: what exactly you are promising to do, and what happens (fees, termination, lawsuits) if you fail to do it. If any part still sounds like legalese, that is a signal to push further, not to give up."},{"title":"Ask follow-up questions in plain language","detail":"Treat this as a conversation, not a one-shot. Type natural follow-ups like \"What does 'net 30' mean here?\", \"Is this auto-renewal or do I have to opt in?\", or \"Rewrite this so a 10th grader gets it.\" You can also ask \"What in this clause is unusual or one-sided against me?\" to surface things you didn't know to worry about. Each answer should get simpler and more specific."},{"title":"Turn the summary into questions for your lawyer","detail":"Ask the AI: \"Based on this, give me 4 or 5 sharp questions to ask my attorney.\" This is the real payoff — instead of forwarding a confusing clause and paying your lawyer to explain the basics, you arrive with focused questions about the parts that actually carry risk. Copy that question list into your email to counsel, or into your own notes before a negotiation."},{"title":"Verify anything that costs money or time — then confirm with a professional","detail":"The AI can misread an unusual clause, and it does not know the specific laws of your state or country. Before you rely on any number, deadline, or penalty it states, re-read that part of the original contract yourself to confirm it matches. For any obligation that involves real money, a long commitment, or legal liability, treat the AI's summary as your briefing document and let a qualified attorney give the final word."}],"prompt":"Act as a clear, careful business translator (not a lawyer, and this is not legal advice). I am a non-lawyer and I need to understand a contract clause before I act on it.\n\nContext you need:\n- I am the [TENANT / CUSTOMER / BUYER / SERVICE RECIPIENT] in this agreement.\n- The other party is the [LANDLORD / VENDOR / SUPPLIER / PROVIDER].\n- This is a [COMMERCIAL LEASE / VENDOR SERVICE AGREEMENT / SLA / PURCHASE CONTRACT].\n\nHere is the exact clause:\n\"\"\"\n[PASTE THE FULL CLAUSE TEXT HERE, EXACTLY AS WRITTEN]\n\"\"\"\n\nDo all of the following, in this order, using plain English a non-lawyer can easily understand:\n1. One-sentence gist: what is this clause really about?\n2. Plain-English breakdown: restate the clause in simple words, defining any legal or technical terms (like \"indemnify,\" \"net 30,\" \"liquidated damages,\" \"cure period\") as you go.\n3. What exactly am I (the [TENANT/CUSTOMER/etc.]) promising or required to do? List each obligation as a separate bullet.\n4. What happens if I miss a deadline or fail to perform? List every penalty, fee, termination right, or consequence, and note who it hurts.\n5. Red flags: point out anything that is unusual, one-sided against me, ambiguous, or that I might easily overlook (auto-renewals, short notice windows, uncapped costs).\n6. Questions for my lawyer: give me 4-5 specific, sharp questions to ask a qualified attorney about this clause.\n\nRules: If any part is genuinely ambiguous, say so plainly instead of guessing. Do not soften or hide risks. Do not tell me the clause is \"fine\" — your job is to explain it, not to approve it.","promptNote":"Fill the three bracketed context lines first — the \"I am the [TENANT/CUSTOMER]\" line is the most important, because it tells the AI whose side to answer from. Paste your real clause between the triple quotes exactly as written, capital-letter defined terms included. Swap the document-type bracket to match what you have (lease, SLA, purchase order), and the whole prompt works for almost any contract.","cloud":{"bestTool":"Anthropic Claude — it handles very long, dense contract text with care and is strong at faithful plain-English explanation without oversimplifying or inventing terms, which is exactly what clause clarification needs.","steps":["Go to claude.ai (Google Gemini works equally well; choose Microsoft Copilot if your contract already lives in a Word or SharePoint file in Microsoft 365 and you want it read in place).","Paste the full prompt from this tutorial, fill in the bracketed context lines, and paste your clause between the triple quotes. For a multi-page document you can also attach the file instead of pasting.","Send it, then read the numbered breakdown — especially sections 3 (your obligations) and 4 (penalties).","Ask follow-ups in the same chat: \"Simplify point 2 more,\" \"Is the renewal automatic?\", or \"Give me an email to my attorney with these questions.\"","Spot-check every deadline, fee, and penalty against the original contract text before you rely on it."]},"local":["Open your local chat interface (Open WebUI if you run Ollama, or the chat window in LM Studio) and select a capable installed model such as a Llama 3.x, Mistral, or Qwen instruct model.","Paste the full prompt from this tutorial, fill in the bracketed context lines, and paste your contract clause between the triple quotes.","Send it and read the plain-English breakdown, paying closest attention to your obligations and the penalties for missing a deadline.","Ask follow-ups right in the chat — \"define 'indemnify' in one sentence,\" or \"list 5 questions for my lawyer\" — the same way you would with a cloud tool.","Because nothing left your computer, you can safely do this with confidential, client, or unsigned-deal text; still verify numbers against the original and confirm anything material with an attorney."],"localNeedsSetup":true,"choose":"For contract and lease clauses, lean local. This is legal, often confidential material — an unsigned deal, a client's lease, pricing and penalty terms your counterparty would love to see — and a local model keeps every word on your own machine, with nothing sent to an outside company or retained on a server. Use a cloud tool (Claude or Gemini) when the contract is a routine, non-sensitive template or a publicly available standard agreement and you just want the fastest, clearest read. When in doubt about confidentiality, run it locally; the plain-English quality is more than good enough for understanding a clause.","example":{"input":"I am the TENANT. This is a commercial lease. Clause: \"In the event Tenant fails to pay Rent within five (5) days of the due date, Tenant shall pay a late charge equal to five percent (5%) of the overdue amount, plus interest at the rate of eighteen percent (18%) per annum on all sums past due. Continued failure to cure such default within ten (10) days following written notice from Landlord shall entitle Landlord to terminate this Lease and pursue all remedies available at law, including acceleration of the entire remaining Rent for the balance of the Term.\"","output":"1. Gist: This is the penalty ladder for paying rent late — it gets expensive fast and can end your lease.\n\n2. Plain English: If your rent is more than 5 days late, you owe a 5% late fee plus 18%-per-year interest on what's overdue. If the landlord then sends you a written notice and you still haven't paid within 10 days, they can cancel the lease AND demand every remaining month of rent for the whole lease term, all at once.\n\n3. What you must do:\n - Pay rent within 5 days of the due date to avoid any penalty.\n - If you get a written default notice, fix (pay) it within 10 days — this window is your \"cure period.\"\n\n4. If you miss the deadline:\n - Day 6: a 5% late fee on the overdue rent. | Hurts you.\n - Ongoing: 18%/year interest on all past-due sums. | Hurts you.\n - After a notice + 10 more days unpaid: landlord can terminate the lease. | Hurts you.\n - \"Acceleration\": landlord can demand ALL remaining rent for the rest of the term immediately. | Hurts you badly.\n\n5. Red flags:\n - 18% annual interest is steep — check if your state caps it.\n - \"Acceleration of the entire remaining Rent\" is the big one: on a 3-year lease this could be tens of thousands of dollars owed at once.\n - The 5-day and 10-day windows are short; a single missed payment can escalate quickly.\n\n6. Questions for your lawyer:\n - Is an 18% interest rate and this late fee enforceable in our state?\n - Can the acceleration clause be softened or capped through negotiation?\n - Does the landlord have a duty to re-rent (mitigate) if they accelerate?\n - What exactly counts as valid \"written notice,\" and how is the 10-day cure period counted?","note":"Notice how it flags \"acceleration\" — a word most tenants skim past — as the clause's single biggest financial risk."},"tips":["Always state which side you are on. \"I am the tenant\" vs. \"I am the landlord\" flips who the clause protects and changes the whole answer.","Feed it defined terms too. If the clause references \"Permitted Use\" or \"Force Majeure\" defined elsewhere, paste those definitions in as well so the AI isn't guessing what capitalized terms mean.","Ask for a risk ranking: \"Of everything here, what are the top 3 things most likely to cost me money?\" It cuts through the noise fast.","Have it draft your lawyer email: \"Write a short, professional email to my attorney attaching this clause and asking these questions.\" You save time and use legal hours well.","Do clauses one at a time. A focused paragraph gets a far sharper read than pasting a whole contract and asking for everything at once."],"mistakes":["Treating the summary as legal advice. The AI explains; it does not approve or protect you. Always let a qualified attorney make the final call on anything that carries real money or liability.","Trusting numbers and deadlines without checking. AI can misread an unusual clause. Re-read that exact line in the original contract before you rely on any fee, rate, or date it quotes.","Forgetting local laws. Contract enforceability depends on your state or country, which the AI may not know. Ask, then confirm jurisdiction-specific points with a professional.","Pasting confidential contracts into a public cloud tool. For unsigned deals or client documents, use a local model so nothing leaves your machine.","Dumping the entire contract and asking \"is this okay?\" You'll get a vague answer. Isolate the specific clause and ask the specific questions — obligations and penalties — instead."],"related":["t5","t8","t9"]},{"id":"cp1","num":31,"cat":"P","title":"Colab: Analyze a Spreadsheet by Asking Plain-English Questions","tagline":"Upload a spreadsheet to a free cloud notebook and get answers by typing questions in plain English — no formulas, no coding, and Google's AI writes the code for you.","audience":"Complete beginners who live in spreadsheets — small-business owners, students, teachers, nonprofit staff, and analysts — who want to ask a data question in normal words and get a real answer. If you have ever stared at a huge CSV and thought 'I just want to know which month was best,' this is for you. No prior coding is assumed or needed.","why":"Spreadsheets are great until the question gets slightly complicated — like 'what was the average order value per region, only counting completed orders?' — and then you are wrestling with pivot tables and nested formulas. Google Colab is a free notebook that runs in your browser, and it has Google's Gemini AI built in, so you can describe what you want in plain English and it writes the working code for you. You run one button, read the answer, and never memorize a formula. Reach for this whenever a question is too fiddly for a quick spreadsheet formula, or when you want a repeatable analysis you can rerun next month by just swapping the file.","platform":"Google Colab","lab":"lab22","need":["A free Google account (the same one you use for Gmail or Google Drive) — nothing to install","Your data saved as a CSV file (in Excel or Google Sheets, choose File then Save As / Download and pick 'CSV'). A CSV is just a plain-text spreadsheet the notebook can read","A rough idea of your question in plain English (e.g., 'which product category sold the most?')"],"steps":[{"title":"Open Colab and create a fresh notebook","detail":"Go to colab.research.google.com in your browser and sign in with your Google account. On the pop-up window (or the File menu) click 'New notebook'. A notebook is just a page made of stacked boxes called 'cells' — some hold notes, some hold code you can run. A blank one opens with a single empty code cell ready to go."},{"title":"Upload your spreadsheet into the notebook","detail":"Look at the narrow strip of icons on the far left edge. Click the folder icon to open the 'Files' panel, then click the upload icon (a page with an up-arrow) and pick your CSV. It uploads into a temporary workspace at the path '/content/', so a file named sales.csv becomes '/content/sales.csv'. Note this is temporary storage that clears when the session ends — that is fine for analysis, and step 6 covers saving your results."},{"title":"Load the file into a table","detail":"In the first code cell, tell the notebook to read your file into a table (called a 'DataFrame'). You can type the two short lines below yourself, or use the AI shortcut in the next step to write them. Then click the round Run button (the triangle 'play' icon) on the left of the cell, or press Shift+Enter. Running '.head()' prints the first few rows so you can confirm the file loaded and the column names look right."},{"title":"Ask your question in plain English and let Gemini write the code","detail":"Add a new code cell with the '+ Code' button near the top. In the empty cell, click the AI features button (the Gemini icon shown inside a blank code cell) and choose 'Generate code', then type a request in normal words, like 'Using the dataframe df, show total Sales for each Category, sorted from highest to lowest.' Gemini turns that sentence into real Python code in the cell — read it, then run it with the play button. (Availability of the in-cell AI features can vary by account and region; if you do not see the button, just type the code from the snippet below, or ask Gemini in a separate chat and paste the code in.)"},{"title":"Read the answer and sanity-check it","detail":"The result prints right under the cell — usually a small table or a single number. Always give it a quick gut-check: does the biggest category match what you'd expect, and do the totals look roughly right? If a number seems off, it is often because a column name was misspelled or the CSV had blank rows; re-run '.head()' to inspect, or just re-ask Gemini more specifically. Treating the AI's code as a helpful draft you verify, not gospel, is the whole skill."},{"title":"Save your work so it does not disappear","detail":"Colab autosaves the notebook to your Google Drive, but to keep a clean named copy, open the File menu and choose 'Save a copy in Drive'. It lands in a 'Colab Notebooks' folder in your Drive, reopenable from any computer. Next month, just upload the new CSV over the old one and hit Runtime then 'Run all' to redo the whole analysis in one click."}],"cloud":{"steps":["Open colab.research.google.com and sign in with your Google account","Click 'New notebook'","Click the folder icon on the left, then the upload icon, and choose your CSV","In a code cell type the two-line load snippet (or ask Gemini to write it) and run it with the play button","Click '+ Code', then in the empty cell click the AI features button, choose 'Generate code', and type your question in plain English","Run the AI-written cell and read the answer under it","Sanity-check the result against what you expect","Open File then 'Save a copy in Drive' to keep it"]},"prompt":"# Two lines to load your spreadsheet into a table\nimport pandas as pd\ndf = pd.read_csv(\"/content/sales.csv\")   # change the filename to match yours\ndf.head()                                 # shows the first 5 rows so you can check it loaded","promptNote":"Change 'sales.csv' to your file's exact name (check it in the Files panel on the left). After this runs, add a new code cell and use Colab's in-cell AI 'Generate code' feature to type your real question in plain English — for example: 'Using the dataframe df, show the total Sales for each Category, sorted highest to lowest.' Mentioning the table's name 'df' and your real column names helps the AI write correct code the first time.","tips":["Name your columns clearly in the spreadsheet before uploading (e.g., 'Order_Date', 'Sales', 'Category'). Clear names make Gemini's plain-English answers far more accurate.","When you ask Gemini for code, mention the table name ('df') and the exact column names — it removes guesswork and cuts errors dramatically.","Ask for one thing at a time. 'Average Sales per Region' works better than a paragraph asking for five things at once.","If a result looks wrong, ask Gemini to 'explain what this code does in plain English' — reading the explanation usually reveals the misunderstanding.","The official Colab welcome guide is at colab.research.google.com — open the Help menu and choose the 'Overview of Colaboratory' notebook to see the newest button labels."],"mistakes":["Uploading an .xlsx Excel file and expecting the simple example to read it — save it as CSV first, or the load line fails on the format.","Typing the wrong filename in the load line — it must match exactly what shows in the Files panel, including capitalization and the '.csv' ending.","Assuming your file is saved permanently — the '/content/' upload area is temporary and clears when the session closes, so keep your original CSV and save the notebook to Drive.","Trusting a surprising number without checking — AI-written code can quietly filter or group the wrong column, so eyeball whether the totals make sense.","Writing a vague request like 'analyze this' — the vaguer the ask, the more random the code; state the exact columns and the exact result you want."],"example":{"input":"A CSV named sales.csv with columns Order_ID, Category, Region, Sales. Plain-English request typed into Colab's in-cell AI 'Generate code' box: 'Using the dataframe df, show the total Sales for each Category, sorted from highest to lowest.'","output":"Gemini writes and runs:  df.groupby('Category')['Sales'].sum().sort_values(ascending=False)\n\nCategory\nElectronics    48,200\nHome Goods     31,750\nApparel        19,400\nBooks           7,900\nName: Sales, dtype: int64","note":"You asked a plain-English question and got a ranked answer in seconds — no pivot table, no formulas. Swap in next month's CSV and re-run to repeat the whole thing instantly."}},{"id":"cp2","num":32,"cat":"P","title":"Colab: Run a Real Open-Source AI Model for Free (GPU-Powered)","tagline":"Flip on a free graphics chip in your browser and run a genuine open-source language model yourself — the actual thing, running on Google's hardware, at zero cost.","audience":"Curious beginners, students, and educators who want to see a real AI model run with their own eyes — not a website that hides the model, but the model itself loading and answering. Perfect if you have heard terms like 'open-source LLM,' 'Hugging Face,' or 'GPU' and want a hands-on, no-cost, no-install first experience.","why":"Chatbots like ChatGPT hide the model behind a website, so it can feel like magic rather than software. Colab lets you download a small open-source model and run it yourself, for free, on a real GPU (a graphics chip that does AI math hundreds of times faster than an ordinary processor) — which demystifies the whole thing and teaches you what 'running a model' actually means. It is also the cheapest possible sandbox: no credit card, no powerful computer, nothing installed on your machine. Reach for this when you want to experiment with open models, learn the Hugging Face ecosystem, or prototype an idea before deciding whether to pay for anything.","platform":"Google Colab","lab":"lab22","need":["A free Google account — the free tier includes limited GPU time, which is plenty to learn","Nothing installed and no payment method — everything runs in the browser","Optional: a free Hugging Face account and access token, ONLY if you later want a 'gated' model like Google's Gemma or Meta's Llama that requires accepting a license first (the model in this tutorial is ungated and needs none)"],"steps":[{"title":"Create a notebook and turn on the free GPU","detail":"Open colab.research.google.com, sign in, and click 'New notebook'. Now switch on the fast hardware: in the top menu click 'Runtime', then 'Change runtime type'. In the box that appears, under 'Hardware accelerator', click the 'T4 GPU' option, then click 'Save'. The T4 is a free graphics chip Google lends you — this one setting is what makes the model run in seconds instead of minutes."},{"title":"Connect and confirm the GPU is really on","detail":"Click the 'Connect' button in the top-right to attach your notebook to a machine; it changes to show a green checkmark with RAM and disk bars when ready. To prove the GPU is active, type '!nvidia-smi' in a code cell and run it (the play button or Shift+Enter). The '!' means 'run this as a system command.' You should see a table mentioning 'Tesla T4' — that is your free GPU reporting for duty."},{"title":"Install the AI libraries","detail":"In a new code cell, type '!pip install -U transformers accelerate' and run it. 'pip' is Python's app-store for code libraries: 'transformers' is Hugging Face's popular toolkit for loading AI models in a few lines, and 'accelerate' is the helper it needs to place a model on the GPU automatically (the 'device_map=\"auto\"' step later depends on it). You will see a wall of installation text scroll by for a few seconds — that is normal; wait for it to finish before the next step."},{"title":"Load a small open model onto the GPU","detail":"In the next cell, paste the loading code from the snippet below and run it. The first run downloads the model's files (a small instruct model, a few hundred megabytes) so it takes a minute — after that it is cached and instant. The phrase 'device_map=\"auto\"' is the magic words that tell it to use your T4 GPU automatically. When it finishes with no red error, the model is loaded and living in memory, ready to answer."},{"title":"Give it a prompt and read the model's reply","detail":"Edit the 'content' line in the snippet to whatever you want to ask, then run the cell. The model thinks for a moment and prints its answer right below. Try a few prompts — ask it to explain a concept, write a limerick, or summarize a paragraph you paste in — and notice you are talking to a model running on Google's hardware that you loaded yourself, with no outside website involved."},{"title":"Save your notebook (and mind the free limits)","detail":"Use File then 'Save a copy in Drive' to keep your working notebook. Free GPU sessions are time-limited and disconnect if you leave them idle, and reconnecting gives you a fresh machine that must re-install and re-download — so save the notebook (the instructions), knowing the model itself simply reloads when you run the cells again. If you hit a 'GPU not available' message, it means the free pool is busy; wait a while or try later."}],"cloud":{"steps":["Open colab.research.google.com and click 'New notebook'","Click Runtime, then 'Change runtime type', pick 'T4 GPU', and click Save","Click 'Connect' in the top-right and wait for the green checkmark","Run '!nvidia-smi' in a cell to confirm you see 'Tesla T4'","Run '!pip install -U transformers accelerate' and wait for it to finish","Paste and run the model-loading snippet (the first run downloads the model)","Edit the prompt text, run the cell, and read the model's reply","Save with File then 'Save a copy in Drive'"]},"prompt":"from transformers import pipeline\n\n# Loads a small, open, no-login-required instruct model onto the free T4 GPU\nchatbot = pipeline(\n    \"text-generation\",\n    model=\"Qwen/Qwen2.5-1.5B-Instruct\",\n    device_map=\"auto\"          # 'auto' puts the model on the GPU for you (needs the accelerate library)\n)\n\nmessages = [{\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": \"Explain what a large language model is, in two sentences.\"}]\nreply = chatbot(messages, max_new_tokens=200)\nprint(reply[0][\"generated_text\"][-1][\"content\"])","promptNote":"Change only the text inside 'content' to ask your own question. 'Qwen/Qwen2.5-1.5B-Instruct' is a small open model that needs no login — a great first pick. To try a gated model like 'google/gemma-2-2b-it', you must first create a free Hugging Face account, accept the model's license on its page, and paste an access token into Colab's Secrets (the key icon) — otherwise it will refuse to download. Bump 'max_new_tokens' up for longer answers, down for faster ones.","tips":["Start with the smallest model that works — a 1-to-2-billion-parameter model runs fast and comfortably on the free T4, while bigger models can run out of memory.","The first model download is slow; every run after that is instant because Colab caches it for the session. Don't panic at the one-time wait.","If you get an out-of-memory error, choose a smaller model or restart the runtime (Runtime then 'Restart session') to clear memory before trying again.","Explore models at huggingface.co — filter for 'Text Generation' and small sizes; look for ones without a license-agreement gate for the easiest start.","Watch your free GPU usage; if you get temporarily cut off, that is the free-tier limit resetting, not a broken notebook. Come back later."],"mistakes":["Forgetting to switch to the T4 GPU first — the model still runs but crawls on the plain processor, making people wrongly think it is broken.","Trying to load a huge model on the free tier — it exceeds the GPU's memory and errors out; pick a small model instead.","Attempting a gated model (Gemma, Llama) with no Hugging Face token — the download is refused; accept the license and add a token via the Secrets key icon first.","Assuming the model is saved to your computer — nothing installs locally; the model lives in the temporary cloud session and re-downloads when you reconnect.","Leaving the tab idle for a long time — the free session disconnects, and reconnecting gives a fresh machine that must re-install and re-download everything."],"example":{"input":"Prompt content set to: 'Explain what a large language model is, in two sentences.' running on the free T4 GPU with the Qwen2.5-1.5B-Instruct model.","output":"A large language model is a computer program trained on enormous amounts of text so it can predict likely next words and, through that, generate human-like responses. It doesn't 'know' facts the way people do; it produces answers based on statistical patterns it learned during training.","note":"That reply was generated by a model you loaded and ran yourself on Google's free hardware — no ChatGPT, no API key, no cost. You just ran real AI end to end."}},{"id":"cp3","num":33,"cat":"P","title":"Colab: Build a Tiny 'Ask-Me-Anything' App on the Gemini API","tagline":"Get a free Gemini API key, store it safely, and build a mini chatbot in a notebook you can run over and over — your first real AI app in about ten minutes.","audience":"Beginners who want to go one step past using a chatbot website and actually build something that calls an AI 'API' — the doorway that lets your own code talk to a powerful model. Ideal for students, hobbyists, and non-technical folks who want a concrete, satisfying first project without installing anything.","why":"An 'API' (Application Programming Interface) is just a way for your code to send a question to a company's AI and get an answer back — it is how every AI-powered app under the hood actually works. Google's Gemini API has a free tier, and Colab is the friendliest place to try it because there is nothing to install and it has a built-in vault for your secret key. Building even a ten-line 'ask-me-anything' loop teaches you the exact pattern behind chatbots, and it becomes the skeleton you extend later — customer FAQ helper, study-question generator, whatever you dream up. Reach for this when you want to learn how apps call AI, or to prototype an idea quickly and freely.","platform":"Google Colab","lab":"lab22","need":["A free Google account","A free Gemini API key from Google AI Studio (aistudio.google.com/apikey) — a long secret code that authorizes your requests; the free tier is enough to learn","No installs and no credit card — everything runs in the browser"],"steps":[{"title":"Get your free Gemini API key","detail":"In a new tab go to aistudio.google.com/apikey, sign in with your Google account, and click 'Create API key' (accept the terms if prompted). It generates a long string of letters and numbers — this is your secret key, like a password that lets code use Gemini on your account. Click to copy it, and treat it like a password: never post it publicly or paste it into a shared notebook."},{"title":"Open a notebook and store the key in Colab's secret vault","detail":"Open colab.research.google.com and click 'New notebook'. On the far-left icon strip, click the key icon to open 'Secrets', then click 'Add a new secret'. For the Name type exactly GEMINI_API_KEY, paste your key into the Value box, and switch on the 'Notebook access' toggle next to it. This vault keeps your key out of your code, so it never gets shared if you send the notebook to someone."},{"title":"Install the Gemini library","detail":"In a code cell type '!pip install -U google-genai' and run it with the play button. This installs Google's official toolkit ('google-genai') for talking to Gemini from Python. Wait for the install text to finish scrolling. The '-U' just means 'give me the newest version.'"},{"title":"Load your key and send a test question","detail":"In the next cell, paste the connection code from the snippet below (Block 1) and run it. It safely pulls your key from the vault with 'userdata.get', creates a Gemini client, sends a single test question with 'client.models.generate_content', and prints the answer from 'response.text'. If you see a sensible reply, congratulations — your code just talked to a real AI model. If it errors, the usual cause is a name mismatch: the secret must be named exactly GEMINI_API_KEY with its 'Notebook access' toggle on."},{"title":"Turn it into a tiny app with a question loop","detail":"Now make it interactive. Paste the 'app' snippet (Block 2 below) into a second cell and run it — a text box appears asking you to type a question, Gemini answers, and it asks again, looping until you type 'quit'. That loop is genuinely a tiny app: input in, AI answer out, repeat. Change the prompt wording or prepend a personality instruction to make it your own."},{"title":"Save it so you can reuse and grow it","detail":"Use File then 'Save a copy in Drive' to keep your app notebook. Because the key lives in Secrets (not in the saved file), you can safely share the notebook and the recipient just adds their own key. Next time, reopen it, run the cells top to bottom, and your app is live again — ready for you to extend into something bigger."}],"cloud":{"steps":["Go to aistudio.google.com/apikey, sign in, and click 'Create API key'; copy the key","Open colab.research.google.com and click 'New notebook'","Click the key icon on the left, click 'Add a new secret', name it GEMINI_API_KEY, paste the key, and turn on 'Notebook access'","Run '!pip install -U google-genai' in a cell","Paste and run Block 1 (create the client and send a test question, printing response.text)","Paste and run Block 2 in a second cell to get an interactive ask-me-anything box","Type questions; type 'quit' to stop","Save with File then 'Save a copy in Drive'"]},"prompt":"# --- Block 1: connect and test ---\nfrom google.colab import userdata\nfrom google import genai\n\nclient = genai.Client(api_key=userdata.get(\"GEMINI_API_KEY\"))\n\nresponse = client.models.generate_content(\n    model=\"gemini-2.5-flash\",\n    contents=\"Say hello and tell me one fun fact about the ocean.\"\n)\nprint(response.text)\n\n\n# --- Block 2: the tiny app (run this in a second cell) ---\nwhile True:\n    question = input(\"Ask me anything (type 'quit' to stop): \")\n    if question.lower() == \"quit\":\n        break\n    response = client.models.generate_content(\n        model=\"gemini-2.5-flash\",\n        contents=question\n    )\n    print(\"\\nGemini:\", response.text, \"\\n\")","promptNote":"This is Google's current official pattern from the Gemini quickstart at ai.google.dev/gemini-api/docs — call client.models.generate_content with a 'model' and 'contents', then read the answer from response.text. 'gemini-2.5-flash' is a fast, free-tier model and a safe default; if you want the newest generation you can also try 'gemini-3.5-flash' (check the current list at ai.google.dev/gemini-api/docs/models). The secret's name in the vault MUST match the text inside userdata.get(...) exactly — GEMINI_API_KEY — or it cannot find your key. To give your app a personality, change 'contents' to something like: 'You are a friendly tutor. ' + question.","tips":["Store the key in the Secrets vault (key icon), never by typing it directly into a code cell — pasted-in keys get shared by accident and can rack up usage on your account.","Start on the free 'flash' model (gemini-2.5-flash) — it is fast and costs nothing on the free tier, perfect for learning before you consider anything paid.","Prepend an instruction to the user's question ('Answer in one short paragraph: ' + question) to steer tone and length without any complex setup.","Bookmark the official quickstart at ai.google.dev/gemini-api/docs — it always shows the current package name, model names, and code.","If you share the notebook, tell the recipient to add their own GEMINI_API_KEY secret — yours stays private in your vault and never travels with the file."],"mistakes":["Pasting the actual API key into a code cell instead of the Secrets vault — anyone you share the notebook with then gets your key. Use the key icon and userdata.get.","Naming the secret something other than the exact text in userdata.get(...) — a mismatch (even lowercase vs uppercase) means 'key not found'. Match them exactly.","Forgetting to flip on the secret's 'Notebook access' toggle — the vault holds the key but this notebook can't read it until the toggle is on.","Copying old code that uses a method that no longer exists — the current SDK uses client.models.generate_content(...) and response.text; if you see 'model not found', check the official docs and use a current model name like gemini-2.5-flash.","Assuming free means unlimited — the free tier has per-minute and per-day request limits, so heavy testing may briefly pause; wait and retry."],"example":{"input":"After setup, the user runs Block 2 and types: 'Give me a two-line pep talk for someone learning to code.'","output":"Gemini: Every expert you admire once stared at an error message they didn't understand — the difference is they kept going. You're not behind; you're exactly where every builder starts, so run that cell and keep climbing.","note":"That interactive box — type a question, get an AI answer, repeat — is a real app calling a real API. It's the same pattern that powers commercial chatbots, just in ten lines you wrote yourself."}},{"id":"cp4","num":34,"cat":"P","title":"Colab: Turn Data into a Shareable, Chart-Filled Report","tagline":"Upload a spreadsheet and turn it into a clean, chart-filled report with written explanations — then share it with a link or export it as a PDF, all from your browser.","audience":"Anyone who needs to present data, not just crunch it — students turning in assignments, managers building a monthly update, nonprofit staff reporting to a board, or teachers making a handout. Great for people who can use a spreadsheet but freeze up when it is time to make charts and write them up into something presentable.","why":"Raw numbers rarely persuade anyone; a clear chart with a sentence explaining it does. Colab lets you combine three things on one page — your data, colorful charts, and written narrative — into a single document you can share with a link or hand over as a PDF, no design software required. And because Google's Gemini is built in, you can ask for a chart in plain English and it writes the plotting code for you. Reach for this whenever you need to communicate findings to other people: it beats emailing a bare spreadsheet, and next period you swap the file and re-run to regenerate the whole report in seconds.","platform":"Google Colab","lab":"lab22","need":["A free Google account","Your data as a CSV file (export from Excel or Google Sheets via Save As / Download then choose 'CSV')","A few plain sentences in mind about what the data shows, for the written parts of the report"],"steps":[{"title":"Create a notebook and upload your data","detail":"Open colab.research.google.com, sign in, and click 'New notebook'. Click the folder icon on the left to open the Files panel, then the upload icon, and choose your CSV; it lands at '/content/yourfile.csv'. A notebook is the perfect report format because it stacks written notes and live charts in one scrollable page, top to bottom."},{"title":"Load the data and take a peek","detail":"In the first code cell, load the file into a table and show the top rows so you can confirm the columns. Type the load snippet below (or ask Gemini to write it) and run it with the play button. Seeing '.head()' print a few clean rows tells you the data is in and ready to chart."},{"title":"Make your charts — by hand or by asking Gemini","detail":"Add a new code cell with '+ Code'. Either paste the charting snippet below, or in the empty cell click the AI features button, choose 'Generate code', and type plainly, e.g., 'Using dataframe df, make a bar chart of total Sales by Category with a title.' Run the cell and a chart appears right under it. Repeat for each view you want — a bar chart for comparisons, a line chart for trends over time — each in its own cell so they stack neatly."},{"title":"Add written explanations between the charts","detail":"This is what turns a pile of charts into a report. Click '+ Text' to add a text cell (these use simple 'Markdown' formatting — type '# My Report' for a big heading, '## Sales' for a subheading, and plain sentences for body text). Put a heading and a sentence or two above each chart explaining what it shows and why it matters. Double-click a text cell to edit, and run it (Shift+Enter) to render the formatting."},{"title":"Run everything top to bottom for a clean render","detail":"Before sharing, make the report render fresh and in order: click 'Runtime' in the top menu, then 'Run all'. This executes every cell from the top so all charts and text display correctly with no leftover half-run state. Scroll through and read it as your audience will — headings, explanation, chart, repeat — and tidy any wording."},{"title":"Share it as a link or export a PDF","detail":"For a live, interactive link: click the 'Share' button in the top-right (it works just like sharing a Google Doc — set who can view). To send a fixed file instead, open the File menu: 'Save a copy in Drive' keeps your master, and 'Download' then 'Download .ipynb' saves the notebook file. Colab's Download menu only offers .ipynb and .py (there is no direct HTML or PDF export), so for a PDF use File then 'Print' and choose 'Save as PDF' as the destination — the whole chart-filled report prints to a clean PDF you can email or attach."}],"cloud":{"steps":["Open colab.research.google.com and click 'New notebook'","Click the folder icon, then the upload icon, and choose your CSV","Run the load snippet and check the first rows with .head()","Add a code cell and paste the charting snippet, or use the in-cell AI 'Generate code' feature to make a chart in plain English","Click '+ Text' to add headings and explanations above each chart","Click Runtime then 'Run all' to render the whole report in order","Click the 'Share' button (top-right) for a live link, or File then Print then 'Save as PDF' to export"]},"prompt":"import pandas as pd\nimport matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n\n# 1) Load the data\ndf = pd.read_csv(\"/content/sales.csv\")   # change to your filename\ndf.head()\n\n# 2) A simple bar chart: total Sales by Category\nsummary = df.groupby(\"Category\")[\"Sales\"].sum().sort_values(ascending=False)\nsummary.plot(kind=\"bar\", title=\"Total Sales by Category\")\nplt.ylabel(\"Sales ($)\")\nplt.tight_layout()\nplt.show()","promptNote":"Change 'sales.csv' to your filename and swap 'Category' and 'Sales' for your real column names (see them via df.head() or the Files panel). For a trend over time, change kind=\"bar\" to kind=\"line\" and group by a date column instead. Prefer not to touch code? Add an empty code cell, click the AI features button, choose 'Generate code', and type: 'Using dataframe df, make a bar chart of total Sales by Category, sorted descending, with a title and axis labels' — it writes the plotting code for you.","tips":["Alternate the cells: a text cell (heading + one explaining sentence) directly above each chart cell. That rhythm is what makes it read like a report instead of a code dump.","Give every chart a clear title and labeled axes — a chart no one has to decode is worth ten clever ones.","Use 'Run all' (Runtime menu) right before sharing so the reader sees every chart freshly rendered and in order, with no half-run leftovers.","For a portable file that opens anywhere, File then Print then 'Save as PDF' beats screenshots — it captures the whole report crisply in one document.","To refresh the report next month, upload the new CSV over the old one and hit 'Run all' — the entire chart-filled report regenerates in seconds."],"mistakes":["Sharing a notebook full of raw charts with no text — add headings and a sentence of context per chart, or your audience won't know what they're looking at.","Clicking 'Share' but leaving access as private-only — set the sharing permission so your intended viewers can actually open it, just like a Google Doc.","Forgetting to 'Run all' before exporting — a chart that wasn't re-run may show blank or stale in the PDF or shared view.","Hard-coding column names that don't match your file — 'Category' and 'Sales' are placeholders; check df.head() and use your real headers or the chart errors.","Assuming the shared link includes your uploaded file — the '/content/' upload is temporary, so a recipient who re-runs it needs the CSV too; a PDF export captures the finished charts as-is."],"example":{"input":"A CSV with columns Category and Sales, plus text cells: a '# Q3 Sales Report' heading and a note reading 'Electronics led the quarter, driven by a strong product launch.' above a bar chart.","output":"A single scrollable page: the title heading, the explanatory sentence, then a labeled bar chart showing Electronics tallest, followed by Home Goods, Apparel, and Books — exported to a clean PDF via File then Print then Save as PDF, ready to email.","note":"You went from a bare spreadsheet to a titled, explained, chart-filled report you can share by link or PDF — without design software, and re-runnable next quarter by swapping the file."}},{"id":"cp5","num":35,"cat":"P","platform":"Vertex AI Model Garden","lab":"lab23","title":"Model Garden: Compare Gemini, Gemma & Llama Before You Commit","tagline":"Try several top AI models in one place, read their scorecards, and pick the right one for your task before you write a line of code or pay for a deployment.","audience":"Non-technical decision-makers, students, analysts, instructors, and small-business owners who need to choose an AI model for a project and want to compare the big options honestly instead of guessing from marketing pages. No coding required.","why":"Model Garden is Google's single catalog of 200+ AI models — Google's own Gemini and open Gemma, Meta's Llama, plus Anthropic Claude, Mistral, and many open-weights models like Qwen and DeepSeek — all browsable in one place. Instead of signing up for three different vendors, you can read each model's 'report card' (benchmark scores, how much text it can read at once, its price, and its license) and type the exact same prompt into each to feel the difference for yourself. Reach for this at the very start of any AI project: testing prompts on Gemini in Vertex AI Studio costs only pennies, while committing to the wrong model later is expensive. Choosing well here saves you money and rework everywhere downstream.","need":["A Google account (a personal Gmail or a Workspace account both work)","A Google Cloud project with billing enabled — new customers get a $300 free-trial credit good for 90 days; browsing model cards is free, and testing Gemini in Vertex AI Studio costs only pennies","The Vertex AI API turned on (a one-click 'Enable all recommended APIs' prompt appears on your first visit)","One real prompt or task you care about (e.g. a customer email to summarize, a paragraph to rewrite) so you can test each model on the same thing","A web browser — Chrome is recommended; no programming or setup beyond signing in"],"steps":[{"title":"Sign in and open Model Garden","detail":"Go to console.cloud.google.com and sign in (or click the free-trial banner to claim the $300 credit — you enter a card to verify identity but are not charged during the trial). At the top, pick an existing project or create one; a 'project' is just a labeled workspace that keeps your work and billing together. Then open the navigation menu, choose Vertex AI, and click Model Garden — or jump straight to console.cloud.google.com/vertex-ai/model-garden. The first time, a banner asks you to 'Enable all recommended APIs' — click it and wait a few seconds; this switches on the engine that runs the models."},{"title":"Browse and filter the catalog","detail":"You'll see a grid of model tiles. Use the search box at the top to type a name like 'Gemini', 'Gemma', or 'Llama', and use the filter pane on the left to narrow by modality (text, image, code), by task, by provider (Google, Meta, Anthropic, Mistral, and others), and by collections such as open models. This is how you find the three you want to compare without scrolling forever."},{"title":"Read each model's scorecard (the model card)","detail":"Click a tile to open its model card. This is the model's fact sheet: an overview, suggested use cases, benchmark numbers (standardized test scores that hint at quality), the 'context window' (how much text it can read in one go — bigger is better for long documents), the license (the legal terms for using it), and pricing. Skim all three cards so you know what you're comparing before you type anything."},{"title":"Test Gemini in the built-in prompt box","detail":"On a Gemini card, click 'Open in Vertex AI Studio' (Google's built-in prompt playground). Paste your real prompt into the text box and click Submit. You can nudge the settings — 'Temperature' controls how creative vs. predictable the answer is, and 'Output token limit' caps how long the reply can be. Read the answer and note how fast and how good it was. Testing Gemini here costs only pennies per run."},{"title":"Test Gemma and Llama on the exact same prompt","detail":"Go back to Model Garden and open the Gemma card, then the Llama card. Open models are tested differently from Gemini: many cards have a 'Try out' box where you type a prompt against a hosted playground endpoint, and some offer a 'Playspace' (a temporary chat app Google spins up for you on Cloud Run). Note that a Playspace runs on rented infrastructure and bills small amounts while it's open, so close or delete it when you're done. If a model offers no playground, you can only truly try it by deploying it (tutorial cp6) — in that case, compare it on its model card benchmarks instead. Keep the prompt and input identical to what you gave Gemini: the only thing that changes is the model, so any difference you see is really the model."},{"title":"Score them on a simple rubric and decide","detail":"Rate each on five things: accuracy, tone, speed, cost, and whether it's 'managed' or 'open'. Gemini is managed — you just call it and pay a tiny amount per use, nothing to run. Gemma and Llama are open — free of license fees, but you'd have to deploy/host them yourself to use them in an app (that's the next tutorial). Pick the model that passed YOUR test at the price you like; you do not have to choose the biggest or newest one."}],"cloud":{"steps":["Open console.cloud.google.com/vertex-ai/model-garden and select your project","Click 'Enable all recommended APIs' if the banner appears","Search 'Gemini', open its card, click 'Open in Vertex AI Studio', and run your prompt","Search 'Gemma', open its card, and run the SAME prompt in its 'Try out' box or a launched Playspace","Search 'Llama', open its card, and run the same prompt in its playground if one is offered","Compare the three model cards' benchmarks, context window, license, and price","Write each model's answer, speed, and cost into a simple table","Pick the winner, then close or delete any Playspace you launched so it stops billing"]},"prompt":"You are one of several AI models I am evaluating for the same job. Task: [DESCRIBE YOUR REAL TASK — e.g., \"summarize this customer email in 3 bullet points and draft a one-paragraph reply\"]. Here is the input:\n\n[PASTE YOUR INPUT HERE]\n\nGive your single best answer. Then, on one final line, rate your own confidence from 1 to 10 and briefly note anything you were unsure about.","promptNote":"Keep the two bracketed parts as your own task and input, and paste this identical text into Gemini, Gemma, AND Llama. Because the only thing you change is which model you're in, every difference in the answers is a real difference between the models — a fair, apples-to-apples test.","tips":["Testing Gemini in Vertex AI Studio is cheap (pennies per run) and browsing model cards is free. For open models, a 'Playspace' spins up on Cloud Run and bills small amounts while it's open — close it when you're done.","Match the model to the job, not the hype: a smaller, cheaper model that passes your test beats a flagship you'll overpay for.","If you'll feed the model long documents, weigh the 'context window' heavily — it's the ceiling on how much text the model can read at once.","Open models like Gemma and Llama have license terms; skim them on the card before you plan to build on one.","Official reference for testing models in Model Garden: cloud.google.com/vertex-ai/generative-ai/docs/model-garden/quickstart"],"mistakes":["Judging models on different prompts — always use the identical prompt and input, or the comparison means nothing.","Assuming the newest or biggest model is automatically best; test specifically for YOUR task and audience.","Forgetting that 'open' models (Gemma, Llama) still have to be deployed or self-hosted to power an app, unlike managed Gemini which is call-and-go.","Leaving a Playspace running after you finish comparing — it runs on Cloud Run and keeps billing until you close or delete it.","Skipping the pricing and license sections on the card, then being surprised by cost or terms after you've built on the model."],"example":{"input":"The same prompt — 'Summarize this two-paragraph refund policy into 3 plain-English bullets' — pasted into Gemini Flash (in Vertex AI Studio), then Gemma and Llama via their playgrounds.","output":"Gemini: crisp 3 bullets, instant, pennies per run, nothing to host. Gemma: nearly as good, but you'd have to deploy it to use it in an app. Llama: solid, a touch wordier. Verdict: start with managed Gemini Flash; revisit Gemma only if a private, self-hosted model is truly required.","note":"The Gemini comparison took minutes and cost almost nothing; the only real caution is closing any Playspace you launched for the open models so it doesn't keep billing."}},{"id":"cp6","num":36,"cat":"P","platform":"Vertex AI Model Garden","lab":"lab23","title":"Model Garden: Deploy an Open Model (Gemma) as Your Own Private API","tagline":"Turn an open model like Gemma into your own private web address (an 'endpoint') that your apps can call — running on infrastructure you control, not a third party's.","audience":"Non-technical builders and small teams who need a private, self-hosted AI model — for example to keep sensitive data on their own cloud, to pin a specific open model version, or to customize serving. Comfortable clicking through a cloud console; no deep coding needed to test it.","why":"Managed models like Gemini are called over Google's shared service — simple, but the model isn't 'yours.' Sometimes you specifically need an open model (Gemma, Llama, and others) running on infrastructure you own — for data-privacy, control, or a fixed version. Model Garden's one-click Deploy stands an open model up as your own 'endpoint,' a private URL your code sends prompts to. Be honest with yourself about the tradeoff: that endpoint runs on a rented GPU machine that bills by the hour whether or not you use it, so undeploying when you're done is not optional. Reach for this only when self-hosting is the actual requirement; otherwise a managed model is cheaper and far simpler.","need":["A Google Cloud project with billing enabled — the $300 free-trial credit works, but a GPU endpoint can spend credit quickly, so watch it","The Vertex AI API enabled","Possibly a GPU quota grant — brand-new projects sometimes must request permission to use GPU accelerators; Model Garden will tell you if so","Agreement to the model's license — Gemma and Llama require accepting terms before Deploy unlocks","A way to test the result — the built-in prompt box on the endpoint page (no code), or the auto-generated code snippet if you want to call it from an app"],"steps":[{"title":"Pick a deployable open model and accept its license","detail":"In Model Garden, use the left filter pane to show open models, then open the Gemma card. Check that the card offers deployment (open models show a Deploy option; managed-only models don't). If a license or agreement box appears, read and accept it — Deploy stays greyed out until you do. Tip: choose a small Gemma size (like a 1B or 2B) for your first try; it deploys faster and needs a cheaper machine."},{"title":"Click Deploy to open the Deploy pane","detail":"On the card, click 'Deploy'. A side panel slides in where you name the deployment and choose the hardware it runs on. Don't be intimidated — Model Garden fills in sensible defaults, and for a first deploy you should mostly leave them alone."},{"title":"Review the settings (keep the defaults)","detail":"You'll see a model name and an endpoint name (an 'endpoint' is your private URL — the name is just a friendly label), a region, a machine type, and an accelerator (the GPU). Google pre-selects a recommended machine and GPU that fit the model. As a beginner, keep these defaults. Advanced options live under an expandable section — you can ignore them for now."},{"title":"Start the deployment and wait","detail":"Click 'Deploy'. Behind the scenes, Google rents a GPU machine, loads the model onto it, and wires up the endpoint. This genuinely takes about 15 to 30 minutes (sometimes longer) — a long wait is normal, not a failure. You can close the pane and track progress under Vertex AI, then Online prediction, then Endpoints, where the status changes to ready."},{"title":"Test the endpoint","detail":"Once the endpoint shows as ready, open it and use the built-in prompt/test box: type a short prompt, submit, and confirm you get a response back in about a second. This proves your private model is live. The endpoint page also shows a ready-made 'Sample request' code snippet with your real project and endpoint details filled in, if you later want to call it from an app."},{"title":"CRITICAL: undeploy and delete to stop the bill","detail":"When you're finished, do BOTH steps in order. Go to Vertex AI, then Online prediction, then Endpoints; select your region and click your endpoint. In the model row, click the Actions menu (the three-dot icon) and choose 'Undeploy model from endpoint', then confirm 'Undeploy' — this releases the GPU and stops the hourly charge. You can only delete an endpoint after every model is undeployed from it, so do that first, then remove the empty endpoint with its Actions menu, 'Delete endpoint'. Undeploying stops the cost; deleting cleans up. Skipping this is the number-one way people accidentally burn their credit."}],"cloud":{"steps":["In Model Garden, filter to Open models and open the Gemma model card","Accept the model's license/agreement if prompted","Click 'Deploy' to open the deploy pane","Keep the recommended region, machine type, and GPU (accelerator), then click 'Deploy'","Wait ~15-30 minutes; track status under Vertex AI > Online prediction > Endpoints","Open the ready endpoint and send a test prompt in the built-in box","When done: open the endpoint, and in the model row's Actions menu choose 'Undeploy model from endpoint'","After the model is undeployed, delete the endpoint (Actions > 'Delete endpoint') to fully stop charges"]},"prompt":"# You do NOT have to write this by hand.\n# After deployment, the endpoint page shows a 'Sample request' with your real\n# PROJECT_ID, REGION, and ENDPOINT_ID already filled in. This just shows the shape.\n\ncurl -X POST \\\n  -H \"Authorization: Bearer $(gcloud auth print-access-token)\" \\\n  -H \"Content-Type: application/json\" \\\n  \"https://REGION-aiplatform.googleapis.com/v1/projects/PROJECT_ID/locations/REGION/endpoints/ENDPOINT_ID:predict\" \\\n  -d '{\"instances\":[{\"prompt\":\"Write a one-sentence welcome message for new users.\",\"max_tokens\":64}]}'","promptNote":"To test with zero code, just use the prompt box on the endpoint page. This curl snippet is only what it looks like when you're ready to call the endpoint from your own app — and Google auto-generates the exact request for you with your real values (the field names can vary by model's serving format), so you copy it rather than type it by hand.","tips":["Start with the smallest Gemma size (e.g. 1B/2B). It deploys faster, needs a smaller and cheaper GPU, and is more than enough to learn the flow.","Set a billing budget alert before you deploy, so a forgotten endpoint can't quietly drain your trial credit.","If Deploy fails with a 'quota' message, that's a common new-project speed bump — request GPU quota, or pick a different region or smaller machine that has capacity.","Deployment is genuinely slow (15-30+ minutes) — go get a coffee; a long wait does not mean something broke.","Official walkthrough: cloud.google.com/vertex-ai/generative-ai/docs/model-garden/deploy-and-inference-tutorial"],"mistakes":["Leaving the endpoint deployed overnight — it bills by the hour even while idle. Undeploy the moment you're done.","Assuming undeploying the model also deletes the endpoint — they're two actions: undeploy the model first, then delete the now-empty endpoint.","Deploying a huge model on the free trial and burning through the $300 credit in a day.","Expecting the endpoint to be ready instantly; provisioning a GPU and loading the model legitimately takes 15-30+ minutes.","Not accepting the model license, then wondering why the Deploy button is greyed out."],"example":{"input":"Deploy a small Gemma to a GPU endpoint, send one test prompt, then undeploy and delete.","output":"After about 20 minutes the endpoint turned 'ready.' The test prompt 'Write a welcome message' returned a clean sentence in roughly one second. Undeploying the model and deleting the endpoint ten minutes later kept the total to a few dollars of trial credit.","note":"The private endpoint behaves like your own API — but it only exists, and only bills, while it is deployed. Off means both live and billing stop."}},{"id":"cp7","num":37,"cat":"P","platform":"Vertex AI Model Garden","lab":"lab23","title":"Model Garden: Ground Gemini on Your Own Data (RAG on Vertex)","tagline":"Make Gemini answer from YOUR documents — with citations — instead of guessing, by connecting your files as a searchable knowledge source.","audience":"Non-technical people who want an AI that answers from their own material — a policy handbook, product docs, course notes, an FAQ, a support knowledge base — accurately and with sources, without fine-tuning, training, or heavy coding.","why":"A foundation model doesn't know your internal documents, and when asked about them it will sometimes confidently make things up — a behavior called 'hallucination.' RAG (Retrieval-Augmented Generation) fixes this by first searching YOUR documents for the relevant passages, then handing only those to Gemini to answer from, with citations back to the source. Think of it as an open-book exam instead of a memory test. On Vertex you can do this with almost no code: create a searchable copy of your files (a data store in Google's AI Applications), then flip on the 'Grounding: Your data' toggle in Vertex AI Studio. Reach for this whenever a wrong answer is unacceptable and the real truth lives in your own documents.","need":["A Google Cloud project with billing enabled and the Vertex AI API turned on","Your documents as files — text-based PDFs, Word docs, or text files — either ready to upload or already sitting in a Cloud Storage bucket or Google Drive","For the no-code path, the AI Applications (Vertex AI Search) API enabled — a one-click prompt appears when you start creating a data store","A handful of real questions your documents should be able to answer, so you can check the grounding works","No coding for the data-store path; the deeper 'RAG Engine' path uses a ready-made notebook rather than pure clicking"],"steps":[{"title":"Understand RAG in one minute","detail":"Picture an open-book exam. Instead of answering from memory, the model first looks up the answer in YOUR book, then writes it and points to the page. The searchable copy of your documents is called a 'data store' (or, in the code-based path, a 'corpus'). RAG just means: retrieve the right passage first, then let the model generate the answer from it. That retrieval step is what stops the guessing."},{"title":"Gather and stage your documents","detail":"Collect the files you want the AI to answer from and either have them ready to upload or place them in a Cloud Storage bucket (Google's file storage). One caution: the documents must contain real, selectable text. A scanned image saved as a PDF has no readable text, so it must be run through OCR (text-recognition) first or nothing will get indexed."},{"title":"Create a data store of your files","detail":"In the Google Cloud console, open AI Applications (this is Google's current home for what used to be called Agent Builder / Vertex AI Search) and use 'Create Data Store'. Point it at your Cloud Storage bucket, Drive folder, or an upload. Google then imports and indexes your documents — behind the scenes it 'chunks' them (splits them into bite-size passages) and 'embeds' them (turns each passage into numbers that capture its meaning) so it can search by meaning, not just keywords. Wait for indexing to finish before testing."},{"title":"Open Vertex AI Studio and turn on grounding","detail":"Go to Vertex AI Studio and start a new prompt (a Freeform or Chat prompt both work), then pick a Gemini model. Open the settings panel on the right and find the grounding options. Click the 'Grounding: Your data' toggle to switch it on, then click 'Customize' — in the panel that appears, choose 'Vertex AI Search' as the source and select your data store (or paste its data store path). Click 'Save'. You've now told Gemini to answer from your documents."},{"title":"Ask questions and check the citations","detail":"Type a question your documents should answer and click 'Submit'. Gemini replies using the retrieved passages and shows the sources it used. Always click through at least one citation to confirm it really appears in your document — grounding dramatically reduces hallucination, but spot-checking sources is still good practice."},{"title":"Optional: go deeper with RAG Engine","detail":"For more control (custom chunk sizes, multiple sources, tuning), Vertex offers RAG Engine: you create a RAG 'corpus', import files, and query it. Be honest about the tradeoff — RAG Engine is mostly driven from a ready-made Colab Enterprise notebook or the Python SDK rather than pure pointing-and-clicking. If you want the simplest fully-clickable route, stay with the AI Applications data store plus the grounding toggle from the previous steps."}],"cloud":{"steps":["Enable the Vertex AI and AI Applications (Vertex AI Search) APIs when prompted","Put your documents in a Cloud Storage bucket (or have them ready to upload)","In AI Applications, use 'Create Data Store' to import your files; wait for indexing to finish","Open Vertex AI Studio and start a new Gemini prompt (Freeform or Chat)","In the settings panel, click the 'Grounding: Your data' toggle to switch it on","Click 'Customize', choose 'Vertex AI Search', select your data store, and click 'Save'","Enter a question, click 'Submit', and confirm the answer cites your documents","(Advanced) Use the Vertex RAG Engine notebook or Python SDK to build a RAG corpus in code"]},"prompt":"Answer the question using ONLY the connected documents. If the documents do not contain the answer, reply exactly: \"That is not covered in the provided documents\" — do not guess or fill in from general knowledge. After your answer, list the source document(s) and section you used.\n\nQuestion: [YOUR QUESTION HERE]","promptNote":"With grounding switched on, Vertex already restricts Gemini to your data store. Adding these instructions makes the model openly admit when the answer isn't in your documents instead of inventing one — which is the entire point of RAG. Replace only the bracketed question.","tips":["Test with questions your documents clearly answer first, to confirm grounding is working, then move on to trickier edge cases.","Keep the data store fresh — re-import when your documents change, or the answers will quietly go stale.","Prefer clean, text-based PDFs; run scanned image PDFs through OCR first, or nothing gets indexed and answers come back empty.","Always click through a citation to the real source at least occasionally — grounding reduces hallucination but doesn't fully eliminate it.","Official docs: cloud.google.com/vertex-ai/generative-ai/docs/grounding/overview and the RAG Engine overview under cloud.google.com/vertex-ai/generative-ai/docs/rag-engine"],"mistakes":["Expecting the plain model to 'just know' your documents — without grounding turned on, it will guess.","Uploading scanned, image-only PDFs that contain no real text, so the data store indexes nothing.","Testing before indexing finishes — if the data store is still importing, answers come back empty or thin.","Trusting grounded answers without ever opening a cited source to verify it.","Assuming full RAG Engine is all point-and-click — the corpus workflow is largely notebook/SDK-based; the fully no-code route is the AI Applications data store plus the grounding toggle."],"example":{"input":"Uploaded a 30-page employee handbook as a data store, turned on 'Grounding: Your data', and asked: 'How many vacation days do second-year employees get?'","output":"Ungrounded, Gemini guessed a generic '10-15 days.' Grounded on the handbook, it answered 'Second-year employees accrue 18 days' and cited page 12 — which was correct.","note":"Same model, same question — grounding turned a plausible-sounding guess into a sourced, correct answer."}},{"id":"cp8","num":38,"cat":"P","platform":"Microsoft Copilot Studio","lab":"lab24","title":"Copilot Studio: An IT Helpdesk Agent That Answers From Your Docs","tagline":"Build a no-code chat agent that answers staff IT questions straight from your own help documents, so the same 'how do I reset my password' question stops landing in your inbox.","audience":"Non-technical IT coordinators, help-desk staff, office managers, and small-business owners who field the same technical how-to questions over and over and want a self-serve answer bot grounded in their own guides. No coding required.","why":"IT teams answer the same handful of questions (VPN setup, password resets, which printer to use) dozens of times a week, and every one pulls someone off real work. A grounded agent reads your existing guides and answers those questions instantly, in chat, at any hour, without you writing a single line of code. Crucially, because you point it only at your documents, it answers from your actual policies instead of generic internet advice, and you can switch off its ability to guess so it says 'I don't know' rather than inventing a wrong step. Reach for this when the same tickets keep repeating and the answers already exist in a doc nobody reads.","platform_note":"","need":["A Microsoft 365 work or school account (personal Gmail/Outlook addresses are rejected at sign-up), or a Copilot Studio free trial started with a work/school email","A current version of Microsoft Edge, Chrome, Firefox, or Safari","Your IT help content in a usable form: a few PDFs or Word docs (password resets, VPN setup, printer guides) to upload, and/or the public URL of your IT support website","About 30 to 45 minutes","To publish: a licensed Copilot Studio plan. The free trial lets you build and test but not publish"],"steps":[{"title":"Sign in and describe the agent in plain English","detail":"Go to copilotstudio.microsoft.com and sign in with your work or school account (or start a free trial). On the Home page you'll see a box that prompts you to describe what you want your agent to do. Type a plain description like 'Answer employees' everyday IT questions using our help documents.' The description can be up to 1,024 characters, so be specific about the topics it should cover. (If you don't see this box, your environment doesn't support natural-language creation; use the manual 'Create an agent' option instead.)"},{"title":"Let Copilot Studio build the first draft","detail":"When you submit your description, the tool reads it and scaffolds an agent for you: it generates a name, a description, and 'instructions' (the rules that steer its behavior), and it lands you on the Overview page. It may also suggest knowledge sources and tools you can accept or dismiss. This is a working draft, not the finished product. Nothing is public yet, so you can experiment freely."},{"title":"Add your IT docs as the knowledge source","detail":"'Knowledge' is Copilot Studio's word for the documents and websites the agent is allowed to answer from. In the Knowledge section, select Add. Choose Documents (the file-upload option) to upload your PDFs and Word guides, or choose Public website and paste your support site's URL. Confirm with Add to agent. This is the single most important step: without it, the agent answers from generic internet knowledge instead of your policies."},{"title":"Lock it to your docs so it stops guessing","detail":"Open the agent's Settings, go to the Generative AI page, and in the Knowledge section turn OFF 'Allow ungrounded responses.' 'Ungrounded' means the agent answering from its own general knowledge instead of your files. Turning it off blocks any reply the agent produces without actually using a knowledge source or tool, so it backs off honestly instead of inventing a step. (This setting works only when generative orchestration is on, which is the default.)"},{"title":"Test it in the test pane like a real employee","detail":"On the right side of the screen is the 'Test your agent' chat pane. Ask a real question the way an employee would type it ('wifi won't connect', 'how do I reset my VPN password'). Check that the answer matches your document and look for the source citation underneath, which tells you which file the answer came from. If it's wrong or missing, that usually means the document needs to be clearer or wasn't added."},{"title":"Tighten the instructions and the greeting","detail":"Back on the Overview page, edit the Instructions field to set a concise, friendly tone and to tell the agent what to do when it doesn't know (for example, 'point the user to helpdesk@company.com'). Then, in the test pane, select the agent's opening (introductory) message to open the Conversation Start topic and edit the greeting so employees know what it can help with. Select Save."},{"title":"Publish to a demo website to share (optional, needs a license)","detail":"When it answers well and you have a licensed plan, select Publish at the top, then Publish again to confirm; a green banner means success. Then select the three dots (…) and choose Go to demo website to get a shareable link with a ready-made chat window. Remember: on the free trial this step is unavailable by design."}],"cloud":{"steps":["Go to copilotstudio.microsoft.com and sign in with your work or school account (or start a free trial).","On the Home page, type a description of your IT helpdesk agent (up to 1,024 characters) into the 'describe your agent' box and submit; wait for the Overview page.","In the Knowledge section select Add, choose Documents to upload your IT PDFs (or Public website for your support site URL), then confirm with Add to agent.","Open Settings > Generative AI and, in the Knowledge section, turn OFF 'Allow ungrounded responses' so the agent answers only from your docs.","In the 'Test your agent' pane, ask a real question like 'How do I reset my VPN password?' and confirm the answer matches your doc and shows a source citation.","On the Overview page, edit Instructions to set a concise, friendly tone and to escalate unknowns to your IT desk email.","Select the introductory message in the test pane to edit the welcome text in the Conversation Start topic, then Save.","When ready and licensed, select Publish > Publish, then the three dots (…) > Go to demo website to share the link."]},"prompt":"You are the Contoso IT Help Desk assistant. Answer employees' everyday technology questions (passwords, VPN, Wi-Fi, printers, software installs, and account lockouts) using ONLY the documents and help pages provided as knowledge. Keep answers short, numbered, and step-by-step. If the documents don't cover the question, say so plainly and tell the user to email helpdesk@contoso.com or open a ticket. Never guess. Be friendly, patient, and assume the person is not technical.","promptNote":"Paste this into the 'describe your agent' box to scaffold the agent, then also paste it (or a trimmed version) into the Instructions field on the Overview page. Instructions are what steer the agent's behavior after it's built. Swap 'Contoso' and the help-desk email for your own.","example":{"input":"An employee types in the test pane: 'My laptop won't connect to the office VPN, what do I do?'","output":"Here are the steps to reconnect to the Contoso VPN:\n1. Open the GlobalProtect app from your system tray.\n2. Select 'Connect' and enter your Contoso email and password.\n3. Approve the Microsoft Authenticator prompt on your phone.\n4. If it still fails, restart your laptop and try once more.\nIf you're still stuck, email helpdesk@contoso.com and put 'VPN' in the subject.\n\nSource: VPN-Setup-Guide.pdf","note":"The agent pulled the steps and the help-desk address straight from the uploaded VPN guide, and cited the file so the employee (and you) can trust where the answer came from. Because 'Allow ungrounded responses' is off, a question your docs don't cover gets an honest 'I don't have that' instead of a confident guess."},"tips":["Feed it a few small, well-titled documents rather than one giant messy PDF. Clear file names like 'Password-Reset.pdf' help the agent find and cite the right answer.","Keep 'Allow ungrounded responses' off while your library is small; it forces honest 'I don't know' answers and surfaces the gaps you still need to document.","Test with the messy, real wording people actually use ('wifi won't work', 'locked out'), not the tidy phrasing in your docs, because that's what employees will type.","Add your public IT support site as a second knowledge source so the agent covers both your internal PDFs and your published help pages.","Re-test every time you add or change a document; grounding quality shifts as your sources change."],"mistakes":["Uploading confidential HR or security docs into an IT helpdesk agent 'just in case.' Only add sources you're comfortable everyone who can reach the agent seeing.","Leaving 'Allow ungrounded responses' on, then being surprised when the agent invents a plausible-but-wrong fix from general internet knowledge.","Expecting to publish on the free trial. The trial builds and tests only; you need a licensed Copilot Studio plan to publish and share a link.","Pasting a website's home URL and assuming it read every page. Public-website knowledge searches the site via Bing, so pages that aren't indexed or sit behind a login won't be found.","Writing vague instructions ('be helpful') instead of telling it exactly what to do when it doesn't know. That one sentence is what stops confident wrong answers."],"resources":["https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/microsoft-copilot-studio/fundamentals-get-started","https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/microsoft-copilot-studio/knowledge-copilot-studio","https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/microsoft-copilot-studio/requirements-licensing-subscriptions"]},{"id":"cp9","num":39,"cat":"P","platform":"Microsoft Copilot Studio","lab":"lab24","title":"Copilot Studio: An HR & Policy FAQ Copilot","tagline":"Stand up a friendly HR assistant that answers 'how much PTO do I have left' and 'what's the parental-leave policy' from your handbook, and points the tricky, personal cases to a real human.","audience":"HR generalists, people-ops teams, and office managers at small and mid-size organizations who answer the same policy questions all day and want employees to self-serve from the official handbook, with sensitive or one-off situations routed to a person.","why":"Most HR questions are the same dozen policy lookups (time off, holidays, benefits enrollment, expense rules) and answering them by hand pulls your team away from the work only people can do. An HR FAQ copilot answers those from your actual handbook, in the employee's own words, instantly and privately. Because it cites the policy document, employees get the authoritative answer rather than hallway hearsay. Reach for this when policy questions swamp your inbox but the genuinely human moments (a leave request, a complaint) still need a person, which you can instruct the agent to route.","platform_note":"","need":["A Microsoft 365 work or school account, or a Copilot Studio free trial (personal email addresses are rejected, so use a work/school account)","Your current HR policy content: the employee handbook and policy PDFs to upload, and/or a SharePoint site or public benefits page URL","A destination for escalations: an HR email address or Teams channel","A current browser and about 45 minutes","To publish: a licensed Copilot Studio plan. The trial builds and tests but can't publish"],"steps":[{"title":"Sign in and describe your HR assistant","detail":"Go to copilotstudio.microsoft.com, sign in, and on the Home page describe what you want in the 'describe your agent' box, for example 'A helpful assistant that answers employee questions about our HR policies and benefits from the handbook.' Copilot Studio builds a first draft and drops you on the Overview page. This is private until you publish, so relax and iterate."},{"title":"Add the handbook as knowledge","detail":"In the Knowledge section, select Add. Choose Documents to upload the handbook and policy PDFs, or SharePoint to point at your HR site, then Add to agent. 'Knowledge' is simply the set of sources the agent is allowed to quote from. Uploading the real handbook is what makes answers authoritative rather than generic. (Note: SharePoint knowledge respects each user's own access permissions.)"},{"title":"Keep answers tied to the handbook","detail":"Open Settings, go to the Generative AI page, and in the Knowledge section turn OFF 'Allow ungrounded responses.' This blocks any reply the agent produces without actually consulting a knowledge source or tool, keeping it anchored to your documents so employees get your policy, not the internet's."},{"title":"Set a warm tone and an escalation rule in Instructions","detail":"On the Overview page, edit the Instructions to give the agent a warm, confidential voice and, most importantly, a clear rule about what NOT to answer. Spell out the sensitive topics (harassment, medical leave, pay disputes, terminations) and tell it to direct those to a named HR contact instead. This one paragraph is what keeps an automated assistant out of situations that need a human."},{"title":"Add suggested prompts so employees know what to ask","detail":"On the Overview page, go to the Suggested prompts section and select Add suggested prompts. Add a few starters like 'How do I request time off?' and 'What's our parental-leave policy?' (you can configure up to 10). These appear on the agent's welcome page in Teams and Microsoft 365 and teach employees what it's good for. Note: they show to end users in those channels only, not inside the Copilot Studio test pane."},{"title":"Test with real employee questions","detail":"In the 'Test your agent' pane, ask questions the messy way people really phrase them ('how many vacation days do i get', 'can i work from home fridays'). Confirm each answer cites the handbook and that a sensitive question ('I'm being harassed') gets routed to HR rather than answered. Edit and re-test until it behaves."},{"title":"Publish or share when licensed","detail":"With a licensed plan, select Publish at the top, then Publish again; a green banner confirms it's live. From there you can share a demo website link or roll it out to Teams (covered in the publishing tutorial). On the trial, you can perfect it in the test pane but can't publish yet."}],"cloud":{"steps":["Sign in at copilotstudio.microsoft.com and describe your HR assistant in the Home page box; wait for the Overview page.","In Knowledge, select Add, upload your handbook/policy files (Documents) or add your HR SharePoint/benefits URL, then Add to agent.","In Settings > Generative AI, in the Knowledge section turn OFF 'Allow ungrounded responses' so answers stay tied to the handbook.","On Overview, edit Instructions to set a warm, confidential tone and to route personal/sensitive matters (harassment, medical leave, pay) to a named HR contact instead of answering.","In the Suggested prompts section, select Add suggested prompts and add starters like 'How do I book time off?' and 'What's the 401(k) match?' (up to 10).","In the 'Test your agent' pane, ask questions in everyday language and confirm answers cite the handbook and sensitive topics escalate.","Select the introductory message in the test pane to edit the greeting so employees know what it can and can't help with, then Save.","When licensed, select Publish > Publish to make it available on your chosen channel."]},"prompt":"You are the Contoso People Team assistant. Help employees find answers about company policies (time off, holidays, benefits, expenses, remote-work rules, and the code of conduct) using ONLY the employee handbook and policy documents provided as knowledge. Always cite the policy you're quoting. Keep a warm, respectful, confidential tone. Do NOT give legal, medical, or individual-case advice: for anything personal or sensitive (harassment, medical leave, disputes, terminations, pay concerns), tell the employee you can't handle that here and direct them to email people@contoso.com or message the HR team. If the handbook doesn't cover a question, say so and point them to HR.","promptNote":"Use this as your 'describe your agent' text and again in the Instructions field. The most important line is the escalation rule. Spell out exactly which topics the agent must hand to a human, because those are the cases where a wrong automated answer does real harm.","example":{"input":"An employee asks: 'i started in march, how many vacation days do i have this year?'","output":"Great question! Per the Contoso Employee Handbook (Section 4: Paid Time Off), full-time employees accrue 15 vacation days per year, earned monthly. Since you started in March, you accrue for about 10 months this year, which is roughly 12.5 days.\nTo book time off, submit a request in Workday under 'Time Off.'\n\nSource: Employee-Handbook-2026.pdf, Section 4\n\nIf your start date or status differs from a standard full-time hire, please confirm with people@contoso.com.","note":"The agent read the accrual rule from the handbook, did the simple pro-rating, cited the exact section, and still nudged the employee to confirm edge cases with a human. That's exactly the balance you want for HR."},"tips":["Mark your handbook as an 'Official source' (three dots ⋮ next to it > Official source > Yes) if you turn OFF generative orchestration (classic mode); it then answers from that source directly with a trusted-source indicator. Official source is not compatible with generative orchestration, so on the default generative setting, keeping 'Allow ungrounded responses' off gives you similar discipline instead.","Write the escalation rule as a concrete list of topics, not 'sensitive things.' The agent follows explicit examples far better than vague categories.","Use a dated file name like 'Employee-Handbook-2026.pdf' and replace it each year so employees never get last year's policy.","Turn on suggested prompts; in Teams and Microsoft 365 they show on the welcome page and teach employees what the agent is good for.","Keep pay-specific numbers out of the docs if the agent is broadly accessible; point to a personalized system (Workday, payroll) instead."],"mistakes":["Uploading documents that contain individual employee data (salaries, reviews). Anyone who can chat with the agent could pull that out; keep it to general policy.","Skipping the escalation rule, so the agent cheerfully 'answers' a harassment or medical-leave question it has no business handling.","Assuming suggested prompts appear in the Copilot Studio test pane. They only show in Teams and Microsoft 365, so test the underlying answers directly.","Forgetting to remove or replace the prior year's handbook, leaving two versions that give conflicting answers.","Publishing on the trial license and wondering why there's no share option. Publishing needs a paid Copilot Studio plan."],"resources":["https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/microsoft-copilot-studio/fundamentals-get-started-teams","https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/microsoft-copilot-studio/knowledge-copilot-studio","https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/microsoft-copilot-studio/requirements-licensing-subscriptions"]},{"id":"cp10","num":40,"cat":"P","platform":"Microsoft Copilot Studio","lab":"lab24","title":"Copilot Studio: Automate a Task with an Action or Flow","tagline":"Go beyond answering questions: give your agent a 'tool' so it can actually do something, like log a helpdesk ticket, post to a Teams channel, or look up an order.","audience":"Non-technical makers who've built a Q&A agent and now want it to take action (create records, send notifications, fetch live data) by adding a ready-made connector or a simple Power Automate agent flow, all through menus rather than code.","why":"An agent that only talks is half the value; the payoff comes when it can do the task the conversation is about, like open a ticket, email a team, add a row to a tracker, or check an order status. In Copilot Studio you grant that ability by adding a 'tool' (Microsoft's word for an action the agent can run), either a prebuilt connector to a service like Outlook or Teams, or a small agent flow you build in Power Automate (a drag-and-drop automation builder, no code). With generative orchestration on (the default), the agent decides when to use the tool based on the conversation, so a user can just say 'log this as a ticket' and it happens. Reach for this the moment your agent's most common request is an action, not a fact.","platform_note":"","need":["A Copilot Studio agent you've already created (see the IT Helpdesk or HR tutorials)","A Microsoft 365 work or school account with permission to use the connector you want (e.g., Teams, Outlook, SharePoint); some premium connectors require a licensed plan","The details the task needs: for example, the Team and channel to post to, or the list/table to write to","A current browser and about 30 to 45 minutes","Willingness to test the action safely before real users can trigger it"],"steps":[{"title":"Decide the one action worth automating","detail":"Pick the single most common thing users want the agent to DO, not just answer. Good first choices: 'post a message to our IT Teams channel,' 'send an email to the facilities inbox,' or 'add a row to a request tracker.' Starting with one clear, low-risk action keeps this simple and lets you learn the pattern before you build anything ambitious."},{"title":"Open the Tools page and add a tool","detail":"In your agent, go to the Tools page in the left-hand menu and select Add a tool. The Add tool pane opens. 'Tools' is where you give the agent abilities beyond conversation. From here you can either search the prebuilt connectors and pick a ready-made action, or select New tool to build your own (Agent flow, Prompt, REST API, Model Context Protocol, Computer use, or Custom connector). Which path you take depends on whether an off-the-shelf action already does what you need."},{"title":"Pick a prebuilt connector, or build an agent flow","detail":"For a ready-made action, search the Add tool pane for the service (like 'Microsoft Teams' or 'Outlook') and select the specific action (like 'Post message in a chat or channel'). If prompted, sign in to connect your account, then Add and configure. For custom logic, select New tool > Agent flow (you can also start from the Flows page); the agent-flow template opens with the required 'When an agent calls the flow' trigger and a 'Respond to the agent' action already placed for you."},{"title":"Tell the tool what information to collect","detail":"An action usually needs a few pieces of input, like a Subject and a Description for a ticket. In an agent flow, add these as inputs on the 'When an agent calls the flow' trigger, put the real action in the middle (post to the channel, create the row), and map values into 'Respond to the agent' so it can confirm back. Make sure the 'Asynchronous response' toggle is Off (under Networking in the Respond to the agent action's settings) so the agent gets an answer in real time, then Publish the flow."},{"title":"Describe the tool so the agent knows when to use it","detail":"Back in the agent (on the tool's configuration page, in the Details section), write a clear Description: one plain sentence about what the tool does and, crucially, WHEN to use it. In generative orchestration, the agent reads that description to decide whether to call the tool, so 'Use this when an employee reports a broken device' works far better than 'Posts a message.' Leave 'Allow agent to decide dynamically when to use the tool' selected so orchestration can trigger it."},{"title":"Test the action end to end","detail":"In the 'Test your agent' pane, make a real request ('log a ticket: my monitor is broken'). Watch the agent collect the details and fire the action, then go verify it actually happened: check the Teams channel, the inbox, or the list. Testing the whole path yourself is how you catch a wrong channel or a mismapped field before a real user does."},{"title":"Save and publish","detail":"Once the action fires correctly and the agent confirms it to the user, select Publish > Publish (with a licensed plan) so the new ability reaches your users. Any later change to the tool needs another Publish before users see it."}],"cloud":{"steps":["In your agent, go to the Tools page in the left pane and select Add a tool to open the Add tool pane.","For a ready-made action, search the Add tool pane for the service (e.g., 'Microsoft Teams' or 'Outlook'), pick the action (e.g., 'Post message in a chat or channel'), sign in to the connection if prompted, then Add and configure.","For custom logic, select New tool > Agent flow (or start from the Flows page); the template opens with the 'When an agent calls the flow' trigger and 'Respond to the agent' action in place.","Add inputs (like Subject and Description) on the trigger, add the action in the middle, map outputs into 'Respond to the agent,' confirm the Asynchronous response toggle is Off (under Networking), then Publish the flow.","Back in the agent, add the published flow as a tool and, in its Details section, write a clear Description of what it does and when to use it.","Map the conversation's collected values to the tool's inputs and set any fixed input overrides.","In the 'Test your agent' pane, run a real request and confirm the action actually fired (check the channel, inbox, or list).","Select Publish > Publish once it works reliably."]},"prompt":"Tool name: Log IT Ticket\nDescription: Use this tool when an employee reports a broken device or an IT problem that a human needs to fix. It posts the issue to the IT support Teams channel. Before calling it, collect a short Subject and a Description of the problem from the employee.\nInputs: Subject (text), Description (text)","promptNote":"In generative orchestration, the agent reads a tool's NAME and DESCRIPTION (in the tool's Details section) to decide when to use it. Write the description in terms of WHEN to trigger, not just what it does. A vague description means the tool never fires (or fires at the wrong moment).","example":{"input":"Employee: 'The projector in Room 4B is dead and I have a meeting at 2.' Agent (after its docs can't fix it): 'I can log this for the IT team, want me to?' Employee: 'yes please.'","output":"Done, I've logged your ticket with the IT team.\nSubject: Projector down in Room 4B\nDescription: Projector in Room 4B not powering on; needed for a 2:00 PM meeting.\nThey've been notified in the IT support channel and will follow up shortly.","note":"Behind the scenes the agent called the agent flow, passed the Subject and Description it gathered from the chat, and Power Automate posted a message to the IT Teams channel. The employee never left the conversation. Always test this path yourself first so a real user isn't the one who discovers the channel was set wrong."},"tips":["Start with one action and the simplest connector ('post a message to a Teams channel' or 'send an email') before attempting multi-step flows.","Name and describe the tool from the user's intent ('use when someone wants to report a broken device'), because that description is how the generative agent decides to call it.","Collect the inputs in the conversation first (the agent auto-generates questions for a subject and description), then pass them to the tool, so the record you create is actually useful.","Use a test channel or your own inbox as the destination while building, then switch to the real one once it works.","Keep flows under the 100-second real-time limit: return a quick confirmation to the user and let any slow steps run afterward."],"mistakes":["Writing a bland tool description ('posts a message'), so the agent never realizes when to use it. Describe the trigger situation explicitly.","Pointing the action at the real production channel or a customer inbox during testing and spamming actual people.","Forgetting the agent flow needs the 'When an agent calls the flow' trigger and a 'Respond to the agent' action with Asynchronous response Off; without those it can't be added as a tool.","Assuming premium connectors are free. Some require a licensed Copilot Studio or Power Platform plan and will prompt for one.","Not testing the whole path end to end, so you find out the inputs were mismapped only after a user's ticket vanishes."],"resources":["https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/microsoft-copilot-studio/add-tools-custom-agent","https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/microsoft-copilot-studio/flow-agent","https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/microsoft-copilot-studio/advanced-flow"]},{"id":"cp11","num":41,"cat":"P","platform":"Microsoft Copilot Studio","lab":"lab24","title":"Copilot Studio: Publish Your Copilot to Teams or a Website","tagline":"Take your agent live: share it as a simple demo web link, or roll it out inside Microsoft Teams so colleagues can chat with it right where they already work.","audience":"Anyone who's built and tested an agent in Copilot Studio and now needs to get it in front of real users, via a shareable demo website or the Microsoft Teams app store, without involving a developer.","why":"A tested agent is only useful once people can actually reach it, and publishing is the step that turns your draft into something colleagues can use. Copilot Studio gives you two easy front doors: a demo website (a ready-made web page with a chat window you can share by link) for quick sharing and feedback, and Microsoft Teams, so the agent lives where your organization already chats. The big catch to know up front: publishing requires a licensed plan (the free trial builds and tests but can't publish), and an org-wide Teams rollout needs an admin's approval. Reach for this once the agent answers well in the test pane and you're ready for real users.","platform_note":"","need":["A finished, tested Copilot Studio agent","A licensed Copilot Studio plan (standalone subscription, or the Teams plan included in select Microsoft 365 subscriptions). Publishing is not available on the free trial","For a Teams rollout: a Microsoft 365 account, and for org-wide availability an IT admin who can approve it","A few colleagues to try it and give feedback","About 20 to 30 minutes"],"steps":[{"title":"Do a final test pass first","detail":"Before you publish anything, run a last round in the 'Test your agent' pane so the version that goes live reflects your most recent edits. Publishing takes a snapshot of the agent as it is right now, so whatever you fix (or forget to fix) is what your users will get."},{"title":"Publish the current version","detail":"Select Publish at the top of the page, then Publish again in the confirmation message. A green banner across the top confirms it worked. 'Publishing' simply promotes your current draft to the live version that channels will serve. If Publish is unavailable, you're likely on the free trial, which is build-and-test only."},{"title":"Share the demo website link for quick feedback","detail":"For the fastest way to get the agent in front of people, select the three dots (…) at the top and choose Go to demo website. This opens a ready-made web page with a chat window. Copy that URL and send it to a few colleagues. It's perfect for a pilot: they can try it and tell you what it got wrong before a wider launch."},{"title":"Add the Microsoft Teams channel for a real rollout","detail":"To put the agent where people already work, go to the Channels page and select the 'Microsoft 365 and Microsoft Teams' channel, then Add channel. 'Channels' are the places an agent can live (a website, Teams, and more). This makes your agent installable from the Teams app store."},{"title":"Share with your team, then your organization","detail":"You choose the audience. Sharing directly with specific people makes the agent appear in the Teams app store (in the 'Built with Power Platform' or Copilot extensions section) with no admin approval needed, which is ideal for a pilot. Choosing 'Show to the organization' rolls it out to everyone under 'Built for your org,' but that step requires your admin to approve it first. Colleagues install it by selecting 'Add for me' in the Teams app store."},{"title":"Re-publish whenever you make changes","detail":"Every future edit stays invisible to users until you press Publish again. Get into the habit: change, test, Publish. If you ever wonder why users aren't seeing an improvement you made, this is almost always the reason."}],"cloud":{"steps":["In your agent, do a final round in the 'Test your agent' pane so the live version reflects your latest edits.","Select Publish at the top of the page, then Publish again in the confirmation message; wait for the green success banner.","For a quick shareable link, select the three dots (…) > Go to demo website, then send that URL to colleagues.","For Teams, go to the Channels page and select the 'Microsoft 365 and Microsoft Teams' channel, then Add channel.","Choose availability: share with specific people (appears in the 'Built with Power Platform'/Copilot extensions section of the Teams app store, no approval) for a pilot, or 'Show to the organization' for a full rollout (needs admin approval).","Tell colleagues to open the Teams app store, find your agent, and select 'Add for me.'","After any future edit, select Publish again; changes don't reach users until you re-publish."]},"prompt":"","promptNote":"","example":{"input":"You've finished an IT Helpdesk agent and want your whole support team using it in Teams by Monday.","output":"You Publish the agent (green banner confirms), open the Channels page, add the 'Microsoft 365 and Microsoft Teams' channel, and share it with specific people on your IT team. It appears in their Teams app store under 'Built with Power Platform.' They select 'Add for me' and start chatting with it in Teams. For the company-wide version, you choose 'Show to the organization,' which goes to your admin for approval before it appears in 'Built for your org.'","note":"Two audiences, two paths: 'share with specific people' is instant and needs no approval, perfect for a pilot, while 'Show to the organization' is the governed, admin-approved rollout for everyone."},"tips":["Use the demo website for your first pilot; it's the fastest way to collect 'it got this wrong' feedback before a wider launch.","Remember that publishing is a snapshot: every edit stays invisible to users until you press Publish again.","For a Teams pilot, share with specific people first; it skips admin approval and avoids pinging your admin unnecessarily.","Check the demo website's authentication setting before sharing widely; decide whether anyone with the link, or only signed-in colleagues, should be able to reach it.","Line up your admin early if you want an org-wide Teams rollout; the 'Show to the organization' step waits on their approval."],"mistakes":["Trying to publish on the free trial. It's build-and-test only; you need a licensed plan to publish at all.","Making changes and assuming users see them. Nothing goes live until you Publish again.","Sending the demo website link out broadly without checking its authentication, so people you didn't intend can chat with it.","Expecting an org-wide Teams agent to appear instantly. 'Show to the organization' requires admin approval and can take time.","Skipping a final test before publishing, so the version that goes live still has the rough edges you meant to fix."],"resources":["https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/microsoft-copilot-studio/fundamentals-get-started","https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/microsoft-copilot-studio/fundamentals-get-started-teams","https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/microsoft-copilot-studio/requirements-licensing-subscriptions"]},{"id":"cp12","num":42,"cat":"T","title":"Build Your Own Telegram AI Assistant You Can Text","tagline":"A private AI assistant you text from your phone like a friend — every message answered by a model running on your own computer, so nothing you type ever leaves your machine.","audience":"Motivated beginners who have never built a bot and maybe never run a Python script, but can copy-paste carefully and follow steps. It is ideal if you already have (or are willing to install) Ollama with one small model and want a genuinely useful first project: an AI you can message from anywhere on your phone that quietly lives on your own PC. No coding background is assumed — every piece of jargon is defined as it appears, and the whole thing is a handful of lines you paste and run.","why":"The apps you already live in — your messenger — are the most natural place to reach an assistant. You text a friend without opening a special website, and your AI should be just as close. This tutorial wires Telegram (a free, fast messaging app) to a model running locally through Ollama, so you get that texting convenience with a rare bonus: total privacy. Because the \"brain\" runs on your own computer and only your phone talks to it, your questions, notes, and half-formed ideas never touch a company's servers or get logged for training. It is also the friendliest possible on-ramp to the idea of an \"agent\": you will watch, in plain sight, how a message comes in, gets handed to a model, and comes back as a reply — the exact loop that powers every fancier AI assistant.","platform":"Telegram + your local AI","lab":"lab25","need":["A computer (Windows, Mac, or Linux) with Ollama installed and at least one model pulled — run `ollama pull llama3.2` once in a terminal. This is the AI \"brain\" that will answer every message.","The free Telegram app on your phone, plus a Telegram account (all you need is a phone number to sign up).","Python 3.10 or newer installed on the SAME computer as Ollama, and a willingness to run a couple of commands in a terminal. (python-telegram-bot needs 3.10+.)","Two small Python packages, installed with a single line: `pip install python-telegram-bot requests`.","About 30 to 45 minutes and some careful copy-pasting. No prior coding experience required — you will paste values into a short, ready-made script."],"steps":[{"title":"Create your bot with @BotFather and copy its secret token","detail":"In Telegram, search for the official account @BotFather (the blue verified 'father of all bots') and open a chat with it. Send the message /newbot. It asks two things: a display name (anything, like 'My Private Assistant') and then a username that must be 5–32 characters and end in the word 'bot' (like rizwan_pocket_bot). BotFather replies with a long secret string called a token — it looks like 110201543:AAHdqTcvCH1vGWJxfSeofSAs0K5PALDsaw. That token is the password that lets your script control the bot, so copy it and guard it like any password. Anyone who has it can run your bot."},{"title":"Make sure your local AI is up and running","detail":"Ollama is the free program that runs open AI models directly on your machine; it listens quietly at the address http://localhost:11434 — and 'localhost' simply means 'this same computer,' so nothing is going out to the internet. Confirm Ollama is installed and that you have downloaded a small model once with `ollama pull llama3.2`. Leave Ollama running in the background. This is the brain your bot will consult for every single reply."},{"title":"Find your own Telegram ID so only YOU can use the bot","detail":"By default, anyone who discovers your bot's username can message it — and every message would run on your computer using your model. To lock the bot to just you, you need your personal numeric Telegram ID (a number, not your @username). Open a chat with @userinfobot and send it anything; it instantly replies with your ID, a number like 123456789. Write that number down — you will paste it into the script so the bot politely ignores everyone in the world except you."},{"title":"Install the two Python pieces the connector needs","detail":"Open a terminal (Command Prompt or PowerShell on Windows, Terminal on Mac) and run `pip install python-telegram-bot requests`. The first package, python-telegram-bot, is a well-maintained library (currently v22, requiring Python 3.10+) that handles all the hard work of talking to Telegram for you — receiving messages and sending replies. The second, requests, is a tiny helper for passing your message over to Ollama. One line installs both."},{"title":"Run the short connector script that glues Telegram to Ollama","detail":"The full, ready-to-paste script lives in the hands-on lab, and it is genuinely short. Conceptually: it builds the bot with Application.builder().token(TOKEN).build(), then registers one message handler written as MessageHandler(filters.TEXT & ~filters.COMMAND & filters.User(user_id=YOUR_ID), reply) — that filters.User part is the safety lock that only lets YOUR messages through. For each message, the reply function sends your text in a POST request to http://localhost:11434/api/chat (with your model name, the system prompt, and \"stream\": false so Ollama returns the whole answer in one piece instead of a stream of chunks), reads the model's answer out of the response's message.content, and sends it back with update.message.reply_text(...). Finally the script calls application.run_polling() to keep listening. You paste in three things — your token, your numeric ID, and your model name — then start it with `python bot.py`."},{"title":"Text your new assistant from your phone","detail":"Open the chat with your bot in Telegram (tap its username in the BotFather message, or search for it) and send a plain message like 'Give me three quick dinner ideas using chicken and rice.' Within a second or two the reply appears — generated entirely on your own computer, by your own model. As long as the script and Ollama keep running on your PC, you can text your assistant from anywhere you have Telegram, including out of the house."},{"title":"Give it a personality, then stop and start it at will","detail":"Paste the short system prompt (in the section below) into the script to shape how the bot talks — its tone, length, and manners. Before you rely on it, glance one more time at the filters.User line to be sure it holds YOUR id and no one else can reach it. When you are done for the day, stop the bot by pressing Ctrl-C in the terminal window; run `python bot.py` again whenever you want it live. It is your assistant, on your terms, on your machine."}],"cloud":{"steps":["In Telegram, open @BotFather, send /newbot, choose a name and a username ending in 'bot', and copy the secret token it gives you.","Message @userinfobot and copy the numeric user ID it replies with — this is how the bot will recognize you.","Confirm Ollama is running and you have pulled a model once, e.g. `ollama pull llama3.2`.","In a terminal, run `pip install python-telegram-bot requests` to install the two pieces the script needs.","Open the connector script and paste in three things: your token, your numeric ID (into the filters.User line), and your model name; add the system prompt below.","Save the file and run `python bot.py`, then leave that terminal window open so the bot stays awake.","On your phone, open your bot's chat in Telegram and text it — the reply is generated locally by Ollama, not in any cloud.","To take it offline, press Ctrl-C in the terminal; run `python bot.py` again to bring it back."]},"prompt":"You are my personal pocket assistant, reached over text message on my phone. Keep replies short and friendly — usually a few sentences or a tight bulleted list — because I am reading on a small screen. Get straight to the answer and skip long preambles and filler. If a request is unclear, make one reasonable assumption and tell me what you assumed instead of asking a string of clarifying questions. When you are not sure of a fact, say so plainly rather than guessing. You run privately on my own computer, so you can be candid, direct, and practical.","promptNote":"Paste this into the script's SYSTEM line — it is sent to Ollama as the first message in the messages array with role \"system\", which the model treats as standing orders for the whole conversation. It shapes tone and length for a phone screen: short, direct, honest about uncertainty. Tweak it freely — change \"short and friendly\" to \"terse and technical,\" add \"always reply in Spanish,\" or give the bot a name. The system prompt is the cheapest, fastest way to change your assistant's entire personality without touching any other line of code.","tips":["Start with a small, fast model like llama3.2 (roughly 2 GB). It replies in a second or two on most laptops, whereas a very large model can leave you staring at a blank chat. You can always swap the model name in the script later once you know your hardware handles it.","Remember the bot only works while BOTH the script and Ollama are running on your computer — it is not hosted in the cloud. If replies suddenly stop, first check that the terminal window is still open and that Ollama has not been closed.","Add a friendly /start greeting using a CommandHandler so that when you first open the chat, the bot says hello and confirms it is alive — a nice sign that everything is wired up correctly.","Want a no-code, multi-channel assistant (WhatsApp, Slack, email) with team-wide guardrails and logging instead of one private bot? That is the OpenClaw lab (lab12) in the Experimentation Station — a governed, multi-channel agent you configure without writing code. This tutorial is deliberately the opposite: one dedicated bot, built by hand, entirely in your control.","Store your bot's username and token somewhere safe, like a password manager. If the token ever leaks or you lose it, @BotFather can issue a fresh one for you with the /token command (which also invalidates the old one)."],"mistakes":["Not restricting who can talk to the bot. If you skip the filters.User(user_id=YOUR_ID) line, ANYONE who stumbles on your bot's username can chat with it — running queries on your computer, using your model, and reading whatever it replies. Always lock the bot to your own numeric ID. This is the one step you must never skip.","Exposing your token. The token is your bot's password — never put it in a screenshot, a public code repository, or a shared chat. If it leaks, send /token to @BotFather to generate a fresh token; that automatically invalidates the old one so no one else can drive your bot.","Forgetting to set \"stream\": false in the Ollama request. By default /api/chat streams its answer back as many small JSON chunks; if the script expects one whole response, it will grab only a fragment or error out. Set \"stream\": false so the full reply comes back in a single response you can read straight from message.content.","Forgetting to start Ollama or pull the model. If http://localhost:11434 is not answering (Ollama is closed) or the model name in the script does not exactly match one you have pulled, the bot will error out or go silent. Run `ollama pull llama3.2` once and keep Ollama open in the background.","Expecting it to work while your computer is asleep or off. The brain is your own machine, so the assistant is only awake when your PC and the script are both running. Closing the laptop lid or ending the terminal takes it offline until you start it again.","Loading a huge model onto a modest laptop and assuming the bot is broken. A very large model can take a long time per reply or run out of memory, making the chat look frozen. Start small, confirm it works, and only size up if your hardware comfortably keeps pace."],"example":{"input":"You (texting your bot from the bus): Draft a short, friendly message to my landlord saying the kitchen faucet is leaking and asking to schedule a repair this week.","output":"Hi [Landlord], the kitchen faucet in my unit has started leaking and it's getting worse. Could we schedule a repair sometime this week? Just let me know which day works and I'll be sure to be home. Thanks so much!","note":"The entire exchange — your request and this reply — was handled by the model on your own computer. Nothing about your apartment, your landlord, or your schedule was ever sent to an outside company."}}];
